<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FUNDS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EIGHT STATES TO BE SPARED MEDICARE CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: NY, Del., Mass., Hawaii, Mo., Ore., Tenn, Vt.)  
(js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hospitals in New York and seven other states will
be spared cuts in Medicare payments under a decision announced
Friday by the secretary of Health and Human Services, Donna E.
Shalala.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials had been considering a policy change that
would have cut $2.1 billion from Medicare spending in the eight
states over the next five years. New York hospitals would have lost
$170 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals in Delaware, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Missouri, Oregon,
Tennessee and Vermont were also spared from cuts, federal health
officials said. The purpose of the payments in question is to help
hospitals that serve large numbers of indigent patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Shalala's decision followed months of intense lobbying by
the senators from New York, Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles E.
Schumer, and Rep. Charles B. Rangel, dean of the state's
congressional delegation. All are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for the Senate in New
York, also opposed the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer hailed the decision. ``We have been working on this a
long time,'' he said, ``and we got a lot of relief today.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare finances health care for 39 million people who are
elderly or disabled, including 2.7 million in New York state. The
program routinely covers hospital care for Medicare beneficiaries,
and the federal Medicare law guarantees extra payments to hospitals
that serve ``a disproportionate number of low-income patients with
special needs.'' The law refers to these institutions as
``disproportionate-share hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals serving more low-income patients get more federal
money. Medicare officials said initially that hospitals in New York
and the other states had exaggerated the number of poor people they
served.
</P>
<P>
   The question at the heart of the dispute is whether people in
welfare programs financed entirely by the states _ home relief and
general assistance programs _ should be counted as indigent when
the federal government computes Medicare payments to
``disproportionate-share hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these patients are single adults with mental illnesses
and drug or alcohol problems. Dr. Shalala ruled Friday that they
could be counted as indigent in computing the state's extra
Medicare payments.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, the senior Democrat on the Ways and Means Committee,
said: ``The purpose of the added Medicare payment to hospitals is
to account for the high costs of serving poor communities. Not
accounting for the care of home relief patients clearly
contradicted the intent of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Estimates by the Healthcare Association of New York State
suggest the size of the cuts that might have occurred: $13.5
million a year at Beth Israel Medical Center, $24.7 million at the
New York City Health and Hospitals Corporation, $6.3 million at
Montefiore Medical Center, $11.7 million at New York and
Presbyterian Hospitals, $7.5 million at St. Luke's-Roosevelt and
$4.5 million at nine hospitals on Long Island. The cuts would also
have affected many other hospitals in New York City and across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth E. Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, said Friday night, ``We were absolutely delighted with
the administration's decision, and the hard work of our
congressional delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some New York hospitals had threatened to sue the federal
government if it made the cuts it had been considering.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involved not only Medicare, but also Medicaid, a
separate health program for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and children who receive cash assistance under the main
federal-state welfare program normally qualify for Medicaid, and
they are also counted as indigent when federal officials compute
the extra Medicare payments allowed to hospitals serving large
numbers of poor people.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials had said that the childless adults in New
York's home relief program qualified for Medicaid only because New
York had received a special dispensation, or waiver, from the
federal government, allowing the state to expand Medicaid
eligibility as part of an experimental project.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health and Human Services said Friday that it
would continue to recognize the extra costs that hospitals incurred
in caring for both types of Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa T. Skolfield, a spokeswoman for the department, said,
``We concluded that people receiving Medicaid because of a federal
waiver should not be treated any different from people in the
regular Medicaid program.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, federal officials abandoned an effort to force New
York hospitals to repay $1 billion of Medicare money they had
received in recognition of the extra costs of treating low-income
patients. But at that time, the federal officials said they would
insist on a stricter interpretation of the law after Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Skolfield said the money to pay for Friday's decision, $2.1
billion over the next five years, would be included in the budget
that President Clinton will send to Congress next month.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals across the country are still planning to ask Congress
to restore billions of dollars cut from Medicare in the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
