<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6768 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-1STLD-WRI     01-15 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TWO 21ST CENTURY FOXES ELOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to reposition quote marks in 5th graf.)  
(DW) 
 By FRANK RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ CEO of the United States may be a big job, but the
White House, like everything else, looks smaller this week next to
the new AOL Time Warner. The most mega mega-merger in history
reduced the imminent presidential primaries to quaint sideshows,
relics of a distant age flickering along the fringes of the evening
news. Press and public alike instinctively recognized that the
first (though hardly the last) consummated marriage between new
media and old is going to shape our lives long after we've
forgotten which politician had which health or tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement and trepidation generated by this deal is in part
about money and Wall Street valuations, sure. But its lasting
effect lies in the sheer velocity and impact of seismic cultural
change. The unofficial precursor of AOL Time Warner synergy, the
movie ``You've Got Mail,'' came out just a year ago and has already
been outrun by Internet time. In that picture, the big chain
bookstores were driving the little independents out of business.
But now _ according to a new Andersen Consulting survey buried
under Monday's avalanche of merger news _ those big bookstores are
themselves being routed by the Net. This Christmas Americans
purchased more (far more) books online than at stores _ even though
less than half of the country is online and most of us who are have
slow connections.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL Time Warner deal accelerates the arrival of an
inevitable future by ratifying it with big clout and bucks. When
the world's largest purveyor of movies, music, journalism, books
and cable puts all its chips on the Internet, that's a virtual Mall
of America. (Conspicuous non-players in this mother of 21st-century
media combinations: a newspaper or major broadcast network.) In
increments within the next decade _ the loose time frame estimated
by AOL's Steve Case and Time Warner's Gerald Levin, with whom I had
separate conversations on Thursday _ everything we watch, read and
listen to will be as speedily accessible on the Internet as e-mail
is now. Which is not to say it will be free.
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street Journal headline announces ``the death of old
media''; Wired.com has spotted ``a music industry death knell'' and
``the end of TV as we know it''; in a December speech at the
Columbia Journalism School, Dan Okrent of Time Inc. declared ``the
death of print.'' I don't disagree, in the sense that the old media
will all be put in new electronic bottles. I can't say I'm upset.
For all the unknowns _ indeed, because of them _ this is a gripping
transitional moment in history. Besides, some of the antique forms
will continue to survive alongside the digital _ and, as Okrent
observed, even books printed on paper will still be sold to an
aging nostalgic elite. But most information and culture we consume
will be available both in greater variety and in handier, more
portable and cheaper packages than we have now.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say it can't be so. Don Imus spoke for many this week
when he said that a citizenry that still can't program a VCR will
never figure out how to download movies or navigate the Web's
infinity of offerings. That's where AOL comes in. It has long been
derided in Silicon Valley as ``the Internet on training wheels,''
but that was and is Case's big marketing idea. A country that can't
be bothered to program a VCR wants an Internet on training wheels.
That means a pre-selected, Reader's Digest distillation of the
Internet that's ultimately not in a PC and doesn't require you to
know what a disk drive, a browser or an operating system is, let
alone how to use one. It's an Internet that will be reached through
a ubiquitous device (``AOL Anywhere'') that looks like (and is as
simple to work as) a phone or TV. AOL TV will be introduced later
this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The other things we like in an appliance besides ease of use are
convenience and speed. We bridle at rewinding videocassettes or
returning our rentals to Blockbuster. It's a pain to search for TV
Guide, or fish out the newspaper's sports section or stock tables,
or the L.L. Bean catalogue, once we're settled into the couch with
clicker in hand and all that unruly paper is in the next room.
Media giants will pander to our laziness by giving us the whole
menu on demand, instantly, no geek expertise required, through
broadband connections such as those Time Warner's cable now adds to
AOL. They'll try to keep us glued, lest we wander into the wider
Internet in search of competing goods, services and information.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will need or want to shop at the virtual mall, but
few corporations have gone broke so far overestimating the appeal
of instant gratification to the American consumer. We are already
adopting DVD players faster than we initially did VCRs _ even
though home DVD players don't yet record _ not just because the
picture is better but because you can fast-forward or rewind in a
click. Once people discover instant digital time, they're suddenly
too impatient to tolerate even a few extra seconds required by
analog.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't guarantee that AOL Time Warner will succeed. Vision
is one thing, execution another. AOL has a history of access and
privacy meltdowns, Time Warner of money-hemorrhaging Web sites and
lumbering cable TV service. The corporate cultures could clash,
too: Case has never watched the most dazzling gem in the mountain
of content he just bought, ``The Sopranos.'' Fierce, perhaps more
nimble competitors will arrive soon, maybe siphoning off AOL Time
Warner brains when they do. Predicting winners in show business is
a fool's errand.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL Time Warner does have a head start and some corporate
DNA on its side. Levin stubbornly championed cable while Wall
Street predicted its (and his) doom. Two other executives on stage
at Monday's baptism were among the first to figure out, some 20
years ago, that the broadcast market could be fragmented into
lucrative, narrow niches: Ted Turner, who saw a global audience for
nonstop TV news, and Bob Pittman, who was present at the creation
of the first 24-hour movie channel as well as MTV. Theirs was a
digital sensibility before digital was cool _ home computers were
just coming on the market _ and you could argue that MTV in
particular, with its quick cuts and demolition of linear narrative,
was a harbinger of the aesthetic of Web surfing. Certainly the Web
is in part a zillion channels as specialized and idiosyncratic as
those of Turner's and Pittman's early wild dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the troubling part of the story. If you
believe that the Internet is the greatest explosion of free
expression and cultural resources of the past century, what happens
when it is merchandised as a mass-market product by the biggest
corporations in history?
</P>
<P>
   In theory and so far practice, the Web is limitless, too
powerful and diverse to be tamed or homogenized by any company, no
matter how huge. Some kid out there may already have a new idea
that will upend AOL Time Warner as Case did Bill Gates on the Net.
But should the new AOL or its coming rivals squelch that kid, who
will blow the whistle?
</P>
<P>
   At this point, almost every journalist in America works for at
least one media octopus. (Me? I'm an author at Random House, owned
by Bertelsmann, AOLs partner in Europe and Australia.) Even the
theoretically pure PBS now has a journalistic conflict of interest:
its broad new ``strategic alliance'' with AOL just happened to be
announced the day of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the specter of Big Brother. ``No country in the
history of the world has had this much information about people
before,'' in the words of the media critic Jon Katz.
Public-interest groups also worry that AOL Time Warner and its kin
will run their fast Internet wires like private toll roads, banning
other Internet providers or diverting them to slow and bumpy
traffic lanes. Case says trust him: if he and his peers fail to
guarantee an open Internet or to protect us from ``the nightmare of
an Orwellian world,'' then ``the backup is government
intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   He also allows that ``the devil is in the details,'' and ``it's
fair for people to say `Prove it' _ and that's what we will do over
the coming months.'' Levin echoes him, as well as vowing
independence for his journalists and artists.
</P>
<P>
   We may be on our own as we seek verification. Even as the
country was debating the vast implications of AOL Time Warner, the
otherwise loquacious current president and his would-be successors
have been all but mum on the subject. That's why it's in the
self-interest of those who haven't yet ventured into cyberspace to
stop procrastinating. You'll have no choice but to go there soon
enough, and on this frontier as on our last, more is up for grabs
now than after the barons lay down the rails.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
