u s BC-FBN-HOUSTON-CASSERLY-     01-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON-CASSERLY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casserly
</P>
<P>
   Operations job Casserly's &QL; 
to lose, sources say &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HOUSTON _ After another day of meetings with owner Bob McNair,
Charley Casserly has emerged as the clear favorite to become the
first vice president of football operations for Houston's NFL
expansion that begins play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources close to McNair told the Houston Chronicle on Friday
that Casserly is the leading candidate, and one went so far as to
say the job is Casserly's to lose, ``and don't expect Charley to
lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair made it clear Friday that he continues to be impressed
with Casserly, but he declined to call him the favorite or the
leading candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley's just farther along than anyone else,'' McNair said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   When Casserly returned to Houston on Thursday for a second
series of interviews with McNair and executive vice president Steve
Patterson, he brought his wife, Beverley, and daughter, Shannon,
another indication of how serious McNair is about hiring Casserly.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to McNair said the Casserly family is checking
out neighborhoods and schools before they leave Sunday. McNair
wants to have the position filled before he leaves for the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still hoping to have this wrapped up in the next two
weeks, but it's an important and complicated process,'' McNair
said. ``This job has a lot of requirements. There's a lot involved
in putting a team together. You've got to remember that we're
building from the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to the league meeting in New York next week
(Tuesday), and I'm going to visit with some people (owners) up
there about some other possible candidates we may interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, the former Washington general manager who spent his
entire 23-year NFL career with the Redskins, and Joe Mack, who
helped get the Carolina and Cleveland expansion franchises off the
ground, are the only candidates to be interviewed so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I are on the same page about so many things,''
Casserly said. ``Everyone knows Houston's going to be a premier
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of the many things that impress me about Bob is his
commitment to do things the right way and how much he wants to win.
He wants to do whatever it takes to have the best football program
around. And he's never wavered from that commitment. How could you
not be interested in a job like that?''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of NFL executives are interested in the job, including Tom
Donahoe, who resigned as Pittsburgh's director of football
operations Friday after losing a power struggle with coach Bill
Cowher.
</P>
<P>
   McNair called Steelers owner Dan Rooney on Thursday to ask for
permission to interview Donahoe. McNair had no idea Donahoe was
going to resign.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Friday afternoon, McNair still had not heard from
Rooney, but getting permission is no longer necessary. Donahoe, who
had eight years left on a 10-year contract, is free to negotiate
with any team.
</P>
<P>
   Like Casserly, Donahoe is one of the most respected personnel
men in the league. Although Donahoe wasn't available for comment
Friday, he has told friends he would be interested in the Houston
job.
</P>
<P>
   Before Casserly returned to Houston this week, others on
McNair's list were Donahoe, Seattle senior vice president Mike
Reinfeldt, Seattle vice president of football operations Randy
Mueller and Tampa Bay director of player personnel Jerry Angelo.
</P>
<P>
   But Casserly has continued to impress McNair with his enthusiasm
for the job. They will have more meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting to know Charley better and better,'' said
McNair, who stopped short of saying he would interview more
candidates. ``I like him a lot. I really do. Our philosophies are
similar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charley's done it at every level of an organization. And he's
been successful at every level. He's asking a lot of questions, and
so am I. We're talking about things like budget, personnel,
scouting and ranges in salary for the various positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said, we may have a small window of opportunity to
make a decision, and I'd hate to lose someone good, someone I
really like, because that window closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teams are interested in Casserly. It is no secret New
Orleans owner Tom Benson wants to talk with Casserly about running
the Saints. Casserly admits that two other teams have shown
interest in him but refuses to disclose them.
</P>
<P>
   League sources say one is the New York Jets. Casserly has a
close relationship with Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   It was Parcells and former Redskins coach Joe Gibbs who really
got McNair's attention regarding Casserly. They gave him glowing
recommendations, as have others in the NFL, including owners,
general managers and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly admits that he is excited about the possibility of
working for McNair. But, like McNair, Casserly insisted that no
agreement has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that Bob and I've had a chance to continue the
discussions we began last week,'' Casserly said. ``There are so
many things you have to talk about when you're starting an
organization from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important things is that we'd want to have our
scouting department up and running by June.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
