<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT DOESN'T TAKE A SHRINK TO SEE THE COWBOYS ARE CRUMBLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was in-your-face trash-talking at its most distasteful. The
fact that it was coming from the mouth of the 57-year-old owner of
the Dallas Cowboys made it that much more repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``John in Plano'' was getting a glimpse _ and an earful _ of a
Jerry Jones, the same one that normally sugarcoats every move by
claiming it's in the best interests of ``owah fans,'' rarely seen
or heard and it wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you like those three Super Bowls?'' Jones taunted, his
voice and temper rising as he outshouted the phone-in caller to
KTCK/The Ticket on the morning of Chan Gailey's firing. ``How did
you like those three Super Bowls?''
</P>
<P>
   John had had the temerity to suggest that it was Jones himself
who might be the problem with the Cowboys and that he should resign
as general manager and hire a real football man for the job.
</P>
<P>
   That, Jones said then and reiterated later that evening at the
news conference called to announce Gailey's firing, isn't going to
happen in this lifetime. He will never be just another owner,
writing checks.
</P>
<P>
   And that in a nutshell, dear fans, is why the Cowboys will
never, as long as Jones is running the show, be much better than
what they were this year. This, unfortunately, is about as good as
it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Those three Super Bowls Jones keeps crowing about? Won when not
only the Cowboys' system was different, but when the entire league
was different, before salary cap and free agency turned it into the
NML _ National Mediocrity League.
</P>
<P>
   The Team of the '90s that Jones is so proud of has won but a
single playoff game since its Super Bowl run in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There's another key ingredient missing now from those Super Bowl
teams: Jimmy Johnson (and yes, he had a heck of a lot more to do
with the third one than the guy who carried the title of head coach
at the time).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson ruined the Cowboys' job for any future coach that might
occupy that same desk because there's no way they can ever match
the reality or the myth that he left.
</P>
<P>
   His ghost may prowl the halls of Valley Ranch forever. It would
serve Jones right.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jerry would ever hire another Jimmy Johnson anyway.
Johnson provided the counter-balance to Jones' bombastic ownership
style. It was Jimmy who made the football decisions then, not
Jerry. It was Jimmy's personality that dominated the team, not the
owner's. Jones will never let that happen again.
</P>
<P>
   The predicament that the Cowboys find themselves in today was
forecast in a letter sports psychologist Dr. Don Beck of the
National Values Center in Denton sent to Jones two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an excerpt from that letter:
</P>
<P>
   ``You claim to be installing \R your\S managerial philosophy
within the Dallas Cowboys in the belief that the basic historic
functions of the traditional `head coach' have shifted into the
system itself where they are now shared rather than being deposited
in a single person. That's well and good, but this new kind of
framework can ONLY work when the CEO is not ego-driven, prefers to
stay in the background, and only acts to keep the total system
operating in a clear, efficient, effective and natural manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``...it sometimes seems you create a dysfunctional conflict
between the progressive operating philosophy you advocate and your
own `overly excitable' personality, a high-rolling entrepreneur's
need for credit, demands for personal status and visibility, and
virtual insistence that you are the Dallas Cowboys _ X's and O's,
socks and jocks, dollars and cents, hearts and minds...
</P>
<P>
   ``You have virtually transformed the Dallas Cowboys Football
Club into the Jones Family Enterprise. That is incompatible with
the very management models you claim to respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Beck's prediction has come all too true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be a forecaster of doom and gloom at all, but
the pattern is so clear,'' Dr. Beck said this week. ``He's locked
into a closed loop. As long as he runs the one-man-band syndrome,
he'll have trouble. The fault lines are designed into his system
and will continue to plague the organization in spite of his best
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, whatever you may have thought of him, never had a
chance. He became the unwitting (no jokes, please) victim of Jones'
own system, the classic scapegoat for the sins of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was fired, it would have been difficult to find a
handful of fans who weren't ready to buy the coach a bus ticket out
of town. Only Jones could make an entire nation feel sorry for
Gailey, but he managed to do so without even half trying.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Beck is right; football Camelot in Dallas is dead and gone.
As long as Jones is running the show, the Cowboys are doomed to
repeat the same mistakes over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   To be perfectly honest, we probably didn't need a sports
psychologist to tell us that.
</P>
<P>
   ``John in Plano'' already had it figured out.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
