<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MILITARY-GAYS-NY     01-15 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MILITARY-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GAY TROOPS IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sat., Jan 15:
</P>
<P>
   The British government has bowed to a ruling of the European
Court of Human Rights and ceased its ban on gays in the military.
Nearly every NATO member has now ended discrimination against gay
men and women in the armed forces. Britain's defense department,
like that of the United States, long maintained that the presence
of openly gay troops would hurt morale and discipline. But there is
ample evidence from other European nations, like France, that this
is not true.
</P>
<P>
   The British military will replace the ban on gays with a code of
conduct that applies to all service members, whether homosexual or
heterosexual. The guidelines would still allow commanders to
respond to inappropriate conduct like sexual relations between
commanders and subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's military did not make the change voluntarily. If
experience is any guide, however, lifting the ban will have little
impact on military life. Canada, which also had a ban on gay
troops, was compelled by a federal court to reverse its policy in
1992. There is no evidence that the change in policy has led to
harassment, resignations or unit breakdowns. Australia has had much
the same experience.
</P>
<P>
   The continued resistance of U.S. military leaders to ending the
compromise ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy is based on the
judgment that openly gay individuals are a risk to unit cohesion
and discipline. Yet several academic studies in recent years
examining foreign militaries and paramilitary organizations such as
fire and police departments have found no evidence that the
presence of openly gay individuals compromised performance.
Researchers have also found that even where there is a long history
of bigotry, a change in policy can be smoothly carried out when
strong emphasis is placed on conduct and compliance with clear
rules that apply to all.
</P>
<P>
   The change in British practice leaves the U.S. military nearly
alone among Western nations in its official policy of
discrimination. It is another clear indication that Washington's
attitude is behind the times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
