<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-COURTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE COZY WORLD OF JUDGES AND LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 15:
</P>
<P>
   Political patronage is so deeply entrenched in some corners of
New York state's court system that well-connected lawyers consider
it a personal entitlement to receive lucrative legal assignments
from the judges they help elect. The public got a revealing glimpse
of this sleazy culture earlier this month through disclosure of a
candid letter written by two officials of the Brooklyn Democratic
Party to protest being excluded from patronage spoils. The two
officials complained about being frozen out of legal work by
another well-connected lawyer who funneled the work to his own firm
instead, notwithstanding their ``unquestioned loyalty'' to the
party.
</P>
<P>
   The letter tacitly confirmed a longstanding arrangement under
which judges channel legal business to party leaders, undermining
the impartiality of local courts in Brooklyn. The question now is
how many judges and lawyers participate in the scheme, and whether
it involves kickbacks or other abuses. The FBI has reportedly
opened an investigation. That shows more curiosity than did
Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes, whose response to the
letter was to issue a statement handing the matter to the state
Grievance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   This week New York's chief judge, Judith Kaye, announced several
steps to identify and, she hoped, destroy pockets of favoritism and
patronage. These steps include the appointment of a special
inspector general to monitor and enforce existing court rules
against favoritism and the creation of a new panel to propose
long-range improvements in the fiduciary appointment process.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of courthouse patronage extends, of course, beyond
Brooklyn. It is practically hard-wired into the state's system of
electing judges, which fosters an unhealthy reliance on party
leaders by judges who are supposed to remain above partisan
politics. The state Legislature shows no interest in switching to a
system of merit selection. But even without that reform, there is
much Judge Kaye can do to depoliticize the courts by creating a
central system for awarding court business that is open to all
qualified lawyers, not just the well connected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
