<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF PLAYING, HORNETS AND KNICKS GRIEVE FOR PHILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ When the National Basketball Association
decided to postpone Friday night's game between the New York Knicks
and the Charlotte Hornets, it gave the Knicks a reprieve of one
game from being placed in the awkward position of playing a team in
mourning. On Saturday night, they will face Charlotte at Madison
Square Garden, as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Thursday night that included executives
from the league and the National Basketball Players Association, as
well as the Hornets representative Elden Campbell, the sides
discussed postponing Saturday's game but quickly dropped the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would probably be pushing our luck,'' said
Patrick Ewing, who, as the president of the players union, was on
the conference call with commissioner David Stern; deputy
commissioner Russ Granik; the union's executive director, Billy
Hunter, and Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we got this one, and we're going to go to the memorial
today and pay our respects to the family. Postponing it was
discussed, but they said that one would be tough. I'm glad we got
at least one.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is a change of plans at the last moment, the
Hornets will play Saturday, board a flight around midnight and
travel to the funeral for their teammate Bobby Phills, which is
planned for 1 p.m. Sunday in Baton Rouge, La. The next day, the
Hornets are scheduled to play Toronto in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   For a day, the Hornets were given time to grieve without having
to think about basketball. Friday, the Phills family, friends and
Hornet teammates were joined by the Knicks, who remained in town to
practice, at a memorial service at Central Church of God.
</P>
<P>
   It was a difficult service for a number of those who spoke.
Coach Paul Silas of Charlotte was weary with emotion after
describing the smile of Phills, his team captain, and expressing
how much of a team player Phills was when he recently asked the
coach to play him off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Hornets' vice president, Bob Bass, broke down and was
consoled at the podium as he sobbed and said, `'The bad thing is, I
never told Bobby that I loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   The expressions of respect for Phills came from every direction:
from his wife, Kendall, to the Hornets' owner, George Shinn, in the
hymn sung by the recording star Regina Bell (who is the wife of
Phills' former teammate, John Battle), and in the message delivered
by the pastors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most painful moments came when David Wesley, the
teammate who the police say was racing with Phills before his fatal
collision on Wednesday, fought off his emotions and described a
light moment he had with his close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to talk about one time,'' Wesley said. ``We were
in a golf cart coming around a hill, and we saw about three shots
of sand go up. And Bobby's still in the sand trap. All of a sudden,
the ball comes out, and it's landing next to the hole. And he's
talking about he won the hole. That's Bobby. We had some great
talks and some great times, and that's the Bobby I know.''
</P>
<P>
   There were humorous recollections, and several uplifting moments
during an inspirational sermon by the Rev. Kenneth Paramore.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he discussed God's enigma by saying, ``God, why is
there a drug dealer on my street, but Bobby is gone?'' And he ended
his sermon by saying: ``Bobby, he won. It may look like he lost,
but he won because he knows the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   More than two hours after the service began, the players,
friends and family members were dismissed. It was close to 4:30
p.m. when everyone left the church. If the game Friday night had
been played, the players would have had less than an hour to get
ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been rough,'' Larry Johnson of the Knicks said.
``I know I wouldn't have been able to focus on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the league was slow to postpone the game, it was clear
from the conversations that Stern and Granik had with the union and
Campbell that it was unfathomable for the teams to play a game a
couple of hours after an emotionally draining service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the league we should do whatever the Hornets wanted to
do,'' Ewing said. ``Those guys felt that they needed time to grieve
and get ready for the ceremony today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
