<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESURGENT NETS' NEXT GOAL IS THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When the Nets' shots were clanging off
the rim and their opponents were making unrestrained dashes to the
basket, the most encouraging aspect about New Jersey was its
seemingly secure spot in the National Basketball Association's
draft lottery. Defeating a team with a winning record appeared to
be improbable. Qualifying for the Eastern Conference playoffs
seemed impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Nets take their home floor Saturday night against
the Boston Celtics, they will be just one victory from ninth place
in the conference standing. While the top eight teams reach the
playoffs, the Nets' proximity to the final berth signifies the
tremendous turnaround that has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   After starting the season 2-15, a run of 13 victories in 18
games has reinserted the Nets into the playoff race. At 15-20, the
Nets are bunched around 9th and 10th place with Orlando, Boston and
Cleveland. In the mediocre Eastern Conference, where a sub-.500
record may get a team into the playoffs, the Nets are a mere three
and a half games out of eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good knowing that we faced a lot of adversity as a
team,'' said Stephon Marbury, who has keyed the Nets' surge with
superb play at point guard. ``We came out when it was really tough
and played hard. We've always played hard, but it was like we were
playing hard in spurts. Now we're playing 48 minutes. We're the
attackers and we're not being attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' ascension is not deceptive. While they benefited from
playing 11 of 15 games at home in December, four of their 10
victories that month came against teams that would make the
playoffs if the regular season ended today. And within the past
week, the Nets handed first-place Miami only its fifth loss in 17
home games and beat a scrappy Orlando club, proving that on the
road, the Nets could not only win but also prevail in close
contests.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Nets have righted themselves, Kendall Gill warns
that they must keep their edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to learn how to handle success, and you do that by not
being too overconfident,'' he said. ``I think we didn't know how to
handle it earlier in the year when we went 5-3 in the preseason. We
thought we were going to come out here and beat everybody like we
had been doing. Now we just have to stay humble, know that we're a
good team, but come out and play hard and know that if we don't
come to play, we'll get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from Thursday's 110-105 victory over the struggling Los
Angeles Clippers, that point has sunk in with the Nets. Even during
their recent resurgence, they displayed a disturbing habit of
losing to lesser opponents. They twice gave away fourth-quarter
leads in losing to the Washington Wizards, dropped a game to a
woeful Chicago Bulls team that was playing without Toni Kukoc, and
lost at home to the Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   If the Nets had won those games, their record would already be
above .500, and they would be tied for sixth in the conference.
Even so, there was a time not too long ago when 15-20 seemed out of
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 2-15, it was like quasi-survival,'' coach Don Casey said.
``We just had to get out of the dysfunctional state that we were
in. We've always had little goals, and one was to get to .500 by
the All-Star break, which is possible, maybe probable. But we've
got some road trips ahead of us. We could slip.''
</P>
<P>
   After his team was humbled by its poor start, Casey said he did
not worry about his club getting too comfortable with success.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are pretty resilient kids,'' he said. ``The fact is that
they stayed together when we were 2-15. There was frustration, but
there wasn't a whole lot of finger-pointing. The coaches didn't
point and say give me better players. The players didn't say give
me better coaches. We kind of stayed together, so I think they
understand the path.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
