A6792 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MIAFUNERAL-AZR &LR;      01-15 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAFUNERAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 GIS FINALLY LAID TO REST AFTER 29 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jon Eric Reid died nearly 29 years ago, but people
don't fade away easily.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on a frigid morning at Arlington National Cemetery, it
mattered little whether the Phoenix soldier perished in 1971, 1991
or even 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If only for a few moments, Army Warrant Officer ``Jake'' Reid
was back. He was summoned during a funeral service and burial
Friday by the memories of his family and his fellow helicopter
pilots who had returned home from the Vietnam War without knowing
whether he was dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   Now they know.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots looked skyward when four UH-1C ``Huey'' copters flew
in a diamond formation over the tree-covered crest where Reid, long
listed as missing in action, will be memorialized. A few of them
smiled when they heard the ``whoop, whoop'' of the rotor blades
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell some of you were going back 30 years in your
hearts and in your minds,'' Senior Army Chaplain Gilley Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid and David M. May were piloting a Huey gunship for the 48th
Assault Helicopter Company on Feb. 20, 1971, when they were hit by
enemy ground fire in Laos. The helicopter landed upright on its
skids, the tail boom broken off and the right rear burning.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the fates of Reid, May and the other two members of
their crew remained uncertain, and their families held out hope
they might have fled the wreck. In 1998, the Army excavated the
site and, last October, identified Reid and May from dental records
and DNA analysis.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of relief as about 65 of Reid and May's
relatives and friends gathered at the 612-acre cemetery, which
looks down on the nation's capital from a hill across the Potomac
River. More than 265,000 people from all military service branches
are buried there.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the coldest, clearest day of the new year, which was
somehow fitting for two families finally getting the clarity they
needed about the fates of two sons long missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today marks the end of a very long journey,'' May's family
said in a statement. He was from Hyattsville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also sadness at the finality of it all, at letting
go of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Eight members of the 3rd U.S. Infantry (``The Old Guard'')
carried the flag-draped casket containing Reid's and May's
co-mingled remains to the grave site.
</P>
<P>
   Seven soldiers fired three volleys into the air.
</P>
<P>
   A lone bugler played ``taps.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Reid's brother, Mike, and his sister, Roxena
Wotring, sat near the casket accepting the greetings of
well-wishers and the thanks of a government. They said they were
gratified that a handful of the 48th Assault Company had traveled
here to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that they were very close,'' Wotring said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were close indeed, said Richard Lester, a fellow
pilot from the 48th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found pleasure in simple things like music, mail from home,
hot chow, cold beer, a periodic cold shower,'' Lester said in
remarks prepared for an earlier chapel service closed to the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   Lester referred to the ``fog of controversy'' surrounding the
U.S. involvement in a war that millions of Americans only know
today through movies and history books. The strife and the war
protests didn't diminish the soldiers' honor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did all they were asked and, with their lives, showed
their commitment,'' Lester said. ``What more could their country
ask?''
</P>
<P>
   After the chapel service and burial were over, Mike Reid was
asked whether the formal ceremonies had contributed to a sense of
closure.
</P>
<P>
   He paused a long time, then replied, ``It helps.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
