<SLUG> BC-LETTERMAN-SURGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTERMAN HAS BYPASS SURGERY AFTER DOCTORS FIND A BLOCKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Letterman, host of CBS' ``Late Show With David
Letterman,'' had successful quintuple bypass heart surgery Friday
at New York Presbyterian Hospital, according to his publicist.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman, 52, had the emergency surgery after a test Friday
morning revealed that an artery leading to his heart was severely
constricted.
</P>
<P>
   On his show, Letterman often jokes about his cholesterol levels
and the oat bran he eats to help lower them. On Thursday, while
taping the show that was broadcast Friday night, he chatted with
Regis Philbin about the fact that he was going into the hospital
for tests.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, Letterman had an angiogram, which provides
pictures of the interior of the heart, because he has high
cholesterol levels and a family history of heart trouble (his
father died of heart disease while still in his 50s). The surgery
took place in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Late Show'' will broadcast reruns until Letterman's
return. It will be the first time that he is absent from the show
for reasons other than vacations, his spokesman, Howard J.
Rubenstein, said Friday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never missed a show since 1982. He's the Cal Ripken of
TV,'' said Rubenstein, referring to the Baltimore Orioles shortstop
with the stellar attendance record.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's surgeon was Dr. O. Wayne Isom, chairman of
cardiothoracic surgery at the New York Weill Cornell Center. He
predicted a rapid recovery, according to the statement. Isom
performed similar surgery on Walter Cronkite in 1997, and on Larry
King in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave has the heart muscle of a 20-year-old,'' Isom said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Post, Letterman's cardiologist, said in the statement
that it was too early to tell how long Letterman's recovery would
take, but that his prognosis for a full and speedy recovery was
excellent because he was in good health and exercised regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's show won Emmy Awards in 1994, 1998 and 1999 while he
was affiliated with CBS, and the show won five while he was
affiliated with NBC.
</P>
<P>
   CBS released a statement Friday that said: ``We're thrilled that
Dave's surgery went well. He is a valued member of the CBS family
and we love him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned first and foremost about his health, but we
can't wait until he's back behind his desk where he belongs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
