<HEADLINE>
LABOR DISPUTE COULD CANCEL SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The inaugural season of the Los Angeles Avengers
could be canceled because of a labor dispute between a group of
players and the Arena Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The league informed its owners it will shut down unless a group
of players withdraws its threat to file an anti-trust lawsuit
against the league.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's expansion draft, which the Avengers were scheduled to
participate in, has been postponed, along with all mini-camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ownership will not do anything with the threat of a lawsuit
hanging over their heads,'' said deputy commissioner Rod Kurpiers.
``The league cannot go forward with the threat of a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of 14 players has recently banded together in hopes of
forming an association. Players currently average between
$1,000-$1,500 per game in the league's 14-game season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the league is trying to bully the players into
forming a union and giving up their legal rights,'' said Jeffrey
Kessler, an attorney representing the association. ``The players
won't be bullied.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Avengers signed former Cal quarterback Justin
Vedder.
</P>
</TEXT>
