r s BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-BASKETBAL     01-15 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-BASKETBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARITY? NOT IN WOMEN'S BASKETBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're about at the halfway point of the 1999-2000 season. Funny,
if someone hadn't said anything, this season looks a lot like last
season. For that matter, it looks like 1997-98 or the season before
that.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the parity that was promised before the season?
</P>
<P>
   As much as I hate to crash the parity party, women's college
basketball appears to be the only thing that hoax Y2K bug actually
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is No. 1, Tennessee No. 2 and Louisiana Tech is No.
4.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's see here. UConn was ranked first for seven weeks last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee ranked second is newsworthy only because the Lady Vols
aren't No. 1. Regardless, does anyone think Tennessee won't make
the Elite Eight? It would be the first time in six seasons if the
Lady Vols didn't.
</P>
<P>
   When the final Associated Press poll was released last season,
the aforementioned three teams were in the top four. In fact, that
threesome has been among the top four at the end of every season
since 1996. Since the NCAA started women's basketball as a Division
I sport in 1981-82, at least two of those teams have finished in
the top four of the rankings eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Are we seeing a pattern yet?
</P>
<P>
   Of the teams currently ranked in the AP top 10, eight started
the season there. Among the AP Top 25, there are only two new teams
since the poll came out before the season began. The Supreme Court
has more turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Top 25 really an indication of parity? Well, it would be
a nice start.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, women's basketball is on its way to another
Tennessee, Louisiana Tech, UConn-type Final Four. Just what you
wanted, right? Another sequel to a sequel you've already seen. The
``Major League/ trilogy had more suspense.
</P>
<P>
   All the optimistic talk about parity was fueled by Purdue's
national championship last season that ended Tennessee's three-year
reign. That talk has been deposited in the ``Mavs-Win-NBA-Title''
folder.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of it is that there are still but a handful of
programs that have committed the resources for a sustained period
to build powers. Those that did _ Tennessee, Connecticut, Louisiana
Tech, Georgia and a few others _ are on a throne that doesn't seem
to be touchable.
</P>
<P>
   For all the progress women's basketball has made _ television,
professional leagues, increased participation and spending _ this
is one area that really needs help.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most appealing aspects of men's college basketball is
the ever-present threat that No. 49 could beat No. 1. It's what
makes the NCAA Tournament arguably the greatest sporting event on
the calendar. Who remembers who won the men's NCAA Tournament last
season? Maybe you don't recall, but I bet you remember that Gonzaga
was one victory away from the Final Four or the season before that
Valparaiso reached the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Now ask yourself, what really memorable victories have there
been over the past two seasons in women's college basketball?
Sixteenth-seeded Harvard winning at top-seeded Stanford in the 1998
NCAA Tournament? Duke ending Tennessee's 1999 season last March?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, but those types of upsets are rare.
</P>
<P>
   As good as women's college basketball is, until teams like Tulsa
or TCU or Eastern Michigan have at least a shot at running with the
Louisiana Techs and Connecticuts, the game is going to be missing
one key element.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise. MUSTANGS' RUCKER FINDS YOU CAN GO HOME AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   After two years of college, SMU guard D-dra Rucker finally found
that getting away wasn't what she really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Carrollton Newman Smith's all-time leading scorer played for two
seasons at San Diego State. The Left Coast, however, never worked
out. Finally, after waiting for three seasons to show off the
potential that made her a 1997 All-State selection, she is thriving
in a place where she never envisioned three years ago: home at
nearby SMU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy I made the move back,'' said SMU's junior guard.
``Had I stayed in California, I don't think I would have developed
into a complete player. It's better for me basketball- and
education-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucker is tied for the team lead in scoring at 15.9 points per
game, leads in assists (3.7) and averages 4.9 rebounds for the 8-5
Mustangs. She was named the WAC's top player for last week and
leads the conference in steals, averaging 3.2 per game.
</P>
<P>
   After coach Beth Burns left SDSU for Ohio State in 1997, Rucker
and five other players transferred. Initially, Rucker told TCU that
she would come to Fort Worth. But, she had a last-minute change of
heart and made the switch to SMU.
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence that one of the reasons she chose Fort
Worth-Dallas is because the only family member who lives in Texas,
her mother, Barbara, lives near Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom and I are really close,'' Rucker said. ``It's a big
deal that she's the only one in Texas. When I played at San Diego
State she would come to a lot of the games and now she doesn't have
to go so far.'' \Nsubheds:FAST BREAKS \Nsubheds:No kidding
\Nagatea:With her team trailing at halftime at Arkansas on Monday
night by 13 points, Tennessee coach Pat Summitt used a little truth
to inspire her team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that we can't feel sorry for ourselves \Rfor
losing to Connecticut last Sunday\S,'' she said. ``Nobody else in
America does.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols rallied for a 79-69 victory, the program's 800th
victory. \Nsubheds:It still counts \Nagatea:Victory No. 500 could
