<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE BEATS ST. MARY'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ St. Mary's center Brad Millard is so big, the
Lakers needed two scouts to evaluate him Friday against Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Millard, the Gaels' 7-foot-3 wide body with surprising athletic
ability, brought Lakers vice president Jerry West and general
manager Mitch Kupchak out to Malibu for an evening at Firestone
Fieldhouse. Clippers general manager Elgin Baylor was there too, as
were eight other NBA scouts.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a guy that's hardly played the last two years
because of a broken left foot. But when you're 7-3, as long as
you're breathing, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, West and Kupchak should have bypassed
Pepperdine and taken in a nice dinner at one of those fancy
restaurants along Pacific Coast Highway. The game was a rout _
frisky Pepperdine breezed to an easy 77-49 victory in both teams'
West Coast Conference opener _ and Millard never left the bench
while nursing an injured right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Tommie Prince and Brandon Armstrong scored 15 points each for
the Waves. Pepperdine (11-5, 1-0) held St. Mary's (5-9, 0-1) to
24.5 percent shooting on 13 of 53 shots. The Waves also forced 28
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   With numbers like that, and no Millard to look over, is it any
wonder West, Kupchak and Baylor slipped out of the arena at
halftime?
</P>
<P>
   Millard hasn't played the last three games, missing the first
because of the flu and the second while serving a suspension for
disciplinary reasons. The official word on Millard's absence Friday
was that the right ankle he tweaked in practice earlier this week
never improved. But some suggest his sour mood over a dismal season
is holding him back more than the tender ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Millard had X-rays taken on the foot Friday, which came up
negative. But he still didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his injuries and pain still in the foot, albeit the
opposite foot, we're not taking any chances,'' St. Mary's coach
Dave Bollwinkle said. ``We want to hold him back until we have a
better evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   Millard, who is expected to be a first-round pick in the NBA
draft in June, is putting up decent numbers, averaging 13.5 points
and 8.0 rebounds. Not bad considering he missed all of 1997-98 and
all but three games last year with the broken left foot. But the
strain of carrying a mediocre team is beginning to show.
</P>
<P>
   Something was bothering him Friday. He mostly just sat at the
end of St. Mary's bench, his chin in his hand and an indifferent
look on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Pepperdine cared much _ about Millard's health, mental
state or NBA future.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves were never in danger after opening a 25-10 lead midway
through the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine pushed into blowout mode early in the second half,
taking a 46-25 lead five minutes in, then survived another 15
minutes of garbage time to notch its third straight win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our defensive schemes, when they're executed well, can
create some turnover situations and steals and I thought we did
some of those things,'' Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff said.
``Sometimes a team will do a good job for a while because we're not
as crisp with our execution. I thought in the second half we
stepped it up and got some steals and we were able to break the
game open.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Greer scored 16 points to lead St. Mary's, which came away
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're one of the top three teams in the conference,
no doubt about it,'' Bollwinkle said.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine plays host to San Diego today at 4 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
