<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS STREAK ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When the mightiest winning machine in the NBA at
last sputtered and crashed, it was the smallest, most
benign-looking cogs that fouled the system and stopped the forward
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers entered Conseco Fieldhouse on Friday
carrying 16 consecutive wins. They left with a decidedly unfamiliar
feeling _ a 111-102 loss to the East-leading Indiana Pacers before
a euphoric sellout crowd of 18,345.
</P>
<P>
   And it all ended because of a pair of afterthoughts named Austin
Croshere and Travis Best. The two reserves scored 22 of the Pacers'
36 points in the decisive fourth quarter and put an end to the
longest NBA winning streak in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things,'' coach Phil Jackson noted, ``come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   This one finally did, 37 days after it started.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a month, the Lakers won and won and won, cranking
out victories like Aaron Spelling cranks out TV shows and inspiring
musings of matching the league-record 33-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Even Spelling misses now and then. The Streak was similarly
fated to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to happen at some point,'' Glen Rice said, ``and
I think the best thing we can gather from this game is we've got to
learn from it. It's definitely going to make us a stronger team. It
seems like when you have a streak like we had and you lose, you
hope that it makes the chemistry and the character on the team
stronger, and you'll be able to go out and get that streak going
again.''
</P>
<P>
   This one ended when the Lakers' vaunted defense at last failed
them in a fourth quarter, and when their trio of stars at last
failed to deliver consistent offense.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-point surge in the fourth got Rice to 20 points, but he
finished 9 for 20 from the field. Shaquille O'Neal missed his usual
close-range flip-ins for the second straight game and made just 10
of 25 shots for 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never usually miss 15 shots,'' O'Neal said. ``A lot of those
were in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Must be the Sports Illustrated jinx or something,'' O'Neal
said, referencing this week's cover that featured him.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, trying to match the output of Reggie Miller,
slipped into some old bad habits, playing wildly at times and
finishing 7 for 19 for 18 points. Miller led the Pacers with 22
points, and Jalen Rose hit 8 of 12 shots for 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think Kobe played a real heady game tonight,''
Jackson said. ``There's a lot he has to learn, experience-wise, in
this kind of an offense, as to how to use it. We didn't get the
ball back into Shaq as much as we could have in the course of the
game. But Shaq wasn't hitting his shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a 15-point game from Ron Harper and some steady
bench play, the Lakers were, as usual, in position to win.
</P>
<P>
   They led by five early in the fourth quarter before the Pacers
aided by three turnovers mounted a 15-2 run that gave them a 94-86
advantage with 5:26 to go. But Rice rattled off eight quick points,
including a pair of 3-pointers, as the Lakers cut the lead to
100-96 with 2:33 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then Croshere knocked the wind out of them with a 3-pointer, and
Bryant fouled out trying to stop Best _ a 5-foot-11 speedster who
dealt Bryant his last three fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Rice hit his final 3-pointer with 37.4 seconds left to make it a
five-point game, but the Lakers chose not to foul immediately, and
their defense failed them, as Miller put it away with a 14-footer
with 18.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew The Streak would end sometime, and the Pacers were
as good an opponent to lose to as any. But that didn't stop the
sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it bothers me. Of course it bothers me,'' Bryant said.
``I didn't want to lose for the remainder of the season. It always
bothers you when you lose. But that's fine. We'll start another
streak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
