<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ARENA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH: FULL (OF HIMSELF) ARENA?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ From afar, critics say Bruce Arena
personifies cockiness in action, emitting an aura of
self-absorbance rarely seen in his profession outside the likes of
a Pat Riley, Jimmy Johnson or Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   (But based on that trio's resumes, it's not such bad company.)
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with employers, colleagues and the media isn't
always exemplary, with occasional comments leaving some red-faced
and others seething.
</P>
<P>
   And it only gets worse for rivals, since he creates the means
for victory everywhere he goes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, as his detractors quickly point out, you can't spell the
word ``arrogance'' without using the letters a-r-e-n-a.
</P>
<P>
   But on the American sporting landscape, no coach is more misread
than 48-year-old Arena, U.S. Soccer's latest men's national team
coach. His team takes on Iran in a friendly at the Rose Bowl on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Men's soccer, you say? That sport in which the U.S takes not a
back seat but the trunk when it comes to global respect?
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's about to change. And you can thank Bruce Arena for
that. Just check the facts: He gets the job done.
</P>
<P>
   After building a dynasty of sorts by orchestrating five NCAA
Division I championships at Virginia, Arena pursued new challenges,
toting his magic wand with him as head coach of DC United in the
newly formed Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a less than memorable start _ an initial 1-6 record,
which had some critics wondering aloud if college soccer's premiere
coach could handle the professional ranks _ Arena's sides won
back-to-back MLS crowns before losing to Chicago in the title game
in the third season.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, United came to symbolize a degree of
professionalisn and attention to detail which many credit to
Arena's presence. Others envied it.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had proved himself domestically, United States
Soccer Federation officials searched elsewhere for a national team
coach to replace exiled Steve Sampson following the World Cup
debacle in France '98.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rothenberg, then president of USSF, seemed intent on
looking abroad, saying Arena lacked the ``international experience
to handle the side.'' Others within the USSF hierarchy seemed split
on the issue. Eventually, a lack of available quality candidates,
and mounting support for an American to coach the U.S., gave the
native New Yorker his chance.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. The U.S. has posted a string of quality
triumphs, including a pair of victories over Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But 2000 brings bigger challenges, with the upcoming Gold Cup
among the obstacles precluding qualifying for World Cup 2002. The
U.S appears ready for not just the periodic big win but performing
with the consistency required to gain credibility on the global
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It a great atmosphere, everybody feels like they're a part of
the team... nothing is going on behind closed doors,'' said forward
Brian McBride, a deadly aerial threat from close range on the U.S.
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce has made a tremendous difference in our mindset. He
always talks about winning games, playing to our style.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Sampson's methods in doling out playing time were
unpopular in France, coupled with a defensive-minded strategy which
arguably hindered their chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Almost to a T, players talk of the fairness and respect
permeating training-camp sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows they have a chance, so long as they perform and
work hard,'' said midfielder John Harkes, one of Sampson's notable
and second-guessed omissions from the '98 roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about the past, but everyone knows Bruce
brings out the best in players ... a plus when there's a coach
wanting to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great feeling, because we're all on the same page,'' said
Cobi Jones, the Galaxy playmaker returning to familiar confines
this week. ``You can feel the best of U.S. Soccer is coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the U.S. team is gaining the confidence found in past
Arena squads. Eventually, look for it to become an aura of
invincibility _ a fine line just short of pomposity. Setting high
standards and refusing to compromise upon them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all that's said about Bruce, he has great rapport with his
players,'' said Dallas' David Dir, recognized by many as MLS' most
outspoken coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I've never heard a player who's been with
him who hasn't respected him. There's a lot of pressure on these
guys, and his presence does a great job taking some of that
pressure of the team. And his teams are always ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't care what others might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that are around me know me and that's the only thing I
feel that's important,'' said Arena in addressing his image. ``It's
important that the coaches and players I work with are treated
fairly and that we have respect for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Followers say Arena's philosophy has tempered somewhat over the
years. Part of it comes from enduring life's challenges. Eleven
years ago, Arena lost his twin sister Barbara to breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That helped me in terms of keeping perspective,'' he said.
``It told me that your time is numbered and that you always need to
do the right thing. I just try to make sure I am always doing the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, inflammatory incidents occur, such as the indelible
locker- room image last year when the former United coach was
heavily toking on a victory cigar after a victory over the Galaxy
in MLS Cup '99.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, for one, expressed views to a reporter
that Arena's actions were ``inappropriate'' considering he was now
the national team coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If L.A. would have won, I'd be smoking a cigar in their locker
room,'' said Arena without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't diminish the fact (United's) a team I was part of for
a number of years and was very friendly with, but I would have
celebrated and congratulated L.A. had they won.''
</P>
<P>
   If the current trend and past successes are any indication,
Arena might very well be lighting a few more victory cigars in the
future, possibly in the nations of Japan and South Korea sites for
the 2002 World Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
