<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON LIKES JORDAN'S POSSIBLE RETURN AS EXEC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Even in a suit and tie, Michael Jordan's return
to the NBA will be good for the game, and for Jordan. So says his
former coach.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson spoke with Jordan on Monday in Los
Angeles just days before it became public that the former Bulls
star was negotiating to join the Washington Wizards. Jordan is
expected to become the top executive for basketball operations and
a part-owner. The deal follows his failed attempt to purchase an
interest in the Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really encouraged him last year in the Charlotte
situation,'' Jackson said. ``I think Michael's competitiveness,
what he likes to do, his love of basketball, the association
between the NBA and Michael Jordan _ all those things, I think,
would be great for him....
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to enjoy it, and it's going to be tough,
and it's going to be intriguing, and it's going to be something
that grabs a hold of him because he's so competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   It could also provide a much-needed boost to a sorry franchise.
The Wizards have a bloated payroll, underachieving talent and no
track record to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been associated with so many things that have been
successful, that it's hard not to feel like he's going to be part
of something that's successful there,'' Jackson said. ``I'm sure
for the players it's a good feeling....
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take him time. He'll make some mistakes, like
any other business, and learn from it and he'll do well. He's got
an eye for the kind of thing he wants to have done. He's had good
coaching from... Dean Smith (at North Carolina) and a good
organization with the Bulls. I think he'll have a good
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Masked man: Robert Horry wore a transparent mask to protect his
broken nose and admitted he's not yet used to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be odd (wearing it), but I think after a while,
I'll start playing and I'll forget about it hopefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Horry isn't sure how long he'll have to wear the awkward-looking
mask, but he's not worried about his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I'm married. I don't need to look good,'' he said. ``I'm
just mad that I can't paint it and do like the Road Warriors used
to do on WWF.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep thinker: Jackson is known for educating his players by
giving them books, and his first gift to O'Neal is something by
philosopher Friedrich Nietzsche. Which book?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not telling,'' O'Neal said. And when did he get it?
``Can't tell you. Can't tell you how me and Phil operate.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal promised to share his impressions once he's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to read it first, so I can get the quotes ready,'' he
said. ``I want to read the book, memorize it, analyze it,
dissecticize it and then come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
