<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN MARINO LACKS CRAFTINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dan Marino is at the stage of his career where you
wish football pants came with pleats, or at least a skosh more room
in the hip and thigh. Age and stretch fabrics are not kind to
Marino's 38-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   The beginnings of middle-age spread, and the braces and bandages
that bind his tortured knees and ankles, disfigure what was a
classic quarterback's silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, his right arm seems to have gone to flab, apparently an
effect of the neck injury that cost him five games last fall. The
man who has thrown for nearly 10,000 yards more than anybody else
in NFL history is only the 31st-rated passer in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   These days, as the game's most awesome tools rust away, he must
rely on savvy to help the Miami Dolphins win games. The trouble is,
that's not Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen Marino referred to as the ``sentimental favorite'' in
these NFL playoffs, because he's the greatest player of his era
never to win a Super Bowl and because he has hinted at an imminent
retirement. Today's AFC divisional playoff against the Jaguars in
Jacksonville could be his last game if the Dolphins lose.
</P>
<P>
   We are supposed to see him in the image of creaky, crafty
quarterbacks from Norm Van Brocklin to John Elway, pitching their
teams to victory without their best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Marino, though, has never played that role or inspired that kind
of sentiment. It's the price he pays for being a little too
talented to love, too loudly demanding of his fumble-fingered
receivers, too stubborn in the application of his enormous ability.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine, a Dolphins fan as well as a Boston Red Sox
fan, calls Marino the Ted Williams of football. Williams refused to
hit to the opposite field, preferring to try to blast baseballs
over or through shifted infields. Marino, too, doesn't set out to
do the little things that separate the gifted athlete from the
masterful, believing he should always be able to connect with even
a double-teamed receiver.
</P>
<P>
   That refusal to acknowledge his limitations might be a reason
for Marino's enormous numbers. His regular-season pass completions
have totaled 11 miles.
</P>
<P>
   That self-confidence might also explain the seemingly
inexplicable _ 17 seasons, 10 playoff appearances, eight Pro Bowls,
but only one Super Bowl and no Super Bowl rings. Ted Williams never
won a World Series either.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs, crime and attitude aren't the only ways to squander great
athletic talent. Another is to rely on it so much that you're
imprisoned by it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Marino doesn't care about winning, or cares more
about personal statistics than about the scoreboard. It's just when
it comes to figuring out ways to win, he can't see beyond the tips
of his passing fingers.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, he had the arm to pull it off, to approach his
own perfectionist standards and to make the Dolphins contenders all
by himself. Now he has trouble hitting the broad side of Dan
Marino, and without craft to fall back on, his plunge has been
precipitous.
</P>
<P>
   The years since run-oriented coach Jimmy Johnson joined the
Dolphins in 1996 have brought a clash of giant personalities. Last
week, before they faced the Seattle Seahawks in the wild-card
playoff round, the two men put their heads together and simplified
the offense, conserving Marino's arm for the pivotal final drive.
</P>
<P>
   It worked and the Dolphins scored an upset 20-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder if Marino would have a ring by now if
Johnson had come along before the quarterback was set in his ways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
