<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SECURITY (Moscow) _ Underscoring its darkening view of
the West, the Kremlin issued a new national security strategy that
inveighs against an expansionist Europe and United States and
contemplates the use of nuclear weapons in war ``if all other means
of resolving the crisis have been exhausted.'' The revised language
governing nuclear weapons is a subtle but unmistakable change from
the previous strategy that allowed the use of nuclear arms only
``in case of a threat to the existence of the Russian Federation.''
By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-SPACE (Seoul, South Korea) _ Having succeeded in making
computer memory chips, consumer electronics and automobiles, South
Korea has set its sights on a far loftier goal: conquering outer
space. The government plans to develop a rocket capable of ferrying
satellites into orbit within the next five years. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-SOLDIERS (Geneva) _ The United States, which wants to keep
the option of sending soldiers into combat at 17, found itself with
few allies in negotiations this week on an international agreement
to set a new minimum age for recruitment and active military
service. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-SPAIN (Madrid) _ A Spanish magistrate will ask Britain
to conduct a new medical exam on Augusto Pinochet, the former
Chilean dictator, with Spanish doctors taking part, according to a
lawyer for victims of the Pinochet regime. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Nozhai-Yurt, Russia) _ To be sure, many
officers and soldiers in the Russian army are still atheists, and
the attitude of many of them toward chaplains appears to be neutral
at best. But the ties between the military and church have
strengthened in recent years. More than 100 churches and chapels
have been established on Russian military bases, according to The
Moscow Times. And Russian draftees can request service in a unit
that has a priest, though it is not always honored. By Michael R.
Gordon. (With map and photo.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-BORDER (Kursumlija, Yugoslavia) _ The Serbian chief
of police here looks weary. For him the war in Kosovo is not only
not over, but it has come closer. He says Albanians from Kosovo are
crossing the border into his district in the adjacent part of
Serbia and attacking villagers and the police. By Carlotta Gall.
(With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYC-DEATHRATE (New York) _ For some reason, people in New York
City died at a remarkably higher rate during the first week of this
year compared to the same period in 1999: Perhaps the suspense of
seeing of computers malfunction proved just too alluring given the
alternative of a funeral. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINA-PRIMARIES (Atlanta) _ Alerted to the closing of polling
places in black neighborhoods during South Carolina's last
Republican presidential primary, the Justice Department has begun
asking pointed questions about both parties' coming primaries,
political officials around the state said Friday. The inquiry
raises the possibility that the primaries could be challenged by
the government under the Voting Rights Act. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   RAPE-PSYCHOLOGY (Undated) _ Rape is primarily a crime of
violence and power, not sex. Or so a generation of social
scientists and feminist scholars have argued. But in a forthcoming
book, two evolutionary scientists say this view is born of
ideology, not science, and is ``based on empirically erroneous,
even mythological, ideas about human development, behavior and
psychology.'' By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-IMAGE (DES MOINES, Iowa) _ In the race for the
Democratic presidential nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley has
tried to cast himself as his party's gruff truth-teller. But he can
be curt and uncommunicative, and former colleagues have said he is
aloof. To his supporters, traits like these are part and parcel of
what make Bradley a different kind of politician. But to the
undecided voters who are vital to his success, Bradley runs the
risk of being viewed as simply surly. By James Dao. (With photos)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IMAGE (Washington) _ Despite three debates this month and
dozens of campaign speeches, Gov. George W. Bush remains something
of a muddle: authoritative and insightful one day, hazy or scripted
or platitudinous the next. He has performed well enough not to
diminish the strong likelihood that he will cinch the Republican
presidential nomination. But he has left unanswered the question of
just how potent an adversary he would be for the Democratic
nominee. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-HISPANICS (San Jose, Calif.) _ The Republican party is
making a big push for Hispanic votes. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
