   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-ABORTION (Washington) _ Adding an abortion case to its
docket for the first time in eight years, the Supreme Court agreed
Friday to decide whether a Nebraska law banning a procedure the
state calls ``partial birth abortion'' is constitutional. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-FUNDS (Washington) _ Hospitals in New York and seven
other states will be spared cuts in Medicare payments under a
decision announced Friday by the secretary of Health and Human
Services, Donna E. Shalala. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-SAFETY (Washington) _ President Clinton announced a program
on Friday to encourage airline pilots to report their own rule
violations, in exchange for immunity from punishment, to make it
easier for the government, the airlines and the pilot unions to
detect trends that could hurt safety. By Matthew L. Wald. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   DP-CAMPS (Washington) _ The story of the DPs, as they were
called, is one that is little remembered today, but it is a
remarkable chapter of the Holocaust era and is the subject of a
three-day conference that began here on Friday night: ``Life
Reborn: Jewish Displaced Persons 1945-1951.'' By Joseph Berger.
(With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-FAST-TRADES (New York) _ Investing in the stock market
for the long term, the strategy that has made the most sense and
the most money for people over the years, is all but dead. And new
numbers show the betting has become faster and more furious there
than at any time since the 1920s. The rapid-fire trading mentality
of a very small group of hyperactive investors has altered the
behavior of large numbers of investors. The consequences are large,
since studies show that investors who trade frequently get lower
returns, and heavy trading contributes to wide swings in the
market. By Gretchen Morgenson. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   GLAXO-SMITHKLINE (London) _ Two British pharmaceutical giants,
SmithKline Beechham PLC and Glaxo Wellcome PLC, are near agreement
on a $80.7 billion merger that would create the world's largest
drug maker, executives close to the talks said here Friday night.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-APPOINT (Undated) _ David Glass, who aggressively
expanded Wal-Mart Stores Inc. from a rural discounter into a
worldwide powerhouse during his 12-year tenure as chief executive
and president, announced Friday that he would step down
immediately. As expected, he will be succeeded by his long-trusted
lieutenant and chief operating officer, H. Lee Scott. By Leslie
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TOURISM (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Determined to
dispel the myths that surround it, South Africa has turned to
Madison Avenue. This month, the country makes its first major foray
into the world of international marketing with an $18 million
promotional campaign. Its emphasis is on enjoying South Africa's
exotic outdoor attractions and urbanity rather than experiencing
the opening of a door to a new multiracial democracy. By Henri E.
Cauvin. (With graphic.)
</P>
