<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN--MARATHON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Marathon forecast: Warm, humid, slow
<TEXT>
<P>
   Runners bracing for balmy conditions
</P>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Sunday promises to be a pleasant day for viewing the Methodist
Health Care Houston Marathon. But not a pleasant day to run it.
</P>
<P>
   Marathoners do not like balmy weather. They want it cold _ low
40s would be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   And without those chilly conditions, there is little chance of a
record being set in the race that begins at 8 a.m. Sunday in front
of the George R. Brown Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have to be good conditions to have a
record,'' said Nicole Carroll, the No. 2 women's seed for the
26.2-mile event. ``It would have to get a bit cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kaitany set the course record in 1989 with a run that
took 2 hours, 10 minutes, 4 seconds. The women's record, 2:27:51,
was established by Ingrid Kristiansen in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   For a record to be broken, four factors seem essential: a
top-quality field, a fast pace, incentive and chilly weather.
</P>
<P>
   This race seems to have three of the four.
</P>
<P>
   The field looks stronger than last year's. Sammy Maritim, who
finished second to Stephen Ngundu the past two years, is seeded
only seventh this time.
</P>
<P>
   Maritim expects the pace to be faster than it was last year,
when his fellow Kenyan, Ngundu, won with a time of 2:14:56.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of rabbits in the race now,'' Maritim said,
``and that will make it faster. Believe me, this will be a very
fast race. We have the best pace-makers we've ever had. Godfrey
Kiprotich will lead the fast group.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiprotich, who also is from Kenya, never has raced here. He is
unlikely to win, but if he sets a brisk pace, everyone else will
have to run faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will see after the first five kilometers how the race is
going,'' said Ngundu, 32. ``If other runners are aggressive, I will
be aggressive, too. If the pace is hot, you adjust yourself and
push to the front. I want to be at the front. You can't let
yourself get too far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of incentive for a record pace. A bonus of
$50,000 will go to any man or woman who breaks the record in his or
her division. That money will be awarded in addition to the
first-place prize of $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact this is an Olympic year brings additional
incentive. Many runners need a fast time to win an invitation to
the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   But still, there is the problem with the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the weather is cold and we can make a fast pace,'' Ngundu
said at a news conference Friday, ``there could be a record.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked if he could run a 2:10 on a warm day, he
grinned and said, ``It's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't say it's likely.
</P>
<P>
   Said Carroll, who is from Brisbane, Australia: ``From where I
come from, this is a bit of a cold snap. Brisbane is very humid.''
</P>
<P>
   She never has run in Houston and wasn't planning to be here to
challenge Ukraine's Tatiana Pozdnyakova, winner of last year's
women's open and No. 1 seed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll intended to run in Osaka on Jan. 31, but a red-tape
snafu kept her from entering that race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is the biggest marathon around right now,'' she said,
``so that's why I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maritim is fond of this course and sees a trend in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year (1998) I was behind by one minute,'' he said.
``The second time I was behind four seconds. This time I don't
know. I changed my schedule of training, and I think it will
help.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks he has overtrained in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I'll try to be smart, and I will be well-rested,''
he said. ``I feel better now than I did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But how about the weather?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the weather is a bit warmer than last year,'' he
said. ``I'd rather it be cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Could he set a record?
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
