<SLUG> BC-NY-COLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLD WIND BLASTS AWAY BALMY CLIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The parkas, earmuffs, gloves and itchy wool scarves
finally came out of the back of the closet Friday, as New Yorkers
accustomed to this winter's balmy weather were served up an
Arctic-inspired reminder that a) the city is not in a tropic zone
and b) it is the middle of January.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions Friday _ with the temperature dropping to 13
degrees in Central Park and the wind gusting to 37 miles per hour _
were far from records for New York. But after three months of
temperatures that were warmer than any recorded along the
Northeast, the sudden and intense cold was more than enough to
cause a collective shiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is brutal,'' said Antonio Pedoto of the Bronx, who had the
unfortunate assignment of serving a nine-hour shift Friday as a
flag man at a construction site in Midtown Manhattan. ``I can't
stand still.''
</P>
<P>
   Commuters offered similar assessments, as they scurried from
buses, subways and cabs to building lobbies, coffee shops or other
places of refuge. ``My face aches,'' said Camille Parson, a ballet
dancer, as she walked along 23rd Street Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the sudden plunge in temperatures was a mass of
Arctic air that moved through central and eastern Canada in recent
days, pulled by the modest snow storm that passed through the city
on Thursday, said Fred Gadomski, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania
State University. The wind and cold together meant a wind chill
factor of about 15 degrees below zero during the morning rush
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures should begin to rise again by early Saturday,
Gadomski said, reaching perhaps as high as 40 degrees by Sunday.
But by early next week, the colder air will return, and another
storm system already streaking east from the northern Mississippi
Valley toward New York threatens to leave the region with the
season's first measurable snowfall, Gadomski said. The outlook for
the coming weeks, he said, is likely to involve more drastic ups
and downs in temperature.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's freeze _ the temperature never rose above 22
degrees _ the Rockefeller Center outdoor ice-skating rink was
nearly empty early Friday, and the normal crush of tourists lining
up outside the Times Square television studios, like MTV's, all but
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The cold front produced a small surge in homeless people's
turning to city shelters, said Olga Beck, a spokeswoman for the
Department of Homeless Services. A total of 6,860 single adults
stayed in the city's 44 single-adult shelters on Thursday night, up
about 100 from the normal count, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Peter's Place, a drop-in center for homeless men and women in
the basement of a church on West 23rd Street, about 70 people
gathered late Friday afternoon, playing dominos, dozing in their
chairs, leafing through newspapers or watching ``The People's
Court'' on a large-screen television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alternative to this would be either I go to jail or I die
out there,'' said Augustus Griffin, 65, who, like many of the other
guests, kept his hat and coat on even while inside the daytime
shelter. ``I can't survive in that cold.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
