<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-IRAN-SOCCER-LADN     01-15 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SOCCER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IRAN SOCCER MATCH MATTER OF PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Harrison Sheppard  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES, Calif., -- The United States vs. Iran soccer match
Sunday at the Rose Bowl represents a thaw in the two nation's icy
relations, but to local Iranians it's a hot ticket, a chance to
express ethnic pride and focus attention on repression in their
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Iranians in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, many of whom fled
their country after the 1979 Islamic revolution, said they plan to
root for the Iranian national team -- but may sit while the anthem
of the current regime is played.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those rare times that Iranians here can speak
out about human rights in Iran,'' said Bijan Khalili, director of
Van Nuys-based Ketab Corp., which publishes a weekly Iranian
newspaper and the Iranian Yellow Pages. ``They're going to sing the
real Iranian national anthem. They're going to bring the real
Iranian flag, which Iranians used for 3,000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County is home to one of the largest populations of
Iranians outside Iran, with estimates up to 500,000, including an
estimated 100,000 to 150,000 in the San Fernando Valley, according
to Iranian organizations and community members. The highest
concentrations are in Tarzana, Encino and Reseda, as well as Los
Angeles' affluent Westside communities, particularly Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 people are expected at Sunday's game, including a
large Iranian-American contingent. A substantial Armenian presence
is also expected to watch the under-23 American team play the full
Armenian national team following the main event.
</P>
<P>
   Most Iranians here have never had a chance to see their national
team in person, so the game represents a once-, or at least first-,
in-a-lifetime opportunity to watch their heroes in action.
</P>
<P>
   It also presents larger opportunities, such as the chance to
dispel stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 20 years, we've been called and branded all kinds of
names, including terrorist,'' said Behrooz Afrakhan, a journalist
in Tarzana who will cover the game for Iranian-language television.
</P>
<P>
   ``With soccer, which is an international means of communication,
we are trying to not only express our passion for it and support
our players, but say to the world, Look at us, we are civilized, we
have a great history and we are law abiding.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohsen Naderi-Nejad, who produces an Iranian talk show out of a
house in Northridge, plans to distribute about 55,000 paper flags
with the pre-revolution Iranian banner on one side and the Stars
and Stripes on the other. He plans to hand them out in the Iranian
community before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The flags, he said, represent a symbol of friendship between the
two peoples, if not their governments. The money to print them,
about $5,000 to $6,000, came from donations by the local Iranian
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell the American people we appreciate your
hospitality,'' Naderi-Nejad said. ``We came to this country and you
gave us a lot of opportunity, especially to our kids. We are
friends, we are not enemies. We are separate from the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition match occurs as the icy relations between the two
nations have begun to very slowly thaw. The United States severed
diplomatic ties with Iran after militants took hostages at the U.S.
Embassy in Teheran in 1979. But Reformist President Mohammad
Khatami, elected in 1997, has called for a ``crack in the wall of
mistrust'' between the two nations and encouraged cultural
exchanges at a nongovernmental level.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the U.S. played Iran in the World Cup in France, a
match universally praised for its good sportsmanship. Later that
year, the two countries hosted each other's wrestling teams. Some
observers, and team members, hope such athletic events will achieve
the same results as did the ``pingpong diplomacy'' between the
United States and China in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope by coming here ... it will help in some way to bring
the two governments to one table, face to face, to talk to each
other and solve their differences,'' said Jalal Talebi, the
director of Iran's national soccer teams and its former World Cup
coach. ``It would give each other a chance to respect each other's
rights, religion and culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's exhibition match grew out of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of focus on the politics and the perceived
tensions (before the game), but it turned out to be one of the
great events of France '98,'' said Jim Moorhouse, communications
director for the Chicago- based U.S. Soccer Federation.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA, the ruling body of international soccer, even presented
both teams with its Fair Play Award. The U.S. Soccer Federation
then decided to propose a friendly game in this country to continue
the spirit and rivalry -- and to try for some sporting revenge for
being knocked out of the World Cup by the 2-1 loss to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Soccer Federation officials said security will be tight at
the game, just as it is for any other large soccer game at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And those who wish to make political statements or
demonstrations can do so in a large grassy area set aside near the
main entrance of the stadium, a standard practice for soccer games,
said Emilio Pozzi, managing director of U.S. events for the
federation.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards will not censor any signs or displays brought
into the stadium, as long as they conform to size and safety
requirements. Generally, flags must be no larger than 2 feet by 3
feet, and sticks, poles and umbrellas are prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they don't impede traffic flow or disturb another
patron that has bought a ticket, they can display anything they
want,'' Pozzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Andy Samuelson contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
