r a BC-TAINTED-SCHOOLS-LADN     01-15 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAINTED-SCHOOLS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA SCHOOL BOND PANEL WANTS $40 MILLION REFUND
</HEADLINE>
 -LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Greg Gittrich  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES, Calif., -- Los Angeles Unified administrators sunk
as much as $40 million of local Proposition BB bond money into a
failed school construction project on contaminated land in South
Gate, bond oversight officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And the bond oversight committee wants the money back.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Soboroff, chairman of the citizens oversight committee,
said the panel signed off on the use of the local bond money after
assurances from district administrators that 40 acres of industrial
property in South Gate could be cleaned up. Those assertions were
obviously incorrect, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us all kinds of documentation to us to show that the
school supposedly could be built,'' said Soboroff, a mayoral
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not going to use the money, if the school cannot
be built, we want the money back,'' he said. ``The taxpayers want
their money back.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, most of the money -- at least $25 million -- has
already been spent.
</P>
<P>
   The district could recoup some of the money by selling the land
contaminated by industrial pollution, but school officials said
it's unclear if it can get back the entire investment.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller said he is anxious
to see documentation of the exact promises the district made to the
bond oversight committee when use of the money was approved two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was well before the current management was in place,''
Miller said. ``This site never was environmentally clean and could
not have been made to be so.''
</P>
<P>
   The district's former administration used the bond money to
purchase dozens of tainted parcels adjacent to the Los Angeles
River. State bond money also may have been used to buy some of the
land.
</P>
<P>
   According to Barry Groveman, co-chairman of the district's
special safety team, the district began condemning property in the
area in the early 1990s. Other acquisitions are still pending and
the district would likely face litigation if they backed out of the
deals.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Groveman, who is running for district attorney,
revealed that the vast majority of the property was purchased
without adequate environmental assessments, despite claims to the
contrary by district administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he reported that LAUSD real estate and construction
officials never obtained reliable estimates on how much it would
cost to clean up the land.
</P>
<P>
   The findings came on the heels of the Belmont Learning Center
scandal and contributed to the school board's decision to oust
Superintendent Ruben Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted on Tuesday to abandon the construction of the
South Gate campus, which was to include a high school and
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the land will likely be sold, but noted the district
is required by state law to clean up the property.
</P>
<P>
   The Proposition BB oversight committee is scheduled to discuss
the use of the bond money for South Gate at its meeting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The oversight committee was established in early 1997 as part of
the $2.4 billion bond's guidelines to win support for the measure.
Concern over how the money would be spent had prompted voters to
reject a similar bond measure in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
