<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-ECON-REVIEW-     01-15 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ECON-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL, WHISTLING PAST THE NEW ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUNCIL BLUFFS, Iowa _ When America Online and Time Warner
announced the biggest merger in history last week, it set off a
furious, if predictable, debate that swept through the airwaves,
chat rooms and hyperactive financial markets, which couldn't decide
if it was a brilliant idea or a marriage made in cyberhell.
</P>
<P>
   Is it good for the country, many asked, for a single media
conglomerate that already bestrides the print and cable world to
also control America's most popular entrance ramp to the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Will it further widen the technological gap between rich and
poor?
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean for America's relations with its allies, who
are increasingly uneasy with the nation's dominance of the Net?
</P>
<P>
   And are these matters that Washington should wade into, as it
did in the Microsoft case, or should they be left to the invisible
electronic hand?
</P>
<P>
   All interesting questions _ except out here on the campaign
trail. America may be plunging into a new global economy at warp
speed, but the major presidential candidates would rather talk
about ethanol subsidies than the future of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans and Democrats alike it's Old Economy 101,
perhaps because times are so good, perhaps because the politics of
the New Economy are far too complex for a slogan, perhaps because
even Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, admits that events are
moving so fast that nobody can truly understand what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't ask about it much because we've filled up all
that empty office space downtown,'' said Midge Leiter, a
47-year-old Democrat who came to a Rotary meeting in Portsmouth,
N.H., on Thursday to hear Gov. George W. Bush. ``Health care is the
big issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the candidates get a bigger earful on managed
care and access to medical insurance than on any other subject. But
it's also remarkable how little is said about the huge range of
potential political issues raised by the explosion of the digital
economy since the last presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Log on, and you are barraged with arguments about the privacy of
electronic records, the wisdom of keeping the Internet tax free,
the national security implications of super-encrypted messaging
that can protect your credit card data or be exploited by
international terrorists. And then there is the thorny issue of
whether the government should play a role in making sure technology
does not further widen the divide between the wealthy Net-savvy of
the world and the digitally deprived.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the dizzying changes in the electronic economy
that leave the candidates mute. Many of the biggest foreign policy
crises that Washington has faced in the past decade have been
rooted in the turmoil that can roil the global markets, from
Russia's economic implosion to the financial meltdowns that struck
Mexico and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests six weeks ago at the World Trade Organization
meeting in Seattle had the chief effect of underscoring to
politicians how potent the issues raised by economic globalization
have become, both in America and abroad. And the politicians'
response has largely been to drive around the whole thing like it
was a bad neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Among the candidates, for example, only Gary Bauer has raised
questions about China's imminent entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's foreign policy speeches have dealt at length with the
traditional issues of the 1980s and early '90s _ national missile
defense, Iran and Iraq, peacekeeping _ but when he got a question
from a voter in New Hampshire last week about how he would have
handled the near-collapse of a huge hedge fund 16 months ago, he
stumbled, then erroneously said that the Treasury had bailed out
the wealthy investors. (He quickly corrected himself after
questions from two reporters, acknowledging that private investors,
not the taxpayers, had bailed out the fund.)
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore may be more comfortable dealing with
questions about the global economy: after all, he participated in
all the administration's midnight meetings about how much to aid
Russia, whether to rescue the Mexican peso and how to keep the
Asian upheaval from spreading to American shores. But as one top
economic aide says, he is ``scared to death to open his mouth'' on
these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame him?
</P>
<P>
   The administration's all-out push to get China into the WTO has
angered labor unions at the very moment Gore most needs their
support. Trade agreements that fail to require other countries to
enact environmental protections have driven a wedge between Gore
and his favorite constituency. His foray into government regulation
of the export of encryption software put him at odds with Silicon
Valley _ at least until last week, when the administration backed
down and dropped virtually all controls on such exports.
</P>
<P>
   And just the mention of Russia, Gore knows, invites the
Republicans to ask uncomfortable questions about what happened to
America's multibillion-dollar ``investment'' in converting Russia
to capitalism with taxpayer-financed ``enterprise funds,'' which
Gore once proudly hailed. Actually, it's no wonder he'd rather talk
about managed care and saving Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed in eight years is that globalization is a
reality, and it's a very controversial reality,'' said Mickey
Kantor, President Clinton's former trade representative and
commerce secretary. ``Economic change has run way, way ahead of the
politicians, and they don't know how to get a handle on it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly the first time.
</P>
<P>
   During the presidential campaign of 1908, when steel and
railroad trusts were a national preoccupation and J.P. Morgan
played the role of Bill Gates, everyone ran on a
don't-mess-with-a-good-economy platform. Then one day William
Jennings Bryan, the Democratic nominee, argued that ``public
ownership is necessary where competition is impossible.'' He
quickly backpedaled, but Wall Street and the business community
decided he was unfit to run the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4860 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-ECON-REVIEW-     01-15 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ECON-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL, WHISTLING PAST THE NEW ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUNCIL BLUFFS, Iowa _ When America Online and Time Warner
announced the biggest merger in history last week, it set off a
furious, if predictable, debate that swept through the airwaves,
chat rooms and hyperactive financial markets, which couldn't decide
if it was a brilliant idea or a marriage made in cyberhell.
</P>
<P>
   Is it good for the country, many asked, for a single media
conglomerate that already bestrides the print and cable world to
also control America's most popular entrance ramp to the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Will it further widen the technological gap between rich and
poor?
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean for America's relations with its allies, who
are increasingly uneasy with the nation's dominance of the Net?
</P>
<P>
   And are these matters that Washington should wade into, as it
did in the Microsoft case, or should they be left to the invisible
electronic hand?
</P>
<P>
   All interesting questions _ except out here on the campaign
trail. America may be plunging into a new global economy at warp
speed, but the major presidential candidates would rather talk
about ethanol subsidies than the future of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans and Democrats alike it's Old Economy 101,
perhaps because times are so good, perhaps because the politics of
the New Economy are far too complex for a slogan, perhaps because
even Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, admits that events are
moving so fast that nobody can truly understand what they mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't ask about it much because we've filled up all
that empty office space downtown,'' said Midge Leiter, a
47-year-old Democrat who came to a Rotary meeting in Portsmouth,
N.H., on Thursday to hear Gov. George W. Bush. ``Health care is the
big issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the candidates get a bigger earful on managed
care and access to medical insurance than on any other subject. But
it's also remarkable how little is said about the huge range of
potential political issues raised by the explosion of the digital
economy since the last presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Log on, and you are barraged with arguments about the privacy of
electronic records, the wisdom of keeping the Internet tax free,
the national security implications of super-encrypted messaging
that can protect your credit card data or be exploited by
international terrorists. And then there is the thorny issue of
whether the government should play a role in making sure technology
does not further widen the divide between the wealthy Net-savvy of
the world and the digitally deprived.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the dizzying changes in the electronic economy
that leave the candidates mute. Many of the biggest foreign policy
crises that Washington has faced in the past decade have been
rooted in the turmoil that can roil the global markets, from
Russia's economic implosion to the financial meltdowns that struck
Mexico and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests six weeks ago at the World Trade Organization
meeting in Seattle had the chief effect of underscoring to
politicians how potent the issues raised by economic globalization
have become, both in America and abroad. And the politicians'
response has largely been to drive around the whole thing like it
was a bad neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Among the candidates, for example, only Gary Bauer has raised
questions about China's imminent entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's foreign policy speeches have dealt at length with the
traditional issues of the 1980s and early '90s _ national missile
defense, Iran and Iraq, peacekeeping _ but when he got a question
from a voter in New Hampshire last week about how he would have
handled the near-collapse of a huge hedge fund 16 months ago, he
stumbled, then erroneously said that the Treasury had bailed out
the wealthy investors. (He quickly corrected himself after
questions from two reporters, acknowledging that private investors,
not the taxpayers, had bailed out the fund.)
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore may be more comfortable dealing with
questions about the global economy: after all, he participated in
all the administration's midnight meetings about how much to aid
Russia, whether to rescue the Mexican peso and how to keep the
Asian upheaval from spreading to American shores. But as one top
economic aide says, he is ``scared to death to open his mouth'' on
these issues.
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame him?
</P>
<P>
   The administration's all-out push to get China into the WTO has
angered labor unions at the very moment Gore most needs their
support. Trade agreements that fail to require other countries to
enact environmental protections have driven a wedge between Gore
and his favorite constituency. His foray into government regulation
of the export of encryption software put him at odds with Silicon
Valley _ at least until last week, when the administration backed
down and dropped virtually all controls on such exports.
</P>
<P>
   And just the mention of Russia, Gore knows, invites the
Republicans to ask uncomfortable questions about what happened to
America's multibillion-dollar ``investment'' in converting Russia
to capitalism with taxpayer-financed ``enterprise funds,'' which
Gore once proudly hailed. Actually, it's no wonder he'd rather talk
about managed care and saving Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's changed in eight years is that globalization is a
reality, and it's a very controversial reality,'' said Mickey
Kantor, President Clinton's former trade representative and
commerce secretary. ``Economic change has run way, way ahead of the
politicians, and they don't know how to get a handle on it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly the first time.
</P>
<P>
   During the presidential campaign of 1908, when steel and
railroad trusts were a national preoccupation and J.P. Morgan
played the role of Bill Gates, everyone ran on a
don't-mess-with-a-good-economy platform. Then one day William
Jennings Bryan, the Democratic nominee, argued that ``public
ownership is necessary where competition is impossible.'' He
quickly backpedaled, but Wall Street and the business community
decided he was unfit to run the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So it's not too surprising that no one in this year's race dares
to wander far from the siren song of the markets.
</P>
<P>
   They are all free traders, promising to destroy trade barriers
overseas, but mindful of Greenspan's message that surging imports
keep inflation in check. (In congressional races, however, where
workers at a local factory can form a large and angry voting bloc,
trade is often still hotly debated.)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, everyone is foursquare in favor of letting
entrepreneurship flourish. But does the AOL-Time Warner deal
encourage innovation and easy access to the Internet for all, or
squash it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too early to judge,'' Bush said carefully when
asked _ for this article _ on Friday. ``It's important for people
in public positions to be mindful of what could happen in access to
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor Gore _ nor the other candidates, for that
matter _ have ventured far into the murky waters of the Microsoft
case, and have taken particular care not to address the question of
whether the company should be broken up, much as Standard Oil was a
century ago, or AT&AMP;T in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is changing too rapidly,'' said Bush, who added,
``I haven't paid that much attention about the details.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are probably wise to be cautious. While the
tycoons owned the trusts, lots of steelworkers and secretaries have
Microsoft in their 401(k) plans. Worse, the terrain keeps changing.
A week ago Microsoft was the biggest gorilla on the block. Now,
assuming the AOL-Time deal comes together, there will be two
gorillas battling for content and distribution, meaning the market
may set up a better competitive fight than the courts ever could.
The fact is, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   But it might be refreshing to determine if Democrats and
Republicans had a different approach to ensuring the privacy of
computerized records, an issue the Supreme Court touched on last
week when it barred states from selling data on drivers' licenses.
</P>
<P>
   And it would be interesting to hear competing plans for bridging
the digital divide. Years ago, when utilities stayed neatly within
state and national boundaries, the government made sure that basic
telephone service reached even the more remote and impoverished
outposts. Does a similar plan make sense for the Internet? And who
should pay to wire up villages in India and ghettos in Brazil _
their own governments? American foreign aid? The World Bank?
AOL-Time Warner?
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the candidates wooing Silicon Valley for cash are
steering clear of such discussions. Instead, they talk about
keeping the Internet tax free, at least for a while, even though it
is not entirely clear why a sale that takes place over the Net
should be treated differently than one that takes place over the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley's attitude is that they just want government as far
away from the Internet as possible,'' an adviser to Gore said the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   So for the next few months at least, it's back to the Farm
Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
