<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      01-15 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Jan. 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-REFUGEES (Knin, Croatia) _ Almost five years after
Croatia promised to allow refugees from the Yugoslav wars to return
to their homes here, the authorities still put endless obstacles in
the way of many of those who want to come back. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-POLITICS (Santiago, Chile) _ On paper, the choice that
nearly eight million Chilean voters face on Sunday could not be
starker. Ricardo Lagos, an austere Socialist and the man President
Salvador Allende Gossens had picked as his ambassador to Moscow
before he was overthrown and killed in 1973, is the candidate of
the center-left coalition that has governed for the last decade.
His challenger is Joaquin Lavin, an ebullient conservative who
started his political career in Gen. Augusto Pinochet's planning
ministry. But one of the many surprises of this tightly fought race
has been how Lagos has run to the right and Lavin has run to the
left. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUG-COSTS (United Nations) _ As more international
attention focuses on an AIDS epidemic spreading out of control in a
number of sub-Saharan African countries and India, France is
prodding the United Nations to find ways to make cheaper drugs
available to poor countries, where treatment is beyond the means of
most people who need it. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-DOLLAR (Quito, Ecuador) _ Just a week ago, President
Jamil Mahuad of Ecuador appeared to be finished, the only
uncertainty about his fate being whether he would resign or be
forced from office by a coup. But by announcing that he intends to
replace the local currency with the American dollar, he has
seemingly gained assurance that he will survive to face at least
the next crisis. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-HEALTHCARE (Montreal) _ When Canada's state-run health
system was in its first bloom, in the 1970s, Americans regularly
trooped up here on inspection tours, attracted by Canada's promise
of universal ``free'' health care. Today, however, few Canadians
would recommend their system as a model for export. By James
Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GOLAN (Katzrin, Golan Heights) _ With the revival of the
Israeli-Syrian peace effort after a nearly four-year stalemate, the
Golan Heights has entered a state of flux. On the surface, the
apparatus of opposition to any Israeli concession of the Golan can
be seen revving its engine, as with a mass rally that the settlers
sponsored in Tel Aviv last Monday. But beneath the surface, a quiet
psychological and practical preparation has begun. By Deborah
Sontag and William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CHECYNYA-GEORGIA (Mozdok, Russia) _ The war in Chechnya has
exacerbated the strains in Russia's relationship with Georgia, a
former Soviet republic. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Despite nuclear tensions and
diplomatic false starts that have dogged U.S. relations with India
in recent years, the Clinton administration plans to court India as
an ally in trying to restart global trade talks that collapsed in
Seattle last month. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TALKING-CARS (Detroit) _ Later this year, hundreds of thousands
of drivers will be able to have conversations with their cars. Tell
the car to get on the Information Superhighway, and it will
download e-mail using relatively slow cellular phone connections. A
computerized ``voice'' will be able to read the e-mail through the
car's stereo speakers, automakers say. It will call out sports
scores on command, not just when a radio station programs them. It
will quote the latest stock prices. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIME-WARNER (New York) _ The journey to last week's
announcement that America Online would buy Time Warner in history's
largest merger began last fall and included secret meetings in New
York and Boston and a key dinner on Jan. 6 at the home of Steve
Case, the chairman of America Online. But the turning point for the
deal came over the New Year's holiday in solitude of the small
library of the Vermont vacation home of Gerald Levin, the chairman
of Time Warner. By Steve Lohr and Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   HEROIN-STRATEGIES (Seattle) _ Larry W. Campbell, chief coroner
of British Columbia, where deaths from drug overdoses have risen
tenfold in the last decade, to 407 last year, said he came to a
conference in Seattle this week for one reason. ``There are ways to
prevent these people from dying,'' Campbell said, ``and I'd like to
learn more about them.'' By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA-COMMISH (Philadelphia) _ Up from Dublin by way of a
street beat in the South Bronx and a prodigious rise to the No. 2
spot in the police hierarchy of New York City, John Timoney is
obviously in control as he completes his second year as
Philadelphia commissioner. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CUBAN-EMIGRES (Miami) _ Tune out the racket, and what
emerges from the feud over the political custody fight over the
6-year-old Cuban boy Elian Gonzalez is a split among Miami's
700,000 Cuban-Americans over U.S. trade and immigration policies,
as well as fatigue with both the old guard's myths of the
pre-revolutionary Cuba and its plots to rout Castro and go back to
take the island. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-BLACK-VOTERS (Atlanta) _ When the Democratic presidential
candidates finally withdraw from Iowa and New Hampshire, where the
electorate is predominantly white, they will move quickly into
Southern states where black voters often play a decisive role. And
at the moment, at least, Vice President Al Gore seems to enjoy a
commanding advantage with African-American voters. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-NOTEBOOK (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Should Iowa and New
Hampshire be allowed to dominate the early going in the nominating
process?; A Kennedy stirs the political waters; A call for action
on matters of faith; A Virginia Democrat thinks independent; Are
term limits the final answer? By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DEBATE (Des Moines, Iowa) _ The debate of the Republican
presidential candidates. By Rick Berke.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-APPEAL (Washington) _ Across his 17 years in Congress,
John McCain has had a rock-solid conservative voting record except
for his defiance of his party leaders on campaign finance overhaul
and anti-tobacco legislation. Yet on the campaign trail, McCain's
passions are more populist than traditionally conservative as he
bashes ``lobbyists in $1,000 suits'' or criticizes Gov. George W.
Bush's tax cut as too skewed toward the rich, saying that he does
not think Bill Gates needs a tax cut. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FAA-NEWSTYLE-JET (Washington) _ Under a decades-old rule,
charter operators follow one set of guidelines, and corporate jets
follow another. But a new class of owners has suddenly blossomed
that does not fit either category, and that is causing an uproar in
aviation safety circles. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Rudy's Washington cheat sheet. By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bill Gates: master of the game. By
Paul Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 2
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 p.m.
