<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CAMPAIGN-INTERPERSONA     01-15 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-INTERPERSONAL-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE PRIMARIES, RUNNING IS NOT A TEAM SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Backstage before the recent Republican presidential
debate in South Carolina, John McCain was yukking it up with his
new friend Gary Bauer when George W. Bush finally showed up _ late,
as usual, and with a Texas-sized security detail. In walked a crowd
of Texas Rangers _ the kind with badges, not baseball bats _
talking into their sleeves about the imminent arrival of the
governor while the other candidates rolled their eyes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to his laid-back image, Bush seemed nervous, wound a
little tight, as he has before several of these events. In a snub
that might have been inadvertent, he stepped in front of Bauer to
have a word with McCain _ the only opponent he sees as a peer,
according to one Bush adviser. Orrin Hatch, whose antipathy for his
Senate colleague McCain is well known, was nonetheless greeting
each of the candidates perfectly correctly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, whom Bush in particular ``doesn't have much use
for, and sees as an interloper,'' according to a Bush adviser, was
staring at the ceiling. And finally, with just minutes until air,
Alan Keyes _ whom the others view mostly ``as an entertainment
dimension,'' according to another Republican adviser _ arrived with
his own security detail, and stood alone for the brief moment
before local party officials lined them all up to wait for the show
to begin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The usual, and usually forced, civility between the candidates
breaks down occasionally even in public. But behind the scenes, the
surprise is not that their exchanges are so nasty _ they aren't _
but that their relationships are so complicated and, even in this
heavily scripted, goal-oriented environment, so personal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Hatch, who has fought a number of Senate turf wars with
McCain, jokes about having been on the wrong side of the McCain
temper, it is with unmistakable feeling. After Forbes sat next to
McCain while they were getting their TV makeup put on before a
joint appearance, he complained that he never, ever wanted to be
put in that position again, and apparently hurt McCain's feelings a
little. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a social conservative who has been tough on Bush during
debates, seems almost poignantly open to a real, and not just a
political, friendship with the governor. ``When there were reports
last week that Bush was annoyed that I had asked him a question
four times in a row in the debates,'' he said in an interview,
``his staff made a point to let me know that not only was that not
true, but that Bush really likes me.'' After he needled Bush to
clarify his position on abortion at a recent debate, he then turned
to him off camera and whispered, ``Good answer.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, issues and ideology seem as irrelevant to the
candidates in choosing their friends as voters say they are in
choosing a candidate. And in the Democratic race, Bill Bradley and
Al Gore, two Ivy Leaguers who share a passion for policy and agree
on a host of issues, probably won't be brunching in this lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   When he was in the Senate, Bradley told at least a couple of
friends that he thought Gore was hypocritical, a phony of the first
order, and in recent debates has done nothing to hide his disdain.
The vice president has gone on referring to Bradley as his friend _
at least until their chat on ``Meet the Press,'' when Gore put out
his hand, offering to shake on a pledge to stop running ads _ and
Bradley stared at it with a look that said, ``Ewww, cooties.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who those around him say rarely mentions Bradley at all,
one way or the other, has again and again called his opponent a
``good, decent man,'' though Bradley does not seem to have been
able to bring himself to return the compliment. ``I agree; I am a
good person,'' he said at one point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Bradley's put it this way: ``They never clicked
politically, stylistically or personally and have nothing in
common. And saying he's a good, decent man is like saying, `Oh,
Bill Bradley has all of his limbs.' I wouldn't return the
compliment, either.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vice president does not seem to be taking it to heart. ``He
really does not get bent out of shape about exchanges like that,''
said his daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff. But for Bradley, it does
seem personal _ in part, friends say, because of his experience as
a tough athletic competitor, and in part because he categorically
refuses to mask his real feelings in any setting. ``He won't hide
his feelings beholding something he thinks is absurd or silly,''
said Robert Reich, the former labor secretary, who has been
advising Bradley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, as the campaign has gone on, McCain's attitude toward
Bush seems to have cooled. ``McCain has real doubts that Bush is up
to the job, and you see that in the body language sometimes,'' said
William Kristol, a friend of both Bauer and McCain who was Keyes'
roommate at Harvard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the candidates who really are friendly, but
have no political reason to advertise the fact, usually don't. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bauer, for instance, have hit it off this year. And
McCain, who despite his moderate following has quite a conservative
record, spent last Fourth of July weekend with Annette Bening and
Warren Beatty, who considered running himself, apparently because
he didn't see a true liberal in the race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the ideological opposites Bauer and Bradley are friendly
acquaintances, having met several times back in Bradley's Senate
days. ``We did establish a little bit of a relationship and we wish
each other well,'' Bauer said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush was once quoted as calling him a ``twerp,'' Bauer
says he has since grown genuinely fond of the Texas governor. When
Bauer was in the middle of a mini-scandal last fall over having had
private meetings with a young female aide, both Bush and McCain
went out of their way to be supportive. At a joint appearance,
according to a Bush aide, Bush pulled Bauer close and whispered,
``You hang in there; I know it's garbage and never believed it for
a moment.'' Of course, as the aide added, ``he knows he's going to
need those people when this is all over.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bauer seems to feel hopeful that even in the craziness and
intense pressure of a presidential race there is room for the
unexpected, uncalculated wild card of human feeling. ``There's just
a human dynamic,'' he said, ``that arguing long distance is
different from standing next to someone and taking their measure.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the context of a campaign, relationships ultimately do
not hinge on who likes whom _ or who doesn't. ``George Bush doesn't
like or dislike people; he respects them or doesn't,'' said an
adviser. ``He may not like a guy, but if he respects his
accomplishments, it's OK.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the adviser also says it is not McCain whom Bush sees as the
true threat, but Forbes, who is willing to spend vast amounts of
money to go negative, as he did against Bob Dole in 1996. ``A lot
more of our strategic decisions, like doing the Iowa straw poll and
waiving the matching funds,'' the aide said, ``were about not
letting Forbes do to us what he'd done to Dole.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And in politics, that's still the ultimate compliment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0042 </DOCNO>
