says he has since grown genuinely fond of the Texas governor. When
Bauer was in the middle of a mini-scandal last fall over having had
private meetings with a young female aide, both Bush and McCain
went out of their way to be supportive. At a joint appearance,
according to a Bush aide, Bush pulled Bauer close and whispered,
``You hang in there; I know it's garbage and never believed it for
a moment.'' Of course, as the aide added, ``he knows he's going to
need those people when this is all over.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bauer seems to feel hopeful that even in the craziness and
intense pressure of a presidential race there is room for the
unexpected, uncalculated wild card of human feeling. ``There's just
a human dynamic,'' he said, ``that arguing long distance is
different from standing next to someone and taking their measure.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the context of a campaign, relationships ultimately do
not hinge on who likes whom _ or who doesn't. ``George Bush doesn't
like or dislike people; he respects them or doesn't,'' said an
adviser. ``He may not like a guy, but if he respects his
accomplishments, it's OK.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the adviser also says it is not McCain whom Bush sees as the
true threat, but Forbes, who is willing to spend vast amounts of
money to go negative, as he did against Bob Dole in 1996. ``A lot
more of our strategic decisions, like doing the Iowa straw poll and
waiving the matching funds,'' the aide said, ``were about not
letting Forbes do to us what he'd done to Dole.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And in politics, that's still the ultimate compliment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6859 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-FOOTBALL-MATH-REVIEW-     01-15 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-MATH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FOOTBALL, 6 PLUS 2 OFTEN EQUALS 6 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (DUPLICATION NOTICE: this has also moved in the `s' category as
FBN-MATH-REVIEW)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Professional football coaches often make more than $1 million a
year. They work long hours, sometimes sleeping in their offices,
looking for a small edge that will give their teams a victory and a
chance to advance to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But when faced with a crucial decision during close games, many
coaches make a mistake that a middle-school math student might
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   The problem comes when a football play known as the two-point
conversion collides with a mathematical principle known as expected
value. Expected value is the average result, over the long term,
that somebody can expect to see from a given decision. On the roll
of a die, for example, it is 3{ _ the average of the numbers 1
through 6.
</P>
<P>
   Adults use the concept, knowingly or not, when they make
decisions about which insurance policy or mutual fund to buy. And
as statistics has become a much larger part of math teaching in the
last decade, expected value problems are popping up in state
curriculums and on standardized tests. Many football coaches, it
seems, could use a few review sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Week after week, after scoring a touchdown, teams try to add two
points by running or passing the ball into the end zone from the
two-yard line, rather than take the safer route of kicking it
through the goalposts for one point. Bill Parcells, the New York
Jets' coach this season, did it against the New England Patriots,
and the Jets ended up losing a game that most likely kept them out
of the postseason. Two college coaches did it over New Year's
weekend; at least one game hinged on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The two-point conversion has been part of the college game for
decades, but the National Football League, looking to add
excitement, adopted it only in 1994. Coaches usually try for the
conversion when they think that one point is of little import but
two would make a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Behind by five points to the Patriots in the third quarter,
Parcells went for two, hoping to pull within three points, the
value of a field goal. The difference between trailing by four
points and five points, on the other hand, seemed trivial. Coaches
even carry laminated cards on the sideline, telling them what leads
and deficits should cause them to go for two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the card and blow it up!'' said Phil Simms, the former
New York Giants quarterback who is now a commentator for CBS
Sports, offering a bit of advice to coaches. ``Too often, teams use
it too quickly, and it ends up costing them at the end.'' Because
it fails so frequently, Simms said, the two-point conversion play
should usually be reserved for the very end of games, when the lost
point cannot come back to haunt a coach.
</P>
<P>
   An expected-value calculation, in which one multiplies the
chance of success by the value that success would bring, echoes the
point. In the NFL this season, two-point attempts worked 37 percent
of the time. So the expected value of a two-point try was 0.74, or
74 one-hundredths of a point: 0.37 (the success rate) times 2 (the
value of a successful attempt). The expected value of an extra
point, by contrast, was about 0.94, since the kicks are good about
94 percent of the time and a successful kick is worth one point.
</P>
<P>
   The statistical difference is significant, and it really does
cause teams to lose games. The Jets, for instance, missed their
two-point try, forcing them to make another one later on, which
they also missed. Had they scored the extra point both times, the
Patriots would not have been in position to kick a last-second
game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequently, coaches will do something that is in direct
violation of the laws of probability,'' said Harold Sackrowitz, a
statistics professor at Rutgers University. He has designed an
alternative card that has columns for both the score and how much
time is left in a game.
</P>
<P>
   A good contrast to the two-point conversion is basketball's
three-point shot, which turns out to be a worthy risk, all else
being equal. Most pro teams make the long-distance shot about
one-third of the time, giving it an expected value of about 1 (.33
x 3). Regular, two-point shots go in the basket about 45 percent of
the time, for an expected value of .9 (.45 x 2).
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of expected value go far beyond sports. In state
lotteries, the expected value of a $1 ticket is often less than 75
cents, because the government keeps so much of the initial pot. In
other words, people who play the lottery every day can expect about
a negative 25 percent return on the investment over their
lifetimes. Casino games often have similarly grim expected values.
And investors use expected values when studying the historical
returns of mutual funds to decide which make sense, depending on
when the money is needed.
</P>
<P>
   So if anybody is looking for an excuse to plop down in front of
the playoff games, think of it as a chance to make a case study of
basic statistics. As strange as it may sound, watching the Vikings
and Rams and the Titans and Colts smash helmets could help a
teen-ager get into college or an adult make a wise financial
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0045 </DOCNO>
