<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6863 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ARMY-REVIEW-NY     01-15 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARMY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA FIGHTS STALINIST BATTLES WITH AMERICAN TACTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since Russian troops launched a new offensive against Chechen
rebels four months ago, U.S. military officials have watched
closely to see if the Russian commanders would avoid the mistakes
they made during their disastrous 1994-1996 campaign. Could they,
as promised, match the U.S. successes last year against Serbia and
against Iraq in 1991, using technological and tactical superiority
to crush a weaker enemy, while minimizing losses and maintaining
popular support?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, it seems, is no.
</P>
<P>
   For U.S. commanders and military analysts, this second Chechen
war has revealed more about Russian strengths and weaknesses than
any spy satellite ever could. And for officials in Washington and
across Europe, the insights are in a way reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty Red Army that many once feared could roll across the
plains of northern Europe today cannot even contain an insurgency
within its own borders. Moreover, even as Russian tactics evolve,
the military and political leadership appear locked strategically
in the Soviet age, said U.S. officials. Even though Russia no
longer has a so-called command society, in which a Stalin can order
many thousands of Chechens to forcibly move to another province, as
he did in 1944, Russian leaders still act as if they can rule with
an iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   In Chechnya, that means fighting a war at great internal and
external cost, instead of pursuing a political resolution that
effectively manages an old ethnic division.
</P>
<P>
   In the haphazard transition to democracy under Boris Yeltsin,
conventional forces bore the brunt of downsizing and shrinking
budgets. Priority was given to the strategic nuclear force, which
today is Russia's only real claim to status as a military power.
Russia still has a standing force of 1.5 million troops, slightly
larger than the one maintained by the United States, but the budget
will be only $4 billion this year, compared with the Pentagon's
$284 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Russians have had to rely on Soviet-era weapons
and equipment, and the troops are chronically untrained, underpaid
and underfed. Draft dodging is rampant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're learning is that a lot of the recent commentary
about the state of the Russian military is pretty accurate, and
that is that it is in pretty lousy shape,'' said Mark N. Kramer, a
senior fellow at the Davis Center for Russian Studies at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Russians seemed to have learned some lessons
from the last Chechen war, said U.S. military officials. When that
conflict began in 1994, some 30,000 Russian troops raced in to
smash the revolt, only to suffer enormous losses, including some
3,000 dead, when they tried to quickly seize Grozny, the rebels'
stronghold and the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a real black eye the first time around by charging to
the train station and stopping to eat supper and getting ambushed
and losing a regiment early on,'' a U.S. general said. ``Although
the war dragged on for nearly two more years, they never recovered
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   After their defeat, Russian commanders shifted the bulk of their
resources to ``first to fight'' divisions, according to a U.S.
defense official who closely monitors the Russian military. Those
units, including the Russian special forces, have led the ground
assaults in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders have also improved their tactics, attacking
far more deliberately and with greater force, American officials
said. An estimated 100,000 Russian troops marched systematically
through northern Chechnya, seizing the countryside and gradually
encircling Grozny, cutting off 6,000 rebels there and another 6,000
in the southern mountains. The American general said that in this
campaign the Russians were exhibiting better command and control,
effectively coordinating complex operations.
</P>
<P>
   They have also made extensive use of air and missile strikes and
artillery bombardments, minimizing the exposure of ground troops to
deadly firefights with dug-in rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Robert Scales, the commandant of the U.S. Army War
College, said this concern over casualties, which badly eroded
public support during the first war, has been one of the most
striking changes in Russian military doctrine in decades, showing a
new sensitivity to the military's need for civilian backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Soviet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian command has also adopted another tactic from NATO's
Kosovo war, mounting a public-relations blitz to rally popular
opinion. They have strictly controlled battlefield reports and
grossly downplayed losses. (The U.S. defense official said the
Russians had underreported losses threefold, which means there are
probably more than 1,000 dead already.)
</P>
<P>
   The Russian offensive began to go awry, as before, when
commanders finally ordered an assault on Grozny on Christmas Day.
Despite three months of bombardments, Russian troops encountered
fierce resistance from rebels dug into a network of fortified
trenches and bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russian troops counterattacked, their offensive now
appears in disarray, raising doubts in the minds of American
analysts about whether the Russians can defeat the Chechens. ``The
Chechens are an enemy that's incredibly tough, prepared to fight
and die for their cause,'' said Scales. ``The Chechens are not
Iraqis.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense official who specializes in the Russian military
predicted that the offensive would fail. He cited the Russians'
military shortcomings, but also their failure to realize the
underlying cause of the conflict: the Chechens' historic
unwillingness to accept political domination by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've learned tactical lessons,'' the official said.
``But I don't think the political leadership or the military
leadership in Russia has learned the strategic lesson. Chechnya is
not a military problem, and it is not subject to a military
solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1146EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
