<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6864 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-REVI     01-15 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO LEAP ACROSS THE POLITICS OF RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ Mixing race and politics, everyone
knows, often produces a volatile brew. But in South Africa, racial
politics are the only politics. Despite all the talk of
reconciliation and transformation during the first five years of
democracy here, that reality remains virtually unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Whites vote for whites. Blacks vote for blacks. The apartheid
laws that separated the races for decades have been swept from the
books, but the divisions they engendered still define the ballot
box.
</P>
<P>
   Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a white man jolted the nation when he announced that
he might leap across the racial and political divide and urged
other whites to think like him. The high-jumper was none other than
Pik Botha, the long-serving foreign minister for the apartheid
regime, the oppressor and opponent of black liberation _ and maybe
soon, he says, a card-carrying member of the African National
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afrikaners, whites should support the ANC,'' Botha, 68, told
the country in a series of newspaper, television and radio
interviews about his plans to join the party that had led the
resistance to apartheid. ``We cannot just continue with blacks
voting ANC and whites voting for the opposition. I want to break
with the racist attitudes of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   And as black party leaders gasped with delight and white party
leaders howled with dismay, the thick political walls between the
races suddenly seemed less sturdy and it suddenly seemed reasonable
to wonder: Which way will white voters go in the new South Africa?
Is this country finally ready to move beyond the politics of race?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer, clearly, is no. Most whites voted decisively
against the ANC in last year's presidential election. But Botha's
willingness to even consider joining the ANC hints at a shift in
mind-set _ if only a modest one _ among some whites as they ponder
their political futures here.
</P>
<P>
   Botha says they have no choice. He warns that if whites, who
make up only about 10 percent of the population, continue to vote
along the color line, they will find themselves relegated to tiny,
powerless parties.
</P>
<P>
   Such parties, while vigorous guardians of minority rights, lack
the power to make policy on issues, like crime and affirmative
action, that preoccupy whites.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Botha argues, joining the ANC would offer
whites a real voice in policy-making and in the selection of
policy-makers. (And some political analysts say that if blacks were
to join the traditionally white political parties, it might give
those parties greater legitimacy to challenge the ANC, offering the
country more of a true multiparty flavor instead of what exists
now, a largely one-party state.)
</P>
<P>
   The ANC government's increasingly centrist philosophy has at
least made such conversations possible. Whites no longer fear that
ANC leaders are all closet Communists, ready to nationalize
industry and seize white land. In fact, the government's fiscally
conservative policies have left behind its partners among the
unions and the Communists as government officials take a tough
stance on wage negotiations and push ahead with privatization
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Botha commended the country's current economic policies and
reminded his fellow whites that it was the ANC that supported a
liberal constitution that protects minority rights, property
rights, civil liberties and Afrikaans as an official language. But
Botha is not your average white man. He has always been a bit of a
maverick, even during the decades when he served the white
government. In the 1980s, he stirred a furor by predicting that
South Africa would someday have a black president. And when that
day arrived, he served under President Nelson Mandela until his own
National Party withdrew from the government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   For most whites, however, joining the ANC is simply unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pik Botha is right when he says this is the key to
normalizing politics,'' said Bob Mattes of the Institute for
Democracy, a nongovernmental organization that surveys public
opinion on politics. ``But leaders moving over is just the tip of
the iceberg. It's not like Pik Botha takes all those people with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Just watching the new government redress some past inequities
makes some whites jittery. More government money and attention is
directed toward blacks now than in the old days when whites
absorbed the lion's share of the government's attention and had the
best jobs, land, schooling and neighborhoods. Now, as the
democratic government spreads the wealth more equitably, those
white privileges are disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Thabo Mbeki, the new president, seems less preoccupied
with racial reconciliation than was his predecessor, Mandela. Mbeki
stresses foreign investment, delivery of services to the poor and a
commitment to help other predominantly black countries in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   And some political analysts warn that even if whites were to
join the ANC in significant numbers, there are no guarantees that
they would have much clout, particularly in a government that
stresses affirmative action and black empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   The party that some believed offered the best hope for
multiracial membership, the United Democratic Movement, has fallen
victim to organizational and financial difficulties and, some say,
racial bickering. Where else to call home? Only the ANC, insist its
loyalists, pointing to its long history of racial inclusion and
prominent white members, who include the current ministers of trade
and industry, and water and forestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are being converted,'' the ANC spokesman, Smuts Ngonyama,
said of whites. ``Even our slavemasters, like Pik Botha, they are
getting converted by the wisdom of the former slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-boiled conservatives roll their eyes at such talk and
deride Botha as a political opportunist long out of touch with his
own people. But even the conservative press seemed reluctant to
slam the door on the possibility that white hearts might be warming
toward South Africa's most famous liberation party.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial last week one newspaper, The Citizen, recalled
Botha's knack for sensing the shifting political winds. ``When Mr.
Botha predicted in 1986 that South Africa would one day have a
black president, how many whites believed him?'' the editorial
read. ``Never say never in politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0055 </DOCNO>
