<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6865 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TALKING-CARS-NYT &LR;      01-15 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKING-CARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING, ONLINE CARS GIVE NEW MEANING TO `INFORMATION
SUPERHIGHWAY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A new era is dawning for automobiles. Later this year,
hundreds of thousands of drivers will be able to have conversations
with their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Tell the car to get on the information superhighway, and it will
download e-mail using relatively slow cellular phone connections. A
computerized ``voice'' will be able to read the e-mail through the
car's stereo speakers, automakers say. It will call out sports
scores on command, not just when a radio station programs them. It
will quote the latest stock prices. It will even be able to check
the traffic and give directions.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million cars and trucks in the United States are
expected to have this conversational capability by the end of the
year, using voice-recognition software to translate drivers' words
into a limited list of computer commands. That is not quite enough
to surf the Internet, but enough to splash in it.
</P>
<P>
   Some marketing experts are skeptical about the need for this
innovation, even if it can be made to work properly. ``Most people
don't want to talk to their car,'' said Jack F. Trout, president of
Trout &AMP; Partners, a marketing strategy firm based in Greenwich,
Conn. ``They want their car to shut up and drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, auto executives are forging ahead. Some Americans
have always used their cars as living rooms, dining rooms and
offices, and they expect this to be no different. Just as
cupholders allowed drivers to sip coffee during their commutes,
executives say, these devices will allow them to work on their way
to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within three years it will be in all of the new vehicles that
we're doing,'' Jac Nasser, Ford Motor's chief executive, said here
last week at the North American International Auto Show, where many
of the talking cars were shown. ``We will do nothing short of
transforming our cars and our trucks into a portal for the
Internet.'' Ford's first talking cars will be the 2001 model year
Lincolns, on sale by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The first General Motors Internet-connected talking vehicles
will roll out of factory doors in a few months, and by year's end,
more than 400,000 cars, sport utility vehicles, pickups and
minivans will be ready to talk back to their owners, said Todd R.
Carstensen, a company spokesman. Many other automakers are rushing
to get their versions ready by next year, if not sooner. One
supplier, Delphi Automotive, already has $2.5 billion in orders
from seven automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Providing Internet access is one of a series of moves by
automakers to add safety and entertainment features _ and the added
charges they bring. Many minivans now come with video screens that
allow passengers in the back seat to watch movies. Some Ford and GM
cars are already equipped with wireless connections to operators
who can give directions, make dinner reservations or call a tow
truck, tracking the car with a global positioning satellite system.
If an air bag deploys, operators can send an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Voice-recognition technology is intended to give motorists
access to computers without requiring drivers to type and steer at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vehicles have to be safe,'' said Lawrence D. Burns, vice
president for research, development and planning at General Motors.
``Driving requires your eyes on the road and your hands on the
wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers will not be able to do many of the things they can do on
their home or office computer, and they will not get results as
quickly because of limits on the vocabulary of the
voice-recognition systems and the relatively slow speed of the
cellular Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the GM and Ford versions will not be able to send
e-mail. Ford's voice recognition software would understand just 200
words. While the systems are intended to be simple to use, Ford
drivers would need to know they should say ``get e-mail'' or ``read
e-mail'' and not just ``e-mail'' to cue the system, which listens
for verbs, or ``tell me the NPR news'' to hear National Public
Radio's latest Internet report.
</P>
<P>
   The system is by no means foolproof. If a backseat driver
interrupts, a Ford's ``voice'' is likely to pause, then utter a
patient-sounding ``say that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Voice recognition in cars ``is really just in its toddler stage
now,'' said Richard F. Doherty, director of research for
Envisioneering, a technology assessment and market research firm in
Seaford, N.Y. ``It is somewhere between being a great show-me
gimmick and a convenience, and it is getting closer to being a
convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Since most people keep the same car for years, automakers are
trying to design communications systems that can be updated as
better technology becomes available. So instead of equipping each
car with a computer that would be outdated almost as soon as it
made it out of the factory, Ford and GM plan to install cellular
communications equipment that links cars to land-based computers
that can be updated as new technology becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet cars would then use cellular phone connections to
link up to an Internet home page preprogrammed with the driver's
preferences for traffic, weather, news and stock reports, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, on the other hand, plans a ``bring your own
laptop'' approach. ``How many phones do you want to deal with? How
many Internet accesses?'' asked Robert J. Eaton, DaimlerChrysler's
vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to install a small screen, microphone and
cellular phone modem in its vehicles sometime within the next two
years. Drivers would then plug in their own equipment, said Stephen
J. Buckley, a DaimlerChrysler electronics specialist.
</P>
<P>
   While no manufacturer has yet set prices on the devices, the
bulk of revenue is likely to come from monthly wireless connection
and Internet access fees, with expected charges of $7 to $75 a
month. With that, drivers could turn on the ignition, tune in to
the Internet, and drop out of the boredom of commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Talking cars have been produced before. In the mid-1980s,
Chrysler New Yorkers would tell drivers ``your fuel is low'' or
``your door is ajar'' or ``fasten your seat belts.''
</P>
<P>
   But the car was a nag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd hear it all the time, and if you didn't address the
issue right away, it would go on and on and on and drive you
crazy,'' said Steve Aretakis, the president of Hasco Spring
Industries in Oak Park, Mich., who suffered through a couple of
years of driving a 1984 New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Aretakis isn't holding his breath for the latest Internet
version of the talking car. ``I haven't had a car since like
that,'' he said. ``I don't really know if I'd want one, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MONUMENTS-LEGACY-REVI     01-15 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONUMENTS-LEGACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAND RUSH: CLINTON PUTS SOME SPACE BETWEEN HIS PRESIDENCY AND
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In late 1998, during the darkest hours of the Clinton
presidency, while friends and foes in Washington obsessed about
whether a sexual affair would force a sudden change in tenants at
the White House, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt began sending
notes to President Clinton about the final years of another
president.
</P>
<P>
   Look West, Babbitt advised, just as President Theodore Roosevelt
had done at the turn of the century. With the stroke of a pen, TR
used a 1906 law called the Antiquities Act to set aside pieces of
the American back yard for the ages _ protected as a national
monument. Clinton could do the same, using the same legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And he has. Chasing Roosevelt's ghost, Clinton arrived at the
wind-chapped lip of the Grand Canyon last Tuesday, exactly 92 years
after Roosevelt went to the same spot. Roosevelt hiked; Clinton
arrived by helicopter. But their intent was the same: using the
power of the presidency to establish a personal legacy that would
outlast that transitory power.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Clinton designated three new national monuments
and expanded a fourth. He has now set aside more federal land _
outside of Alaska _as monuments than any other president. More than
2.7 million acres of federal land, or an area about twice the size
of Delaware, has been given new monument status, which restricts
development while aiming to keep the area in a wild state for
perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even lame ducks have wings,'' said Babbitt after leading
Clinton on a tour of rust-colored high ground in Arizona, newly
enshrined as the Grand Canyon-Parashant National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little that any president facing a hostile
Congress can do to change the course of domestic events in his last
months in office. One major exception is the environment. The
Antiquities Act gives a president power to confer eternal
protection on a piece of the public domain as ``an object of
historic and scientific interest.'' Land that has been given
monument status may no longer be used for any purpose or in any way
that would change its character. That is, if the land has
traditionally served as grazing territory, or been hunted or
fished, such use might be continued. On the other hand, logging,
mining or off-road driving would be forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Of late, Clinton has signaled his intent to use the Antiquities
Act like a golfer who has just discovered the power of a titanium
driver. He is likely to designate another half-dozen national
monuments, protecting desert land in Oregon, coastal cliffs in
California, the river banks that Lewis and Clark explored in
Montana and ancient Indian sites in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with a one-year-old executive order that brought to a
halt all new road building on 40 million acres of National Forest
land _ a move that could nearly double the size of land protected
as wilderness _ Clinton's conservation legacy would place him among
the giants of American presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The big stick actions of the president over the last two years
have come as somewhat of a surprise to people who once thought
Clinton's idea of green extended no further than the Astroturf he
had long ago in the back of his pickup truck. Then, too, this was
the man who just a few years ago had to be nudged, on the basis of
polling done by adviser Dick Morris, to spend his summer holiday in
the Rockies, trying to look presidential while swatting at horse
flies and wincing at sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the president was far less decisive when he took
office in 1993. Just months after moving into the White House, he
made a daring move to abolish nearly a century of federal land
management policies that had catered to mining, timber and oil
interests. But when Western Republicans raised a stink, Clinton
backed off, to the howl of environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What started as a love affair is now looking like it may turn
out to be date rape,'' said Jay Hair, then the executive director
of the National Wildlife Foundation, in a memorable jab at the
president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildlife Federation looks more kindly on Clinton today, as
well they might. Before the executive actions of last week, Clinton
also initiated a federal land purchase that protects Yellowstone
National Park from mining, put 70,000 acres of riverbank on the
last free-flowing stretch of the Columbia River into the National
Wildlife system and began his string of monument designations with
one of the biggest ever _ the 1.7 million acres of Grand
Staircase-Escalante in southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he has had a very strong second half from the
environmental point of view,'' said Jim Lyon, legislative director
for the Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, mainly in the rural West, accuse Clinton of making
big land grabs at the expense of small communities. They also say
that Clinton cares less about the land than he does about linking
himself to spectacular scenery for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an agenda that is not necessarily good for society _ he
just wants to leave a legacy,'' said Rep. Barbara Cubin, R- Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the public is overwhelmingly in favor of more
wilderness and national parks _ which many monuments ultimately
become. Grand Canyon, Zion, Bryce and Olympic _ now among the most
popular national parks _ all started as monuments.
</P>
<P>
   It is also good politics, Democrats say, to have Republicans
carping about presidential orders to protect stunning pieces of
federal land. The Democrats say one of their best issues in 1996
were efforts by a handful of Western Republicans to close down some
national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a huge upsurge in public sentiment on behalf of
protecting open space,'' said Babbitt. In Arizona, while leading
Republicans opposed Clinton's designation of the new monuments, a
poll by the Arizona Republic showed 80 percent support for the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidents, Republicans and Democrats, have looked to
public land for a legacy. All but three of the 15 who came between
Teddy Roosevelt and Bill Clinton established national monuments, of
which there are more than 100 today. Although a subsequent
president _ or a veto-proof majority of Congress _ could overturn a
declaration, no monument has ever been revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt recalled that his grandfather, a rancher and merchant in
northern Arizona, strongly opposed Roosevelt's 1908 declaration
that set aside Grand Canyon as monument. He had a water claim in
the canyon and a ranch on the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many years went by before my grandfather, in his mellow
years, said he always was in favor of protecting the Grand
Canyon,'' said Babbitt. ``As I told the president: History is on
our side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
