<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MONUMENTS-LEGACY-REVI     01-15 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONUMENTS-LEGACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAND RUSH: CLINTON PUTS SOME SPACE BETWEEN HIS PRESIDENCY AND
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In late 1998, during the darkest hours of the Clinton
presidency, while friends and foes in Washington obsessed about
whether a sexual affair would force a sudden change in tenants at
the White House, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt began sending
notes to President Clinton about the final years of another
president.
</P>
<P>
   Look West, Babbitt advised, just as President Theodore Roosevelt
had done at the turn of the century. With the stroke of a pen, TR
used a 1906 law called the Antiquities Act to set aside pieces of
the American back yard for the ages _ protected as a national
monument. Clinton could do the same, using the same legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And he has. Chasing Roosevelt's ghost, Clinton arrived at the
wind-chapped lip of the Grand Canyon last Tuesday, exactly 92 years
after Roosevelt went to the same spot. Roosevelt hiked; Clinton
arrived by helicopter. But their intent was the same: using the
power of the presidency to establish a personal legacy that would
outlast that transitory power.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Clinton designated three new national monuments
and expanded a fourth. He has now set aside more federal land _
outside of Alaska _as monuments than any other president. More than
2.7 million acres of federal land, or an area about twice the size
of Delaware, has been given new monument status, which restricts
development while aiming to keep the area in a wild state for
perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even lame ducks have wings,'' said Babbitt after leading
Clinton on a tour of rust-colored high ground in Arizona, newly
enshrined as the Grand Canyon-Parashant National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little that any president facing a hostile
Congress can do to change the course of domestic events in his last
months in office. One major exception is the environment. The
Antiquities Act gives a president power to confer eternal
protection on a piece of the public domain as ``an object of
historic and scientific interest.'' Land that has been given
monument status may no longer be used for any purpose or in any way
that would change its character. That is, if the land has
traditionally served as grazing territory, or been hunted or
fished, such use might be continued. On the other hand, logging,
mining or off-road driving would be forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Of late, Clinton has signaled his intent to use the Antiquities
Act like a golfer who has just discovered the power of a titanium
driver. He is likely to designate another half-dozen national
monuments, protecting desert land in Oregon, coastal cliffs in
California, the river banks that Lewis and Clark explored in
Montana and ancient Indian sites in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with a one-year-old executive order that brought to a
halt all new road building on 40 million acres of National Forest
land _ a move that could nearly double the size of land protected
as wilderness _ Clinton's conservation legacy would place him among
the giants of American presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The big stick actions of the president over the last two years
have come as somewhat of a surprise to people who once thought
Clinton's idea of green extended no further than the Astroturf he
had long ago in the back of his pickup truck. Then, too, this was
the man who just a few years ago had to be nudged, on the basis of
polling done by adviser Dick Morris, to spend his summer holiday in
the Rockies, trying to look presidential while swatting at horse
flies and wincing at sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the president was far less decisive when he took
office in 1993. Just months after moving into the White House, he
made a daring move to abolish nearly a century of federal land
management policies that had catered to mining, timber and oil
interests. But when Western Republicans raised a stink, Clinton
backed off, to the howl of environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What started as a love affair is now looking like it may turn
out to be date rape,'' said Jay Hair, then the executive director
of the National Wildlife Foundation, in a memorable jab at the
president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildlife Federation looks more kindly on Clinton today, as
well they might. Before the executive actions of last week, Clinton
also initiated a federal land purchase that protects Yellowstone
National Park from mining, put 70,000 acres of riverbank on the
last free-flowing stretch of the Columbia River into the National
Wildlife system and began his string of monument designations with
one of the biggest ever _ the 1.7 million acres of Grand
Staircase-Escalante in southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he has had a very strong second half from the
environmental point of view,'' said Jim Lyon, legislative director
for the Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, mainly in the rural West, accuse Clinton of making
big land grabs at the expense of small communities. They also say
that Clinton cares less about the land than he does about linking
himself to spectacular scenery for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an agenda that is not necessarily good for society _ he
just wants to leave a legacy,'' said Rep. Barbara Cubin, R- Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the public is overwhelmingly in favor of more
wilderness and national parks _ which many monuments ultimately
become. Grand Canyon, Zion, Bryce and Olympic _ now among the most
popular national parks _ all started as monuments.
</P>
<P>
   It is also good politics, Democrats say, to have Republicans
carping about presidential orders to protect stunning pieces of
federal land. The Democrats say one of their best issues in 1996
were efforts by a handful of Western Republicans to close down some
national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a huge upsurge in public sentiment on behalf of
protecting open space,'' said Babbitt. In Arizona, while leading
Republicans opposed Clinton's designation of the new monuments, a
poll by the Arizona Republic showed 80 percent support for the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidents, Republicans and Democrats, have looked to
public land for a legacy. All but three of the 15 who came between
Teddy Roosevelt and Bill Clinton established national monuments, of
which there are more than 100 today. Although a subsequent
president _ or a veto-proof majority of Congress _ could overturn a
declaration, no monument has ever been revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt recalled that his grandfather, a rancher and merchant in
northern Arizona, strongly opposed Roosevelt's 1908 declaration
that set aside Grand Canyon as monument. He had a water claim in
the canyon and a ranch on the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many years went by before my grandfather, in his mellow
years, said he always was in favor of protecting the Grand
Canyon,'' said Babbitt. ``As I told the president: History is on
our side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
