<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6870 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RUDY'S CHEAT SHEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I was disappointed to learn that David Letterman's
producers slipped the first lady the contents of her New York pop
quiz in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever other problems she has, Hillary Rodham Clinton never
struck me as the sort of girl who would crib on a quiz.
</P>
<P>
   I have been badgering Rudolph Giuliani to see me, so I could
give him a pop quiz on Washington. But now, to be fair, I'll have
to provide an advance peek. So, Mr. Mayor, call me when you're
ready to ace this.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Is the capital named after an Italian? (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the District of Columbia was named for Christopher
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Who was the Tidal Basin Bombshell? (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Fanne Foxe, a stripper at the Silver Slipper who became a basin
dipper with a congressional tippler.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) If you see a Froot Loop in a white sweater
with a huge crimson M on it, running around Capitol Hill shouting
``Hotty, toddy, gosh almighty, who in the hell are we? Hey! Flim
flam, bim bam, Ole Miss, by damn!'' should you call the Capitol
Police to come with their butterfly nets? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   No, that's Trent Lott reliving his days as a college
cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Why is there no J Street here? (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Myth has it that Pierre L'Enfant, the capital's designer,
refused to name a street J because he was feuding with John Jay,
the first chief justice. But it was more likely a worry that J and
I looked too similar.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) What does it mean when the light on top of
the Capitol is on? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Congress is in session. Legend has it this was how wives checked
to see if their husbands were in making laws or out making whoopee.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) What's the city's highest point? (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Embassy, the better to spy on us.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Which senator conducted the longest
filibuster in history? (Hint: He has also ``bumped into'' the most
women in elevators.) (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Strom Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Thus spake which scandal vixens?
</P>
<P>
   a) ``I can't type. I can't file. I can't even answer the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   b) ``I'm like, all right, `I love you, Butthead.'''
</P>
<P>
   c) ``He 'sposed hisself, and that's not right.'' (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Ray, Monica Lewinsky and Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Which elite men's club in Washington has
this sign by the phone? `` `Just left,' 25 cents; `On his way,' 50
cents; `Not here,' $1; `Who?' $5.''(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The Alibi Club.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Match the hotel with the transgression: The
Vista ... the Jefferson ... the Ritz Carlton. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Marion Barry got busted for smoking crack ... Dick Morris
played footsie with a call girl ... Marv Albert played bitesie on a
girl.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Why would you, as senator from New York
(pop.: 18,175,301), be a Pigmy compared to Larry Craig of Idaho
(pop.: 1,228,684)? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   It's the seniority, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Match the scandal fashion: vicuna coat ...
good Republican cloth coat ... Gap dress. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Adams ... Pat Nixon ... Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Why aren't there any skyscrapers? (END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Buildings cannot overshadow the Capitol and monuments.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) How did ladies of the evening become known
as ``hookers''? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   During the Civil War, Gen. Joseph Hooker rounded up 3,900
prostitutes to limit business to a triangle near Pennsylvania
Avenue. It was dubbed Joe Hooker's division, and the women,
hookers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) What felonious fellow has a bust outside
the Senate chamber? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Spiro Agnew.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Why don't cabs in Washington have celebrity
voice directives? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Our mayor is not a control freak.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Bensonhurst is to lasagna as the Lower East
Side is to the knish as Capitol Hill is to what? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Senate bean soup.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) What is a whip? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to do with what you've banished from Times Square. It's
the lawmaker who rounds up votes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) What subway is without crime, except of the
white collar variety? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The Senate subway.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) What is ``the candy seat''? (END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The last desk on the aisle on the Republican side on the Senate
floor, traditionally stocked with candy.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) ``My distinguished colleague'' is
Senate-speak for what? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   You talkin' to (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) me? (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
