<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6885 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MINORITY-ANGEL-LADN     01-15 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-ANGEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE RIDING ON BACK OF `ANGELS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Steve Carney  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES, Calif., -- When ``City of Angels'' premieres
SUNDAY, the hospital drama with the mainly African-American cast
will carry with it the future of other multicultural programs,
minority groups say.
</P>
<P>
   But its creators insist they're just trying to make good
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make it out like it's some kind of trailblazing Jackie
Robinson of television,'' said Paris Barclay, an African-American
and one of the show's creators.
</P>
<P>
   Even though its genesis predates the controversy, ``City of
Angels'' has landed on the TV landscape amid charges from minority
groups that this season's television offerings feature an
unprecedented lack of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, some see the show as not just another Steven
Bochco drama, whose cast happens to be African-American. To them
``City of Angels'' is a saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a high-stakes kind of thing,'' said Alicia
Maldonado, spokeswoman for MALDEF, the Mexican American Legal
Defense and Educational Fund, based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's successful, it can mean other things for other
groups,'' Maldonado said. But if it fails, it might sour network
executives on the idea, and a similar chance for such a
high-profile minority show might not come for years.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bochco, creator of ``Hill Street Blues,'' ``NYPD Blue''
and ``L.A. Law,'' asked Barclay two years ago about doing a medical
drama with a mostly minority cast. Barclay has won two Emmy awards
for directing ``NYPD Blue'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to do a black drama for a long time,'' Bochco
said. ``There's such an extraordinary talent pool to draw from, and
it's been under-utilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope we don't get buried under the burden of our
own historical significance,'' he said. ``I hope we get the same
chance as any promising new show, and find its audience and
succeed. You hope you succeed or fail on your merits.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``City of Angels'' cast includes Bochco veterans Blair
Underwood (``L.A. Law'') and Michael Warren (``Hill Street Blues'')
as well as Vivica A. Fox (``Independence Day'' and the Fox series
``Getting Personal''.) In addition, more than half of the writing
staff and crew are minorities or women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing this to be politically correct. I'm not doing
this to be Crusader Rabbit. I'm doing this,'' Bochco said,
``because I want to. I'm passionate about it. I have a creative
commitment, not a political commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   And the show should make good business sense, as well, Barclay
said.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have other minority shows in the pipeline, he said,
and even if ``Angels'' doesn't survive, the networks should be
interested in catering to viewers of color. After all, census
officials say that by 2050 no racial group will make up more than
50 percent of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly why minority groups want to know why TV
doesn't reflect the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   When the four major television networks announced their new Fall
shows last May, not a single one had a minority in a leading role.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
threatened boycotts, but starting earlier this month the networks
began agreeing to add minority actors, writers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
   For the NAACP, ``Angels'' carries much weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of things should be a long way behind us,'' said
Frank L. Berry, director of the NAACP's nine-state Western Region.
``In any case it's an important step, and we certainly want to be
in a position to work with those who want to produce the best
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochco said dramas with predominantly African-American casts
have failed in the past because they were too tightly focused on
the experience of being African-American. He said he wanted to make
a show with a broader melodramatic appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``An inner-city hospital is a very legitimate environment to
populate with a significantly African-American cast,'' Bochco said.
And the setting allows for universal tales dealing with issues of
death and life.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the show won't deal with race, he said. For
example, two medical students -- one white and the other
African-American -- are continually squabbling over perceived
favoritism for one or the other.
</P>
<P>
   One viewer said the show's realism alone should draw fans. Dr.
Clarence Sutton Jr., a trauma surgeon at Providence Holy Cross
Medical Center in Mission Hills, trained and is now on the faculty
at L.A. County/King-Drew Medical Center in Willowbrook, between
Watts and Compton.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying there aren't enough black shows on.
I think this is going to be a shining star,'' said Sutton, who
operated on the most seriously wounded child from the Jewish
Community Center shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very true-to-life. For sure, people in the medical
profession are going to appreciate it,'' he said. ``I'd be
interested in watching this myself. I can relate to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barclay, invoking Martin Luther King Jr., said he hopes viewers
judge the show by its content and characters, not the color of
their skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people like Bochco dramas,'' with their complex characters,
and quirky, compelling story lines, Barclay said, ``they'll
probably like this show.''
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong drama with the predominantly black cast will debut
at 8 p.m. SUNDAY, JAN. 16, and will begin appearing in its regular
time slot Wednesday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
