<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flu Hurts Worse Than the Shot
</P>
<P>
   The flu is battering the nation, filling hospitals and doctors'
offices. Patients, many of them elderly, crowd emergency rooms,
shivering with fever.
</P>
<P>
   Many have only themselves to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rita Charon, an internal medicine specialist at Columbia
University's College of Physicians and Surgeons, said she is
getting so tired of arguing with older people who do not want a flu
shot that she is tempted to forget informed consent and jab them
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine is the only way to protect against the misery of
influenza. For some, it can be a matter of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Flu kills 20,000 Americans a year; most are very old or have
other debilitating illnesses. But even though the U.S. Centers for
Disease Control reports that this year's vaccine is right on
target, most Americans, as usual, are shunning the shots.
</P>
<P>
   People who got the shot and say they got the flu anyway most
likely got another respiratory virus, experts say. Or they were
infected before they built up immunity _ it takes about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now that flu season is in full swing, how can people protect
themselves?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edwin Kilbourne, a flu expert at the New York Medical
College in Valhalla, says he has one constant refrain:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a flu shot. It's not too late.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By GINA KOLATA
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Is Not Believing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the paragraph you are now reading really on the page? Or was
it digitally implanted on your glasses when you weren't looking?
</P>
<P>
   Look out the window. Was that really a Pepsi truck passing by,
or did Pepsi cut a deal with the company that installed the
windows?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's so hard living in the Digital Age, because you just
never know.
</P>
<P>
   These existential musings were prompted by word that CBS News
has been dropping logos into various programs, including a a CBS
billboard looming behind Dan Rather in Times Square on New Year's
Eve _ magically replacing the NBC sign that was actually there.
</P>
<P>
   Is this ethical? It was ``a mistake,'' Rather said. ``There is
no excuse for it.'' But Andrew Heyward, president of CBS News,
defended such fakery, saying its use on ``The Early Show'' was
``whimsical and creative.'' As for the Times Square
sleight-of-mouse, he called it an ``extension of our graphics, a
change in this very festive, in effect, set.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   States' Rights Upheld at the Supreme Court  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress might be forgiven for assuming that it was protecting
state employees against job discrimination on the basis of age when
it extended the federal age discrimination law to states in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   That was two decades before a new Supreme Court majority would
start seeing federal-state relations in a new light and tilting the
balance in favor of the states.
</P>
<P>
   So it should have been no great surprise when the court ruled,
by a vote of 5-4, that states are immune from suit under the Age
Discrimination in Employment Act. State workers have remedies under
state laws, which are typically weaker.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not all bad news for the federal government. The
court unanimously upheld the Drivers Privacy Protection Act, which
bars states from selling personal information contained in motor
vehicle records. South Carolina and other states, which have made
millions by selling the information to direct marketers and others,
had argued that the prohibition infringed on their sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in a busy week, the justices were unanimous in ruling
that unprovoked flight at the sight of a police officer can, in
context, be suspicious enough to justify a stop-and-frisk search.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   At Microsoft, a New No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after founding what became the world's most
powerful software company, Bill Gates stepped down as chief
executive, handing the reins to his longtime business partner and
closest friend, Steven Ballmer. Gates is not going away, though; he
will continue as the company's chairman and chief software
strategist. Nobody is expecting a kinder, gentler Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   Impresario and Angel  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 18 of the 40 stages in London's West End up for sale and
large American leisure-time groups said to be among the leading
bidders, guardians of British culture feared for the future of the
world's largest theater district.
</P>
<P>
   Then an angel descended in the form of Andrew Lloyd Webber. In a
$145 million deal, the composer's Really Useful Co. and a financial
partner, Nat West Equity Partners, bought 10 of the leading houses,
in part to guarantee chances for risky shows.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN HOGE
</P>
<P>
   Federal Script Approval  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been getting an advance peek at some of the
scripts of the major networks' most popular television shows, from
``ER'' to ``Chicago Hope,'' and pushing anti-drug messages in the
plots. Networks participate willingly because approval from the
White House Office of National Drug Control Policy permits them to
offer less of their valuable air time for public service
announcements. But the deal raised questions about government
interference in the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MARC LACEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Buy for the Jets  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Jets may not have a head coach, but they have a new
owner: Robert Wood Johnson IV. The great-grandson of Johnson &AMP;
Johnson's founder agreed to pay the estate of the oilman Leon Hess
a stunning $635 million for the team. The first item on his to-do
list is persuading Bill Parcells to reconsider his resignation as
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD SANDOMIR
</P>
<P>
   A Stay of Execution  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders rid themselves of a problem that threatened to
upset progress toward domestic peace and membership in the European
Union. They agreed not to hang the convicted Kurdish guerrilla
leader Abdullah Ocalan, at least until the European Court of Human
Rights can rule on his case, probably sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN KINZER
</P>
<P>
   Drug Trafficking Online  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Service said its seizures of prescription drugs
imported from abroad soared last year, as more and more consumers
used the Internet to buy medicines from overseas pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   The agency seized 9,725 packages with prescription drugs last
year, about 4.5 times as many as in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposed legislation to crack down on domestic
drug sales over the Internet in December, but administration
officials are still working on how to regulate foreign Web sites
selling to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
<P>
   Up in Smoke  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes not only pose deadly risks to smokers but are also
the leading cause of residential fires that kill more than 900
people a year. Philip Morris Cos. said it had designed a type of
paper making cigarettes burn less hot, reducing the chance of
igniting some fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Still Expelled  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that people have a right to feel safe while watching a
football game, a federal judge upheld the expulsions of six high
school students in Decatur, Ill. Judge Michael McCuskey found no
evidence of bias in expelling the students, who are black. A civil
rights suit had been filed by Rainbow/Operation Push, which is
headed by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who had led demonstrations
protesting the school district's action last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DIRK JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   Openly Gay in the Military  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Britain unveiled a new code of conduct for its armed forces that
ends its practice of barring gay men and lesbians from the
military. The government said it had no choice after the European
Court of Human Rights ruled last fall that Britain's ban violated
the basic human right to privacy. The code, which applies to gays
and heterosexuals, says ``unacceptable social conduct,'' including
sexual harassment and overt displays of affection, will result in
disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SARAH LYALL
</P>
<P>
   Open and Closed  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one had complained before, but the South Carolina Republican
Party acknowledged that it did not use all of the state's polling
places in previous presidential primaries. Many of the closed
polling places were in black areas, which prompted an inquiry by
the Justice Department after several voters filed a complaint. The
Democratic primary may also be affected, but Democratic leaders who
instigated the complaint said they helped taint the far more
crucial Republican primary Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
<P>
   Stolen From Cyberspace  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A wily extortionist, probably based somewhere in Russia or
Eastern Europe, made good on a threat to reveal some of the 300,000
customer credit cards he claims to have stolen from CD Universe, an
online music retailer. The attack highlights who may really be at
risk from shopping on the Internet: businesses that fail to protect
the credit card information of their customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN MARKOFF
</P>
<P>
   Wretched Masses, Smuggled  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were promised passage to America. What the 18 Chinese men
got was a cargo container aboard a freighter from Hong Kong to
Seattle, with flashlights, minimal food and buckets for toilets. At
the end of a 15-day journey, three were dead, the others severely
dehydrated and malnourished. Smugglers' use of these containers is
on the rise, immigration officials say, with at least eight such
discoveries in the last two and a half weeks in West Coast ports;
the Seattle incident marks the first known deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``These containers were designed to carry machinery and cargo,
not people,'' said a spokeswoman for the federal immigration
service. Hong Kong authorities pledged a crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
