<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Jan. 16, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Relations between India and
Pakistan are at their worst in decades. Things weren't supposed to
be this way in a subcontinent protected by the threat of
Armageddon. But rather than make the region safer and calmer, many
experts agree that India and Pakistan's open possession of nuclear
weapons appears to have raised the risk of limited wars that could
spiral out of control. By Celia Dugger and Barry Bearak. (Moved in
`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ECON-REVIEW (Council Bluffs, Iowa) _ America may be
racing into a new global economy, but the major presidential
candidates would rather talk about ethanol subsidies than the
Internet. For Republicans and Democrats alike, it's Old Economy
101, perhaps because times are so good, perhaps because the
politics of the New Economy are far too complex for a slogan. By
David E. Sanger. (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-INTERPERSONAL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Publicly nice,
privately nasty, or vice versa: The usual, and usually forced,
civility between the presidential candidates breaks down
occasionally even in public. But behind the scenes, the surprise is
not that their interplay is so brutal _ it isn't _ but that their
relationships are so loaded, so complicated and, even in this
heavily scripted, highly goal-oriented environment, so personal. By
Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENTS-LEGACY-REVIEW (Seattle) _ At the Grand Canyon,
President Clinton has used the power of his office to establish a
personal legacy by designating three new national monuments and
expanding a fourth. There is very little that even an unimpeached
president facing a hostile Congress can do to affect domestic
events in his last months in office. One major exception is the
environment. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-MATH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Watching a football game could
inflict serious mathematical damage on children. It could even
affect their ability to score well on college boards. The problem
comes from the intersection of a mathematical principle known as
`expected value' and a play known as the two-point conversion. By
David Leonhardt. (also moved in the `s' category as
FBN-MATH-REVIEW)
</P>
<P>
   SPY-SATELLITES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The spy-satellite business,
for decades a secretive monopoly of advanced nations, is trying to
go commercial. But the photographs pose questions of practicality,
security and privacy: In theory, nosy neighbors can now peer over
tall fences. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-JAIL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Seeking asylum, some immigrants
find a fate worse than criminal. A first-hand account of conditions
experienced by Chinese refugees being held on immigration charges
in Oregon. By Nicholas D. Kristoff.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMY-REVIEW (Undated) _ For U.S. and European government
and military officials, the second Chechen war has revealed more
about Russian strengths and weaknesses than any spy satellite ever
could. The insights are reassuring. The mighty army that many once
feared could roll across northern Europe cannot even contain an
insurgency within Russia's own borders. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-CORRUPTION-REVIEW (Berlin) _ Germany's 1962 `Spiegel
Affair' and 1983 `Flick Affair' were pivotal moments when the
post-war republic woke up first to its stifling constraints on
freedom and then to corruption at its heart. But perhaps there has
been nothing quite like the `Kohl Affair' in its threefold drama:
the dismantling of a demigod, the burial of the `ancien regime,'
the abrupt inversion of German politics. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Cape Town) _ The changing mix of South
Africa's racial politics and realities: Pik Botha, the longtime
foreign minister for the apartheid regime, is joining the African
National Congress. He has urged other whites to consider such a
course. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Lynn Hoogenboom (e-mail, lyhoog(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
