</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL-MATH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Watching a football game could
inflict serious mathematical damage on children. It could even
affect their ability to score well on college boards. The problem
comes from the intersection of a mathematical principle known as
`expected value' and a play known as the two-point conversion. By
David Leonhardt. (also moved in the `s' category as
FBN-MATH-REVIEW)
</P>
<P>
   SPY-SATELLITES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The spy-satellite business,
for decades a secretive monopoly of advanced nations, is trying to
go commercial. But the photographs pose questions of practicality,
security and privacy: In theory, nosy neighbors can now peer over
tall fences. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-JAIL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Seeking asylum, some immigrants
find a fate worse than criminal. A first-hand account of conditions
experienced by Chinese refugees being held on immigration charges
in Oregon. By Nicholas D. Kristoff.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMY-REVIEW (Undated) _ For U.S. and European government
and military officials, the second Chechen war has revealed more
about Russian strengths and weaknesses than any spy satellite ever
could. The insights are reassuring. The mighty army that many once
feared could roll across northern Europe cannot even contain an
insurgency within Russia's own borders. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-CORRUPTION-REVIEW (Berlin) _ Germany's 1962 `Spiegel
Affair' and 1983 `Flick Affair' were pivotal moments when the
post-war republic woke up first to its stifling constraints on
freedom and then to corruption at its heart. But perhaps there has
been nothing quite like the `Kohl Affair' in its threefold drama:
the dismantling of a demigod, the burial of the `ancien regime,'
the abrupt inversion of German politics. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Cape Town) _ The changing mix of South
Africa's racial politics and realities: Pik Botha, the longtime
foreign minister for the apartheid regime, is joining the African
National Congress. He has urged other whites to consider such a
course. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
