<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6892 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-BLACK-VOTERS-111     01-15 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-BLACK-VOTERS-1115(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT OF BLACK VOTERS IS CRUCIAL FOR GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., La., Miss., S.C., Tenn., Texas)  (lb) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Democratic presidential candidates finally
withdraw from Iowa and New Hampshire, where the electorate is
predominantly white, they will move quickly into Southern states
where black voters often play a decisive role.
</P>
<P>
   And at the moment, at least, Vice President Al Gore seems to
enjoy a commanding advantage with African-American voters, despite
former Sen. Bill Bradley's passionate commitment to the cause of
improving race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls, lists of endorsements and interviews with
dozens of Democratic strategists and black political leaders all
suggest that Gore holds a distinct early lead over Bradley among
black voters in states like Florida, Georgia, Louisiana,
Mississippi, South Carolina, Tennessee and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Those states all vote in the first two weeks of March, shortly
after the Iowa caucuses on Jan. 24 and the New Hampshire primary on
Feb. 1. And in each of those places, political history suggests
that black voters could make up a significant share of the
electorate, particularly in states where competitive Republican
primaries may drain white voters from the Democratic contests.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who will deliver remarks at the annual Martin Luther King
Jr. holiday commemoration at the Ebenezer Baptist Church here on
Monday, is counting on black voters in the South to provide a fire
wall of protection against the possibility of an early loss in New
Hampshire, where some recent polls show Bradley with a narrow lead.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters will also be important in the New York primary on
March 7 and, to a somewhat lesser extent, in the California voting
the same day. Those two primaries award the most Democratic
delegates, and Bradley may prove more competitive with black voters
in those states, where he is better known and will have an enormous
incentive to spend time and resources, Democratic strategists say.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic candidates have strong _ and largely similar _
positions on issues that tend to appeal to black voters, whether
generic concerns like education, health care, crime and economic
growth, or narrower topics like affirmative action and racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   And both use deeply personal anecdotes to connect with black
voters: Bradley describes the discrimination he witnessed against
black teammates with the New York Knicks, and Gore recalls how his
father took him to see slave rings in the basement of a mansion in
their Tennessee town.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Bradley has been more direct than Gore in using his
candidacy to call for a war on poverty, which disproportionately
afflicts black Americans, and to appeal for racial harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm president, I want one thing to be known,'' Bradley said
in a poignant speech about race that he delivered in New York last
April. ``If you want to please the boss, one of the things you'd
better show is how in your department or agency you've furthered
tolerance and racial understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the pursuit of black votes, Gore holds a card that seems
to trump Bradley's oratorical outreach: the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore's ties to President Clinton have hurt him with some
voters, they are an enormous asset among blacks. For seven years,
Gore has played loyal lieutenant to a president who remains
immensely popular with black Americans, and he has used his office
to champion causes, bestow access, deliver federal aid and raise
political funds for black officials across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Those leaders are now rewarding Gore's efforts, often
emphasizing that they hold nothing against Bradley but have little
reason to look beyond the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In interview after interview last week, black political leaders
explained their support for Gore by citing the Clinton
administration's appointment of black officials, its economic
successes and its support for cities and affirmative action. A CBS
News poll taken last month showed that 88 percent of
African-Americans approved of Clinton, compared with 51 percent of
whites. ``Look, Bill Bradley is a fine fellow and he has a good
record,'' said Bill Campbell, the two-term mayor of Atlanta, who is
black and is a longtime backer of Gore. ``But I don't understand
how anyone would imagine that black voters would desert a vice
president who has been so remarkably supportive of the
African-American community. When a constituency is appreciated and
respected and assisted on critical issues, that ought to count for
something, and it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis of Georgia, a black Democrat who supports Gore,
echoed Campbell's remarks. ``There's a loyalty to Gore that Senator
Bradley cannot shake,'' Lewis said. ``It's just impossible. There's
a hold there and he cannot pull it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Campbell are far from alone. Gore has been endorsed by
29 of the 38 black Democrats in Congress, while Bradley has yet to
be endorsed by any. In addition to Campbell, Gore has the backing
of the black mayors of Cleveland; Houston; Jackson, Miss.; Macon,
Ga.; Memphis, Tenn.; Minneapolis; Newark, N.J.; New Orleans;
Savannah, Ga.; St. Louis and Washington. He also has the support of
a number of influential black state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Because presidential primaries typically draw a low turnout, and
are usually dominated by party activists, such endorsements can be
critical if elected officials mobilize their political machinery on
behalf of a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gore organizers in the South, and even some unaligned party
leaders, predict that blacks could make up 35 percent to 40 percent
of the Democratic primary electorate in states like Georgia,
Louisiana, Mississippi and South Carolina. Gore, himself a
Southerner, should win the overwhelming majority of those votes,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say if the election were held today, clearly Gore would
get 80 percent'' of the black vote in Louisiana, said Ben Jeffers,
an African-American who is that state's Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Bill Clinton captured huge majorities of the black vote
in Democratic primaries in key states, winning at least 70 percent
in Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Illinois, Louisiana, Mississippi,
North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Tennessee and Texas, according to
surveys of voters leaving the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was key in terms of Clinton's strategy, and it's one of
the reasons why I really don't think, unless Gore has some kind of
meltdown, that Bill Bradley has any chance of beating Al Gore,''
said David Bositis, an expert on black voting trends with the Joint
Center for Political and Economic Studies. Three recent national
polls all showed that blacks favored Gore over Bradley by margins
of between two and three to one.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's list of notable African-American supporters features
only a smattering of local elected officials, including three state
assemblymen from New York City and the minority leader of the Ohio
state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent names belong to Bradley's former colleagues
in the National Basketball Association, like Julius Erving and
Willis Reed; entertainment figures, like the film director Spike
Lee and the actor Lawrence Fishburne; and academics like Cornel
West of Harvard and the historian Roger Wilkins of George Mason
University, who is misidentified in a Bradley campaign release as a
law professor at George Washington University. They are men with
fans, but not with political organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign has made it transparent that its insurgent
strategy depends on breakthrough victories in northeastern states
like New Hampshire and New York that aides believe will catapult
him with tornadic velocity into a newly reordered political
universe.
</P>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, the campaign reasons, black voters,
like all voters, will be compelled to give Bradley a fresh look.
Bradley aides acknowledge that the task will not be easy, and that
they will have little time to gain traction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black community votes in such a unified fashion that it
has become a tradition that we stick together,'' said Jacques
DeGraff, a black Baptist minister who serves as senior adviser to
the Bradley campaign. ``Traditionally, we deliver 80 percent to the
candidates we get behind. So it takes a great deal of activity to
begin the shift. At first it will be imperceptible. Then it will be
a trickle. And then I believe it will be a flood.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Sheriff Nat Glover of Duval County, Fla., a black
Bradley supporter, said that Bradley would be able to sell himself
to black voters once he had a chance to make contact. Glover, who
only met Bradley four months ago, said he was impressed at how
Bradley's experience as a teammate and roommate of black basketball
players seemed to have shaped his racial sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Glover also said he knew of no other black elected officials
in Florida who were supporting Bradley. ``I've been in the company
of individuals who are certainly considering supporting Bill,''
said Glover, whose county includes Jacksonville. ``I haven't
noticed a ground swell, but I have noticed quite a bit of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   As the race has tightened, Gore has found countless ways to send
messages to black voters. He campaigned in November at the Memphis
church where King spoke the night before he was killed. Last month
he staged an ``African-Americans for Gore'' rally in Atlanta,
declaring, ``Anyone who says affirmative action is no longer
needed, because we've reached the promised land, has confused
wilderness with Canaan.''
</P>
<P>
   He regularly recalls the civil rights legacy of his father, Sen.
Al Gore Sr., while neglecting to mention that the elder Gore voted
against the Civil Rights Act of 1964, a year when he faced
re-election in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president hired a black woman, Donna Brazile, as his
campaign manager and took an unusual trip to the United Nations
last week to call for help for African countries ravaged by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Brazile suggested in a recent interview that the
Republican Party used black partisans like Gen. Colin Powell and
Rep. J.C. Watts Jr. as window dressing, Gore soothed Powell with a
phone call but was careful to neither criticize his aide nor
dispute her point.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore has repeatedly warned that Bradley's proposal
for expanding access to health care would disproportionately harm
minorities because it would replace Medicaid, the state and federal
health program for the poor, with a system of federal subsidies
that Gore maintains would be inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has dismissed those assertions as scare tactics and he
characterized them in a recent debate as the most offensive charges
made by Gore in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Lester, a Democratic pollster who is not working for either
candidate, said polls he had conducted in Chicago, Miami, Atlanta
and North Carolina showed that Bradley had picked up support among
white Democrats but had not gained on Gore with black voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for blacks to take a second look at Bradley, not only
would he have to have momentum but he would have to blow Gore out
in the early states,'' Lester said. ``As long as Gore is standing,
I don't see any compelling evidence that black voters will leave
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
