<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T REMOVE OLD OPERATING SYSTEMS WHEN UPGRADING UNLESS PC IS
SLOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I've got a 233-megahertz Pentium II computer, one of the
first ones, which came with Windows 95. I put Windows 98 on it, and
recently upgraded to Windows 98 SE. A friend said I should format
my hard drive and do a fresh install of Windows 98 SE, and that all
those old versions of the operating system are going to cause me
problems. I hate to go through that, but I want my computer to stay
trouble-free. Is he right?
</P>
<P>
   A: John Dvorak, the bellicose computer columnist who seems to
turn up in every Ziff-Davis publication available, has a theory
that operating systems undergo ``OS decay.'' Over time, they
collect digital detritus that wears down reliability and
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's had the misfortune of having to reformat a hard
drive, then reinstall the Windows operating system, has found a
silver lining. The fresh installation does feel peppier.
</P>
<P>
   However, I'm not sure the problem is related to upgrades to the
operating system. When you install a new version of Windows, the
setup routine overwrites the old versions of key files with the
latest versions.
</P>
<P>
   (The one exception is the backup that Windows makes of the
previous installation. When you install a new version of the OS, it
rolls everything up into a big, compressed data file of about 100
megabytes. If you choose to uninstall the new version of the
operating system, Windows' setup just unpacks everything and
restores your drive to its previous state.)
</P>
<P>
   However, the installation routine will leave behind files that
may relate to the older version but aren't part of the operating
system itself. For example, those who upgrade from Windows 95 to
Windows 98 often have problems with their modems. That's because
the Windows 95 modem drivers are often quite different from the
Windows 98 versions. Downloading the latest drivers from the modem
manufacturer's Web site is the fix.
</P>
<P>
   You can suffer this sort of OS decay if you install and
uninstall different kinds of software, and if you change hardware
components frequently. For example, when you upgrade to a new video
card, chances are there are still some video drivers left on your
system. There may even be lines in the Windows Registry that try to
load them. My approach to doing a fresh installation is the old
saw, ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it.'' If your computer is
running well, leave it alone. If not, start backing things up and
get ready for a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I upgraded to Internet Explorer 5 and Outlook Express 5. Now,
I no longer have a spell checker in Outlook Express 5. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   A: Microsoft got in trouble with the federal government for
tying one product to another when Internet Explorer became
integrated into Windows 98. Seems like the feds may have missed
another one ...
</P>
<P>
   In Outlook Express 5, you must have Microsoft Word 95, 97 or
2000 on your computer with its spell-checking feature installed
before you can check your spelling in the e-mail program. No Word,
no spell-check. This is spelled out in the help file that comes
with Outlook Express 5. Just do a search in the Help function for
``spelling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com. The bulk of e-mails prevents
individual replies to each unpublished letter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6896 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NUNS-RECRUIT-ART-2TAK     01-15 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUNS-RECRUIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIMINISHING SISTERHOOD COMPETES RECRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTSDALE, N.Y. _ For young women in a culture saturated with
alluring images of riches and sensuality, it is an unlikely
advertising come-on. Turn your back on money and men, and spend
your life helping people who are sick, poor and uneducated.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ultimate tough sell, but the message is: Forget the pop
star Madonna. Become a nun.
</P>
<P>
   These days the Sisters of Mercy of the Americas, one of the
nation's largest orders of Roman Catholic nuns, is making the pitch
with a vengeance, and it is using all the tools of the modern age:
test markets, target audiences, catchy graphics and, new this
month, a Web site. One recruitment poster that was sent last week
to college campuses shows a close-up of God's hand reaching out to
Adam's from Michelangelo's ``Creation of Adam.'' Adam is holding a
cellular phone, and the text reads: ``Do you have a call waiting?''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters have no choice. For more than three decades, the
number of Catholic nuns in the United States has fallen like a
stone, to 83,000 last year from 180,000 in 1965. Compounding the
decline is the aging of their population; the median age of
American nuns is 68. The result has been a draining of resources
from the many charities and institutions that the sisters helped
create.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a personnel crisis,'' said Professor Scott Appleby,
director of the Cushwa Center for the Study of American Catholicism
at the University of Notre Dame. ``Sisters really did build the
American Catholic Church through their teaching in the parochial
school system and their staffing of Catholic hospitals. They have
been the backbone of the church in this century, and it's
absolutely critical to address the question of the next generation
and who will succeed them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the recruitment campaign, the New York, New Jersey and
Brooklyn chapters, or communities, of the Sisters of Mercy teamed
up to create the posters and brochures, which are aimed at women 21
to 35. ``If you appear old and nonvibrant, that becomes an obstacle
to anyone wanting to enter religious life,'' said Sister Patricia
Wolf, president of the New York community, adding that the images
showed a ``connection to the world and also to humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and sisters themselves point to a number of factors
responsible for the dwindling population of nuns, a decline far
more precipitous than the corresponding drop in the number of Roman
Catholic priests.
</P>
<P>
   The women's movement and cultural revolution of the 1960s opened
up a world of new opportunities for women, from careers in law to
stints in the Peace Corps. Moreover, where it was not uncommon in
the 1950s and 1960s for Catholic women to join the ranks of nuns if
they were not yet engaged to be married by their college
graduation, in the 1970s and beyond it became more acceptable for
women to marry later in life. And given the booming economy of
recent years and a return to family values, taking vows of poverty
and chastity is, in some sense, a countercultural, even radical,
move.
</P>
<P>
   As laypeople steadily replace nuns on the staffs of Catholic
schools and social service agencies, young women are losing their
exposure to nuns and the more modern ways in which they live today
_ wearing street clothes, often residing in apartments and holding
down demanding jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conundrum,'' said Appleby, ``is that as the number of
sisters falls and the ones who remain are drawn into leadership
positions, there is less opportunity for that personal contact that
was so effective earlier in the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Other religious orders now are trying to turn the tide by
injecting some of that face-to-face contact. The Religious of the
Sacred Heart of Mary, an order with 1,100 members worldwide, is
taking advantage of its Hamptons real estate by holding ``Come and
See'' weekends several times a year at its retreat house in Sag
Harbor in eastern Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance to come and get to know us in an informal
setting,'' said Sister Mary Alice Young, director of development
for the order on the East Coast, based in Tarrytown. ``The sisters
talk about their own experience, and people can ask questions
without being embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Sisters of Mercy, the Religious of the Sacred Heart of
Mary last year created a Web site, and for the last two years the
community has run advertisements in Catholic newspapers. ``One of
the things you're constantly hearing is that the baby boomers and
generation X are totally separate entities, and you have to learn
to reach the generations differently,'' Sister Mary Alice said.
``It's speaking to a whole different world than the one I grew up
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, there are similar efforts. In Indiana, the
Sisters of Benedict assembled a lay committee of professionals with
experience in marketing and communications. The sisters now have a
toll-free number, a Web site and advertising. One ad beckons with
the cheeky line: ``You don't have to be perfect to be a nun. God
knows we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   And in California, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles
has made the recruitment of nuns and priests a high priority. Later
this month, the archdiocese will invite 150 to 250 people to its
annual ``7 to 11 Day.'' Starting at 7 a.m., the men and women trail
the priests and nuns as they go about their day. Later they are
treated to dinner with Cardinal Roger Mahony and a talent show.
Past acts have included comedy and line dancing.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope among nuns that they can tap into this millennial
moment, when gift shops sell nothing but angels, and best-selling
books, rock songs and television shows unabashedly deal with issues
relating to religion, the soul and the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that probably more than at any recent time, there is a
real quest today for spirituality,'' said Sister Patricia of the
Sisters of Mercy. ``The media gives evidence of that. You have
something like `Touched by an Angel' on television and other shows.
So an attraction to religious life is perhaps even more possible
than it has been at other times.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A sampling of reactions on two traditionally Catholic campuses
in Westchester County, however, found that for most students, the
idea of becoming a nun was just short of unthinkable. Jessica
Hogan, a senior at Iona College in New Rochelle, said: ``I never
considered it. It seems outdated and old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Delia, a 29-year-old graduate student at Mercy College
in Dobbs Ferry, who is from a ``very strong Catholic family,'' said
she had considered the profession as a girl. Ms. Delia's mother was
a nun for seven years before leaving, and both her aunt and cousin
are nuns. ``I've grown up around nuns, so I have a different
outlook than a lot of people,'' Ms. Delia said. ``You can be part
of a religious order and still be a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she decided the religious life was not for her. The
recruitment posters might help, Ms. Delia said, but she believes
that the reason young women have shunned the sisterhood is the
diminishing power of the Catholic Church over their lives. ``The
problem is young people don't stay in the church,'' she said. ``You
have to have that belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming a nun is a lengthy affair. At the Sisters of Mercy, an
international order with 5,700 members, first there are periodic
discussions between a prospective sister and a vocation director
for six months to a year. A formal application is then made to the
leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   If accepted, the candidate lives with other sisters for two
years but retains her outside job and assets. For the next two
years she is a ``novice,'' giving up her job and pursuing spiritual
development. Then, just before taking her first vows, she disposes
of her assets and begins a ministry in keeping with the order's
mission. Three to five years later, she takes her final vows.
</P>
<P>
   The New York, New Jersey and Brooklyn regional communities of
the Sisters of Mercy are determined to increase the minority
representation among their members, who are overwhelmingly white.
One of the posters shows an African-American woman in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't reflect as a community the ethnic background of New
York City,'' Sister Patricia said in her spacious office on a
former estate here. ``Just walk around. We have a significant
amount of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Barbara Ann Catherine Gourdine, 40, is a relatively new _
and young _ member, having made her temporary vows two years ago.
She is also African-American, one of only two in the New York
community, which has 187 members. She actually joined the order at
21 but left in 1988. ``In leaving it gave me a chance to grow and
find out who I was as a person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has had to adjust to living with three women in a house
after years of living alone in an apartment, and she recently took
a job teaching in a Catholic school after 10 years in a public
school. ``It's not what I expected,'' she said, ``but I am happy.''
</P>
<P>
   With members from Staten Island to the Adirondacks, as well as
the Worcester, Mass., area (the result of a merger), the New York
community of the Sisters of Mercy is spread thin. The order
sponsors two high schools, three health-care centers and three
social-service agencies. There are pastoral duties and community
outreach, as well, but half the members are retired.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nuns resist the idea that they face extinction, and they
look to their history for solace. ``In some ways, you could say,
`Well, it's dying out and the last person should turn out the
lights,''' Sister Mary Alice said. ``But we were founded by only
six sisters 150 years ago. So what you need are committed women.''
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, there will always be those.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
