<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6903 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-ART-570(     01-15 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-ART-570(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOLAN SETTLERS, ISRAEL-SYRIA TALKS MEAN UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG and WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATZRIN, Golan Heights _ Everybody here knows Moshe Zaidon, the
white-haired manager of a local cafeteria, who walks the pleasant,
orderly streets with a sense of ownership that many of the pioneer
settlers possess. ``There goes Moshe from the cafeteria,'' people
say, and they wave.
</P>
<P>
   Most don't know, however, because it is a hard thing for Zaidon
to admit, that for more than two decades he has possessed a
deep-seated belief that the time would come when they all would
have to pull up stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from the beginning that we were living on Syrian
land,'' said Zaidon, 59. He was reclining in his favorite
leatherette chair in his immaculate living room, which is decorated
with Laurel and Hardy figurines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, the Golan became by law an inseparable part of
Israel,'' he continued. ``But deep inside, I knew this day might
arrive. If there was a chance of peace with the Syrians, I always
knew that we were the bargaining chip.''
</P>
<P>
   With the revival of the Israeli-Syrian peace effort after a
nearly four-year stalemate, the Golan Heights, a scenic northern
region replete with gorges, waterfalls and sometimes snow-capped
mountain peaks, has entered a state of flux. On the surface, the
apparatus of opposition to any Israeli concession of the Golan can
be seen revving its engine, as with a mass rally that the settlers
sponsored in Tel Aviv last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the surface, at the collectives, the kibbutzim, the
military bases and the businesses that have established themselves
in this area about the size of Rhode Island, a quiet psychological
and practical preparation has begun. In the four large Druse Arab
towns in the Golan, where many residents are self-protectively
working to suppress their excitement at a possible return to Syrian
control, planning for a very different future is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Any peace agreement would entail an Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan Heights, experts agree. But since a peace agreement is by no
means certain, much of Golan life is frozen, with residents
anxiously continuing their daily lives. Some Israeli settlers are
digging in their heels defiantly, like those who collectively own
the Golan Heights Winery, which is considered Israel's finest. They
are planting new vineyards, boosting their bottling capacity and
expanding into new export markets.
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Zaidon, who has sponsored several residents'
meetings with lawyers and property assessors, have started to think
about what it would it take to dismantle three decades of Israeli
life in the Golan Heights. Eden Springs, Israel's principal water
bottling company, under pressure from its public shareholders, has
already prepared a detailed plan for relocating its entire plant to
northern Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, at least one kibbutz has made a quiet decision to
move as a group to the Galilee, the northern region that most
closely resembles the Golan. The Golan religious council has
written a clause into its standard divorce agreement stating that
no property division would be adversely affected by the outcome of
diplomatic negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And one Golan business has used the possibility of a withdrawal
as a marketing tool. An advertising flier for the two-year-old
Howard Johnson hotel at Mount Hermon asked, ``Who knows how long
you have to visit this enchanted spot?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For decades, the military, which captured the Golan after brutal
battles in 1973, considered the area a strategic necessity to
defend northern Israel against what used to be sporadic shelling by
Syria. Now, though, in the face of what some believe to be a
severely deteriorated Syrian army, it is reassessing its security
plans. Last week, the Israeli army's alpinists, who guard Israel's
only ski resort, conducted their routine training exercises in the
deep snow at the peak of Mount Hermon. But they felt sentimentally
aware that this could be the last winter that their elite unit of
reservists was called into duty to patrol the quiet northern border
on snowshoes and skis.
</P>
<P>
   For the Druse in the Golan Heights, who will stay put, the mood
is very different. Dr. Taiseer Maray, 40, for instance, a
biologist, lives in Majdal Shams, bordering the cease-fire line
between the Golan Heights and Syria. Since childhood, he has been
separated from his older brothers, who made lives in Damascus. Now,
in an exchange of phone calls, the estranged siblings have
discussed reuniting on the family land in the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``How incredible that would be,'' Maray said, ``all to live
under the same flag.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS AS USUAL: Planning for Growth, And for Closing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victor Schoenfeld is a thoroughly Californian figure: a Palo
Verde-reared winemaker trained at the University of California at
Davis. He exudes the kind of easy informality that masks formidable
technical mastery and an intense competitive drive.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last nine years, Schoenfeld has labored in the
unlikely vineyards of the Golan Heights, where the grapes are grown
amid the rusting wrecks of Syrian tanks. He is chief winemaker for
the Golan Heights Winery, the region's largest employer, whose
tallest blending tank is topped, like an army command post, with an
Israeli flag.
</P>
<P>
   With a thousand acres of local vineyards supplying an
ultramodern winemaking complex, the company produced four million
bottles last year. It also chalked up a record $12 million in
earnings. More important to Schoenfeld, his complex cabernets and
fruity chardonnays are beginning to be recognized internationally
as more than just kosher curiosities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, with the prospect of Israeli withdrawal and Syrian
sovereignty, the coming fall harvest could be the winery's last.
``It's a little bit hard on morale,'' Schoenfeld said. ``To think
that a big chunk of your life might be in vain . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But Schoenfeld and his colleagues don't let themselves think
that way. The company is undertaking an $8 million expansion
despite the political uncertainty, and projecting sales to double
to $24 million by 2001. ``The investment program is going forward
as if there were no peace process, because as a business there is
no alternative,'' said Adam Montefiore, the winery's international
marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   The winery's plans stand in stark contrast to those of Eden
Springs, its next-door neighbor in the Katzrin industrial park. A
publicly traded company seeking foreign investors, it has already
bought rights for what it says is a comparable mineral water source
in the upper Galilee. If Syria takes over, the plant and its work
force would all be moved, managers told employees here this month.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Golan Heights winery, relocation is not an option,
its executives say. This cool highland plateau is the only area
under Israeli domain capable of producing a lot of high-quality
wine grapes, they say. And, for the moment, there is no outside
pressure on the company to seek alternatives. The eight
shareholders are all kibbutzim and collective farms in the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Montefiore, an English immigrant, chooses to believe that no
matter what flag flies over it, the winery will survive. But
Schoenfeld is less sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have assumptions that have no basis in
reality, that we'd be able to lease the vineyard from the
Syrians,'' he said. ``If this were France and Belgium, I'd have an
easier time imagining some kind of cooperation. But it's the Middle
East.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing, in his New York Giants parka, at the gate to Mount
Hermon, Yitzhak Tsuela worried that international sentiment could
not be aroused to defend the ski resort that his moshav _ a
collective _ had built.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't create a sympathetic image,'' he said, waving at
the skiers. ``Everyone will say, `They're rich.' But they forget,
when we came here there was nothing. We started with a single
Austrian chairlift that the Israeli government gave us to help us
get off the ground.'
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Majdal Shams, which is adjacent to the moshav, are
furious when they hear these Israelis talk about how they created
something from nothing. That nothing was their land. They seethe
when Golan settlers talk about how they, unlike the West Bank
settlers who displaced Palestinians, took over barren territory.
When Syria lost the Golan to Israel during the 1967 Israeli-Arab
war, an estimated 50,000 to 100,000 Arabs fled.
</P>
<P>
   In the foothills of Mount Hermon, many of the Druse stayed put,
and grew into a community of 16,600, outnumbering the Jewish
settlers, according to Israeli government statistics. The
government says there are 14,400 Jewish settlers, which the
settlers believe is an undercount.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those in the West Bank, the Golan settlers are primarily
secular and traditionally affiliated with the Labor Party of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Also unlike those in the West Bank, few make biblically based
claims to the Golan as part of the greater land of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet hillside town, Majdal Shams, within shouting distance of
Syria, is the largest community in the Golan. Its residents belong
to the Druse religion, which considers the Koran sacred but also
has its own religious texts. In Israel, many Druse have sworn
allegiance to the state, and serve in the army. But in the Golan
Heights, most have refused to take Israeli citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people here have never lived in our country,''
Maray said recently, at the clinic he runs. ``But to be so close to
the cease-fire line has kept our dream realistic. At night, we can
see the lamps burning in our brothers' and sisters' homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Living in Israel has been a mixed experience for many in Majdal
Shams. They say they have always felt like second-class residents,
with textbooks labeled ``Mathematics for Druse'' or ``History for
Druse.'' Maray, who received a doctorate in biology from Hebrew
University in Jerusalem, said he cannot find work in his field in
Israel. Still, he acknowledges that he, like others, benefited some
from the educational and material opportunities of a Westernized
society.
</P>
<P>
   Maray said he expected that Majdal Shams would turn into a
crossroads if peace were made. It is a border town, and its
residents are fluent in both Hebrew and Arabic. After feeling
isolated in Israel, the Druse would be poised to become part of the
Syrian elite, he said. Their savings, which do not amount to much
in Israel, would count for significantly more in Syria's
underdeveloped economy, and their ability to negotiate the two
cultures could be valuable.
</P>
<P>
   As the negotiations proceed, the town's residents try to remain
calm. In the mid-1990s, when peace talks reached a peak before they
were frozen, the atmosphere among the Druse was almost hysterical.
Construction projects halted; businesses stopped placing orders;
some residents even traded in their cars for models that would have
higher resale value in Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very optimistic,'' Dr. Maray said. ``But we have
learned not to take too many concrete steps.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A CRUCIAL VANTAGE POINT: A Coveted Aerie From Which to Spy  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dressed hood-to-toe in a white Windbreaker with legs, Roni Idri,
29, carried an Uzi on his back as he schussed down a snowy ridge of
Mount Hermon several hundred feet from the Syrian border. One of
the elite army alpinists whose days may be numbered, he was asked
whether the skiing soldiers ever caught anyone trying to slip
across the mountaintop border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who?'' he asked, mystified until it dawned on him. ``You mean,
the enemy?''
</P>
<P>
   Above him, the geodesic crown jewels of Israel's electronic
espionage network sat on twin promontories of the snowy
7,300-foot-high ridge. After escorting journalists to the
off-limits peak the week before last, the army announced that the
two dense clusters of dish-encrusted antennae and Buckminster
Fuller radar domes were off the record and should not be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   But they can be clearly viewed not only from the ski resort
below but from Damascus, just 26 miles to the north. And Damascus
wants Idri's ridge back, military hardware and all _ even if the
spy stations are staffed by American or other Western troops.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel, this is the hardest piece of the heights to give
back. The Mount Hermon early warning stations give it unimpeded
surveillance of Syrian skies and military bases. Its top-secret
listening devices can reportedly monitor almost all electronic
communications throughout Syria and southern Lebanon. Though
Israeli military posts dot vantage points throughout the Golan,
none offer the strategic advantage of Mount Hermon.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts here say the withdrawal of the heavy artillery
and tank battalions Israel maintains across the Golan can be safely
compensated for by an extensive _ and very expensive _ system of
airborne and satellite radar stations, antiballistic missiles and
new wings of F-16 fighter jets. But Israeli negotiators are
demanding some continued Israeli military presence, at least
transitionally, on the mountaintop itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is to our advantage to be up on the hill rather than down
in the valley,'' said a senior officer at a Golan Heights military
base. ``Peace would make a difference, but it depends on what kind
of peace you get.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, said the commander, who keeps a daily eye on his Syrian
counterparts encamped across the fortified border, a genuine peace
would justify this painful trade-off. ``They act like we act,
according to the rules set up after 1973,'' he said respectfully.
``I would like one day to see Syrian officers as people I could
talk to, as people who share the same mission that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   A CLOUD OF UNCERTAINTY: Lives Hang in the Balance As Talks Go On
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Syrian talks, which resume Wednesday in the
Washington area, are a fact of life in the Golan. Tandem trailer
rigs drive the picturesque, winding roads beside the Sea of Galilee
adorned with banners that say, ``We will not budge from the
Golan.'' Cappuccino-serving waitresses in the cafe here wear
T-shirts with the same slogan.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate market is frozen with uncertainty. ``There is
not a single house on the market in the entire Golan Heights,''
said Gila Yaakobi, the manager of Golan Realty. Construction has
slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all in an unclear situation now on the Golan,'' said
Moshed Hed, a factory owner who has stalled plans to build on a new
site. ``There is an atmosphere of hesitation, and it has
repercussions in every field.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Jewish Golan Heights, as in Majdal Shams, the 1995
negotiations with Syria served as a kind of fire drill. During that
period, many underwent counseling about how to reorient themselves
psychologically and how to prepare their children for a traumatic
move. In the last few years, many received job retraining in
preparation for leaving agricultural life. Those people, to some
extent, have been bracing for the moment when they might have to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   New immigrants from the former Soviet Union make up a third of
Katzrin's population, and they have been pestering Aryeh Eilat, a
Russian who works as a kind of answer man for the municipality.
They want to know how much compensation money they will receive
from the government and whether they will get green cards from the
United States, too. That kind of gritty pragmatism turns off Eilat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think peace is worth a lot,'' he said. ``Maybe it's worth
the future of my child and my family. But it's such a disgusting
thing to let yourself be sold in the market like an apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he and his wife are already discussing the relative
merits of other regions. Scuttlebutt claims that the government
would be willing to help them relocate in either the sparsely
populated Negev or the Galilee, which they prefer. They have not
gone as far as some neighbors, though, who are taking weekend
drives to scout out new lives.
</P>
<P>
   Few like to admit any kind of preparation publicly, because it
makes it seem as if they have given up the fight. ``We certainly
don't want to give anyone the impression that we have reconciled
ourselves to the situation,'' Zaidon said. ``On the other hand, we
can't stick our heads in the sand. That's what they did in the
Sinai.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Israeli government handled the forcible evacuation
of the Sinai after the Egyptian-Israeli peace accord of 1979 serves
as the model for what not to do, many Israelis say. But Nurit
Kliot, a geographer at the University of Haifa and an expert on the
Sinai evacuation, said she had already seen the government
repeating past mistakes. She said officials were sending
conflicting signals to the Golan settlers, as they did to the Sinai
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kliot was referring to leaks last week suggesting that Barak
was asking the Syrians to let settlers stay in the Golan after the
Israeli military withdraws. Most experts consider this a condition
that Syria would never accept and see it as a ploy aimed at
convincing the settlers that the government is pushing for their
rights. But many settlers are taking the reports at face value.
</P>
<P>
   The government's evacuation from the Sinai town of Yamit, which
ended with violent clashes between settlers and soldiers, led them
to overcompensate the settlers financially, Ms. Kliot said. Instead
of being paid the value of their property, they were paid ``their
property-plus-plus,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This fostered animosity toward the settlers, who were
derogatorily referred to as the ``Yamit millionaires.'' With that
lingering bad impression still fresh, the ski resort operators say
they have never calculated the worth of their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be seen as Shylock, giving up everything for
money,'' Tsuela said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sharon Tsuela, added, in a reference to Syrian
President Hafez Assad, : ``If Assad comes and makes us go, we will
go to Canada. That will be enough of Israel for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking in his living room, Zaidon said he could not imagine
starting over at the age of 59. ``For younger people, it may be
easier,'' he said. ``But I have to make myself face it. Holding on
to the land with our fingernails would be a mistake. After there is
an agreement, and then a referendum, that will be the beginning of
our end here in Katzrin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
