<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6911 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FLA-CUBAN-EMIGRES-NYT     01-15 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CUBAN-EMIGRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTODY CASE OVERSHADOWS SHIFT AMONG CUBAN IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Wiry and wearing a red St. Louis Cardinals baseball cap,
Carlos Rodriguez, 18, speaks in the vernacular of American youth.
Just finishing high school, Rodriguez has lived in Miami for the 10
years since he and his parents fled Cuba, where he said his father
was a political prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch at the Versailles Restaurant in the heart of Little
Havana last week, Rodriguez was speaking about the one subject that
has held Miami and people around the nation spellbound this month:
the custody fight over the 6-year-old Cuban boy Elian Gonzalez.
Rodriguez acknowledged that he shared the contempt for Fidel Castro
that many Cuban-Americans here feel. But he did not share the view
that Elian, whose mother drowned fleeing Cuba with him in November,
should be given to the relatives who are holding him here.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Cuban-Americans, Rodriguez has relatives in Cuba who
want to emigrate. ``I have a sister waiting to come over,'' he
said. If Elian is not returned to his father, who remains in Cuba,
President Castro might retaliate by prohibiting the legal
emigration of the 20,000 Cubans whom the United States agrees to
admit each year. ``I'd rather sacrifice one boy for 1,000 people,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   The strident Miami voices _ the P.T. Barnums of media
manipulation, the high-powered lawyers, the organizers of
demonstrations _ that have been filling the nation's airwaves and
front pages celebrate what they see as the martyrdom of a mother
for her child's freedom from Communist tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last week with some of Miami's 700,000
Cuban-Americans, most seem to remain united in opposition to
Castro. A poll by WLTV-Channel 23 here found that 88 percent of
Cuban-Americans also oppose the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's ruling this month that Elian be returned to his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   But tune out the racket, and what emerges from the feud over
Elian is a split over American trade and immigration policies and
fatigue with both the old guard's myths of the pre-revolutionary
Cuba and its plots to rout Castro and go back to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups have formed to challenge the Cuban American
National Foundation, which has long been controlled by exiles of a
generation ago. Two groups, Cambio Cubano and the Cuban Committee
for Democracy, would scrap the punitive measures against Cuba, like
the longstanding U.S. embargo, and move toward normal diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   But for the larger Cuban-American community here, most
differences with the old guard lie more in priorities than in the
substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much a difference of opinion as a difference in
agenda,'' said Lisandro Perez, director of the Cuba Research
Institute at Florida International University here.
</P>
<P>
   Max Castro, a sociologist at the University of Miami, said:
``These are people who do not participate in hard-line political
organizations. They have been able to transcend the hard-line
groups. They have overcome the hyperhatred of Castro; not that they
support Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   These mellowing views do not align neatly along the class and
generational lines that mark the assimilation of many other
immigrant groups. Much of Little Havana, though mixed today with
other Latino immigrant groups, remains emphatically Cuban. Cigar
rolling thrives, third-generation children speak Spanish at home,
quinceaneras _ 15-year-old girls _ still mark their transition to
adulthood in lacy white dresses at big parties.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the contrast between the threats and official
pronouncements and the daily life of Little Havana starker than at
the white stucco matchbox of a house where Elian has settled with
his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, who has petitioned a state court
for his custody.
</P>
<P>
   All day Thursday, as every day, television networks' big white
vans muscled against the house's chain-link fence with satellite
antennas on their roofs and 20-foot microphone booms hovering over
the small yard. Just home from school, Elian rolled out from the
backyard, chewing blue gum, wearing a new wristwatch and driving a
new battery-powered toy stock car.
</P>
<P>
   Four men _ Gonzalez and relatives _ seated themselves on metal
kitchen chairs at one side of the yard. Around and around Elian
drove, indifferent those watching, neither sad nor happy, tracing
the same loop. He did not nod or wave to the relatives keeping an
eye on him or to the reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The little house in Little Havana has become a sanctuary of
anti-Castro sentiment, where a few women stand vigil at the fence
every day to defend the interests of Elian's mother. ``His mother
died in the sea,'' said Marta Santana, who immigrated here 40 years
ago. ``He's living. She sacrificed herself to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the house, however, views are more diverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all a political thing,'' said Mike Freire, 45,
who came to Miami at age 6 and sells cigars made in the Dominican
Republic throughout the United States. ``They're just using the kid
as a basketball.'' He wants the child returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is the psychological effect,'' Freire said. ``It's
horrible, what we are doing to him. The politicians are wrong.''
This is not a view that Freire is comfortable expressing. ``You
have to watch what you say,'' he said. ``You might be accused of
being a Communist.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Rojas, 36, who works for an advertising agency and has
three daughters, ages 11, 10 and 4, clings to her Cuban culture,
requiring Spanish to be spoken at home and preparing Cuban dishes.
When her daughters start dating, she said, they will be chaperoned,
and they will not wear short skirts.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Ms. Rojas, whose parents fled Cuba in 1958 and
whose husband is a police officer, is a hard-liner. She would keep
Elian here and topple Castro. But she draws the line on the
American embargo against trade with Cuba because, she said, it has
worsened the lives of Cubans. ``A lot of people are starving,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Efrain Quevedo, 37, a sales manager for a food company, and his
wife, Terry, an investigator for the City of Miami, take issue with
the Cuban-American leadership's efforts to steer American policy
toward upending the Castro regime. ``Unless the people there do
something,'' Quevedo said, ``I don't think the United States is
going to be able to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quevedo takes issue with demonstrations that disrupt the
lives of others, like the traffic-stopping protests earlier this
month in Miami against Elian's repatriation. ``It's all right as
long as it's peaceful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing concern for newer immigrants of the 1980s and
1990s _ young and old, employed or unemployed _ is not so much
Castro and Communism as economic opportunity. ``For me, Castro is
nothing,'' said Luis Fernandez, a manager of the restaurant
Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   Managing restaurants ``is my profession,'' he said. He left Cuba
for Chile four years ago and moved to Miami only two months ago.
``Here, when you work more hours, you get paid for more hours.''
Someday, he said, he will start a business. ``I've promised myself
that if the government changes, I'd still never go back. This is my
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
