<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6916 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CROATIA-REFUGEES-ART-     01-15 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-REFUGEES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SERBS IN CROATIA, A PLEDGE UNKEPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNIN, Croatia _ Almost five years after Croatia promised to
allow refugees from the Yugoslav wars to return to their homes
here, the authorities still put endless obstacles in the way of
many of those who want to come back.
</P>
<P>
   An enormous Croatian flag, brightly lit through the night, rides
high above the medieval fortress that squats above this ugly town
like a heavy helmet.
</P>
<P>
   When Croatia declared independence from Yugoslavia in 1991, Knin
became the center of resistance by Croatia's Serbs, the capital of
a self-styled republic created with support from Belgrade by rebel
Serbs who controlled almost one-third of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Serbs are gone, and the town is populated almost
entirely by Croats from neighboring Bosnia, who themselves fled the
horrors of the Bosnian war from 1992 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like a science fiction movie,'' like ``Invasion of
the Body Snatchers'' or ``The Stepford Wives,'' said Jeannie
Peterson, director of the Knin office of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe, who knew the town in the war
years. ``The buildings look almost exactly the same, but the people
are completely different. This is a Bosnian Croat town now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton accords, which settled the Bosnian war, Franjo
Tudjman, Croatia's president, promised to help refugees return.
</P>
<P>
   But Croatia's local housing authorities ignore requests from
Serbs who fled Croatia after Tudjman's army swept away the Serbian
statelet here in the summer of 1995. The authorities use legal or
administrative hurdles to block the Serbs' return, refusing to let
them repair houses so smashed that not even the Croatian refugees
from Bosnia, desperate for a home, can live there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy has been clear,'' said a European diplomat.
``Promise that Serb refugees can return, but put every obstacle in
their path.''
</P>
<P>
   The Croatian authorities are understandably reluctant to push
out their ethnic brothers from Bosnia, and have often given the
Bosnian Croats temporary legal authority to remain in houses that
belonged to Serbs _ for centuries a substantial presence in
Croatia. And Zagreb has no real desire to have a majority of Serbs,
no matter how chastened, back in areas like Knin.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the new housing _ and there is not nearly enough _ is
assigned to ethnic Croats, not to ethnic Serbs, say officials of
both the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, the two international
agencies most active here.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few Croatian Serbs stayed on and survived, and those who
wanted to come back can't do it,'' Ms. Peterson said. The Croats,
she said, require the Serbs to have a lot of documents, which are
very hard to get. ``If Serb houses are damaged, it's hard to get
reconstruction assistance, which is supposed to be available to
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 26 villages in the Knin area that were part of a Croatian
government reconstruction program, only 6 are not purely Croat, and
even in those only Croat houses are being rebuilt, said another
official of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Of more than 4,000 applications by Serbs to rebuild their houses
in the Knin area, only two are known to have been granted so far,
according to an internal report of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Officials who work for the U.N. refugee agency say they already
have 3,000 Croatian Serbs on their books who have returned to the
area and need resettlement help, so they are reluctant to encourage
any more to return.
</P>
<P>
   And resettlement is complicated, like a three-cushion pool shot.
For a Croatian Serb to be resettled, either a house must be
restored or a new one built, or a Bosnian Croat family must be
repatriated to Bosnia, where a refugee Bosnian Muslim family is
probably living in the Bosnian Croats' house and must also be
resettled.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Bosnian Croats here, whom Tudjman offered
citizenship as ``migrant settlers'' on land formerly settled by
Serbs, express little interest in returning to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   According to the high commissioner's figures, said Guenther
Scheske, the agency's office director in Knin, at least 120,000
Croatian Serbs fled the area when Tudjman's troops retook it in
1995. Some think up to 200,000 or more fled.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,400 Serbs remained, and an estimated 30,000 have returned
since 1995 from Bosnia or Yugoslavia, although the Croatian
government says the number is 60,000. At least 18,000 Bosnian Croat
``migrant settlers'' have come here, along with 4,600 other Bosnian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The next prime minister of Croatia, Ivica Racan, vows to do
better in living up to Zagreb's promises of refugee resettlement.
He is the beneficiary of an opposition coalition's victory in
parliamentary elections on Jan. 3 that overthrew Tudjman's Croatian
Democratic Union, which had run Croatia since 1990. Tudjman died in
December, and a presidential election is scheduled for Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, NATO and the European Union have made better
performance on resettlement, and on Croatia's support for
Muslim-Croat cooperation in Bosnia, their main tests for better
relations with Zagreb. But Racan acknowledges that he must be
careful, as a new Croatian president will also have to be, not to
ignore the fervent nationalism in a Croatia that remembers
atrocities committed by Serbs in the 1991 war and domination from
Belgrade before that, in Tito's Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are cases like that of Danilo Stanic. He was one of
the many Serbs who fled in 1995. His restaurant and the apartment
above it in nearby Gracac, a flourishing spot for truckers and
locals, have been taken over by a Croat from Australia who came to
fight with the Croatian army and was apparently rewarded for his
patriotic pains.
</P>
<P>
   Stanic, 38, who lives down the road in his mother's house, which
he has slowly repaired himself, is working through the Dalmatian
Solidarity Committee, a local legal aid and human rights
organization, to get his restaurant back. When he and his wife,
Gordana, opened it in 1989, they called it Alpina, because they had
earned the money to build it from jobs as guest workers in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The new occupant, Ivo Kovac, has renamed it Tvrdi Kamen, meaning
tough or solid stone, a play on Hard Rock Cafe, and it is a popular
and profitable spot. ``He's earning money in my restaurant,''
Stanic said. ``He bought a new Jeep this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanic said he went there several times early on to have a
drink, but that Kovac avoided him. Two years ago, Mrs. Stanic said,
she spoke to Kovac, who offered a low price for the restaurant and
then said he could burn it down as easily, a conversation Kovac
denies.
</P>
<P>
   Stanic admits that like most Serbs here he fled out of fear in
1995, encouraged by Croatian Serb leaders. Like many, he believes
this mass flight was part of a deal between Tudjman and the Serbian
leader, Slobodan Milosevic. But he notes that several hundred Serbs
who stayed behind, many of them elderly, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Stanic went to Belgrade, then ended up in a village near Sombor,
where his aunt and mother thought it would be easier to live. ``In
Serbia the refugees live very hard,'' he said. ``Like me, they left
their property behind and work for very little money and everyone
misuses them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanic traveled here in 1998 to look around and file
applications to return and get his property back. He came back for
good, he said, nine months ago. He began fixing up his mother's
house and salvaging appliances, like his two refrigerators, washing
machine and boiler, from the Knin dump. ``The boiler just had two
bullet holes,'' he said happily. ``Now it's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stanic said he isn't even very bitter as he tends his sheep,
bought after he sold his car. He said he has all the right
documents and is sure Croatia will recognize his legal claims
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young Croatian state has not yet gotten on its feet,'' he
said. ``There will be changes here for the good, with a new
government. I don't think they'll behave like the old one. If I
thought differently, I'd go live in Slovenia. It's like this after
every war.''
</P>
<P>
   In the office of the Dalmatian Solidarity Committee, Lazar
Dragicevic, with a big red face and white hair, twisted his hat in
his hands as he described his problem in deciding whether to
return. Now 68, he is trying to get his pension restarted, but
needs more documents. And just to travel here from Serbia, where he
is now living unhappily in Banat, costs half as much as the pension
he isn't getting. ``I'm getting no help from the officials,'' he
said. ``That's why I came here.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to return to his house by the pretty Otuca River, but
his children are reluctant, his wife has high blood pressure, and
there is little work here except farming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best to be in your own house,'' he said. ``We're not
worried about the Croats now. We have no other citizenship. And
after four years, it should be possible to live together.'' He
sighed. ``It's a hard decision, though.''
</P>
<P>
   When Croatian troops retook the area in Operation Storm in
August 1995, Dragicevic and his family fled on tractors. ``We were
afraid,'' he said. ``The storm was coming, and they were hitting us
with grenades. There was no time to get anything. We just left.''
</P>
<P>
   Dragicevic's brother, Mico, 66, a shepherd who was out with the
flock, hid with his wife, Ljubica. Croatian soldiers arrested them
on Aug. 8 of that year and took them to Zadar, where they were
detained with other Serbs in a large hall. Five days later, they
were able to contact their daughter in Zagreb, who went to get
them. They returned to Gracac in mid-September, but their house was
looted, though not burned, and their animals stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 64 sheep and one cow and one goat and two pigs, and
everything was gone,'' Ljubica Dragicevic said. ``After that, no
one mistreated us. But they took us away and they stole everything,
and now we're too old to work.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly six months, Lazar and Mico had no contact with one
another and had no idea if the other had survived. Finally, the
International Committee of the Red Cross connected them.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame? ``Politics,'' Ljubica Dragicevic said, ``and
those who want to sit in high places.''
</P>
<P>
   They are urging Lazar to return with his family. ``We're both
illiterate,'' Mico said. ``We never went to school. We're not
up-to-date.''
</P>
<P>
   Ljubica moved to the stove, averting her face. ``I'd prefer our
people come back,'' she said softly. ``We have no friends or
relatives here. I do feel threatened. I can't say I'm a Serb, or
people immediately treat you differently.''
</P>
<P>
   She stopped for a long moment, then said: ``We're lonely here.
All the people here now are foreign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
