<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      01-15 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COURTING INDIA IN HOPE OF RESTARTING TRADE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite nuclear tensions and diplomatic false
starts that have dogged U.S. relations with India in recent years,
the Clinton administration plans to court India as an ally in
trying to restart global trade talks that collapsed in Seattle last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that closer cooperation will help defuse the
disputes between rich and poor countries that undermined the
Seattle meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Few expect the United States and India, the world's two largest
democracies, to forge a close friendship overnight. But
administration officials hope that upcoming high-level visits can
send the message that the rift between developing and developed
countries was confined to the chaotic Seattle meeting and did not
reflect a broader breakdown in globalization.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers will visit India this week
for talks with senior Indian leaders on a range of international
economic and financial issues, including the best way to restore
confidence in the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Summers will also pave the way for a visit to India by President
Clinton, tentatively scheduled for March, administration officials
said. It will be the first time a sitting U.S. president has
visited India since Jimmy Carter made the trip in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Seattle, there's definitely an economic challenge in
managing the integration between industrial and developing
countries,'' Summers said before leaving for India Saturday.
``India has had a major voice from the developing country
perspective. It's natural that the two largest democracies should
consider ways in which integration can be managed.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the administration is playing down the possibility of
tangible progress during Summers' trip, officials talk privately of
hopes that they are laying the groundwork for a ``quantum leap'' in
relations, forging a Third World-First World democratic alliance
that could prove warmer and more stable than U.S. ties with China
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, these officials say, the two sides would jointly find
ways to move globalization forward in a strategic dialogue that
would go beyond the often testy bilateral talks on regional
stability and nuclear proliferation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that if we can find a meeting of the minds with Delhi,
that's a strong place to work the Third World,'' a Clinton
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   India, though also eager for better ties with the United States,
seems less optimistic about a breakthrough in the short term. Some
Indian officials are still smarting from what they characterized as
U.S. pressure tactics at the Seattle trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides agree that the time is ripe to create a more
positive atmosphere,'' said Naresh Chandra, India's ambassador in
Washington. ``But I think the U.S. will find that things move much
faster when we're not pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of working out a new relationship with India was
on full display in Seattle. Apparently convinced that India might
back the U.S. trade agenda and help break an impasse with other
Third World countries, the Clinton administration put on a
full-court press.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who visited the World Trade Organization negotiating
session to give a lift to the talks, seated himself next to
Murasoli Maran, India's commerce minister, at a business lunch.
Clinton also phoned Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee during the
negotiations, and Summers cajoled his Indian counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, India stood four-square against the U.S. negotiating
position, deeply disappointing some U.S. officials. India was among
the developing countries that cried foul when the Clinton
administration pushed hard to link new trade talks to labor rights,
a position many developing countries viewed as a ruse to protect
workers in wealthy countries from competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hoped that India could be pried away'' from other
developing countries, Chandra said. ``But we do not believe that
trade and labor belong together.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, administration officials hope the time is right to push
ahead with diplomatic overtures to India. The two sides recently
broke a longstanding logjam over bilateral trade, with India
agreeing to stop requiring special permits for a range of imports.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the newly elected Indian government appears set
to open its market, speed up privatization of state-controlled
companies, increase economic growth and reduce the tangle of
regulation that has discouraged foreign investment. That should
provide the basis for a steady dialogue about common interests,
Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of issues that have tended to distract
us,'' he said. ``My trip is in the spirit of building a more
cooperative relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ECUADOR-DOLLAR-NYT &LR;      01-15 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-DOLLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOR'S SWITCH TO U.S. DOLLAR MAY BUY REPRIEVE FOR PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Just a week ago, President Jamil Mahuad of
Ecuador appeared to be finished, the only uncertainty about his
fate being whether he would resign or be forced from office by a
coup. But by announcing that he intends to replace the local
currency with the U.S. dollar, he has seemingly gained assurance
that he will survive to face at least the next crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a desperate, last-gasp measure, but he has bought
himself some time and got himself some oxygen,'' a Latin American
diplomat here said of the surprise move to try to establish
stability after months of an economic crisis. Mahuad made his
announcement in a televised speech Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Another diplomat described the plan as a ``Hail Mary pass''
attempted because Mahuad ``was astute enough to realize the
probability that he would not be around on Friday'' if he relied
only on the state of national emergency he had decreed Jan. 6 for
this nation of 12.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Radical though the shift to the U.S. dollar may be, most of the
evidence seems to indicate that Mahuad decided to make the change
more out of political expediency than ideological conviction. Just
days before the announcement, the former Central Bank president,
Pablo Better, noted in a resignation letter made public Wednesday
that Mahuad had dismissed the idea as ``a leap into the void.''
</P>
<P>
   As a short-term political tactic, however, dollarization has
worked even better than Mahuad, a Harvard-educated lawyer and
former mayor of Quito, had reason to expect.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken last week indicates that about 60 percent of
Ecuadoreans support Mahuad's decision and want to give
dollarization a chance to work.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of opposition parties, labor unions and Indian
organizations that was howling for Mahuad's resignation after the
sucre, the national currency, lost 20 percent of its value against
the dollar in the first week of the new year has been put on the
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this measure, Mahuad has been successful in changing the
national agenda, removing his person as the focus of debate and
substituting something else,'' said Simon Pachano, a professor at
the Latin American Faculty of Social Sciences in Quito. ``We are
not talking now of when he will leave and who should replace him,
but whether this plan can work and is good for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, protesters and opposition parties have shifted
their attack away from Mahuad to the dollarization program, which
they say will make the country poorer and limit its ability to make
decisions for itself. ``More than a dollarization of the economy,
this measure can be considered the Panamaization of the economy,''
said Leon Roldos, a Socialist legislator and rector of the
University of Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
   The main group representing Indians, who constitute about
one-third of Ecuador's population, was planning to go ahead with an
indefinite campaign of civil disobedience beginning Saturday as
part of an effort to drive Mahuad from office. But a parallel
``people's parliament'' set up by Indians has also attacked the
plan, saying that it would ``dollarize poverty, privatize wealth
and repress the resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's general popularity has gotten a much-needed
bounce from the measure, though, with polls indicating that his job
approval rating has jumped to 22 percent from a dismal 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to see him make a decision, any decision,''
said Juan Manuel Urbina Palacios, a stationery store owner in
Quito. ``This government has been drifting for 18 months without
anyone at the helm, and the economy has gone to hell as a result.
Something had to be done to stop the collapse of the sucre before
we all went broke and starved to death, and I guess this plan is
worth a try.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has clearly gained some breathing space, Mahuad is by
no means considered out of danger yet. For one thing, the unending
political turmoil of recent years has left Ecuadoreans convinced
that their heads of state can be replaced at any time for any
reason _ and Mahuad is even weaker than some of his predecessors
because his party does not have a majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the country even had three presidents in one week.
Congress threw the eccentric but popular Abdala Bucaram out of
office on grounds of ``mental incompetence'' and, after a confusing
tussle, finally replaced him with Fabian Alarcon, a legislator who
is now facing corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bucaram, facing charges himself, finally fled to Panama. But in
order to gain his party's support for the legislation needed to put
dollarization into effect, Mahuad has had to agree to changes in
the criminal code expected to lead to the dropping of those charges
and Bucaram's return from exile. Given the transitory nature of
political alliances here, there would be more turmoil if Bucaram,
as most analysts here predict, came back and withdrew his support
for Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
   The president also continues to be held in low regard by the
armed forces, and he lost his best and most loyal intermediary with
the military when Jose Gallardo, a retired general, resigned as
minister of defense Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a man, they have no respect for him,'' a diplomat here
said, describing how the military views Mahuad. ``And it amazes
them to have to stand up to their fellow citizens and defend
someone they view as corrupt and inefficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Pachano, the author of a book titled ``Chaotic Representation:
An Analysis of the Ecuadorean Electoral System,'' said, ``Unless
Mahuad can give clear signals that he will carry ahead the process
of reform, the lack of confidence in him as an individual will
continue to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, he continued, ``people will say yes to the song
but no to the singer'' and demand that a stronger, more decisive
leader take Mahuad's place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
