<SLUG> BC-CHILE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHILE'S ELECTION, CANDIDATES CONVERGE IN CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ On paper, the choice that nearly 8 million
Chilean voters face on Sunday could not be starker.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Lagos, an austere Socialist, agnostic and the man
President Salvador Allende had picked as his ambassador to Moscow
before he was overthrown and killed in 1973, is the candidate of
the center-left coalition that has governed for the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   His challenger is Joaquin Lavin, an ebullient, deeply Catholic
conservative who started his political career in Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's planning ministry and wrote several books defending the
dictator's economic record.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the many surprises of this tightly fought race has
been how Lagos, 61, has run to the right and Lavin, 46, has run to
the left.
</P>
<P>
   Although the election will probably be cast as historic whoever
wins _ Lagos would be the first Socialist president since Allende,
Lavin the first right-wing president since Pinochet _ the campaign
has been almost devoid of conflict, with both candidates skirting
discussion of human rights or any other of the sensitive issues
that make Chile's political past so painful.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are competing for an emerging majority that
rejects the political extremes: Christian Democrats, working-class
voters, tradition-bound women and a new, generally apolitical
generation that does not remember the 1973 military coup that
toppled Allende and brought Pinochet to power, or the intense
repression that followed it.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent campaign stop in the small agricultural settlement
of Chepica, Lagos, whose party once pushed expropriations of
foreign enterprises and worker takeovers of factories, suggested
that he would be a reliable friend of business. ``Investors all
over the world want to invest here to cultivate our land and
promote our coastline and rivers,'' he said, ``and Chile will grow
as the money pours in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin, meanwhile, shared a stage in Santiago with Mapuche
Indians and working-class voters from around the country, promising
to better the educational opportunities of their children. ``I'm
going to govern for the poor,'' he said in what has become a stock
campaign line.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has highlighted a paradox of Chilean politics
today: a society with a long history of political polarization and
conflict now abhors confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Pinochet in the 15 months since he was detained
on charges of human rights abuses while seeking medical treatment
in London has helped submerge the rather messy political past. It
has particularly helped Lavin, who has been able to take a number
of liberal positions _ including a suggestion that military
spending can be cut _ without looking over his shoulder to see how
the former dictator would react.
</P>
<P>
   But both candidates have also shelved potentially hot social
issues, like whether divorce should be legalized or abortion
sanctioned to save the life of the mother _ issues that touch the
lives of millions in a Roman Catholic country with high rates of
illegal abortion and marriage separation.
</P>
<P>
   And neither man, nor Chile's rather passive and conservative
news media, has made more than passing mention of the arrests of
dozens of former military and police officers since Pinochet was
detained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither candidate,'' said Loreto Rebolledo, an anthropologist
and journalism professor at the University of Chile, ``wants to
show himself to be a polarizer or extremist. So both are running as
centrists.''
</P>
<P>
   The news from London last week that a team of doctors has found
that Pinochet is too ill to stand trial and could return to Chile
as soon as this week added a potentially decisive new twist to the
campaign. The re-emergence of the former dictator could scare
centrist voters away from Lavin, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   But, even then, both candidates studiously kept to their scripts
on the stump, struggling to say as little as possible about the
general, who dominated politics here for almost two decades. Lavin
said he did not know whether he would have the time to welcome the
general at the airport on his probable return, while Lagos said he
could not celebrate the government's seeming diplomatic victory.
</P>
<P>
   Both suggested that Pinochet, 84, could still face criminal
charges in Chile, although it is hard to imagine either pushing
very hard for a divisive trial. Lagos will need to assuage the
military, which remains a powerful political force and continues to
support its former commander. And Lavin is unlikely to upset his
conservative, pro-Pinochet base, or several former Pinochet allies
who are likely to hold high posts if he wins Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of both candidates characterize their opponents as
Trojan horses who will show their true colors only after they are
inaugurated, and the rank-and-file activists for both men remain
highly polarized. Hinting at possible trouble if the election is
contested or even close, there has been a disturbing rise in
scuffles between the rival camps in recent days, and aides to the
two candidates have been trading charges of voter manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Lavin broke new ground for the right during the
campaign by visiting families of people who disappeared during the
Pinochet dictatorship, as a gesture of reconciliation. Last week,
he said he would ask the current defense minister, Edmundo Perez
Yoma, a Christian Democrat, to continue taking part in a new
dialogue between the military and human rights lawyers intended to
give families of the disappeared more information about them.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos, for his part, startled some fellow Socialists by seeking
out icons of world capitalism like David Rockefeller so they could
appear together in photographs in the Chilean press. He is also
pushing a plan to attract foreign companies into joint ventures
with the state-owned copper concern, and pledging to hire more
police officers to fight crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't aspire to the be the second Socialist president of
Chile,'' Lagos said in an interview last year. ``I aspire to be the
third president of the Concertacion,'' the ruling Christian
Democratic-Socialist coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has run a sluggish, cautious campaign that has neither
excited his Socialist Party base nor instilled confidence in more
conservative Chileans. Lavin, with heavy financing from business,
has run a slick, marketing-driven campaign that enabled him to hold
Lagos, once seen as the runaway victor, to a virtual dead heat in
the first-round balloting last month.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published Friday showed Lavin ahead by a whisker, 50.4
percent to 49.6 percent, with a margin of error of 2.1 percentage
points. The closeness of the race is in sharp contrast to the two
presidential elections since Pinochet stepped down in 1990, which
the center-left coalition won by landslides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
