<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 3 to 6 inches of snow will blanket parts of northern and
eastern New England on Sunday as a low-pressure system from Ontario
draws Atlantic moisture over a dome of obstinate cold air banked
across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, arctic air will retreat across parts of the
southern New England and northern Middle Atlantic states, but the
retreat will be short-lived. For, in the wake of the Ontario low,
another blast of Arctic air will arrive for Sunday night and
Monday, accompanied again by strong winds from the north-northwest.
</P>
<P>
   By early Sunday morning, the Arctic invasion will be underway
across the upper Midwest, where bands of moderate to locally heavy
snow showers and squalls will spurt off the relatively tepid waters
of Lake Superior and Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, precipitation will be widespread across the Far West,
aided and abetted by a extremely wide plume of mid-level moisture
from the eastern Pacific. Along the West Coast, a compact but
potent disturbance will produce fitful showers of rain from western
Washington to central California Sunday morning, with a few
thunderstorms, perhaps with small hail in parts of western Oregon
and northwest California. The disturbance will produce a burst of
snow early in the northern Sierra Nevada, with the burst shifting
to the Bitterroot Mountains of Idaho later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The broad Pacific plume of moisture will aid snows in the
Wasatch and Unitas of Utah, with snowfalls in the latter mountain
range challenging 2 feet by Monday morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Chill Wind &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, at the summit of Mt. Washington in northern New
Hampshire, temperatures hovered near minus 25 degrees Fahrenheit
while winds gusted to 100 mph. This combination produced wind-chill
values below minus 100 degrees. Though such a value warrants
extreme caution, it has little physiological basis. Wind-chill
values are an artificial attempt to measure the cooling power of
the wind on exposed human skin. Originally, wind-chill values were
tabulated by Paul Siple circa 1940, when he measured how fast water
in plastic containers froze under varying Antarctic wind
conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
