<HEADER>
A6953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-APPEAL-2TAKES-     01-15 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-APPEAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PRAGMATIC McCAIN IS CONSERVATIVE WITH A POPULIST STREAK  
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not long into his campaign appearances, Sen. John
McCain often jokes about two Arizona mentors, one from the right
and one from the left.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls how a nostalgic Barry Goldwater once told him that if
he had defeated Lyndon B. Johnson in the 1964 presidential race,
then McCain would never have languished in a Vietnamese prison
camp. ``I said, `You're right, Barry. It would have been a Chinese
prison camp,''' McCain winds up. ``He was not amused by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or else he tells how Rep. Morris Udall walked into a New
Hampshire barbershop during the 1976 Democratic presidential
primary campaign and said, ```Hi. I'm Mo Udall, and I'm running for
president of the United States.' And the barber said, `Yeah, we
were just laughing about that this morning.'''
</P>
<P>
   The stories break the ice and send the crowds into peals of
laughter. But they also do something more. They show that McCain is
someone who can reach across party lines, and they signal what is
to come: a tour de force by a candidate who at times can seem hard
to place along the modern ideological spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   What is puzzling about this is that across his 17 years in
Congress, McCain has had a rock-solid conservative voting record
except for his defiance of his party leaders on campaign finance
overhaul and antitobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition gave him perfect scores on its top
issues for years until he dropped to a 73 percent rating in 1998.
The liberal Americans for Democratic Action, by contrast, has never
given him more than a 20 percent rating in the last decade, and in
the two years after Republicans took control of Congress the group
gave him a score of zero.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the campaign trail, McCain's passions are more populist
than traditionally conservative as he bashes ``lobbyists in $1,000
suits'' or criticizes Gov. George W. Bush's tax cut as too skewed
toward the rich, saying that he does not think Bill Gates needs a
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought that Republicans were mostly concerned
about the working men and women of America,'' McCain says. ``I
didn't know our concern was the wealthiest.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly McCain strikes conservative themes, too, such as when
he calls for a permanent ban on Internet taxation or points out
that his voting record has been steadily anti-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here is an avowed small-government conservative who time and
again agrees with his questioners that programs deserve more money
and who just this week proposed a new government post for a
``reform czar.'' He wants to try out school vouchers, but will not
take money away from public schools to do so. Instead, he proposes
to raise the money for the pilot project by closing some corporate
tax subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain can even sound remarkably like a Democrat when he says,
``Too many Americans go to sleep at night desperately fearing
illness or injury to themselves or a family member because they are
without health insurance to pay the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he rejects ideas like former Sen. Bill Bradley's plan
for universal health care coverage as ``big government solutions''
and admits, ``I don't claim to have some silver bullet'' to solve
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's friends and supporters say that what is on display is
the thinking and improvisation of a man who hates dogma and canned
answers, who is more of a Goldwater iconoclast than a movement
conservative, and who, despite his rebel cries, is a conciliator
who wants to solve problems.
</P>
<P>
   He is visibly uncomfortable when he has to deal with the
polarizing social issues that have come so much to define left and
right in American politics. That may be part of the reason he
botched the incendiary issue of the Confederate battle flag flying
in South Carolina, when he tried to see both sides this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the process _ hardly in the spirit of the bus he calls the
Straight Talk Express _ he first said that the flag was a symbol of
``racism and slavery'' and then later in a written clarification
aligned himself with the pro-flag movement by calling the banner a
``symbol of heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John doesn't see things in a doctrinaire way,'' said Sen.
Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., one of McCain's closest friends in the Senate.
``He understands that issues are complicated. He's not afraid to
think out of the box.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel acknowledged: ``Sure he walks himself into minefields; he
walks himself into swamps. That's the down side in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who has worked closely with McCain on
foreign policy, said: ``I think what John is is a pragmatist. He
wants to get things done. He wants to find a place of common
sense.'' Kerry added: ``He's still very conservative. People make a
mistake not to know this.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the tone of McCain's campaign comes from his own gut
instincts and reactions to people. The senator, who is running
things on a shoestring, has only one full-time issues aide, John
Raidt.
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledges that in areas like health care, ``I'm not as
comfortable with it as issues I grew up with.'' Sometimes at his
town hall meetings he simply tells a questioner that he does not
have an answer and says, ``I'll be glad to educate myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An admission of not knowing all the answers is sometimes well
received,'' he muses to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain cites Theodore Roosevelt as a role model, and his
campaign tries to pull together all the disparate threads of his
thinking into a Roosevelt-style Republicanism that challenges the
party's big-business establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, the model for McCain is TR,'' said Marshall
Wittmann, a congressional analyst at the conservative Heritage
Foundation, who is part of McCain's kitchen cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt ``was inherently conservative, a very conservative man
believing in the institutions of America,'' Wittmann said. ``But he
also prodded these institutions to reform,'' he added. ``He was the
great trust buster, so he could give more legitimacy to
capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans, however, say McCain is straying too far from
his party's orthodoxy. After traveling with McCain one day
recently, William Bennett, the former secretary of education who
has been advising both McCain and Bush, said he told the senator he
needed more of a ``theme to this pudding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You know you're being outflanked here,''' Bennett
said. ``People wonder whether you're calling your conservative
voting record into question. You need to show some passion on a
couple of conservative issues on which you have a record already,
like missile defense or school vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as the first votes of the primary season near, has sought
to galvanize his party's conservative base. Originally Bush tried
to run from the center as if already in the general election
campaign, using his ``compassionate conservatism'' to distinguish
himself from the harder-edged conservatism of Congressional
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with McCain drawing support from independents and
moderates, Bush has tried to paint himself as the true conservative
of the duo. He has charged that the senator's ideas on campaign
finance law would ``hurt Republicans and hurt the conservative
cause.'' He has put heavy emphasis on his sweeping tax-cut proposal
and constantly tries to tie McCain to Vice President Al Gore,
saying that they are the ``two voices'' in the campaign who say his
plan is too large.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in South Carolina, McCain has been sounding
conservative themes. He has been running ads in which Rep. Lindsey
Graham speaks of McCain's ``17-year pro-life voting record'' and
says that McCain ``has voted to take pornography off the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is clear on the stump that he yearns for a middle ground
even on intractable matters like abortion. He regularly says that
single-issue groups have made ``a cause into a business,'' and he
implores people on both sides to work together to improve foster
care and make adoption easier. ``I'm tired of the polarization that
exists on this issue,'' he told one ardent anti-abortion voter in
New Hampshire recently, after saying that though he is
anti-abortion he would not use that as a litmus test for
appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing better illustrates McCain's desire for dialogue
than his friendship across party lines with Kerry, a decorated Navy
lieutenant who came home from Vietnam and led protests against the
war while McCain was being tortured in North Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   One night almost a decade ago, the two senators found themselves
sitting across from each other on a military transport plane flying
a congressional delegation to Kuwait after the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   The two not only became close friends, but they also worked
together to bring about normalization of U.S. relations with
Vietnam. Sometimes McCain tells his audiences how Vietnam veterans
searching for reconciliation are returning to see the country where
they fought and taking their children with them, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry says he has watched his friend change and grow to become
the remarkably unguarded presidential candidate he is now. ``John
was more closed,'' Kerry said. ``I think he would have shut people
out faster. He would have shut ideas out faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1452EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
