<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-PRIMARY-NYT &LR;      01-15 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BLOCKING NEW YORK VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Jan. 16:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush prides himself on his little-d democratic
style in his home state of Texas, but he has now fallen under the
spell of New York's exclusionary politics. In his campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination, Bush has joined a plot by New
York state party leaders to bounce his leading competitor, Sen.
John McCain, from the March 7 presidential primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   By filing objections to McCain's petitions in congressional
districts around New York state, Bush and New York's top Republican
leaders, Gov. George Pataki and the GOP chairman, William Powers,
have set the stage for challenging the McCain effort to get on New
York's ballot. A spokesman for the state party has said that any
challenge to McCain's access effort would be solely to ``protect
the integrity of the primary process'' in New York. Not so. These
objections are not about integrity; they are about narrowing the
choice for New York voters. They are about letting party leaders
control the names of candidates on the state ballots.
</P>
<P>
   State rules for adding a candidate's name to this year's ballot
are slightly different for Democrats and Republicans, but both
parties require thousands of voters' signatures on petitions, an
outdated political tactic that effectively limits choices to the
parties' favorites in the name of assessing a candidate's
grass-roots support in the state.
</P>
<P>
   For Democratic voters this year, primary choices will probably
include Al Gore, Bill Bradley and Lyndon LaRouche, who each
received more than the 5,000 required signatures statewide. For
Republicans, who need more than 20,000 signatures gathered under
intentionally difficult guidelines, Bush and Steve Forbes are the
only two candidates with almost certain access to ballots in all 31
congressional districts. McCain managed to get enough signatures
for only 25 districts. Other Republican contenders decided to
bypass the state altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Finding Republican signatures has become an especially tricky
business because of a time limit of about 30 days and a requirement
that voters can sign only one candidate's petition. So, when
Republican Party regulars snared more than 90,000 signatures for
Bush, they also made those 90,000 names automatically off limits
for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   What most New Yorkers do not realize is that challenging these
signatures is a seasonal industry, providing thousands of dollars
of legal and paralegal work for a swarm of veteran nitpickers
around the state. They follow a list of requirements with surgical
precision, excising the name, for example, of someone who says he
lives in the village of Montauk, not the town of East Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this unfairness, the state's party leaders are satisfied
at their lean ballot offering. There are no plans for Pataki,
Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver to reopen the state's ballots so that candidates can be
chosen by voters, not a few party bigwigs. What is worse, Bush also
seems content to run in this skewed contest.
</P>
<P>
   William Dal Col, the campaign chairman for Forbes, who spent
about $750,000 to get on New York's ballot, fumed last week at the
expense and effort. ``The Berlin Wall fell 10 years ago in
Germany,'' he said. ``When will it fall in New York?'' That is a
good question.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
