<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PHILADELPHIA-COMMISH-     01-15 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILADELPHIA-COMMISH-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA POLICE CHIEF LEADS WHILE WELCOMING BACK TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ ``Start locking them up,'' Police Commissioner
John F. Timoney ordered as he saw enough of the latest crime
statistics from a particularly rough southwest neighborhood. As he
frowned, the depredations flashed onto a giant computer screen at
his weekly meeting with field commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it's out of control out there,'' he declared, a
touch of his old side-of-the-mouth, New York Police Department
roots showing in his annoyance. ``I mean, two cars exchanging
gunfire before innocent civilians,'' he said. ``That's crazy. We
need a sense of urgency out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous glances were exchanged in the gathering of dozens of
subordinate brass in the Philadelphia police academy's gymnasium as
the commissioner made it clear he wanted a flood of personnel to
confront the raucous southwest drug scene. No one disagreed with
the commissioner until a respected 29-year veteran of the force,
Inspector Joe O'Connor, politely took it upon himself to warn
against police ``panic,'' noting that to shift too many officers
from such perpetually troubled areas as Sunrise might prove
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney beamed at the back talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't mistake a sense of urgency for panic, Joe,'' he said
with a smile and a glare that cut the room like a laser. ``We're
hemorrhaging in southwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Up from Dublin by way of a street beat in the South Bronx and a
prodigious rise to the No. 2 spot in the police hierarchy of New
York City, John Timoney is obviously in control as he completes his
second year as Philadelphia commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   As ever, he was bolstered at the command meeting by a computer
specialist recruited to pump out each new deed and pattern of crime
in the high-tech manner Timoney revels in. He was also gauging,
praising and challenging his subordinates for the usual three hours
of face-to-face dialogue, repeatedly invoking ``shoe leather''
policing as the point of all the sophisticated tracking of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders of the department engaged in this edgy new
thrust-and-parry, the Timoney touch was clearly on the job in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides _ the bottom-line statistic among police professionals
measuring success _ have fallen markedly across the commissioner's
reign. There were 420 in the city in 1997, then 338 in his first
year, as he began drastically revamping the department's analytical
and operational methods, and 295 last year _ the first time in 16
years the toll was under 300.
</P>
<P>
   Until lately, this city, like Baltimore and Washington, had been
resisting some of the national drop in crime. And now, in the same
way Philadelphia turned to the generation of New York leadership
groomed under former Police Commissioner William J. Bratton, a new
mayor in Baltimore has signed on Edward T. Norris, New York's
deputy commissioner of operations, to take on the day-to-day
running of its Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   This city's satisfaction with Timoney was made clear during the
recent campaign for mayor as the major candidates praised his work
and vied in their promises to keep him on the job. Mayor John F.
Street called the commissioner soon after his victory to go out on
two of the precinct roll-call drop-ins that have become the Timoney
signature.
</P>
<P>
   But still more satisfying to the commissioner seems to be the
back talk of Joe O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's a good cop,'' the commissioner said after the weekly
``compstat'' meeting. This is a command technique adapted from the
New York Police Department that is a high-intensity blend of
careful information and candid vetting of police performance. It is
at the heart of the shake-up of the 7,000-member force Timoney has
under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest lie told in law enforcement is, `We work well
together,''' the commissioner said, noting that the tradition had
been for commissioners to stay in their five-star bunkers. The
method he learned and helped develop in New York was to get in the
face of the police officers and share ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compstat is a great forum for really talented people _ you
spot them right away,'' along with the phonies, he said, heading to
a meeting of city elders. On the way, he stopped at a funeral
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cop's kid shot himself,'' the commissioner said as he
offered his city a hard-eyed look, driving through it without a
siren or flasher. ``Wonderful kid. No explaining it.'' A sidewalk
crowd of mourners, many of them from the job, took careful note as
the commissioner arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning friends and influencing enemies is time well spent,''
Timoney, 51, later explained, emphasizing the need to show up at
the scene of the city's cares and complaints.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As a street officer, he learned Spanish and ran marathons to
stay in shape. Now, while an ailing foot heals, he journeys from
his home in Rittenhouse Square and relives a classic Thomas Eakins
tableau three days a week, rowing on the city's shimmering river.
The serenity is a needed tonic, for the commissioner acknowledges
that he is frustrated by regular run-ins with the city's police
union and by the iron hand he says the city's board of outside
arbitrators exercises in protecting what he considers wayward
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even give detective shields out,'' he complained of
the city's heavy civil service tradition. ``The only way to change
it is to take them head on and use the bully pulpit every chance I
get,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't underestimate the better instincts of cops,'' he said of
his reaching out to the rank and file by praise and prod. ``Don't
underestimate their need for a pat on the back, to be on a winning
team, on the cutting edge of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said he was fortunate the city has strong news
media. The Philadelphia Inquirer recently uncovered a years-old
problem of the department's miscategorizing some possible rape
cases. Timoney ordered a review and tightened the procedures under
which charges are investigated, but also quarreled with the
sweeping tone of the articles.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in the Timoney department include an intense program
other forces are studying for dealing with the abuses of racial
profiling. ``When I came here, cops were getting credit for the
number of people they simply stopped every month,'' he said. ``Can
you believe that nonsense? We've reduced our stops by 50 percent.
You get credit when you lock them up.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said he most likely was working toward a ``burnout''
period two or three years hence when, he said, he might move to
federal law enforcement. ``Right now, my selfish ancillary goal is
to keep the feds out of Philadelphia,'' he said emphatically,
referring to the half-dozen federal court restrictions the
demoralized force was under when he took over.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In demanding the best of his new blue line, Timoney made sure
his most cherished mentors were at his swearing in: former
Commissioners Bratton, Raymond W. Kelly and Benjamin Ward of New
York. He seeks their advice, but he also holds dear the street
maxim he learned from his old South Bronx patrol partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name was Richie Sable, a tough, good cop, and he would
always say the mission of the police is to protect the most
vulnerable _ children and the elderly _ against the bullies and
cowards. For them, my cops here will take that extra step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
