<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-NEWSTYLE-JET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA PONDERING RULES FOR A NEW STYLE OF JET OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 
(ko) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The runway is 4,300 feet long, and the pilot's
manual says the corporate jet needs 4,000 feet. Can it land there?
</P>
<P>
   That depends on how the plane is owned, and even federal
regulators say the rules governing questions like this no longer
make sense because of widespread changes in the financial
arrangements that people make when they fly in business jets.
</P>
<P>
   Under a decades-old rule, charter operators follow one set of
guidelines, and corporate jets follow another. But a new class of
owners has suddenly blossomed outside either category, and that is
causing an uproar in aviation safety circles: those who have shares
in a plane.
</P>
<P>
   Charter flights _ air taxis, in effect _ must operate under
strict, airline-style rules. Charter clients are not expected to
know enough to make their own decisions about runway lengths,
weather or how tired a pilot might be. And the plane must be able
to land without using more than 60 percent of the runway's length.
</P>
<P>
   The company plane that ferries executives, on the other hand,
has looser rules; the owner is supposed to know more about safety,
and to take on more responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, 1,600 companies or individuals have
bought ``fractional shares'' in business jets, an ownership
arrangement akin to buying a week at a time-share condominium. And
no one is sure what rules should apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, scrambling to keep up, has
set up an advisory panel made up of members of the different
segments of the industry to draft new rules by the end of the
month. Agency officials are determined to change the safety rules
for business jets and to stay on top of the new economic
arrangements, before a crash forces them to act.
</P>
<P>
   People in the industry say that the crash of such a plane would
hurt business aviation, even planes operated as charters.
</P>
<P>
   Shared operations now rival airlines in the number of planes and
pilots. Some say they adhere to airline-style rules, but they do
not get airline-style oversight from the Federal Aviation
Administration, and critics say some operators, especially smaller
ones, may take advantage of looser rules. Those rules include
these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter and airline pilots may work 14 hours a day, including
no more than 10 hours at the controls; corporate pilots have no
limits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter pilots must have a weather report from the ground
before they may begin an approach; corporate pilots may begin the
approach, take a look and make their own judgment. Corporate pilots
also have looser limits on weather acceptable for takeoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charter operators must have a maintenance plan approved by the
FAA, with work done by mechanics screened for drugs; corporate
pilots may use any licensed mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the new type of ownership has meant more flexibility in
flying. Mark Fruchter, an air charter operator in Reading, Pa., had
two clients who wanted to charter his Beechjet to Hilton Head,
S.C., which has a 4,000-foot runway. He flies that plane there with
his family, but his customers were stymied by the rule about runway
length. Now they are fractional owners of an eight-passenger
corporate jet offered by one of Fruchter's competitors, and make
the flight routinely.
</P>
<P>
   To others, the looser rules may have brought too much freedom. A
fractionally owned Learjet 60, operated by Bombardier Aerospace on
a flight from Dulles International Airport outside Washington, had
brake trouble while landing at Hyannis, Mass., and ran off the
runway, destroying the plane. No one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The crash is still under investigation, but an FAA official
studying safety issues for corporate aviation pointed out that if
the flight had been a charter it would never have been allowed to
land at Hyannis, because the runway is shorter than called for
under charter rules.
</P>
<P>
   To charter a plane, said Jack Olcott, the president of the
National Business Aviation Association, all you need is ``a credit
card and a Yellow Pages.'' Such people should be protected from
risk, Olcott said. People or corporations who own their own planes
are much more sophisticated, and have earned the right to decide
what is an acceptable level of safety, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your lawyers get very deeply involved,'' he said. ``As an
owner, you're liable for that airplane even though you're not in
it. Nobody goes into fractional ownership with the same degree of
naivete that they book a charter flight.''
</P>
<P>
   But others in the industry say people who used to charter planes
but now own fractional shares to fly 100 to 200 hours a year
probably know little about the details of operating the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate-type aviation, whether by charter or under fractional
ownership, is extremely safe. No passengers have died in
fractionals in seven years, and other than the crash that killed
golfer Payne Stewart last year no deaths have occurred on charter
trips in the period.
</P>
<P>
   And the web of rules about safety, financing and ownership can
have perverse complications. A company bringing Stewart to Dallas
said it would pay for his flight. Even though he was a fractional
owner of a Learjet, he could not use it for hire _ it would then
have to meet the stricter rules for charter operations. So Stewart
chartered a different plane, which crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory group's meetings have been bitter at times,
participants say, with huge financial stakes apparent to all sides.
Charter operators contend that management companies for fractional
owners have prospered under looser regulations. Fractional
advocates say they actually operate at a high level of safety, with
potential purchasers often sending in auditors to evaluate safety
programs that are in many ways stricter than those used by
corporate flight departments or airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants say the panel is developing a hybrid rule,
borrowing some sections from the rule on charters and airlines and
some from the section on private planes. Whether this will pass
muster with the FAA remains to be seen; some officials there have
said they would be uneasy about adopting the lowest common
denominator.
</P>
<P>
   All sides agree one one thing: that the way the rules are
finally written and put into effect will be an important test for
the industry and the regulators, who often find themselves racing
to catch up with new economic models for aviation that have an
unexpected impact on safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1509EST &QL; 
