<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ALCHEMY IN ST. LOUIS FOR CARDINALS AND RAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ This city normally shivers in January, but the
excitement of holding its first professional football playoff game
is generating a warmth that cuts the chill.
</P>
<P>
   By noon Friday, the streets were filled with fans wearing Rams
blue and gold, turning out for two sizzling pep rallies. Organizers
handed out sombreros at the first rally. Later, a sea of blue and
gold Rams jackets and caps flooded Union Station. A band blasted
music and fight songs; cheerleaders led cheers.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This season marks the confluence _ and a clash _ of four
distinct legacies: St. Louis, the Cardinals, the Rams and Los
Angeles. This weekend the distinct identities may finally merge,
though only time (and winning) will tell.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the master of ceremonies introduced Cardinal stars of
the past: defensive back Roger Wehrli (1969-82), tight end Jackie
Smith (1963-77) and quarterback Jim Hart (1966-83). Each received a
hearty round of applause. But the introductions of the former
Cardinals crystallized the awkward juxtaposition of Los Angeles and
St. Louis; Rams instead of Cardinals, blue and gold instead of
cardinal and white. This was a mixed metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said: ``It's a very weird feeling; it's a tough thing, for
the old Rams and for us, too. We don't really have a home anymore.
Whatever history was here before is not going to be perpetuated by
these guys and certainly not by the Cardinals in Phoenix.'' Smith
has campaigned for a kiosk at the Trans World Dome with St. Louis
Cardinals memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place in the stadium where people can come by and
take their kids in there and say, `Here is St. Louis football
history,''' Smith said. ``It's not going to be put out there,
because football history here starts when the Rams came here as far
as most people are concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart has adopted these Rams out of an emotional necessity to
have football roots. ``They welcome me here,'' Hart said. ``I'm not
welcomed out there.'' Meaning Phoenix. Hart played on three
Cardinal teams that reached the playoffs. He is the Cardinals'
career leader in touchdowns thrown, total passing yardage and
passes completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to the Cardinal offices out there and felt like a
total stranger,'' Hart said. ``They go, `Who?' I said: `Hey, wait a
minute! I had a small part in building this organization.'''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for the National Football League from St. Louis is to
guard its rich history more rigorously. Baseball covets its history
with the intensity of a fetish, while pro basketball and until
recently the NFL were content to stay in the here and now. In an
ideal world, to keep fans' discomfort at a minimum, franchises
would be free to move but teams' colors and nicknames would stay
put, as with the Cleveland Browns. ``When the NFL allowed Mr.
Bidwill to take the red and white colors and the name, that was a
foregone conclusion: people were going to forget about red and
white and Cardinals eventually,'' Hart said. ``These playoffs will
do a lot more to make them forget about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans move on. They adjust, take what's given, and learn to like
it. In Indianapolis they love the Colts, stolen from Baltimore;
Tennesseans love the Titans, stolen from Houston. Here they now
love the Rams, stolen from Los Angeles. ``We're football fans,''
said John Hartfield, a native of St. Louis who began following the
Cardinals football team in 1969. Hartfield was enraged when the
Bidwills took the team to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us felt like jilted lovers,'' he said. ``When the team
left, they in essence divorced us, so we divorced ourselves from
the team. Bill Bidwill is a guy who steps on your loyalty and takes
advantage of you. We love the old Cardinals players: that's our
memories; that's our history.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century this franchise has represented _ and
played with _ the emotions of so many football fans. They began in
1898 as the Morgan Athletic Club in an Irish-American neighborhood
in Chicago. They became the Chicago Cardinals, the St. Louis
Cardinals and now the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   This is an odd marriage. The Rams began in Cleveland, moved to
Los Angeles in 1946, to Anaheim in 1980 and to St. Louis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil, the Rams' head coach, is a sun-drenched
Californian who coached high school and junior college in
California. He was a Rams assistant, then head coach at UCLA. As
head coach of the Philadelphia Eagles he played against St. Louis
from 1976 to 1982. Vermeil thinks the transplant has successfully
taken root.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans appreciate being able to identify with a
winning team,'' he said. ``I think now it's the St. Louis Rams and
no longer the Los Angeles Rams who moved here.''
</P>
<P>
   For old St. Louis Cardinals players, dyed in cardinal and white,
the Rams are still hard to digest. ``To say that the Rams are my
team, in my heart, no way,'' Hart said. ``The last playoff game I
played in was against the Rams, and they beat us pretty soundly, so
there wasn't much love lost there.'' In 1975 the Rams beat the
Cardinals in Los Angeles, 35-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head says, `Yes, I'm in St. Louis, and that's my team,'''
Hart added. ``But in my heart, my team is Jackie Smith and Dan
Dierdorf and Johnny Roland. They are my team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
