<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     01-15 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ANOTHER NIGHT OF RECKLESSNESS AND DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The games continue. League and life carry on. One day after a
service and hours before a funeral, the grieving Charlotte Hornets
came to Madison Square Garden Saturday night to play the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a guess Saturday if David Wesley, the point guard in
the other Porsche, was going to play. He stood up in the church
Friday afternoon in Charlotte, N.C., and said of his friend, Bobby
Phills, ``He was my partner in crime.'' A term of endearment,
perhaps, but with an ongoing investigation of drag racing as the
cause of the accident that took Phills' life, at 30, it was, just
the same, a peculiar expression.
</P>
<P>
   Not to overanalyze, because few of us can really imagine what
it's like being David Wesley right now. But there are more people
than Wesley realizes who can, said one who had survived a
comparable experience, one so harrowing it nearly swallowed him
whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you eventually find out in a situation like the one this
young man is in is that there are so many people who have been
there,'' said Bobby Ojeda. ``There are people who have survived
trauma, a plane crash, the loss of a child in an accident they feel
they could have prevented. They are out there, complete strangers,
and what I found is that they want to share these stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long time but these were the people that I did
listen to more than anyone else. If the opportunity arose, I would
most certainly do that for this young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ojeda, onetime Mets' pitching star in a fantasy we simply
remember as '86, would tell David Wesley a story he would find
chillingly similar, in that it involved professional athletes and
recklessness, bad luck and death, and Ojeda as the one, chosen by
some unseen force, by fate, to get on his with life after burying
two Cleveland teammates, two friends.
</P>
<P>
   It's been well documented how Ojeda couldn't, how he slipped
into self-destructive grieving that included long periods of
isolation, tormenting his wife, shutting out his kids. The sight of
them reminded him too much of the fatherless children left behind
by his buddies in the speedboat that March night in 1993: Steve
Olin and Tim Crews.
</P>
<P>
   They were out on Little Lake Nellie near Winter Haven, Fla.,
when it was too dark, and as the autopsy revealed, Crews, the
driver, had had at least one too many beers. They never saw the
pier. Ojeda survived because he was slouched in the boat.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't look at himself in the mirror for six months. When
people told him that he would eventually feel better, he felt fury
as never before. On the telephone Friday from his home in Rumson,
N.J., he said he was certain that people who care about David
Wesley were telling him the same thing; he could almost feel
Wesley's anger, his confusion, his need to revisit those last,
tragic moments, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can get a whole lot lower than I was at
the bottom,'' Ojeda said. ``No circumstances are ever alike, but
he's going to have issues, no doubt. And there's no blueprint, no
one man who has answers. I would tell him to not shun the people
who have been there for him. I wouldn't tell him to move forward
too quickly but to continue doing things you've got to do. To sit
and dwell isn't a real good idea. This young man, he's a basketball
player. It's something to hold onto.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ojeda said he didn't emotionally recover for three years.
It took him months to be receptive to therapy, a long and painful
process that is not to be confused with the psychological testing
baseball ordered for John Rocker. If therapy taught Ojeda one thing
that has helped him cope, it is that life is not necessarily an
off-target curve ball that can be gripped better next time. Young
people, especially athletes, often think of life as a
self-correcting process, but the reality is that things happen to
people, terrible things. In retrospect, what Ojeda and the others
did was careless, undoubtedly preventable, but they were imperfect
people.
</P>
<P>
   If people paused to consider the potential outcome of every
single act, maybe they would never do anything. Then they would be
withdrawing from life, as Ojeda tried to do after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Even while lamenting the irresponsibility of what transpired
last week it should be put in the context of a culture that is
fascinated with speed and toys, from kids with their Playstations
to adults who have made Nascar the country's fastest growing sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took the number of people who drive too fast in their
cars, what would it be, 80 percent?'' Ojeda said. ``Now, I know 80
percent of the people don't have Porsches, but I have seen guys in
Fords doing 85 miles an hour. What happened here is that they wound
up with the worst possible ending, and thank God they didn't kill
anyone else. But I think the racing is almost irrelevant. The fact
is that only Wesley was there; only he knows what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And more to the point, only he has to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   Ojeda, of course, is not the critic speaking, as much as he is
the survivor of almost seven years. David Wesley is at five days,
and counting. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
