<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-TRANSFORMATION-A     01-15 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TRANSFORMATION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAR THE ONE ABOUT GORE THE CHARMER? NO JOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(hm) 
 BY NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX CITY, Iowa _ The ordinary Iowans who turn up to see Vice
President Al Gore have often been startled by the candidate they
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the Great Soporific whom they expect, a man as wooden
as a giant sequoia and about as capable of giving an engaging
speech, they have often been surprised to find themselves wowed and
inspired by Gore in his stump speeches. He even tells funny jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly the most common remark one hears from Iowans who
have come to listen to his talks, even from those who are not going
to vote for him, is that he is far more lively, charismatic and
humorous than they expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, he used to seem kind of cold, but he was so much better
than that,'' gushed Lorene Jambura, a retired alcohol counselor in
Davenport, Iowa, after she watched Gore speak. ``He seems very
human, very relaxed and very down to earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the other Democratic candidate, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, falters in his quest for the nomination, he will have
accomplished something that many thought was impossible: Gore's
aides acknowledge that it was the pressure from Bradley that, over
the last few months, led Gore to emphasize an informal, folksy and
sometimes passionate style. This has been a gradual shift, perhaps
still incomplete, but it seems to be working with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw him, he was so stiff, just the way Jay
Leno used to poke fun of him,'' said Don Paulson, a machinery
operator who saw Gore speak a few years ago and was stunned by a
stump speech the other day. ``Now he's so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's style had seemed a major weakness of his candidacy. He
cannot be faulted for lack of experience or knowledge, but his
difficulties inspiring voters or lighting a spark among audiences
created doubts about his electability.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And they raised concerns that even if he were elected, his would
be a ``passionless presidency,'' a characterization sometimes made
of former President Carter's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Gore's presentations are inconsistent. At times,
especially when he touches on highbrow or intellectual topics, he
can come across as distant and professorial. His gestures sometimes
seem guided by an aide with a remote-control transmitting device.
If Clinton is a master at feeling other people's pain, then Gore on
those occasions comes across as so robotic that he barely feels his
own.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yet when he is fully charged, Gore can juice up his audiences
and keep Iowans almost spellbound, alternately laughing at his
jokes and riveted by his stories. He speaks in shirt-sleeves
without a tie, holding a microphone in one hand and strolling in
front of the crowd without a lectern or notes, his Tennessee accent
seemingly stronger than ever. He calls on members of the audience
and elicits their tales with the charm and vigor of a television
talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so glad to be back in Muscatine,'' Gore said with such
feeling as he began a speech in Muscatine, Iowa, that one might
actually have supposed he meant it. Strolling about in a brown
shirt and waving to a few people in the audience whom he
recognized, Gore chatted in a conversational tone, saying, ``First,
I'll tell a little about myself.'' Offering a brief biography in
which he described his parents growing up poor, he reminded people
of his past as a Vietnam veteran and onetime journalist and largely
skipped over his political career. He concluded by describing his
pride as a new grandfather and his conclusions on child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preferred technique is to give that grandchild whatever he
wants,'' Gore said. ``And if that causes any problems, give him
back to his parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore often asks all the grandparents in the audience to raise
their hands, and then asks if anyone has as many as 15
grandchildren, or 20, gradually raising the number until he has
identified and congratulated the person in the room with the most.
Although he sometimes asks the question several times a day, Gore
always seems suitably stunned that anyone could have as many as 27
or 30 grandchildren, and even if audiences know it is a bit of an
act, they love it.
</P>
<P>
   Audience participation seems to have become a central tool for
Gore. He often begins an event by going around the room and shaking
every single person's hand, even if it takes nearly an hour. In his
talk, he constantly asks for a show of hands on this or that, and
when he takes questions, he prowls the floor with a spare
microphone, asking people for their stories as well as their
queries.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on anecdotes, grandchildren and handshaking means
there is less time for hard-core discussions of the issues, which
plays into the campaign's decision to avoid controversy as Gore
sits on a comfortable lead in Iowa. And interviews with more than
50 Iowa voters who listened to Gore's speeches in recent days
suggest that at least in this state, the strategy is successful as
showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him three times in the last few months,'' said
Gertrude MacQueen, a longtime Democratic organizer in Iowa City,
``and I think he's getting better all the time. He's much more
relaxed than he used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bell, a paralegal who listened to Gore in Cedar Rapids,
said she was still not sure she would vote for him, but she was
impressed by what she saw. ``I think he's kind of funny,'' she
said. ``I was surprised, because people always say he's so
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore clearly studies his audiences and adjusts the message
accordingly. But paradoxically, he seems most effective and
passionate with farming and working-class groups, for whom he laces
his speech with ``God bless you'' and corny jokes that leave people
bubbling about how natural and sincere he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came across as just one of us, a down-home kind of guy,''
said James Munson, a retired auto worker who said he would probably
now vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In front of college crowds, Gore cuts out the ``God bless you''
refrain and becomes more measured and thoughtful _ but also more
distant and dry, and sometimes patronizing. Thus he ends up coming
across as most artificial in front of precisely the people who are
closest to him in education and background.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For years, one of the puzzles about Gore was that for all his
stodgy public image, in private he seemed relaxed, funny and
surprisingly willing to ham it up. He may well be, for example, the
best American politician at balancing a stick on his nose. Yet this
side of him used to vanish whenever Gore got within shouting
distance of a podium.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's informal approach has emerged as Bradley was capitalizing
on his image as an independent thinker, free from the constraints
of Washington. Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman, said the change was
partly a conscious effort to do away with the trappings of the vice
presidency on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice presidency is an impediment,'' Lehane said. ``You
want to strip it away, whether it's rope lines, stages or whatever,
and go back to the basics: a candidate speaking to a group of
people in a circle.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One factor that may work in Gore's favor these days is the
standard of comparison. In the past, he tended to be compared with
President Clinton, who is unsurpassed in his ability to empathize
with an audience and build a rapport, so that even Demosthenes
might seem stiff in comparison. These days on the campaign trail,
Gore is more often compared with Bradley, who has acknowledged his
own weaknesses as a public speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a better speaker than Bradley was,'' said Christine
Carpenter, a school psychologist who listened to both men and has
still not decided how to vote. ``Gore was more entertaining, told
more jokes and was more animated. He really had a better speech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
