u a BC-DRUGABUSE-WHEELCHAIRS     01-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGABUSE-WHEELCHAIRS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: is violence.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appan, who is studying at Kingsborough Community College and
hopes to become a business consultant, said victims like him got
little attention or support because they were poor and nonwhite. An
immigrant from Guyana whose sister and best friend were killed in
shootings, Appan said he was struck by the outcry over shootings in
middle-class schools across the country. But the phenomenon, he
said, is nothing new in poor urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that they did all this because of Columbine,''
he said, referring to the Colorado school shootings last year.
``Because it touched home. Because it was in suburbia. What about
the thousands of young people who die or are wounded every year in
the cities?''
</P>
<P>
   Hermina Jackson, an adviser to the state on rehabilitation
programs for the disabled who has been paralyzed for 30 years, said
the system had failed those urban victims. She said that under the
current welfare system, there was no incentive to get jobs, because
those people would lose Medicaid and face thousands of dollars in
medical bills. They would need more than $40,000 a year on average
to pay their medical bills, a difficult task for young men who
often have no more than a high school education.
</P>
<P>
   For former criminals like Johnnie Montalvo, the lack of programs
and the lure of the streets can be overwhelming. That Montalvo is
even alive is astonishing. During his 35 troubled years, he has had
buckshot and bullets fired into his arm, cheek, neck, left thigh,
right forearm, left buttock, stomach, left hand and spine.
</P>
<P>
   He has only one lung, and reconstructed intestines. A 1996 razor
attack left a 10-inch scar from his right temple to his chin. The
seats of his Buick are still stained with his blood from a 1997
shooting. A portrait of Lazarus, whom Jesus raised from the dead,
hangs from his rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in December on the Sunset Park street corner he has long
dominated, he was holding court again. As he sat in his wheelchair,
friends and gang members paid their respects. Everyone, it seemed,
had heard the stories. Montalvo says his paralysis is his penance
for past wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   And his wheelchair has clearly made an impression on some of the
young around him.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Rosario, 23, from Sunset Park, cited Mr. Montalvo and three
other people he knew in wheelchairs as among the reasons he was
becoming a police officer. ``He's like a prophet,'' Rosario said.
``It's all fine and dandy to be a tough guy, but in the end, 90
percent of the people wind up like him, or dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, Nick Corredor, a former drug dealer shot by a
rival in 1993, said he had learned his lesson. He enrolled in John
Jay College of Criminal Justice last fall, majoring in deviant
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Montalvo says his days of crime are over. He and Corredor speak
at schools against gun violence, part of a group called the
Gunrunners. Run by Ruben Tavares, 34, a former Bronx gang member,
the group ends its visits by having children play them in
wheelchair basketball, giving a sense of their confinement in steel
and rubber.
</P>
<P>
   But while Montalvo renounces his past, he struggles to make a
clean break. Last year he spent four months in jail in
Massachusetts before being acquitted of helping a man flee a
drive-by shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The birth of his first child in 1997 put new pressure on him to
``do the right thing,'' he said. He is raising the boy alone. The
mother is in jail on a drug conviction.
</P>
<P>
   He and his son are living in an East New York public housing
project. They subsist on $670 a month in welfare. Montalvo, who
talks of opening his own gas station, says he is eager to do right
by his son, but is trapped by a criminal record that bars him from
bank loans, public housing and many jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get discouraged,'' he said, as he sat on the corner. ``It's
hard out here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to do it,'' he added, ``but sometimes you have
to do things to survive.`
</P>
<P>
   Aiken said renewed religious faith had given him hope of going
to college and becoming a recording engineer. But he said despair
and lack of opportunity were leading many friends down the wrong
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my close homeboys in wheelchairs, they're
incarcerated,'' Aiken said. ``A lot of people in wheelchairs end up
going the wrong way because they don't have other options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
