<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-NOTES16-COX     01-15 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republicans wade into S.C. flag flap
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ The leading Republican presidential
candidates stepped gingerly into the minefield of racial politics
last week on the subject of the Confederate battle flag that flies
atop the South Carolina Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina Republican primary is Feb. 19, and the
state's largely white Republican electorate is listening keenly for
any suggestion that the flag should come down, knowing they risk
offending African-Americans and white voters elsewhere who find the
flag offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush said he would not fly the flag in
Texas ``because of the symbolism,'' but left it to South
Carolinians to decide what to do in their state. Bush also attended
a campaign event last week at a former plantation in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) gave varying answers so often last
week that he took the highly unusual step (for him) of reading from
a statement when asked about the flag.
</P>
<P>
   He began the week by telling a national television audience that
the flag is a ``symbol of racism and slavery.'' That description
upset some of his South Carolina supporters, and he amended his
words a couple of days later to say the flag is ``a symbol of
heritage,'' more in line with the language used by advocates for
keeping the flag flying.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after that on a radio program in New Hampshire, a
caller asked McCain if he sees the flag ``in any way as a symbol of
a movement that was to some degree based on the enslavement of
human beings?''
</P>
<P>
   His answer: ``Historians differ on the original causes. For
years it was viewed strictly as a states' rights issue. Later
historians have viewed it as also an issue of slavery as well. And
I think there's still divided opinion. But I don't think there's
any doubt that slavery played a major role, particularly as far as
fostering of the abolitionist movement is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to his campaign bus, reporters again asked
McCain what caused the Civil War. ``I don't think there's any doubt
that slavery was the prime factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN WALL RESURFACES
</P>
<P>
   _ IN NEW YORK STATE
</P>
<P>
   McCain lashed out Thursday at Bush's New York state supporters,
accusing them of trying to keep him off the March 7 primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the Berlin Wall came down. ... Let us not have the kind
of Stalinist politics that the state of New York and the Republican
Party have been practicing,'' McCain said, specifically citing Gov.
George Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers, both Bush
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans have complex and stringent requirements to
get on the state ballot, including obtaining signatures in all 31
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign has said it has gathered enough signatures to
get on the ballot in 25 or 26 districts. But Bush's forces in New
York are reviewing the petitions before deciding whether to
challenge them. Out-of-place punctuation is just one reason to
declare a signature invalid in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizonan appealed to Bush to let his petitions stand. The
governor declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important for all of us to play by the same
rules,'' Bush told reporters in Portsmouth, N.H. ``It's a process
to encourage grass-roots participation, and I am confident that
Chairman Powers will run the party in a way that's fair for
everyone. ... What's fair is that we all play by the same rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and Steve Forbes are the only Republicans who will be
on the ballot everywhere in the state. Three of the six Republican
candidates did not even try.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes filed suit four years ago to force his way into the
primary, and McCain has filed a lawsuit to make it easier for him
this year.
</P>
<P>
   GORE ACCUSED OF PLAYING TRUMPED-UP RACE CARD
</P>
<P>
   Willie Horton, the black man who raped a woman while on a
furlough from a Massachusetts prison, resurfaced in Democratic
presidential politics last week. Bill Bradley accused Vice
President Al Gore of race-baiting because he was the first
candidate in the 1988 campaign to raise the issue of furloughs
against Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The racial dimension to that _ there were probably a lot of
other people who fit into that category,'' Bradley said in an
interview with the Boston Herald. He said he would have found
another way to question Dukakis' crime-fighting credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign enlisted Dukakis to dispute Bradley's
claim. Gore aides and Dukakis pointed out that Gore did not name
Horton or state his race when he brought up problems with the
furlough program in a Democratic debate.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.), another
presidential candidate in 1988, also came to Gore's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Horton became a symbol of negative campaigning when George
Bush's campaign used his case and picture in a commercial against
Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ERA IN POLITICS?
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan says he represents the
future in politics. But he talked a lot about the past Friday at a
convention of students.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the students that he is the ``reigning champ'' of
the New Hampshire Republican presidential primary. He emphasized
his Republican roots by noting that he worked in the Nixon White
House ``before you were born, all during the Vietnam War, which I
thought was a just cause.''
</P>
<P>
   He did look ahead, as well. The former journalist and
presidential speechwriter predicted that NATO expansion would
eventually result in American troops fighting in northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know it, but you and your brothers and sisters are
committed to go to war if Belorussia tries to grab Bialystok from
Poland,'' Buchanan said in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   He also predicted that he would have a strong showing in the
presidential race this year, ushering in ``an era of multiparty
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
