<HEADER>
A6975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-15 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE VANITY OF HUMAN WISHES, ONCE AGAIN ON DISPLAY
</HEADLINE>
   (hm) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my favorite sports philosophers, Willem Hendrik ``Butch''
van Breda Kolff, who coached Bill Bradley in college (``Bill is not
hungry,'' he said at the time) and Wilt Chamberlain in the pros (he
benched the Dipper as a quitter), liked to declaim that ``each
man's strength is his weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch would say it so many times in so many ways _ ruefully,
bombastically, pointedly, kindly, self-referentially _ that it
seemed like an all-purpose description of the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it sounded like perfect descriptions of the three
very human conditions of Bill Parcells, John Rocker and Robert Wood
Johnson IV, the current trinity of sports, our secular religion,
the father, the son and the holy gold.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, the least interesting and most vulnerable of the three,
has been treated with the greatest disrespect. Baseball's
implication that Rocker was mentally ill because of his expressions
of bigotry seemed almost Soviet; if they don't agree with Kremlin
policy, commit them to the loony gulags. Of course, one assessment
of mental illness is in the extent to which someone does not deal
with current reality. If indeed Rocker is mentally ill _ and his
behavior in uniform could lead to that conclusion _ it is in his
bent for self-destruction. In the current reality, an entertainment
figure does not attack the public unless it is a cry for help.
Otherwise, it seems crazy to blow your career blowing off steam.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand (and he is a left-hander), Rocker is a closer,
a very special type of athlete, Horatio on the Mound, the Lone
Ranger riding in from the bullpen with the game on the line. His
arm is the final barrier that every foe with a club is trying to
break down. It's not paranoia when they are out to get you. Perhaps
it's paranoia if you can't shut it off. But maybe he has to stay in
character all the time so as not to lose his edge. Do remember that
baseball was not publicly suggesting that he get psychiatric
testing or counseling while he was playing and winning and helping
to boost ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it's not as if Rocker called a news conference to express
his fear and ignorance. He offered it to a magazine writer while
tramping through the woods waxing wildlife. It wasn't even faux hip
and smirk-funny, like the mercenary bump-and-grind of drive-time
shock jocks who pretend their cruelty is satire. Rocker should
plead the radio defense.
</P>
<P>
   The strength/weakness of Parcells is more subtle. Street-smart
bully that he is, Parcells, like New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
has created a land-mined area around himself. He is rarely called
out, and then he generally sneers his way past the discussion. In
the wake of the first reports of Bill Belichick's here-and-where,
observers sighted Parcells' fine hand pulling the strings.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief time of uncertainty, a few dared remind that
Parcells had a history of leaving every franchise in disarray, the
same way that Billy Martin or Napoleon would win but burn out the
bullpen. But then the backlash was lashed back, and it was pointed
out that every franchise had improved dramatically under Parcells.
Even le deluge apres Bill was not as deep as the troubled waters on
which he walked.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' strength/weakness is his willingness, nay, his need,
to take responsibility/control. Of course. The coach has always had
to make a collective out of rambunctious, often selfish youngsters.
But the modern coach is dealing with young millionaires who need to
be intimidated by the raw power of a confident personality who can
make front-office as well as on-field decisions. You can't adjust a
modern star player's game unless you can also threaten to dump him.
Why would anyone ever think that the manipulative skills of a
modern coach wouldn't also extend to his own job?
</P>
<P>
   But even coaches need daddies, sugar daddies actually, and
everyone seemed happy that the Jets got a bona fide philanthropist,
a man dedicated to giving away the money of his father and
grandfather. The National Football League apparently found that
more appealing than the sports expertise of Charles Dolan, who
controls Cablevision, Madison Square Garden, the Knicks and the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know either man, although I've met them: Johnson 10
years ago, when he was helping to pay for a public televison show I
was the host of, and Dolan last year, when I was the host of a
health show on one of his channels. Both appeared smart and
low-key, although it was not hard to imagine their competitive
juices.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast meeting, there was a current of restlessness
about Johnson; he did not seem self-satisfied and his questions
were probing. Dolan, self-deprecating in a speech to a group
honoring his philanthropy last month, introduced two good friends
in the audience: George Steinbrenner and Don King.
</P>
<P>
   For many rich and influential people who have quietly put their
thumbprints on their times but not their footprints in cement,
there must come a time when they want People Magazine/Sports Center
recognition, when fame becomes the name of their game.
</P>
<P>
   They have achieved goals with their energy and money, and in a
celebrity culture, they believe they can achieve even more as a
brand. That's strength and weakness. There are few faster ways to
boost brand equity than owning a major sports franchise. We give
them free publicity every day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that Rocker was not a football player, available
for the Jets to buy on eLinebacker. That would have been synergy.
Then the news media, instead of calling Rocker crazy, would call
him crazy like a fox, suggesting he was only feigning madness to
scare offensive lines and cause quarterbacks to sack themselves.
How wonderful if an enlightened new owner as dedicated to winning
as Johnson would buy him as part of a welcome-back package for
Parcells, a CEO-president-general manager-coach who would know just
how to spank and stroke him.
</P>
<P>
   The spin would go so: This boy is so fiery, so filled with the
toxic slime you need to succeed in the arena, that some of it just
leaked out. Hey, we can stand a little pollution in exchange for
all that light and heat. Just be glad he only talks dirty. He
doesn't crack up cars, beat up cameramen or kill his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Rocker isn't crazy enough to stand up to his
rehabilitation. Alas, that may be his real van Breda Kolffian
strength and weakness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
