<HEADLINE>
MARC DAVIS, 86, MASTER ANIMATOR FOR WALT DISNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marc Davis, one of the top cartoon animators who have worked on
Walt Disney films, died Wednesday. He was 86 and lived in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was also a designer, worked for Disney from 1935
until his retirement in 1978. He was one of a core group of
animators whom Walt Disney, borrowing a phrase used to describe
U.S. Supreme Court justices, called ``the nine old men.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Disney, vice chairman of Walt Disney Co., said Davis
``helped to define the art of animation'' and raised it to new
heights. ``His abilities as a draftsman were second to none,''
Disney added, ``and as a result, he often took on the most
complicated assignments of drawing heroines and villainesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was so highly praised for his work on female characters
that he was called Disney's ``ladies' man.'' He worked on the
design of characters like Cinderella and Maleficient, the evil
fairy in ``Sleeping Beauty,'' and imbued them with vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Another veteran animator who was one of the ``nine old men,''
Frank Thomas, said that a number of Disney people had a hand in
creating the appearance of Snow White, of ``Seven Dwarfs'' fame.
Davis then worked on her movements to make her look like a graceful
young woman, realistic and appealing. Thomas said that Davis ``did
the same for Cinderella.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also worked his magic on Cruella DeVil, the eccentric
villainess in ``101 Dalmatians'' who wanted to make coats from
Dalmatian puppy fur.
</P>
<P>
   What has been called Davis' talent for ``personality animation''
has also been lauded for enhancing the appeal of cartoon animals
like Bambi.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was born in Bakersfield, Calif. He received art training
at the California School of Fine Arts in San Francisco, the Otis
Art Institute of Los Angeles and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Alice.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Davis worked on the Disney theme parks
Disneyland and Walt Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of the rides for both parks have been designed by
Marc Davis,'' Christopher Finch wrote in his 1973 book ``The Art of
Walt Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He begins each of them as if he were planning a cartoon. His
first task is to establish the atmosphere and chief features of the
ride, including all the characters who will contribute to it. Then
he prepares a storyboard, which gives the project a structure and a
sequence.'' Davis also worked on other Disney recreational sites.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994 the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences has
held an annual ``Marc Davis Lecture on Animation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
