<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AMERICA'S-CUP-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CHALLENGERS REMAIN IN AMERICA'S CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (hm) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The hammerhead sharks and fishermen who
frequent the Hauraki Gulf will have a few days' respite from the
television helicopters and the spectator fleet that have disrupted
their routines of late.
</P>
<P>
   For now but not for long, the America's Cup races among the
challengers are over on the unpredictable stretch of water that
local yachting hero Peter Blake calls, quite appropriately, ``a
natural amphitheater.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 of the original 11 challengers remain. And though there
have been surprises in this marathon disguised as a regatta _ Young
America's early demise and Stars and Stripes' strong finish and
eventual defeat _ precious few are surprised to see that Prada
Challenge and America One have emerged as the Louis Vuitton Cup
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Prada, which represents Italy's Yacht Club Punta Ala, has a
single sponsor, which deals in luxury and has afforded its team
exactly that in its first bid for the Cup. The Italians were the
first challenger to complete their compound here, and the first to
build their two boats. A year ago, they were already in Auckland,
honing their skills and learning the vagaries of the gulf.
</P>
<P>
   America One, which represents San Francisco's St. Francis Yacht
Club, has had to work much harder to pay its considerable bills.
``For me,'' said the skipper and syndicate head, Paul Cayard, ``the
toughest part was last spring and summer, dealing with the stress
of pushing the program forward operationally and hiring people. I
was telling them we were solid as a rock, while knowing that I
didn't have all the money yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the combination of a top yacht designer (Bruce Nelson) and a
fine crew (which includes John Kostecki and Gavin Brady) and
Cayard, one of the most able and visible personalities in the
sport, ended up producing a successful campaign. And though Cayard
says he ``still needs to raise a million bucks to get all the way
to March,'' the performance of his new boat, USA-61, in the
semifinals should help the cause.
</P>
<P>
   With his French father, American mother, Swedish wife and deep
connections with Italy (he skippered Il Moro di Venezia in the 1992
America's Cup finals), Cayard can claim to represent a number of
constituencies. And after winning the prestigious Whitbread Round
the World race in his first attempt in 1998, he is in position to
become yachting's leading man if he can defeat Prada and then the
defenders, Team New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   America One holds a 3-2 edge over Prada in this regatta, but one
of those victories came when the Italians' mast snapped on the
first leg. The other four races have been won by margins of 17
seconds, one minute, 23 seconds and, most recently and memorably,
eight seconds, when the two boats sailed the final leg within a few
meters of each other and with the crews screaming at each other and
the referees. America One won that round, but it remains to be seen
which boat Prada will use against the Americans in the challengers'
finals, which begin Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be ITA-45, which they used in the first two round robins
and the semifinals? Or the newer ITA-48, which was used in the
third round robin and has been modified?
</P>
<P>
   Skipper Francesco de Angelis said that because of the
unpredictable weather, the decision will be made and announced at
the last possible minute. This being Auckland, each boat must be
able to thrive in all conditions. Both syndicates will announce
their choices on Jan. 20.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Looking at ITA-45 and USA-61, Stars and Stripes tactician Tom
Whidden said, ``I think they're both pretty good boats.'' He added:
``Probably America One might be a little better in the light air,
and Prada might be a little better in the breeze. And for sure
America One, the way it is today, is a little faster downwind than
Prada.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: In Cayard and the Italians, the America's
Cup, seldom a ratings buster (especially when the protests start to
fly), has an attractive challenger matchup and an audience on both
sides of the Atlantic, as well as in sailing-crazy Auckland. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1547EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FACES-ELECTORATE16-CO     01-15 2480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACES-ELECTORATE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parties try to court a changing black electorate
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton is the Democrats' not-so-secret weapon
among black Americans. But the president is not on this year's
ballot and that concerns Rep. Bennie Thompson (D-Miss.).
</P>
<P>
   Black voters have turned out in force to support Clinton and
those he has campaigned for. The president has astronomical
approval ratings from African-Americans, as high as 87 percent in
some polls.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bill Bradley nor Al Gore, the Democratic candidates for
president, has yet to generate anywhere near the same level of
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   And for Democrats, the fewer African-Americans who vote, the
harder it is to win elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an eternal optimist, but I'm also a realist and looking at
it right now, we have a lot of ground to cover before November
2000,'' said Thompson, a 30-year veteran of Deep South politics.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Democratic nominee can reach Clintonian heights
among black voters will go a long way toward determining his fate,
especially in some Southern states. Some Republicans believe Texas
Gov. George W. Bush also would make inroads among black voters if
he is the GOP nominee, but he will have to overcome a legacy of
distrust of the Republican Party by African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Thompson's worry about black voter turnout lies a story
of remarkable political loyalty. Democratic presidential candidates
have won at least 83 percent of the votes of African-Americans in
every election since 1964. That includes the Republican landslides
of 1972 and 1984 in which Richard Nixon and Ronald Reagan won 49
states.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more African-Americans identify themselves as
independents, believing that the Democratic Party takes them for
granted. ``We're disrespected by one party and ignored by the
other,'' said Georgia Rep. Tyrone Brooks, a Democrat who has
supported Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is most pronounced among younger people.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Williams, a Republican who heads Black America's Political
Action Committee, said Democrats should see the growing
disaffection of younger black voters as ``a warning sign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans are moderate to conservative on public
policy issues. There is no reason why the Democratic Party should
have a monopoly on our votes,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Issue by issue, Republicans would seem to be able to compete
with the Democrats, said David Bositis, an analyst with the Joint
Center for Political and Economic Studies in Washington. For
example, black Americans are no less receptive to tough penalties
for criminals than are Americans as a whole, and church-going
African-Americans tell poll takers that they are open to
restrictions on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks have, in fact, given Republican candidates up to a third
of their votes _ spectacularly strong showings for GOP candidates _
in scattered elections. ``We will no longer blindly support a
Democrat,'' said the Rev. Emmanuel Cleaver, a Democrat and the
former mayor of Kansas City, referring to a recent Senate election
in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   But those occasions are the strong exception to the rule over
the past 40 years. Black voters are, by and large, Democratic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they grow impatient with Democrats, they rarely move
into the Republican column. ``The level of mistrust is too great
and the party has done nothing to try to ease it,'' Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in the words of Renee Amoore, who heads the GOP's drive to
recruit African-Americans, ``Black people see Republicans as people
with two heads.''
</P>
<P>
   A MATTER OF TRUST
</P>
<P>
   A number of recent events illustrate the problem Republicans
face in attracting support from the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, black residents of South Carolina filed a
complaint with the U.S. Justice Department that alleges the South
Carolina Republican Party deliberately closed polling places in
black areas during the last two presidential primaries, which are
open to all voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans say, 'See, we hold this open primary.' But what
they're doing is holding a white primary,'' said A. Lee Parks, an
Atlanta lawyer who is best known for his advocacy on behalf of
opponents of majority-black electoral districts and affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if only 5 or 10 percent voted Republican _ it doesn't
matter,'' Parks said. ``You have to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans denied that race was at play in their decision to
close some polling places. But Democrats jumped all over the issue,
although they hardly could be in favor of having more blacks vote
in the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   Also in South Carolina, controversy over the Confederate battle
flag, which flies atop the state Capitol, caused headaches for
Republican presidential candidates. They did not want to offend
white South Carolinians who vote in the GOP primary, but anything
other than a condemnation of the flag might serve to reinforce
perceptions of Republican insensitivity to black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the South Carolina incident, Donna Brazile, Gore's
campaign manager, asserted that Republicans use such high-profile
African-Americans as Gen. Colin Powell and Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma as political props.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans bring out Colin Powell and J.C. Watts because
they have no program, no policy,'' Brazile said. ``They'd rather
take pictures with black children than feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   There were cries of outrage from Republicans, including Powell
and Watts. Gore and Brazile offered apologies of sorts to Powell,
but no other prominent African-American or Democrat challenged the
premise of Brazile's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   And her words were only her most recent efforts to galvanize
African-American support for Gore by accusing Republicans of racial
insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party's tepid response from African-Americans may
be a public relations problem, which could be corrected. Or it
could reflect a fundamental incompatibility. But whatever the
reason, it remains a vexing problem that shows no signs of easing
this year, not even if Bush is the party's presidential nominee,
according to Rusty Paul, the former Georgia Republican Party
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In November 2000, you'll see traditional voting patterns take
hold,'' Paul said glumly. He tried to recruit black Georgians
during his four years as chairman from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who works for Republican Steve Forbes' presidential
campaign, was especially discouraged by the final weeks of the 1998
campaign in Georgia, when Republican candidates for governor and
lieutenant governor made what were widely perceived to be
race-based appeals to conservative white voters.
</P>
<P>
   One Mitch Skandalakis ad, for instance, criticized Lt. Gov. Mark
Taylor for supporting a change in the state flag and maintenance of
``racial quotas'' in state programs.
</P>
<P>
   Both Guy Millner and Skandalakis lost their elections, and
``three TV commercials probably voided everything I did in four
years,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   CYNICISM AND POWER
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who can still count on getting the vast majority of
black votes, are focusing their efforts on turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-nine-year-old Byrdie Malbory helped register more than
1,000 new voters in Atlanta last year. But she complained that she
faces cynicism about the value of voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been trying to figure it out. Here's a white Republican
and here's a white Democrat and people tell me, 'What difference
does it make? They all stand for the same thing,''' Malbory said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been able to achieve incremental increases in the
turnout of minority voters in selected races. Democrats elected
Ronnie Musgrove governor of Mississippi, partly on the strength of
a strong showing from black voters, even though Musgrove lacked
strong ties to African-Americans, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   A concerted campaign to get blacks to the polls included three
intensive days of campaigning by Jesse Jackson and 50,000
pre-recorded telephone calls from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who were not at home and got it on their answering
machines were taking their recorders to church to prove the
president called,'' Thompson said, chuckling. ``These are people
who never in their wildest dreams ever expected to hear the
president's voice. ... I heard people saying, 'I'm going to have to
vote now.'''
</P>
<P>
   A similar turn of events helped a Democrat win a narrow victory
in the Philadelphia mayor's race. There, appearances by Clinton
late in the campaign were credited with driving up turnout among
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to think where we would have been without Clinton,''
said Regina Thomas, a Washington-based consultant to the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Similar targeted drives should work again in 2000, Thomas said.
In Florida, voters may have a say on affirmative action programs,
which Rep. Alcee Hastings (D-Fla.) predicted would produce a huge
black vote.
</P>
<P>
   One of the proving grounds will undoubtedly be Missouri, where
Sen. John Ashcroft, a Republican, faces a tough challenge from
Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan.
</P>
<P>
   Race already has taken center stage in the campaign. Ashcroft
and Sen. Christopher ``Kit'' Bond, also a Missouri Republican, led
fellow Republicans in rejecting the nomination of Ronnie White to a
federal judgeship.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans voted along party lines to reject White on the
grounds that he is too lenient when it comes to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   White, a justice on the Missouri Supreme Court, is
African-American, and his supporters alleged that the Republicans
were playing racial politics with the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen such a statewide organization like the one
that has mobilized against Ashcroft,'' Cleaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver was one of several leading African-Americans in Missouri
to back Bond in his 1998 election, when he ran against Attorney
General Jay Nixon. Nixon put off some blacks with his handling of
lawsuits over school desegregation and busing.
</P>
<P>
   Bond also built ties to the black community by helping direct
federal housing funds to Kansas City as chairman of a Senate
Appropriations subcommittee, Cleaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the black leaders in Missouri who backed Bond were
chastened when the senator announced his opposition to White, and
they have vowed to seek vengeance against Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Carnahan have tried to muddy the issue by digging
up 40-year-old photos of Carnahan in black face when he performed
in minstrel shows as a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver predicted the move would backfire because Carnahan has a
solid record on civil rights issues. ``All it will end up doing is
reminding people that Ashcroft led the charge against Ronnie
White,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   RIPE FOR CHANGE?
</P>
<P>
   But the Missouri campaigns bring into relief the issue of
whether Democrats deserve so many votes from black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   By most economic measures, the Clinton administration has been
good for black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy has helped raise black household incomes, cut
black unemployment rates and reduce poverty at rates faster than
for those of whites.
</P>
<P>
   But African-Americans still fare worse than whites in most
categories, and little has changed for the very poor, in which
blacks are disproportionately represented.
</P>
<P>
   On another level, Clinton has had a mixed record at best on
issues of concern to African-Americans, said Ronald Walters, a
political scientist at the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the worst things that have happened were the crime
bill and welfare reform, both of which Clinton supported,'' Walters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton intended both issues to appeal to moderate and
conservative white voters in his re-election campaign in 1996,
Walters said. But black Americans _ disproportionately represented
in prisons and on the welfare rolls _ had the most to lose from
harsher prison sentences and limits on government assistance
contained in both pieces of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But one other thing happened that galvanized black support for
Clinton: impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here were blacks who felt they had been put upon by the right
and Clinton was being punished by the right and there was a
tremendous sense of identity,'' Walters said.
</P>
<P>
   But with Clinton set to leave office and impeachment a rapidly
fading memory, black Republicans believe the time is ripe for a
major push.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's candidacy and his message of compassionate conservatism
should appeal to black voters, said Terea Jeter Chappell, the
president of the Republican Vanguard, an organization of black
Republicans in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the things this man has done in the state of
Texas, test scores for black children have increased
dramatically,'' Chappell said. ``That's why he received 27 percent
of the black vote in his re-election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's support for something he calls affirmative access also
may help to blunt criticism of Republicans who want to end racial
preference programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's term is vague, but he has stated his clear opposition to
quotas. His call for equal opportunity may get a warm reception
from African-Americans, Chappell said.
</P>
<P>
   Amoore, who chairs the Republican Party's New Majority Council,
acknowledged the difficulty of addressing the affirmative action
issue when appealing for black support. ``It makes it real hard.
When you go into the black churches, you always get the question on
affirmative action,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Paul is pessimistic about Republican chances in the
black community, Amoore said she can break down resistance. ``My
thing is, all Republicans are not far to the right,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Smith, a losing candidate for the Virginia House of
Delegates last year, was succinct in his advice to his party. ``We
need to get off the anti-affirmative action kick,'' said Smith, who
is black.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting a sea of change anytime soon in the votes
of black Americans. Republicans appear far more interested in
drawing Hispanic votes this year, believing Bush's success in Texas
will translate into a strong showing nationally if he's the
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But even slight increases in the number of blacks who vote for
Republicans could cause seismic shifts in Southern elections, where
Republicans already command large majorities among white voters.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Glenn, a black Republican running for Congress from
Georgia, said the party can only slowly change its image of being
dominated by southern white males.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton had it right when he said, 'I'm, going to make
my cabinet look like America,''' Glenn said. ``We've got to run
candidates for the school board, local offices, state and federal
office and the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
