<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT RATE OF NEW YORK POLICE OFFICERS RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Capt. John Murolo joined the Police Department
in 1979, he says, he intended to spend at least 25 years on the
job. But last November, when Murolo, the commander of the 114th
Precinct in Queens, became eligible for retirement at the end of
his 20th year, he waited only a few weeks before filing his papers
and leaving the force for a new career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something that is making people like me, who should
be the future of the job, leave,'' said Murolo, who is now a
security official at Columbia University. ``It is much more
difficult to be a precinct commander today than it was years ago.
You are held accountable for everything, and the hours that the
process stole from my family absolutely impacted on my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Murolo was part of a surge of retirements last year that union
officials say depleted the force of many of its most skilled and
experienced supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 some 66 officers who held the rank of captain or above
filed for retirement, a 53 percent increase over the year before,
when 43 filed for retirement, according to department statistics.
In addition, during the last six months, 96 lieutenants retired, or
twice as many as in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say the increase is really just a return to an
established pattern, set several years ago, when every year 60 or
so high-ranking officers would retire. For example, in 1996, 65
officers who held the rank of captain or above filed for
retirement, they said. And they said the officers who were leaving
now were, as often as not, being drawn from their jobs by
employment opportunities spawned by the vibrant economy.
</P>
<P>
   But union officials said the departures were also greatly
influenced by what they described as the officers' frustrations
with a constant pressure to produce, a burden that they said has
fallen particularly hard on precinct commanders as they struggle to
secure continuing drops in crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among captains, the mind-set used to be `40 and out,''' said
John Driscoll, the president of the Captains Endowment Association.
``But the mind-set now is `20 and out' because the morale level is
so perceptively different that, given any opportunity to leave,
they go.''
</P>
<P>
   Several police officials said they considered talk of poor
morale to be something of a fixture of life on the force, like the
green globe lights that greet officers at the front doors of many
station houses. Often, they said, the discussion of slumping morale
grows louder when contracts are about to expire, as they are now,
and unions begin to jockey for leverage at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Michael Markman, who commands the Personnel Bureau, said a
larger factor in the decision of many officers to leave was their
ability to time their departures to coincide with a 6 percent
salary increase that is to go into effect March 1. With accumulated
leave for unused vacation and sick time, many supervisors were able
to file for retirement many months ago and will be carried on the
payroll through March, when the raise will be part of their pension
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Markman said that often even those retiring officers who do not
secure a job in the private sector find that with tax breaks and
other factors, their yearly pension payments come close to matching
their take-home pay while they were working.
</P>
<P>
   A large number of officers started to qualify for full
retirement benefits last November after a four-year lull stemming
from hiring limits in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of many senior officers would accelerate a trend
in which the experience level of supervisors has dropped in recent
years. For example, in 1995, more than 70 percent of the officers
who held the rank of captain or above had over 20 years on the job.
Today less than 50 percent do.
</P>
<P>
   But Markman said that supervisors who have less time on a job
are not necessarily less qualified, especially since many of the
younger captains came to the department better educated than their
predecessors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This young agency is achieving remarkable drops in crime and
addressing quality-of-life issues that were never addressed before
by the more senior agency,'' he said. ``They're out there. They're
energized.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Scotto, president of the Detectives Endowment
Association, said book knowledge alone could never replace the sort
of street smarts that veteran officers acquire on the job. ``In a
year and a half I expect to lose most of the senior
investigators,'' he said, ``and these are the premier
investigators, the ones with the most experience. You can't replace
those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The department is trying to retain its talented people by
expanding the number of promotional opportunities, Markman said.
For example, he said, there are 468 captains today, compared with
394 four years ago. The increased number means there is an ample
supply of skilled replacements when veteran commanders retire,
Police Commissioner Howard Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' Safir said, ``we have tons of people who are
qualified to be precinct commanders, and we get to cherry-pick them
and select the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Several commanders who retired recently predicted that the
department would have to turn to its deep bench very soon, because,
they said, they expected the number of captains and other
supervisors filing for retirement to continue to increase this
year. Already, during the first 10 days of 2000, five officers who
hold the rank of captain or above have put in their paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Costello, who was the second-in-command in the vice
division until he filed his papers last October, said many captains
wince when they see qualified commanders transferred for slight
crime increases in their precincts. For some, he said, the pressure
to produce and avoid such a fate can become unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We end up brutalizing these cops to get your numbers,'' he
said. ``You take these rookies and you make them into summons
machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Palamar, who was the No. 2 commander for the Police
Lab until he filed for retirement last month, said his decision to
leave was complex, and included an interest in seeking
opportunities outside the department. But many of his colleagues,
he said, cited job stress in discussing their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With beepers and cell phones you found yourself working 24
hours a day,'' he said. ``People would tell me that if they worked
in private industry, in the same kind of job, they would be making
300 grand with a chauffeur and other perks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
