<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SOC-U.S.-IRAN-760(2TA     01-15 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-IRAN-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MATCH WITH U.S., IRANIANS SEE HOPE FOR DIPLOMACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Having traveled across the Atlantic Ocean and
a wider political gulf, the Iranian soccer team recently arrived
for the first time in the United States, only to discover that this
extraordinary road trip was really a homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's match against the Americans at the Rose Bowl will not
be so different from any match played at Azadi Stadium in Tehran.
An estimated 500,000 Iranian-Americans live in Southern California,
and they have given Los Angeles the nickname of Tehrangeles.
</P>
<P>
   Of the expected 50,000 spectators, officials said as many as
40,000 could be there to support Iran, where soccer is a consuming
secular passion. Fans are coming from as far as Toronto and
Washington. Messages on Web sites have provided ticket holders with
instructions on wearing shirts of red, white and green, Iran's
national colors, depending on the location of their seats. ``If we
do this around the stadium, we will have the flag of Iran just by
sitting there,'' one message said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere we go, Iranian people come to see us,'' said
Mohammad Khakpoor, a defender on the Iranian team. ``We are never
strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first meeting, Iran defeated the United States, 2-1, at
the 1998 World Cup in France. The rematch does not carry the
importance, novelty, emotion or anticipation of the first game. It
will, after all, most likely be played in a half-empty stadium with
nothing officially at stake in the outcome. Some Iranians in and
out of Iran have also grown cautious about this game's symbolism,
given their disappointment over the slow pace of change in the
government of the relatively moderate president, Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the game represents the most visible appearance of a
sports team from Iran in the United States since diplomatic
relations between the countries were severed after the 1979 Islamic
revolution and the taking of hostages that year at the American
Embassy in Tehran. Tens of millions are expected to watch on
television in Iran, where the match starts at 1:30 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Iran participated in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, and, next month,
Iranian wrestlers will compete in their fifth tournament in the
United States in the past five years. American wrestlers are
traveling to Tehran this weekend for the second time. Soccer,
however, is the national sport in Iran, and as an important
unifying and political force, it could provide a useful foundation
for rebuilding the relationship between the two countries,
Iranian-Americans, Iranian players and officials say.
</P>
<P>
   No one is naive enough to expect that 20 years of enmity will
cease because of one soccer match. But Sunday's game could serve as
a kind of chisel for chipping away at demonizing stereotypes that
portray Iran as a country of fanatics and the United States as the
Great Satan, Mayereh Tohidi, a professor of political sociology at
the California State University at Northridge, said.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, the match confirms what many Iranians in
and out of Iran believe, that the ``angry, no-talk policy'' with
the United States is no longer useful. And it reflects a desire for
improvement in everyday connections between families, like easier
acquisition of visas, Farideh Farhi, a political scientist in
Honolulu, said.
</P>
<P>
   Jalal Talebi, who coached Iran in the 1998 World Cup and is now
the team's general manager, said: ``I believe this is a good way to
start. Nothing will happen if we keep ignoring each other. We are
in 2000, the new millennium. They have to sit down and talk. Sooner
or later they will do that. That's what everyone wishes. The people
in Iran do, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Iranian-Americans interviewed pointedly wanted to distance
the game from politics, saying they had been exhausted by decades
of such talk. Instead, they embraced the match as a means of
exhibiting kinship, sportsmanship and rejuvenated pride in what it
means to be Iranian. Many said they would have dual loyalties. Tens
of thousands of paper flags, featuring the American flag on one
side and the Iranian flag on the other, have been printed for the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to realize that life is beyond politics,'' Alireza
Ghaffari, 44, a research engineer at the California Institute of
Technology who has lived in the United States since 1977, said.
``This is purely sport. This is everyday life. I hope Iran wins,
but it is not important who wins. What is important is that the
game is being played.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Iranian players and officials have commended American soccer
officials for respectful treatment during their stay in the United
States. The atmosphere has been decidedly relaxed and informal, and
security has been so low-key as to be invisible. A largely
Iranian-American crowd of 30,000 showed up on Wednesday night at
the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum for Iran's 2-1 victory over
Ecuador, with spectators waving flags, blowing plastic horns,
standing through the sunroofs of Mercedes-Benzes in ecstatic
support.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the players visited Universal Studios then
trained at the University of Southern California, simply changing
into their shorts and jerseys on the practice field, posing for
photos, speaking briefly with reporters and offering to continue
the interviews at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to see the team,'' said Beshid Bahmanyar, a
loan officer who lives in Los Angeles. ``I'm also sad that the
mullahs have destroyed my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Heightened security is expected for Sunday's match, Iranian
officials said. Some form of demonstrations is expected. At the
1998 World Cup, several thousand Iranian supporters protested at
the American match in Lyons by wearing T-shirts and hanging banners
in support of expatriate leaders based in Iraq and France. Some
Iranian-Americans have said they plan to raise black-gloved fists,
distribute posters and to refuse to sing Iran's national anthem in
protest of the fundamentalist Islamic regime.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being a sporting event, Sunday's match will carry
inevitable political intrigue as well, coming several weeks before
momentous February elections in Iran, in which the opposition hopes
to gain a majority over conservatives in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   A match that is cleanly played and undisturbed could reinforce
the position of those who want a dialogue with Americans, while a
match troubled on the field or in the stands could play into the
hands of conservatives who view the United States government as the
devil incarnate, Middle East experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For diplomacy, it's more important that the Iranians win,''
Richard Dekmejian, a professor of political science at Southern
California, said. ``Politically and psychologically, it means much
more for Iran than for the U.S. At this stage of their national
development, it could go a long way toward repairing their hurt
sense of pride and dignity. The push for change is there. This is
one more element that could contribute to it. When you are most
sure of yourself, you can bring yourself to negotiate with the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Khatami, Iran's president, called for cultural
exchanges to break the ``wall of mistrust'' separating Iran and the
United States. While the governments remain far apart, the two
countries are well into re-establishing links on personal and
sporting terms. Southern California has the largest Iranian
population outside of Iran. Many of the wealthy, well-educated
expatriates fled to places like Beverly Hills and the San Fernando
Valley when the Shah was deposed and Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
came to power.
</P>
<P>
   Khakpoor, the Iranian defender, played last season for the
MetroStars. Talebi, the World Cup coach, lived in Palo Alto,
Calif., for 17 years, and his family still lives there. At the 1998
World Cup, the Iranian players handed flowers to the Americans as a
gesture of peace, the teams posed for a picture, exchanged jerseys
after the match and were given the Fair Play award by soccer's
world governing body.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's leader, remarked in a
speech that the ``strong and arrogant opponents felt the bitter
taste of defeat,'' the celebration in the streets of Tehran was not
heavily politicized, according to Farhi, who joined in the
reveling. She said Iranians who wanted to burn American flags were
halted by the crowds, as were those who wanted to spray
anti-American graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for friendship,'' Khakpoor said. ``We don't
have any fight with any people. I try to be a good representative
for our culture, our people, our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1554EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
