<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NURSINGHOME-FRAUD-     01-15 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NURSINGHOME-FRAUD-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDICTED NURSING-HOME OWNER SEEKS APPROVAL TO EXPAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York State Health Department is considering
an application to expand a nursing-home business in Brooklyn, even
though the owner was recently indicted in a $62 million Medicaid
fraud case and has been suspended from the Medicaid program, a
health official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Lawrence Friedman, submitted the application on Dec.
13, two days before he was indicted by a grand jury in state
Supreme Court in Brooklyn following an investigation by the state
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given our ongoing legal action, we are adamantly opposed to
the application,'' said Scott Brown, a spokesman for Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer, ``and feel strongly it should be denied.''
</P>
<P>
   In late December, Spitzer criticized the Health Department for
allowing Friedman's two adult day-care centers in Canarsie to
continue operating after Friedman was indicted on charges of grand
larceny, conspiracy and falsifying medical records.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-count indictment accused Friedman of drawing robust
immigrants into the centers, which are intended for the frail, and
billing the Medicaid program for unnecessary or nonexistent
services. The centers will continue to receive the bulk of state
reimbursements for services deemed appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment was issued after an 18-month investigation, in
which the Health Department ``fully'' cooperated with the attorney
general, the department has said. During that time, however, the
department approved six expansions of Friedman's business, which
enabled him to increase his billings from $4 million a year to $47
million by the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman's two adult day-care centers _ intended to provide
physical therapy and rehabilitation to the disabled elderly who can
still live independently _ quickly grew to account for one-quarter
of all state adult day-care Medicaid billings, the attorney general
has said.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent application, Friedman asked for permission to
transfer the operation of 41 beds at the financially troubled Dover
Nursing Home in Brooklyn to his own Parkshore nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, as Friedman's application awaited approval in
Albany, the owner of the Dover home, Morey Adler, was also waiting
to hear from the Health Department so he could close his nursing
home and transfer his elderly clients.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Friedman started building a 41-bed unit at his
nursing home, according to records.
</P>
<P>
   A department spokesman, John Signor, said ``no decision has been
made'' on Friedman's application.
</P>
<P>
   Signor said that because the review process included an
assessment of character and competency, ``the actions the attorney
general has taken would be weighed heavily in our consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department did not tell the attorney general's office
of Friedman's pending application, said Brown, Spitzer's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Friedman's day care center, Dan Klores, said,
``The Parkshore nursing home hasn't done anything wrong, runs a
first-rate facility, and anyone is welcome to see it at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Adler could not be reached for comment. But as recently as
Tuesday, his health care consultant, Anthony J. Maddaloni, wrote to
the Health Department, saying that while the application was
pending, Dover would begin discharging its residents because of
financial losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
