<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-GEORGIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ARMS IN PIPELINE TO CHECHNYA, GEORGIA SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Russian troops have sold arms on the black
market from one of their bases in neighboring Georgia, and some of
the weapons are being smuggled to rebels fighting in Chechnya,
according to Georgian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The officials say they seized a truck with contraband weapons
soon after it left a Russian military base outside the Georgian
capital, Tbilisi, and have documented the episode on videotape that
has been shown on Georgian television and on Russia's independent
network NTV.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials, however, say that the tape was fabricated and
that the allegations have been made for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   A former Soviet republic, Georgia has been gradually emerging
from Moscow's shadow and has sought to develop economic and
political ties with the West. The Georgian president, Edward A.
Shevardnadze, has even said that Georgia plans to apply for NATO
membership in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Chechnya has worsened the strains in Russian-Georgian
relations. Tensions grew late last year when the Russians proposed
stationing troops on the Georgian side of the border with Chechnya,
which is formally a Russian republic although its status was left
in limbo after the 1994-96 Russian-Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian purpose in proposing the troop deployment in Georgia
was to seal the southern approach to the Chechen highlands _ where
Chechen rebels can easily hide _ but the Georgians refused, balking
at being drawn into the Chechen conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the Russians have complained that rebel supplies and
fighters continue to make their way across the frontier,
allegations the Georgians assert are not true. Russian warplanes
and helicopters have also occasionally strayed into Georgian
airspace and dropped bombs on the Georgian side of the border,
drawing protests from Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1994-96 war, there were reports that Russian troops
stationed in Chechnya sometimes sold weapons that ended up in the
hands of their adversary. Russian officials insist that their
troops are far more disciplined this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgians say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russians are selling weapons which are being used to fire on
their own people,'' Avtandil Ioseliani, Georgia's deputy security
minister, said in a telephone interview. ``They should stop blaming
others and instead put the blame on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Georgian officials said they had intercepted a truck
filled with arms from the Vaziani military base near Tbilisi.
Russian troops stationed there are scheduled to be withdrawn under
a recent Russian-Georgian agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Vakhtang Kutateladze, Georgia's minister of national security,
said in a telephone interview that a Georgian truck had been hired
and its driver told that he would be picking up a supply of food
and delivering it to Tskhinvali, capital of the separatist South
Ossetia region in northern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   After he arrived at the base, however, the truck's civilian
license plates were replaced with Russian military ones. The driver
delivered one shipment to Tskhinvali, but became suspicious and
informed the Georgian Ministry of Security.
</P>
<P>
   The next day a second shipment was stopped by Georgian security
forces. Georgian officials say they did not follow the truck all
the way to Tskhinvali to apprehend the buyers because they were
wary about venturing into South Ossetia, which has been struggling
to secede from Georgia and merge with North Ossetia, a Russian
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian officials said the buyers were believed to be people of
the region, but offered no specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Kutateladze said the truck was filled with about $50,000 worth
of arms, including boxes of mortar shells; more than 50,000
cartridges for machine guns; pistols; explosives, and guns and
shells designed for mountainous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot be sure, but we think the shipment was intended for
Chechnya,'' Kutateladze said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have been pounding the rebels from the air,
including 180 strikes in the past 24 hours, and using artillery.
The rebels, however, have mounted fierce resistance, using
relatively light arms like machine guns and mortars, which are
especially effective in Grozny, the Chechen capital, and in the
highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Zdanovich, spokesman for the Federal Security Service,
told Russian television that allegations of illicit arms sales from
Russian bases in Georgia had been investigated, but that no proof
had been found.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that the videotape was a fabrication, implying that
the Georgians were trying to cover up their failure to stop
smuggling by attributing it to the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tape was made primarily for domestic political consumption
and only secondly for Russia and the international community,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
