<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-KLANSMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FINDING GOOD IN PRESENCE OF KLANSMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, N.Y. _ James W. Sheeley had his moment of fame and
disdain in the big city last October when he led a puny Ku Klux
Klan rally in New York City. Then the grand dragon scampered back
to his home among the largely white hamlets of northern Orange
County.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Brian Randazzo came calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Hey, Jimmy. What's going on here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy and Brian had grown up, played ball and gone to church
together in the village of Coldenham. Brian became a substance
abuse counselor and pastor at the Brick Reformed Church. Jimmy
became a prison counselor and a substitute high school teacher. In
October it became clear that he had also become a Klansman.
</P>
<P>
   Even before joining in 1997, he said: ``I had white feelings. I
felt it was time to stand up and be proud to be a white man.'' He
hadn't been trying to hide, he told Randazzo, saying, ``I washed my
hood and robe and hung it outside on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheeley's coming out as the New York-New Jersey leader of the
American Knights of the Ku Klux Klan has stirred months of meetings
and discussion here about race and intolerance, issues rarely
raised publicly in the small towns of this region.
</P>
<P>
   It has seeped into people's lives. Erica Cron was studying the
civil rights movement in the eighth grade when her teacher,
referring to Sheeley, told the class, ``It could still happen
today.'' Students at Valley Central High School say there is more
emphasis on Black History Month this year. There was a candlelight
unity rally at the school last month. On Sunday, Randazzo is
preaching Martin Luther King Jr.'s sermon ``Loving Your Enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said Jimmy Sheeley had an evil influence,'' Randazzo
said. ``I think Jimmy Sheeley had a good influence.''
</P>
<P>
   It has given King's birthday a meaning here that eludes many
communities. ``I remember when they first come out with the
holiday, it was like you had to be politically correct and think
about it,'' said Karsten Wilson, a physical education teacher.
``But now it's actually serving a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Randazzo has invoked King to guide his parishioners through
their anger toward their neighbor. ``We didn't respond to him with
hate, because as King said, hate begets hate, violence begets
violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Randazzo invited Sheeley, 46, to a meeting at his church in
November. Sheeley told the audience that the Klan was not violent
or hateful, but was a white separatist group fighting for white
people in the face of intermarriage and civil rights for
minorities. The crowd grew especially tense, Randazzo said, when
``he called everyone in the room mongrels.''
</P>
<P>
   The community wanted to separate itself from Sheeley. ``If we
accept this one, how many more will there be?'' said Carrie Meyer,
17, a high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Shorter-Magwood, a black woman involved in the protest,
said: ``I felt Randazzo had taken a very bold move. He lived in a
community that was predominantly white, in a congregation that was
predominantly white, but he saw a need to bring the community
together.''
</P>
<P>
   She has childhood memories of racist activities in the small
towns of Orange County. Her parents feared harassment while driving
to Newburgh in the 1950s from their home in the Catskills. ``I
remember my mother saying we had to drive slowly and `Children, be
quiet,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheeley, a slight, nasal-voiced man who lives with his mother
and twin brother, shrugs off the town's reaction. ``When you go
public as a Klansman, you have to deal with it,'' he said. He quit
his prison job after being caught there with Klan literature, which
is considered contraband, and he stopped doing substitute teaching
last year. He says he is running for the U.S. Senate and plans
another rally in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although a pariah to some, he said, ``I get a lot of people who
come up to me in the store and say, `Keep going.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Randazzo will also keep going.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the sign in front of Montgomery's Brick Reformed
Church reads: ``Rev. Dr. King's Dream Is Still Alive in Montgomery,
Alabama and New York!''
</P>
<P>
   And so is his nightmare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1615EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
