<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-CRUISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURERS TO ATTEMPT RECORD CRUISE AROUND WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Herb McCormick is executive editor of Cruising World.)  
(ko) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Shakespeare said all the world's a stage, and Reid Stowe
took him at his word. On a glorious day last week, Stowe sat in the
sun-baked pilothouse of his 70-foot schooner, Anne, and took in the
glistening Hudson River from the peace of his Manhattan berth. But
his mind was still adrift with thoughts of his most recent
adventure, a meandering six-month journey of offshore performance
art that he and his bride, Laurence Guillem, theatrically dubbed
the Odyssey of the Sea Turtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're totally happy to be alive right now,'' he said. ``It
wasn't the smoothest voyage throughout. But we're back. It's real
nice to be here, and we're real positive about going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Stowe's travels in the three decades since he chucked his
surfboard and began cruising _ across the Atlantic and Pacific
Oceans, to Antarctica, up the Amazon River _ have filled dozens of
logbooks. But all of his treks have been a mere tune-up for where
he is headed.
</P>
<P>
   This December, Stowe and Guillem plan to start a three-year,
nonstop ramble around the planet, an expedition they've entitled A
Thousand Days at Sea. If successful, it will be the longest sea
voyage out of sight of land and without resupplying ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measure of man's enlightenment has often been gauged by
what he could do with a boat on the sea,'' Stowe said somewhat
euphorically. ``I feel like we can help a little bit in the
evolution of mankind, just by leaving the earth and going to live
on the water. It's sort of a simple thing. But it's not that simple
because no one has ever attempted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent 194-day sea-turtle safari was a test run during which
the 48-year-old sailor and artist quite literally used the South
Atlantic as a broad natural canvas. Before hoisting sail last June
5 _ he and Laurence were married the week before _ Stowe drew a
picture of a giant turtle on a navigational chart. Once under way,
he plotted a course that would allow his 60-ton vessel to trace the
image as closely as possible through the sea.
</P>
<P>
   As a symbol, the sea turtle fulfilled several purposes. ``All of
my voyages have been centered around themes,'' Stowe said. ``I
prefer to sail a course that's beautiful as opposed to straight or
functional, like work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also something to be said about not racing around all
the time. So this voyage was sort of an antidote to our
speed-obsessed society. And the turtle is also a reminder about
endangered species and the environment. I'm sure it's going to be
interpreted in different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   If Stowe didn't know it beforehand, he soon learned that the
actual rendering of giant marine reptiles across a liquid domain
subject to the vagaries of wind and weather is no easy task. Just
days after leaving New York, his engine failed, and his tired,
bagged-out sails also limited his maneuverability. But he pressed
on across the equator and into the southeast trade winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get far enough south and east, so there would be
room to give the turtle some volume,'' he said. ``And with our old
sails we weren't able to hold as close a course into the wind as I
wanted, so we weren't able to draw out the spotted fin like we'd
planned. And we had envisioned a huge turtle, but we were making
slow progress, so we had to make it smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   The finished work, which can be seen on Stowe's Web site,
www.1000days.net, was still 1,900 nautical miles long by 1,400
nautical miles wide. ``On the map you see our day-to-day points
like a constellation,'' he said. ``It's a turtle drawn there,
clearer than any constellation in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Stowe says that he and Guillem ``lost touch with the shore''
during the weeks of the cruise but that they also ``lost that sense
of timelessness'' once the mission was accomplished and they
realized they'd have to sail quickly to arrive back in New York by
the new year.
</P>
<P>
   A brush with Hurricane Lenny in late November as they negotiated
the Caribbean on their northbound leg brought some anxious moments,
but real danger loomed on their approach to the city in
mid-December. ``We were trying to tack in but we were blown
backward 30 miles by a sleet squall,'' Stowe said.
</P>
<P>
   But they persevered, and on Dec. 17, ``we came screaming up the
Hudson and got stuck in the mud right next to the dock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Guillem was recently in her native France visiting
relatives, Stowe continued making plans for his thousand-day trip,
for which he is actively seeking sponsorship. Part of that process
involves dealing with members of the news media, some of whom find
his earnestness and motivation ripe for ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   Stowe is unfazed. ``Sure, we get teased a bit, but that's OK,''
he said. ``I know what we've done and where we're going.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1616EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MLK-LESSONS16-COX     01-15 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-LESSONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lessons on King leave out leader's impact, some educators say
 &HT;    By Rochelle Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Small brown, black and tan hands shot into the air and
giggles resounded through the auditorium as hundreds of students
indicated their love for Happy Meals, pizza, and the Discovery
Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Morani Bonner, a teacher's aide at Brookview Elementary School,
explained to the children that the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. is
largely responsible for their ability to enjoy those childhood
pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to pretend it's the 1960s,'' Bonner said. He
changed his diction to a Southern drawl. ``No Happy Meal for you,
boy, because our restaurant says `Whites Only.'''
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta students know that King wanted children of
different races to go to school together. They know he was the
leader of the civil rights movement, for which he won a Nobel Peace
Prize in 1964. They know about Selma and Montgomery, Ala., the
March on Washington and ``I Have a Dream.'' They can recite his
birth date, the date an assassin gunned him down in Memphis, Tenn.,
and the milestones of the 39 years between.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their grasp of the facts about King, said Asa Hilliard,
a Georgia State University professor of urban education, ``It is
also my experience that not only here, but everywhere else, it is
superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoolchildren may know the words to ``We Shall Overcome,'' but
because there is no uniform emphasis on King, they may not
understand what life would have been like for them under
separate-but-equal laws, Bonner explained to the Brookview
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to pass along trivial knowledge (about history), and I
guess they get the cherry tree story on George Washington,'' said
Hilliard, who reviews social studies textbooks for publishers. He
has found them lacking in-depth information about King and most
other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we have a high priority on cultural
knowledge,'' Hilliard said. It would be impossible to focus on
every historical figure, he acknowledged, ``but some figures stand
out so much, and King would be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia mandates on social studies education provide many
opportunities for classroom discussion of King's legacy. The
significance of King's birthday, which is officially celebrated
Monday, and holidays like Presidents' Day and Memorial Day are
taught in first-grade lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-grade history covers the civil rights movement as part of
the political and social change that took place after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Influential Georgians are an eighth-grade subject and the civil
rights era from 1947 to present day is studied through high school.
Each school district has its own mandates.
</P>
<P>
   But the curriculum does not guarantee students will understand
how important King is, said Howard Taylor, a Georgia State
University assistant professor of social science education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear the biggest celebration will be `Good, I'm out of
school tomorrow,' '' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions about instruction that go beyond the curriculum, such
as field trips to the King Center for Non-Violence Social Change in
downtown Atlanta, are left up to each school and sometimes the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the priority, it's usually exercised by individual
teachers, a principal here or there that has some kind of
consciousness,'' Hilliard said.
</P>
<P>
   Brookview students have been studying King since they came back
from winter break. But emphasis on King is not so apparent at
Atlanta's Booker T. Washington High School _ King's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   King's birthday is recognized at Washington, but not
overemphasized, Principal Shirley Kilgore said. Every morning last
week, junior Charles Allen, 16, read parts of King's life story to
his classmates during the daily announcements. Some teachers
discussed King in class and the media center continuously played a
video of King's life, which various classrooms came to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the classroom, King is primarily discussed based on his
connection to the school, Kilgore said. There is a corner in the
school's archives for King. Lena Horne, another alum, has one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgore wants students at the school, which is on the rebound
from a period of low student performance, to learn from King that
``if this man was here in this building and he achieved great
things, it's possible for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several factors influence the unevenness in recognition, Taylor
said. King was a black man who rose to fame during one of this
country's ugliest periods. He was a relatively recent figure, and
adults don't agree on his significance and contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Also, reading and math are pushed in schools, which often
lessens the emphasis on history. And, Taylor said, patriotic
holidays have lost so much significance that most people celebrate
them by catching department store sales.
</P>
<P>
   He said King's accomplishments, courage and martyr status and
the moral lessons students can learn from his life, should make him
more significant to metro Atlanta children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard to find an Atlantan that has been more
influential than Dr. King, as a thinker, as a man, as a leader,''
Taylor said. ``There is not a person who is more significant, and
yet, I would like to see more of an emphasis in the curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   At Dacula High School in Gwinnett County, Principal Dolford
Laysom said he does not want to weigh the significance of one
influential historical figure over another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to place a value judgement on either, but (King
is) probably more on the forefront than a George Washington''
because of his influence on modern times, Laysom said.
</P>
<P>
   King's contributions are recognized in history classes and
during Black History Month at Dacula. But the students seem to be
well-versed on King, Laysom said. And King's dream is exemplified
at Dacula, where less than 10 percent of the school's 1,800
students are nonwhites.
</P>
<P>
   The students recently elected an African-American Mr. Dacula and
the multiracial Black History Month Committee is co-sponsored by
white and black teachers, Laysom said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Alexander, whose two daughters attend the predominately
white Peachtree Elementary School, also in Gwinnett, said she is
satisfied with what her daughters have been taught about King. She
said she doesn't want them to be overwhelmed in elementary school
with too much information about the civil rights movement to avoid
the ``major baggage'' that adults still have about the divisiveness
and violence over race during that time period.
</P>
<P>
   But when they graduate from Gwinnett schools, she wants them to
have a complete and balanced picture of the contributions made by
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want white kids graduating thinking it's a black
problem and it was just black people working on it,'' Alexander
said of the civil rights struggle King led. ``I want them to
recognize there were many white people working on it and it was a
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
