<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hill, Garnett `bring it'
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's something that might spice next month's
All-Star Game: Grant Hill and Kevin Garnett have a rivalry going.
</P>
<P>
   The pair had fun going after one another last Saturday, starting
in the second quarter when Hill drove to the basket and threw a
Karl Malone-style off-arm elbow into Garnett's face. Then, early in
the fourth quarter, the two stood face-to-face jawing. ``I am
coming right at your (bleep),'' Hill said. ``Bring it,'' Garnett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill brought it, hard. Eventually, Hill's nonstop drives to the
basket caused Garnett, as well as Joe Smith and Radoslav
Nesterovic, to foul out. Hill finished with 40 points. Garnett had
22 points, 14 rebounds and eight assists and Minnesota won.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, all parties tried to downplay what appeared to be a
pretty zesty feud between two of the game's top players. ``We're
just having fun,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Pistons coach Alvin Gentry said it was personal, but in a
competitive sense. ``Believe me, Kevin Garnett is telling his
coaches that he can stop Grant Hill and Grant Hill is saying, `No,
I don't think you can,''' he said. ``It's just the competitiveness
of the game. There is no bad blood. Everything was forgotten once
they walked off the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the sentiments of many in the league, Garnett said:
``Isn't that incredible? Three big men foul out.''
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINTS &AMP; COMPLIMENTS
</P>
<P>
   After the Pacers beat Washington, Wizards players complained
afterward about coach Gar Heard's substitution patterns. Said Rod
Strickland: ``You have to play the starters. You can't take
everybody out, because you have a whole different flow. I feel you
should just live and die with your starters and we don't always do
that. This wasn't the first time.'' ... Bucks coach George Karl is
softening on his center, Ervin Johnson, who plays because Robert
Traylor has struggled. ``He's kind of proved me wrong. I think
Ervin could start for a lot of teams in this league and play 30
minutes. When he left Seattle, I didn't think he could be a
starter. Now he's one of our top four players.''
</P>
<P>
   NO DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons are not interested in Donyell Marshall despite
reports that the contract of retired center Bison Dele would be
dealt to the Warriors, who could clear Dele's money off their cap.
The two teams earlier spoke about Loy Vaught for Marshall. Nothing
came of it.
</P>
<P>
   LAYUPS
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, coach Butch Carter took a shot at free agent-to-be
Tracy McGrady, saying he ``is good defending second-tier players
and not good enough, or old enough, right now, to guard first-tier
players.'' ... Dee Brown and the Raptors are in a fight over his
left knee. Brown did not require the surgery that was performed on
his left knee Wednesday in Orlando, according to Raptors team
physician Paul Marks. ... Rick Carlisle and former Pacer Byron
Scott are on the short list to replace Larry Bird as Pacers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
