<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phillis a tragic loss to league
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bobby Phills graduated from Southern University with
3.8 GPA in biology. Phills had intentions of becoming a
veterinarian, yet ended up an overachieving NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   His death in a traffic accident last week was painful for those
who knew him, because he was a thoughtful man and role model. And
it hurt because it was unneccessary.
</P>
<P>
   Phills, 30, died _ and left his wife without a husband and his
two small children fatherless _ because he engaged in the immature
act of drag racing with teammate David Wesley. Worse, Phills had
been ticketed for speeding on Charlotte streets in the past, which
should have slowed him down.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday happened, and a man atypical of the NBA was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way before I thought I could do this, I expected to work 9 to
5 as a veterinarian,'' Phills told the Charlotte Observer the week
before his death. ``I know what I have up here, mentally. I don't
need to be a basketball player to be a success in life.''
</P>
<P>
   He cherished the life basketball created for him and did not
abuse it. Rather, he was a significant server of the community.
</P>
<P>
   His father is the head of the agriculture department at Florida
A&AMP;M, which accounted for the son's belief in higher education and
for his personal demeanor. He carried himself without the swagger
of many athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad thing how many athletes get lost after their
careers are over because that's their only niche,'' Phills said.
``They don't know how to live their lives without a basketball in
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very secure with myself. I have a great family. I was
raised by a great family. I have the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   And his family now has a nightmare, as do the teammates who were
the last to see him alive. Wesley, in particular, is taking Phills'
death hard. He was his closest friend on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Phills held the good of the team close. He sacrificed his
starting small-forward position by volunteering to come off the
bench. Starting was important to both Anthony Mason and Derrick
Coleman, two forwards with strong personalities who probably would
not have accepted coming off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of that situation, Phills went to Paul Silas and told the
Charlotte coach he would become a reserve to keep Mason and Coleman
happy. The Hornets went on to win 12 of their next 18 games, with
Phills averaging 14.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told (Silas), `If it would solve the problem, then
have me come off the bench,''' Phills said.
</P>
<P>
   Silas said: ``This goes to what's deeply inside of a real pro.
You don't find that often in this league. An attitude like that has
to evolve. It comes with experience and character. Bobby would
choose a championship ring over a start or a couple of minutes of
playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in Charlotte, Phills was playing golf when a motorcyclist
crashed nearby. The rider was on fire, and Phills ran to the scene
to help extinguish the flames. Unfortunately, the man eventually
died because of the burns, but the family acknowledged Phills for
allowing them a chance to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Phills' good-guy nature, Detroit coach Alvin Gentry said:
``The fact that he was a good player is about the 20th most
important thing on the list. If you polled the people in the NBA,
you'd be hard pressed to find anybody who didn't think that he was
a great guy with great character.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
