<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Washington needs Jordan
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe Michael Jordan could be the elixir to a toxic
situation in Washington. Not only are the Wizards underachieving,
but they have internal tumult that has turned Gar Heard's first
year as a head coach into a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan could become the Wizards' president of basketball
operations this week, with part-ownership quickly following. For
certain, Jordan would not embrace the madness that has wrecked a
franchise wallowing in poor attendance and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Rod Strickland bickered with Heard almost
immediately. Guard Mitch Richmond came into the season out of
shape, got injured and had his own run-ins with Heard. Strickland
and Richmond complained publicly about not playing late in games.
Forward Juwan Howard, who has a contract worth $106 million, gets
booed regularly at the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jordan nor his agent, David Falk, has spoken about the
negotiations. A deal is far from complete, because owner Abe Pollin
insists on maintaining control of the team at least until after the
2001 NBA All-Star Game in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Vancouver interim coach Lionel Hollins. He has led the
Grizzlies to a 6-7 record, including a 4-1 on an Eastern road trip.
The players prefer his calm approach over fired Brian Hill's
forceful nature.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To the Golden State Warriors. They were so horrible that they
got P.J. Carlesimo fired, though he had something to do with that,
too. And their losing streak under Garry St. Jean reached 11 going
into Saturday night. They are totally uninspired.
</P>
<P>
   KUKOC TRADE RUMORS
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc showed his value to a team last week when he returned
to the lowly Chicago Bulls from the injured list and led them to
their first three-game winning streak since Michael Jordan retired
two years ago. And so, he's now trade bait.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any team that feels close to an NBA title is interested
in the 6-foot-11 Croatian, who becomes a free agent in the summer.
One rumor has him going to the Lakers for Glen Rice, with the
Lakers moving Kukoc to Toronto for Tracy McGrady, and a first-round
Raptors pick going to the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Another rumor has Kukoc going to the Lakers, who would deal Rice
and either Derek Fisher or Tyronne Lue to Miami, which would send
Jamal Mashburn, Voshon Lenard and a draft pick to the Bulls. PIPPEN
NOT PULLING PUNCHES
</P>
<P>
   All that winning on Michael Jordan's coattails has gone to
Scottie Pippen's head, apparently. Asked a simple question about
Dallas forward Michael Finley's chances to make the All-Star team,
Pippen went off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an All-Star-caliber player,'' Pippen said, ``but look at
his team's record. Who can't put up numbers for a team that's
playing to ... outscore you and not playing to win?
</P>
<P>
   ``No knock against him as a player; he's a good player,'' Pippen
said. ``But I don't consider him an All-Star just because he's
putting up numbers. I can take some of the worst players in the
league (and put them) on that team and they can score.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
