<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growl with the Grizzlies
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apparently Bill Laurie is running the Grizzlies, even
though he's trying to wriggle out of a bid to buy the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Sun says general manager Stu Jackson wanted to
fire Brian Hill and replace him with assistant coach Lionel Hollins
on Nov. 24 after the Grizzlies were whipped in Charlotte. Although
current ownership approved, Jackson could not dismiss Hill because
Laurie would not give his approval. Terms of the stalled deal
stipulate that the Missouri billionaire have a say in significant
personnel matters.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson waited, the Grizzlies went on to lose 10 of their
next 11 games. Hill was fired Dec. 16, and under new coach Hollins,
the Grizzlies recently completed their most successful road trip,
winning four of five games on a difficult Eastern swing.
</P>
<P>
   ISSEL JAWS WITH PAYTON
</P>
<P>
   Recall Dan Issel's shouting match with Utah's Jerry Sloan? Now
the Denver coach has gotten into a verbal dispute with Seattle
trash talker Gary Payton. It backfired on Issel, big time.
</P>
<P>
   Payton had been trash talking all night, especially with Ron
Mercer, who had the temerity to suggest that Nick Van Exel give him
the ball in the post so he could go at Payton. Mercer and Payton
went mouth to mouth until Issel chimed in during the third quarter.
Payton cursed Issel, both were hit with technicals and Payton, then
scoreless, scored 23 points over the final 18 1/2 minutes of the
game, won by Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Issel called Payton over to the side and apologized to him.
Payton shook his hand and said, ``I'm sorry, too, Coach.''
</P>
<P>
   MAVS COOL ON RODMAN
</P>
<P>
   New Mavericks owner Mark Cuban, while still interested in
flamboyant free agent Dennis Rodman, has no interest in waiting
until February for Rodman to decide whether he wants to play in his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not acceptable,'' Cuban said of Rodman's apparent
desire to wait until after attending the Super Bowl and Pro Bowl
before returning to the NBA. ``I just told (Rodman's
representatives) that we didn't want to be strung along.'' WHO
NEEDS FRIENDS?
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant does not have a relationship with any of his Laker
teammates. He's so distant, Rick Fox says, ``Maybe he's moving
toward the intimidation factor. Maybe he has a game plan in his
mind he's putting to work. I just think that it's going to be a
long 20 years in this league if he continues to isolate and not
reach out or let people in.'' TARPLEY SIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   The setting _ the Kirov factory sports center in Perm, located
in Russia's distant Ural Mountains _ isn't quite what Roy Tarpley
was used to when he starred with the NBA's Mavericks nearly 15
years ago. But that's where Tarpley is, playing for Perm's Ural
Great team. Tarpley, 35, lives there with his American girlfriend
in a three-room apartment and apparently is happy to be playing and
getting paid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
