<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EVICTIONS-REAL-1150(3     01-15 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVICTIONS-REAL-1150(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT HARASSMENT OR IS IT THE LAW? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four times in 10 months, always early in the morning,
the knocks came at Naoka Honda's door and a stranger handed her
legal papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you fail to make complete payment of the rent or surrender
possession of the premises within said time period,'' the papers
said, ``the landlord will commence summary proceedings to recover
possession of the above referenced premises.''
</P>
<P>
   Each time, the rent for Ms. Honda's apartment on East 22nd
Street had already been paid in full and on time.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth proceeding, the landlord, Thurcon Development
Co., signed an injunction, agreeing to pay Ms. Honda $8,000 in
overcharges, $7,000 in legal fees and a $3,500 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a citizen in this country, so I am not fully
knowledgeable about the law,'' Ms. Honda, a jazz singer from Japan,
said. ``I was really scared.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all a series of unfortunate errors, the landlord's
lawyer, David Brody of Borah, Goldstein, Altshuler and Schwartz,
said. ``I think the best way to phrase it, the most accurate way,''
Brody said, ``is that there were mistakes made and the proceedings
started because there is no fail-safe system set up to keep such
mistakes from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Eviction attempts, in the torrid residential market of today,
rarely resemble the thuggish, brutal harassment that screamed into
headlines during New York City's last real-estate boom: the co-op
and condominium conversion frenzy of the mid- to late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, scores of buildings _ solidly maintained apartment
houses as well as decrepit single-room-occupancy hotels, even
tenements _ were coveted for conversion, and sometimes aged, poor
residents suddenly found themselves and their possessions dumped on
the street.
</P>
<P>
   These days, instead, efforts to get rent-regulated tenants out,
particularly in the more desirable neighborhoods of Manhattan, have
taken more subtle, sophisticated and legalistic turns: immediate
summons for a slightly late rent payment, sudden citation for an
old lease-breaching dishwasher and, more substantially, charges
that a roommate is illegally subletting, challenges to a family
member's right of succession when the primary tenant leaves or
dies, a landlord's demand to personally occupy the apartment (or
several apartments).
</P>
<P>
   It is an evolution, driven by breath-snatching market-rate rents
and scant supply, that partisans on opposite sides of the
landlord-tenant divide see either as entirely proper pursuit of
procedure or as grinding, often baseless legal harassment.
</P>
<P>
   There are still isolated cases of outright viciousness, like
that of a Lower East Side landlord, Alvin Weiss, sentenced to seven
to 14 years in prison for attempted murder last March after
confessing that to make apartments vacant he had hired a hit man to
burn out one tenant and to give another, an addict, a potentially
fatal overdose of heroin. But those are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get the type of cases that we saw in the mid-1980s,
when they put the goons in the buildings,'' said Ralph Carbone, the
union leader for lawyers in the enforcement unit of the New York
State Division of Housing and Community Renewal, which prosecutes
harassment cases.
</P>
<P>
   A few malicious landlords ``would get several vacancies in the
building, put their goons in to live as theoretical tenants and
then have them cause excessive noise at all hours, verbally and
physically abuse legitimate tenants, literally destroy the property
by breaking walls, knocking out windows, doing all sorts of vicious
things. That's not what we are seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the city's largest landlord organization,
Joseph Strasburg of the Rent Stabilization Association, rues those
days. ``You had owners, and there were some, who went to great
extents of conduct, criminal in nature, to evict a tenant,''
Strasburg said. ``They knocked down the stairs, closed down the
elevators, turned off electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   But those days are gone, Strasburg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a hypothetical that you'll always find some owners
who wish to harass a tenant? Maybe,'' he said. ``But the owners we
deal with on an everyday basis, it's my experience that they want
to know what their rights are and to make sure that the tenant has
not taken advantage of them. Then they follow a legitimate legal
process recognized under the rent laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way in the last 15 years in cleaning up our
industry,'' Strasburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Tenant advocates charge, however, that there are still tactics
to decry in the arsenals of some landlords. ``We have definitely
seen a flood of cases where rent-regulated tenants are brought to
court for what we consider frivolous claims by landlords seeking to
regain possession of the apartment,'' said Angelita Anderson,
executive director of the Citywide Task Force on Housing Court. The
task force is a nonprofit organization that advises tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKee, associate director of the New York State Tenants
and Neighbors Coalition, said: ``It's important to say that not all
landlords do this. There are some landlords who would never harass
a tenant. So I'm not trying to tar every landlord.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in a market that tenant advocates say includes quite a few
contentious new landlords as flush with Wall Street profits as are
their prospective renters or buyers, ``the stakes are so much
higher,'' McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landlords see gold at the end of the tunnel,'' he said. ``If
they can just get those pesky rent-regulated tenants out they can
cash in. If you have somebody paying $7,200 a year in rent and you
can get them out and decontrol the apartment, you can start
collecting $60,000 a year, which you can in some neighborhoods in
Manhattan. That's a tremendous incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   The incentive lies in the fact that if a landlord is able to
raise the rent to $2,000 during a period of vacancy, the apartment
becomes permanently decontrolled and the owner is free to charge
market-rate rents.
</P>
<P>
   There are several steps a landlord can take to reach that $2,000
level. First, upon achieving a vacancy, the owner is entitled to
the statutory vacancy bonus, enacted two years ago by the state
Legislature, which adds a minimum of 20 percent onto the rent for a
two-year lease, or 18 percent for a one-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   If the landlord renovates the apartment, he or she can then _
under what is termed an Individual Apartment Improvement _ add
one-fortieth of the renovation costs to the monthly rent. If, for
example, the landlord spends $40,000 on renovation work, which in
upscale neighborhoods would almost be necessary, $1,000 would be
added to the rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not hard for a landlord to get an apartment, no matter
what the old rent was, up to $2,000 a month,'' McKee said. ``He can
then charge the incoming tenant whatever the market will bear _
anything that a rich person from, say, Europe or Hong Kong is
willing to pay.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Judge Walter Strauss, who retired from the Housing Court bench
in September, said: ``This goes on to a much greater extent in
Manhattan than in the other boroughs. In Manhattan, because there
is so much interest in residing there, the landlords are very
aggressive if there is a nonpayment or another reason for them to
try to obtain the apartment again, to evict.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss spent four years in Housing Court in Manhattan and his
last year in Brooklyn. ``My experience in Brooklyn, and I suspect
the other boroughs,'' he said, ``is that landlords are not so
inclined to want to get the apartment back _ they just want to get
their rent.''
</P>
<P>
   The salvo of eviction notices against Ms. Honda, the jazz singer
from Japan, apparently was sparked when she discovered that her
apartment at 31 East 22nd St. had been improperly decontrolled.
``After she asserted her right to be treated as rent-stabilized and
filed an overcharge complaint, she began receiving baseless
nonpayment proceedings,'' said her lawyer, Seth Miller of Collins,
Dobkin and Miller. ``In each instance my client had paid the lease
rent on time; they had cashed the checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Honda's initial market-rate rent, in 1994, had been $1,000 a
month. After the Division of Housing and Community Renewal found
that her apartment should have remained stabilized, her rent was
set at $875.
</P>
<P>
   The first proceeding against Ms. Honda was filed in October
1997; the second in March 1998. In both of those actions, the
landlord, Thurcon Development, agreed to drop the case. The third
time, in May 1998, a Housing Court judge fined the landlord $150
and dismissed the case.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after the fourth action in August 1998, Miller said,
``We brought an injunction proceeding and after some legal
wrangling, they decided to sign a consent injunction'' _ requiring
that Thurcon Development pay Ms. Honda's legal fees, overcharges
and a $3,500 penalty by Feb. 7, 1999; a total of $18,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrifying experience,'' Ms. Honda said. ``Especially
because I am a singer and I'm not in the apartment all the time _
sometimes I go out of town to sing _ I was scared that when I come
back my stuff would be out on the street. It's a hard way I have to
learn how to live in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody, the landlord's lawyer, said: ``In terms of the four
nonpayment proceedings, essentially, Thurcon's bookkeeping
operation was in two separate offices, and the easy way to say it
is that the person sending in the information to us honestly
believed there were rents outstanding. And the way my office is set
up, we probably generate 2,000 to 3,000 nonpayment proceedings a
month, so the person who received the information wouldn't have any
reason to know there was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw the way this practice operates, you would realize
that to a large extent it relies on paralegals,'' Brody continued.
``I talked to the attorney who actually handled the nonpayment
proceedings and it is her recollection that with at least three of
the four proceedings, at the time we served the demands for
payment, there actually was rent outstanding, although by the time
the petitions went out the rents may well have been paid. And that
happens with a certain amount of regularity simply because
sometimes checks do not clear or we do not get told of that before
the petition goes out, which is pretty much on an automatic
cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Quantifying harassment by landlords is a murky exercise.
Different agencies deal with different aspects of the problem in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, the police handle some instances as criminal
complaints. Then, although it may seem confusing, tenants cannot
file harassment charges in Housing Court, but can only bring
actions for specific code violations. At the same time, baseless
litigation brought by landlords in Housing Court is sometimes
withdrawn before being adjudicated.
</P>
<P>
   Tenants can file harassment complaints of all kinds with the
State Division of Housing and Community Renewal. The most frequent
complaints these days, said Carbone, the union leader in the
division's enforcement unit, ``concern baseless litigation, failure
to provide basic services, verbal abuse by an owner or an owner's
employee; intrusive acts, for example, entering an apartment under
false pretenses, putting cameras in hallways, investigators spying
on tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   While the nature of complaints filed with the state has shifted,
their numbers have decreased sharply. ``We got about 2,100 in
1997,'' said Joseph Lynch, the commissioner of housing and
community renewal, and about 1,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch pointed out that the higher numbers in 1997 may have been
prompted by the fact that ``that was when the rent-regulation laws
were being renewed through a fight in the Assembly and Senate, and
extensive media coverage of that went on for months.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the commissioner said, some cases ``fall out because
they are not really harassment; they end up as somebody complaining
about loud music in the building, and they blame the owner for
that.'' And, at the same time, many charges are first winnowed
through a mediation process to determine if they should be
prosecuted by the enforcement unit. ``A lot of these cases are
settled over the phone with the tenants and the owners,'' Lynch
said, ``so they don't become a docketed case.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which leaves parties to the process disputing whether, in
fact, there has been any marked increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owners are being much more aggressive,'' McKee of the tenants
and neighbors coalition said, ``because even if a landlord doesn't
have a case, they can hope that the tenant won't fight back, won't
be able to afford a lawyer or will just be too frightened and move
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson of the Housing Court task force said: ``We have
seen, I'd say, at least three or four new cases every day for the
last two years, and before that, maybe, once a day, maybe none _
the kinds of cases we never saw a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an attorney working on a case,'' Ms. Anderson said,
``where tenants are living on the Lower East Side in a
rent-stabilized walk-up and the landlord wants the apartment for
his grandmother in a wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Justice Fern Fisher-Brandveen of state Supreme Court, the
administrative judge for Housing Court, sees no marked increase in
frivolous proceedings. ``Our judges meet on a monthly basis and
that's not an issue on the front burner,'' she said. ``There's
always going to be some abusers of the system, by both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Strasburg of the Rent Stabilization Association, the landlords'
group, concurred. ``We can point to tenants who harass owners,'' he
said. Strasburg cited the case of a woman on Manhattan's East Side
who, he said, left her bathtub water running for three years before
reaching a buyout settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the landlord in that case, Sally Unger of
Kossoff, Alper and Unger, declined to discuss specifics of the
settlement and said that the tenant was forbidden to discuss the
case, under a confidentiality agreement. But, she said, the dispute
began in 1996 when the landlord challenged the woman's succession
rights to the apartment after her mother moved out.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a means of retaliation, she started running the hot water,
incessantly,'' Ms. Unger said _ from about the end of 1996 through
November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the landlord's workers heard the water running, through
the hallway,'' Ms. Unger said. ``She didn't answer the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The building's boiler, installed in 1994, began breaking down,
regularly. Eventually the police were called. ``We had a cop
testify at the trial,'' Ms. Unger said. ``She had installed a sheet
of plastic over the tub so it would run off quietly. The porcelain
had been worn away and was black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome,'' Ms. Unger said, ``is that we settled it and
she's going to be moving out.''
</P>
<P>
   Succession rights are also at issue in the proceedings initiated
by Standard Realty Associates against Candela Prol _ as is an
elderly man's old roof deck.
</P>
<P>
   No one denies that Ms. Prol and other tenants in the six-unit
brownstone at 107 West 11th St. enjoy a remarkable deal. The
previous landlord, St. Vincent's Hospital and Medical Center,
barely raised rents for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   For a three-bedroom apartment, Ms. Prol pays $275 a month _ up
from $225 in 1962. And that's the highest in the building.
</P>
<P>
   For the last eight years, until the death of her father, Julio,
of a stroke in June at age 74, Ms. Prol and her husband lived in
the apartment with her father. A friend of the family also shares
the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, Julio Prol, a classical guitarist, built a wood
deck atop the building, lining it with white fences and plants.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, the building was bought by Standard Realty. Soon
after, Standard's president, Kenneth Rosenbloom, sent a letter to
the tenants saying that until their residency rights were verified,
their rent checks would not be accepted. ``He was concerned about
who was in occupancy and who wasn't entitled,'' said Rosenbloom's
lawyer, Joseph Burden of Belkin, Burden, Wenig and Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   ``They immediately issued eviction notices to four of the six
tenants,'' said Ms. Prol's lawyer, Stephen Palitz of Finder,
Novick, Kerrigan, Anderson and Palitz.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Palitz said, Rosenbloom arrived at Julio Prol's
apartment with police officers. ``They conducted a bogus search,''
Palitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Prol said her father was terrified. ``For him to cry, I just
haven't seen it in a long time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the police had been brought to the apartment, Burden
said: ``St. Vincent's had corresponded with Prol that the deck was
not in a legal condition. There's a violation issued by the
Buildings Department from September that the deck has to be
removed.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, however, Cassandra Vernon, a spokeswoman
for the Department of Housing Preservation and Development, said a
violation was issued when inspectors questioned whether the roof
deck ``may have required plans to be filed with the Department of
Buildings (DOB).
</P>
<P>
   ``HPD then referred the information to the Department of
Buildings,'' the statement continued. ``DOB inspected the building
on 9/27/99 and found no cause for action.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on Nov. 23, workers sent by the landlord tore down the roof
deck.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, on Aug. 12, the landlord had sent an eviction notice
to Candela Prol, saying her right to be in the apartment had
``terminated on the death of the tenant of record'' _ her father.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the grounds for eviction, Burden said: ``Ms. Prol
has connections to another apartment on Jane Street. And my client
was aware that a portion of the Prol apartment had been sublet to
nonfamily members.''
</P>
<P>
   Palitz countered that it is Ms. Prol's mother who lives in a
studio apartment on Jane Street. And, he pointed out, the Rent
Regulation Reform Act of 1997 states that the daughter of a
regulated apartment's primary tenant (as well as other specified
family members) who has lived in the apartment for ``no less than
two years'' is entitled to remain.
</P>
<P>
   The law also protects roommates who have lived with the tenant
for two years and can demonstrate an emotional or financial
connection with the primary tenant.
</P>
<P>
   Burden then indicated that the landlord was reconsidering the
eviction proceedings against Ms. Prol. ``First we thought it was
rent controlled,'' he said. ``But there is an order from, I think,
1966, saying that it was not subject to rent control any more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding was that it was no longer subject to any
regulation,'' Burden continued. ``But Palitz has brought to my
attention a case from 1980, very similar to this one, which says
that if a unit becomes decontrolled, then it became stabilized in
1974. I'm evaluating it along with my client to determine how we
should proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Burden said, Rosenbloom's goal ``is to have, not
himself, but various members of his family living in the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very big family,'' Ms. Prol said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Rosenbloom hopes to go to market-rate rents, Burden
said, ``No, it's not his intention at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Burden notified Palitz that his client was dropping
eviction proceedings against Ms. Prol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
