<SLUG> BC-GORE-CONFEDERATE-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SHIFTS ATTACK TO BUSH, CRITICIZING STAND ON FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENACOOK, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore is stepping up his
appeals to independent voters here, criticizing Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the likely Republican nominee, over the Confederate
battle flag and soft-pedaling his criticisms of his Democratic
rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the Confederate battle flag should be removed from the
South Carolina Capitol because it was a symbol of racism and that
Bush was ducking the issue because he needed to preserve his
conservative support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he, Governor Bush, has avoided taking a position or
has ducked the issue because he is playing to some of his
supporters that I think have some pretty obsolete and even hateful
attitudes,'' Gore said Saturday in an interview with the Rev. Jesse
Jackson on CNN's ``Both Sides With Jesse Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   With the New Hampshire primary less than three weeks away, Gore
is trying to tone down his previously harsh criticism of Bradley.
Gore's goal in the state, where there are as many independents as
Democrats and Republicans, is to shuck any vestiges of the rancor
that has characterized his campaign for weeks and instead to seize
the mantle that Bradley has worn so well here, as a nonpolitician
above the bickering.
</P>
<P>
   He told a rally at a school gymnasium here, where he campaigned
with former Sen. Eugene McCarthy, who galvanized the anti-war vote
in 1968, that what he had in common with Bradley was more important
than their differences.
</P>
<P>
   At a town meeting on Friday night in Salem, N.H., Gore boasted
of his cross-party credentials as a member of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was so intent on reaching as many voters as possible that
he insisted on taking his motorcade Saturday into the teeth of an
ice storm in Berlin, in northern New Hampshire. The Secret Service
canceled Gore's plans to fly to Berlin because of the weather, so
Gore decided to drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1655EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7016 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TALKING-CARS-1STLD-WR     01-15 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKING-CARS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING, ONLINE CARS GIVE NEW MEANING TO `INFORMATION
SUPERHIGHWAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to delete 1st sentence, correct spelling to Jacques A. Nasser
in 6th graf, rewrite 10th graf, and insert new 11th and 12th grafs
with more on safety issue.)  
(mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Later this year, hundreds of thousands of drivers will
be able to have conversations with their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Tell the car to get on the information superhighway, and it will
download e-mail using relatively slow cellular phone connections. A
computerized ``voice'' will be able to read the e-mail through the
car's stereo speakers, automakers say. It will call out sports
scores on command, not just when a radio station programs them. It
will quote the latest stock prices. It will even be able to check
the traffic and give directions.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million cars and trucks in the United States are
expected to have this conversational capability by the end of the
year, using voice-recognition software to translate drivers' words
into a limited list of computer commands. That is not quite enough
to surf the Internet, but enough to splash in it.
</P>
<P>
   Some marketing experts are skeptical about the need for this
innovation, even if it can be made to work properly. ``Most people
don't want to talk to their car,'' said Jack F. Trout, president of
Trout &AMP; Partners, a marketing strategy firm based in Greenwich,
Conn. ``They want their car to shut up and drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, auto executives are forging ahead. Some Americans
have always used their cars as living rooms, dining rooms and
offices, and they expect this to be no different. Just as
cupholders allowed drivers to sip coffee during their commutes,
executives say, these devices will allow them to work on their way
to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within three years it will be in all of the new vehicles that
we're doing,'' Jacques A. Nasser, Ford Motor's chief executive,
said here last week at the North American International Auto Show,
where many of the talking cars were shown. ``We will do nothing
short of transforming our cars and our trucks into a portal for the
Internet.'' Ford's first talking cars will be the 2001 model year
Lincolns, on sale by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The first General Motors Internet-connected talking vehicles
will roll out of factory doors in a few months, and by year's end,
more than 400,000 cars, sport utility vehicles, pickups and
minivans will be ready to talk back to their owners, said Todd R.
Carstensen, a company spokesman. Many other automakers are rushing
to get their versions ready by next year, if not sooner. One
supplier, Delphi Automotive, already has $2.5 billion in orders
from seven automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Providing Internet access is one of a series of moves by
automakers to add safety and entertainment features _ and the added
charges they bring. Many minivans now come with video screens that
allow passengers in the back seat to watch movies. Some Ford and GM
cars are already equipped with wireless connections to operators
who can give directions, make dinner reservations or call a tow
truck, tracking the car with a global positioning satellite system.
If an air bag deploys, operators can send an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Voice-recognition technology is intended to give motorists
access to computers without requiring drivers to type and steer at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vehicles have to be safe,'' said Lawrence D. Burns, vice
president for research, development and planning at General Motors,
anticipating criticisms that computers might distract drivers and
cause accidents. ``Driving requires your eyes on the road and your
hands on the wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are concerned that even if the car does most of the
talking, drivers can be distracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only think about so many things at once, and if you're
in a traffic jam and changing lanes and thinking about your stock
quotes,'' that may be too much, said Michael J. Suman, a group vice
president at Johnson Controls Inc., which is working on the
systems. ``We want to be sure that the driver isn't talking to the
car and forgetting to keep the car on the road safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers will not be able to do many of the things they can do on
their home or office computer, and they will not get results as
quickly because of limits on the vocabulary of the
voice-recognition systems and the relatively slow speed of the
cellular Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the GM and Ford versions will not be able to send
e-mail. Ford's voice recognition software would understand just 200
words. While the systems are intended to be simple to use, Ford
drivers would need to know they should say ``get e-mail'' or ``read
e-mail'' and not just ``e-mail'' to cue the system, which listens
for verbs, or ``tell me the NPR news'' to hear National Public
Radio's latest Internet report.
</P>
<P>
   The system is by no means foolproof. If a backseat driver
interrupts, a Ford's ``voice'' is likely to pause, then utter a
patient-sounding ``say that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Voice recognition in cars ``is really just in its toddler stage
now,'' said Richard F. Doherty, director of research for
Envisioneering, a technology assessment and market research firm in
Seaford, N.Y. ``It is somewhere between being a great show-me
gimmick and a convenience, and it is getting closer to being a
convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Since most people keep the same car for years, automakers are
trying to design communications systems that can be updated as
better technology becomes available. So instead of equipping each
car with a computer that would be outdated almost as soon as it
made it out of the factory, Ford and GM plan to install cellular
communications equipment that links cars to land-based computers
that can be updated as new technology becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet cars would then use cellular phone connections to
link up to an Internet home page preprogrammed with the driver's
preferences for traffic, weather, news and stock reports, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, on the other hand, plans a ``bring your own
laptop'' approach. ``How many phones do you want to deal with? How
many Internet accesses?'' asked Robert J. Eaton, DaimlerChrysler's
vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to install a small screen, microphone and
cellular phone modem in its vehicles sometime within the next two
years. Drivers would then plug in their own equipment, said Stephen
J. Buckley, a DaimlerChrysler electronics specialist.
</P>
<P>
   While no manufacturer has yet set prices on the devices, the
bulk of revenue is likely to come from monthly wireless connection
and Internet access fees, with expected charges of $7 to $75 a
month. With that, drivers could turn on the ignition, tune in to
the Internet, and drop out of the boredom of commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Talking cars have been produced before. In the mid-1980s,
Chrysler New Yorkers would tell drivers ``your fuel is low'' or
``your door is ajar'' or ``fasten your seat belts.''
</P>
<P>
   But the car was a nag.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd hear it all the time, and if you didn't address the
issue right away, it would go on and on and on and drive you
crazy,'' said Steve Aretakis, the president of Hasco Spring
Industries in Oak Park, Mich., who suffered through a couple of
years of driving a 1984 New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Aretakis isn't holding his breath for the latest Internet
version of the talking car. ``I haven't had a car since like
that,'' he said. ``I don't really know if I'd want one, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
