<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-REPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY OFFERS GLOOMY FORECAST FOR EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From eroding soil in Kazakhstan to melting glaciers in the
Peruvian Andes to depleted fisheries off New England and elsewhere,
the world's ecological health at the dawn of the millennium is
deteriorating, the Worldwatch Institute concluded in its annual
State of the World report, which was released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Species are disappearing, temperatures are rising, reefs are
dying, forests are shrinking, storms are raging, water tables are
falling: Almost every ecological indicator shows a world on the
decline. And with the global population expected to hit 9 billion
in the next 50 years, those indicators are likely to worsen, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scale and urgency of the challenges ... are
unprecedented,'' said the Worldwatch president, Lester Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a growing population is especially disturbing, he
said. ``If we continue the irreversible destruction of these
systems, our grandchildren will never forgive us.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year since 1984, Worldwatch has examined indicators such as
energy production and tropical deforestation to get a measure of
how the world is faring. It has often painted a bleak and
unforgiving portrait, spurring the fury of conservative think tanks
and the fervor of environmental groups. It has done so again this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old stuff _ just more doom and gloom about the
Earth coming to an end because of what humans are doing,'' said
Myron Ebell, director of international environmental policy at the
Competitive Enterprise Institute. ``And it's all nonsense, of
course. They've been saying this for years, and it never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oppenheimer, chief scientist at the Environmental
Defense Fund, said the reports ``provide us with a road map, not
only to the immense problems that the global environment has
encountered, but also to solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings this year:
</P>
<P>
   --Earth's temperature has risen 0.8 degrees Fahrenheit in 30
years, and glaciers have melted, sometimes with striking results. A
prehistoric body surfaced in 1991 in the Alps, as did another last
year in the Yukon. ``Our ancestors are emerging from the ice with a
message for us: the Earth is getting warmer,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   --Extinction threatens 11 percent of bird species, 25 percent of
mammal species, and 34 percent of fish species.
</P>
<P>
   --The world is pumping 160 billion tons of water a year in
China, India, North Africa, the Middle East, and the United States.
This is more than aquifers can provide without running dry. The
water irrigates farms that produce 160 million tons of grain a year
to feed 480 million people. The pumping cannot be sustained.
</P>
<P>
   --Vicious circles known as ``feedback loops'' are wreaking havoc
with nature. For instance, global warming is causing more frequent
and more damaging hurricanes. They are destructive in part because
they cause mudslides, especially in developing countries: Hurricane
Mitch provoked a slide in 1998 in Central America that killed
10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Mudslides are more likely where land has been stripped of trees.
And when burned, the trees spew greenhouse gases that fuel global
warming. ``As pressures on the Earth's natural systems build, there
may be some disconcerting surprises as trends interact, reinforcing
each other and triggering abrupt changes,'' said the report's
author, Chris Bright.
</P>
<P>
   If the population and climate are not stabilized, ``there is not
an ecosystem on Earth that we can save,'' Brown said. He urged a
limit of two children per family and a faster transition to solar
and wind power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Worldwatch forecasts represent a mixed picture in my
mind,'' said Dan Esty, director of the Yale Center for
Environmental Law and Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gotten some things right and some things wrong,'' Esty
said. ''It's still important for people like Lester Brown to raise
the alarm on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a slight danger of a Chicken Little,
sky-is-falling effect that might inure people from taking that
message seriously, especially if mistakes in forecasts are not
corrected and analyses are not based on good foundations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Competitive Enterprise Institute, which like many
conservative think tanks champions free-market capitalism and
ecological solutions based on free enterprise rather than
government regulation, issued an advance rebuttal last month to the
report. It is called ``Earth Report 2000: The True State of the
Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   It notes among its findings that American life expectancy in the
20th century has risen from 56.4 to 76.5 years. Cancer incidence
and death rates have dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, Lester Brown and the Worldwatch Institute try
their darndest to spin a tale of impending woe, and every year they
come up empty,'' said Jerry Taylor, director of natural resource
studies at the Cato Institute, another conservative think tank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
