<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-JATRAS-NYT &LR;      01-15 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JATRAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN J. JATRAS, 73, FORMER PRESIDENT AND CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF
TELEX CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (js) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen J. Jatras, former president and chief executive of Telex
Corp. and a member of the Oklahoma Regents for Higher Education,
died at his home in Tulsa, Okla., on Jan. 8. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was complications from a brain tumor, his
daughter, Stephanie Buffum, said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in McKeesport, Pa., Jatras worked at Lockheed Corp. and
Midwestern Instruments before joining Telex as its president in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   Jatras held that post until 1981, when Roger M. Wheeler, the
entrepreneur who was chairman and chief executive of Telex, was
shot and killed at a Tulsa country club.
</P>
<P>
   Jatras added Wheeler's titles, and presided over seven years of
rising profits at the company, a producer of computer terminals and
peripheral equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Hard times hit Telex in 1987, however.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings began to shrink and its stock price fell sharply. In
response to those developments, a group led by Asher B. Edelman,
the New York investor, began a hostile $888 million bid for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Telex repelled the takeover, but was left heavily in debt and
tied to a new partner, Memorex.
</P>
<P>
   Jatras became vice chairman of Memorex Telex, a position he held
until 1990, when he greatly scaled back his role at the company, a
move leading to his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his business career, Jatras was active in
education.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 he was named a member of the University of Tulsa board
of trustees. In 1991 he was appointed to the Board of Regents of
Tulsa Junior College, which subsequently became Tulsa Community
College.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma named Jatras to a vacant
seat on the Oklahoma Regents for Higher Education. In May of the
following year he was appointed to a full nine-year term on the
board.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 inductee into the Oklahoma Hall of Fame, Jatras was a
strong advocate of the expansion of OneNet, Oklahoma's statewide
telecommunications and information network for education and
government.
</P>
<P>
   Jatras received his bachelor's degree in electrical engineering
from Carnegie Mellon University, and an M.S. degree, also in
electrical engineering, from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   He was a lifetime trustee of Carnegie-Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   A marriage to the former Frankie Jean McKinney ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Jatras is survived by five children, Stephanie, of Tulsa;
Andrew, of Boulder, Colo.; Cindy Hadden, of Tulsa; Todd, of
Brooklyn, N.Y.; Shawn, of Ramona, Calif.; and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7028 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      01-15 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REPUBLICAN CANDIDATES SQUARE OFF IN LAST IOWA DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Stands for Des Moines-dated item on budget)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspaper   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSTON, Iowa _ In the final Republican debate for this key
state's Jan. 24 presidential caucuses, front-runner Gov. George
Bush sparred with his two closest rivals Saturday over his record
of cutting taxes in Texas and whether his $483 billion tax-cut plan
helps low-income women.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon meeting, sponsored by the Des Moines Register, was
more amicable than one in Durham, N.H. last week where Bush and
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., pointed fingers at each other and argued
vociferously over taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As they began their last week of campaigning before the Iowa
caucuses, the candidates ranged over a wide variety of topics, some
old and some new. Among them: Education, preserving family farms,
environmental protection, and U.S. policy on China.
</P>
<P>
   Bush holds a commanding lead in most Iowa polls. The Des Moines
Register's Iowa Poll, for instance, last week put Bush at 45
percent, with publishing magnate Steve Forbes running a distant
second with 18 percent. The other candidates, McCain, conservative
activist Gary Bauer, conservative radio commentator Alan Keyes, and
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, all lingered far behind in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is officially not competing in Iowa and has no formal
organization in the state.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidates were allowed to question each other, Bush
criticized McCain's $170 billion tax plan that would deny
deductions for business expenses for transportation, meals and
continuing education. Bush said the plan would hurt working
Americans, particularly the ``single mom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I have to say to the single mom is that I've
got a tax cut for you and Gov. Bush doesn't,'' McCain shot back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Bush responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it is true,'' McCain said, insisting his plan addresses
the looming financial problems of the Social Security trust fund
while paring down the $5.6 trillion national debt. Bush defended
his plan, saying it sets aside $2 billion to save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Forbes charged that the real estate tax cuts that Bush
supported in Texas had no impact on the wallets of six of 10
Texans. Bush, raising his voice in one of the few heated moments of
the debate, told Forbes _ the scion of the wealthy Forbes
publishing family _ that ``it may not be real in million-dollar
houses, but it's real if you got a $40,000 house.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his real estate tax cuts could amount to a 25 percent
reduction for some Texas homeowners. ``It's really real for a lot
of folks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on taxes was interspersed with a few unusual moments,
including Hatch's repeated touting of his paid TV commercial, a
so-called ``fireside chat,`` and Keyes substituting a prayer for
his closing remarks.
</P>
<P>
   With Iowa's economy much improved since the rust-belt era of the
1980s, morality and character are top agenda items for Iowa
Republicans, according to the Register's Iowa Poll. Among
Republicans, 72 percent responded that upholding the highest
standards of personal conduct is an ``unbreakable rule'' for
candidates. By contrast, only 40 percent of Democrats agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a morality-and-character question, Bauer invoked
his service in the Reagan administration, recalling that Reagan
always wore a coat and tie in the Oval Office. ``I don't have to
remind or embarrass this audience about what the current president
did in this office,'' Bauer said, referring to President Clinton's
meetings with then-White House intern Monica Lewinsky for Oval
Office trysts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a president's oath of office includes an implicit
pledge to preserve the dignity of the office of the presidency.
Bush said that if elected, he would appoint officials who see
``service to our country as a privilege and will not stain the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Iowa caucuses, registered voters in each party meet
around the state to select delegates to their party's presidential
nominating conventions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-MIDEAST-$ADV17-COX     01-15 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MIDEAST-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH LEGACY AT RISK, CLINTON SEEKS TO GUIDE MIDEAST PEACE ALONG
TWO TRACKS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., Jan. 17 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to build momentum this week(CQ) for the most
ambitious foreign policy goal of his remaining term, President
Clinton is slated to host the three key players in his crusade to
broker peace in the Middle East before he leaves office next year.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa return Wednesday for their third round of
land-for-peace negotiations under Clinton's auspices.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat
comes to the White House, amid talk of a possible Barak-Arafat
peace summit near here in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hopes to help press Barak and Sharaa forward in talks he
initiated between the two men in December, then followed up with a
week of slow-starting negotiations earlier this month in the rural
hamlet of Shepherdstown, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   He also means to prod Arafat and Barak along toward their
pledged goal of completing a so-called framework agreement _ at
least outlining areas of broad agreement and a timetable for
resolving outstanding disputes _ by mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   If there is ``sufficient progress,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright might try to arrange a February summit between
Arafat and Barak, said her spokesman, James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to rule out the possibility that Clinton might
bring together Barak and Arafat this week, as was reported in the
Israeli press, though no such meeting has yet been announced in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Making peace between Israel and its Arab neighbors is a goal
that has eluded successive presidencies since the Jewish state's
birth half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   That quest is far from over. Israel faces both hard bargaining
and painful compromise if it is to strike meaningful peace accords
with Arafat and Sharaa, both of whom must confront similar
difficulties to win agreements with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In his mind's eye, though, Clinton can doubtless already imagine
an October White House ceremony, with Arabs and Israelis inking an
historic peace pact on the sun-splashed lawn, before the admiring
gaze of a grateful nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is now looking to history,'' said Michael Hudson,
director of the Center for Contemporary Arab studies at Georgetown
University, where Clinton attended law school. ``Strangely enough,
he may actually have the possibility of a major foreign policy
victory in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't erase from Clinton's biography his mixed overall
policy record and his House impeachment _ and subsequent Senate
acquittal _ over his relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. If it wouldn't remove the stain of scandal,
though, it would go a long way toward taking out the sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he could pull it off, I think he would be in the same class
as Jimmy Carter, who, with Camp David, really did leave an
important legacy,'' said Hudson. ``Even if he can pull off half of
it, he'll be remembered as a peacemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to suggest that Clinton's Mideast peace gambit
is being driven only by his need to resurrect his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is this country's strongest ally in the oil-rich Middle
East, and American presidents have tried since 1948 to ensure
Israeli peace with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   It might well be argued, in fact, that five decades of treaties
and betrayal, enmity and war, somehow stretch beyond recognition
the definition of a peace process.
</P>
<P>
   What it has all been about, though, is far more than settling a
border dispute. The grand geo-strategic vision has always been to
build a Jewish state in a sea of Arab opposition stretching back at
least to 1917.
</P>
<P>
   That's the year when British Foreign Secretary Arthur James
Balfour declared his country's support for ``the establishment in
Palestine of a National Home for the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   Inconveniently for large numbers of Palestinians, Britain had
just seized control of Palestine from the Ottoman Turks, and so was
able to translate what became known as the ``Balfour Declaration,''
into a policy promoting Jewish migration to the area in the years
prior to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust provided global impetus to speed that process and,
in 1948, under the auspices of the United Nations, Israel was born,
and quickly attacked by its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter brokered peace between Israel and Egypt
in 1978, during the summit at Camp David, the presidential retreat
in the Maryland suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's Palestinian Authority struck a broad peace accord with
Israel in 1993 _ in office for less than a year at the time,
Clinton had little to do with the agreement, other than to host a
formal signing ceremony on the White House lawn. Jordan struck its
own peace accord with Israel the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians agreed to formally recognize Israel's right to
exist, however, only in December 1998, when Clinton journeyed to
Palestinian controlled Gaza. Even now, far from all Palestinians
have bought into peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Formally, Syria and Israel remain in a state of war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, Clinton is encouraged by several
factors.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Barak was elected last spring on a pro-peace
platform. The highly decorated career soldier visited the White
House a few weeks later vowing to ``leave no stone unturned,'' in
the pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for Israel would be peace with its neighbors for the
first time ever. Not only would Israel be able to, in theory at
least, reduce the high state of military alert the country has cut
its teeth on, but it could begin to look to the day when it is
fully integrated into the Arab region, economically as well as
socially.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's adversaries, moreover, appear to be living on, if not
borrowed time, certainly not an excessive amount of it.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, 70, and Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, just one year
his junior, have begun to realize they don't have forever to strike
a deal on terms they can at least influence heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's control over the Palestinian people isn't exactly
unchallenged: he stays in power, and alive, largely with the help
of an extensive security force. He appears to understand that to
prevent his thin consensus for peace from shattering, he must
deliver, and sooner rather than later, on the fruits of peace. That
is, chiefly, long-delayed economic development for the Gaza and
West Bank lands Israel is handing over to Palestinian control as
part of the price of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat and Barak have pledged to work out, by mid-September, the
outstanding issues dividing them, such as the future of Jerusalem
and the question of Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Observers believe Assad is ready to end his country's state of
war with Israel to prepare the way for his son to one day succeed
him. If war continues, along with the heavy reliance on military
influence in Syria that comes with it, those prospects are
considerably dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the price for Israel is land, in this case, the return to
Syria of the Golan Heights, strategic land Israeli troops seized
during the 1967 Arab-Israeli War. Barak _ ``He has put peace at the
top of his agenda,'' Clinton said last spring _ has signaled his
willingness to give up the Golan, over the objections of many
Israelis, in exchange for security guarantees and the establishment
of economic and diplomatic ties with its large Arab neighbor to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Syrian-Israeli deal is a deal that can be structured,''
said Mideast expert Jon Alterman of the U.S. Institute of Peace, a
quasi-governmental think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither side wants to fight the other,'' said Alterman, ``and
the United States is serious about wanting to make (a peace accord)
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   These factors, and others, argue in favor of Clinton being able
to help broker peace between Israel and Syria and Israel and the
Palestinians. The question on many an analyst's mind is, ``At what
cost?''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which already sends Israel some $3 billion a
year in military and economic aid, is likely to have to increase
that dramatically to help compensate Israel for lands it plans to
withdraw from and for military facilities in intends to leave
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also weighing an Israeli request to deploy U.S.
troops to the region, perhaps as part of a larger U.N. mission to
help police the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately a lot of this is about making people feel
comfortable,'' Alterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is unquestionably good at that, and he's clearly
committed to putting in the time it takes to help shepherd talks on
the Israeli-Syrian track as well as the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
   What's unknown, and at this point unknowable, is just how flawed
a set of accords Clinton is willing to swallow in the interest of
being able to declare himself the first great peacemaker of the new
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can probably lock up the treaties he needs,''
Alterman said, ``but the durability of the peace will depend on the
implementation, and that is something he can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CHILD-VISITATION     01-15 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHILD-VISITATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OF PARENTS AND GRANDPARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Jan. 16:
</P>
<P>
   At a time when family relationships are changing, the Supreme
Court is weighing a case involving grandparents' visitation rights
that raises the fundamental question of who decides how children
are reared. The justices heard arguments last week on a Washington
state statute that permits grandparents and others to seek
court-ordered visitation, over a parent's objections, if such
visits would be in a child's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Parents have a right under the Constitution to rear their
children without government interference. Only in cases where harm
or threat of harm to a child exists has government been allowed to
usurp the decision-making rights of the parents. But Troxel vs.
Granville poses a case where a state court overrode a parent's
judgment in recognizing other ties.
</P>
<P>
   Jenifer and Gary Troxel petitioned for visitation with their two
young granddaughters after their son, Brad Troxel, the children's
father, committed suicide. The children's mother, Tommie Granville
Wynn, who was not married to Brad Troxel, did not cut off the
children's contact with the Troxels but opposed overnight stays.
The trial judge went against the mother's wishes and ordered one
weekend visit a month, along with other requirements. The
Washington Supreme Court ruled that the statute violated the
mother's protected right to autonomy in making child-rearing
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The states generally have laws that allow grandparents to seek
visitation with grandchildren, but Washington's law is unusual
because it allows ``any person'' at ``any time'' to petition a
family court and get visitation rights if the court determines that
such visits would be best for the child. During argument, the
justices seemed clearly troubled by a law that Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor called ``breathtakingly broad.''
</P>
<P>
   The statute allows virtual strangers with no significant
relation to the child to petition for visitation, forcing parents
to incur legal costs to oppose frivolous requests in court. The law
also sets the bar for visitation far too low in using a ``best
interest of the child'' standard. That standard may be appropriate
in custody disputes when state intervention is necessary because
the parents cannot agree or when there is no fit parent to whom the
court can defer. But when used in a visitation context, the ``best
interest'' standard, which is subjective and broadly defined,
allows a state court to substitute its judgment for the parent's.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court should affirm the Washington court's decision
that the statute is clearly unconstitutional. Parents have
longstanding legal primacy in child rearing that must be protected
from state intrusion. But in some extraordinary cases, a child may
have exceptionally close attachments to grandparents or other
adults, and arbitrarily ending those bonds could cause a child
substantial psychological harm. A law based on a standard of harm
might provide the court reason to look more closely at this issue,
but the Washington statute does not serve as a basis for doing so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-US-MIDEAST-$ADV17-COX     01-15 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MIDEAST-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH LEGACY AT RISK, CLINTON SEEKS TO GUIDE MIDEAST PEACE ALONG
TWO TRACKS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., Jan. 17 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
