<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A DORM ROOM RENT-FREE, WON IN AN ONLINE LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day there seems to be a geometric increase in the number
of deals being offered through the Internet. Get Rich Quick! Lose
Weight Now! Earn Free Dollars!
</P>
<P>
   So when Ray Shawn Williams decided on a lark to fill out a form
for an online lottery that promised the winner a semester of free
student housing, he figured it was just another gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he also figured he had nothing to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a sophomore at Long Island University in Brooklyn, had
been living on campus, but the cost of room and board, nearly
$4,000 a semester, wasn't covered by his student aid. His college
adviser suggested that he would probably find it less expensive to
live off campus.
</P>
<P>
   So Williams, who gets some money from his parents in Boston but
also works 20 hours a week in the shipping department at Sony,
began searching for a place in November. Brokers told him he could
get a studio in Bedford-Stuyvesant for about $515 a month, and he
was about to take a place when he got a call from someone telling
him that he had just won six months of free housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caller said, `I have good news to tell you. You filled out
a form for free rent, and you won.' I said, `Really? I did? I don't
even remember. You're kidding me? This has to be a joke.''' But it
wasn't a joke. An organization called Educational Housing Services,
which describes itself as the largest noncollege provider of
student housing in New York City, had randomly selected his name in
a drawing that had 10,000 entries. Beginning Jan. 1, he was
entitled to free rent in one of the company's dormitories, at 200
Tillary Street in downtown Brooklyn, not far from his campus.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams asked if he would get the offer in writing, and
the voice said yes, he decided that the call was probably valid.
``I was, like, thank you,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the new year, Williams moved into the
building, a former produce distribution center that is now filled
with large loftlike rooms, each occupied by three students. He has
what can only be called an instant bedroom: a single piece of
furniture with a bed on top, desk underneath and on the end, a
closet. ``I've never been in a bunk bed so high,'' he says. ``At
night it's beautiful, looking out on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The 800-square-foot space, in addition to accommodating his two
roommates in similar setups, has a large kitchen area, a television
hanging near the ceiling, and a bathroom with lockers for each
student. If he decides to stay in the dorm after this semester, his
rent will be $700 a month.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall by his bed is a poster for Missy Elliott, a rapper,
producer and director whose work he admires. ``I just love her
music,'' he says. ``She's original.'' Since the age of 3, he says,
he has wanted to sing and dance, and remembers as a young child
mimicking Michael Jackson in his video for ``Thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   In high school, he began working for radio station WJMN in
Boston, and continued after he graduated, but eventually his
parents prevailed on him to go to college, to have training that
would offer him a backup if he doesn't make it as an entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, who is 22, seems to be off to a good start. He
appears in a music video now airing for ``Do It Again (Put Your
Hands Up)'' by Jay-Z, and will be in one coming out later this
month for Ja Rule. This semester, he is taking all his classes at
night so he will be free for daytime auditions. He is majoring in
media arts, which is giving him training in television and video
production.
</P>
<P>
   Although Williams is gratified by his good fortune, and
estimates he'll be able to save a few thousand dollars between now
and June that will help him rent an apartment in the future, it's
not the first time he has been a winner. Three or four times over
the years, he says, he has been the ``lucky caller'' to a radio
station, getting free tickets to concerts and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never won cash,'' he says, ``but you never know. I'm a
living witness that you should go for something you see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
