<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COURTS-OVERHAUL-NY     01-15 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COURTS-OVERHAUL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: PARTISAN RANCOR THREATENS EFFORT TO OVERHAUL NEW
YORK'S COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After New York's chief judge called last week for a
sweeping restructuring of the state's antiquated court system,
experts predicted that the proposal would end up like a similar one
did last year _ a victim of death by partisanship in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   For a quarter-century, partisan rancor in the capital has
scuttled efforts to streamline one of the most byzantine court
systems in the nation, law professors and watchdog groups say, and
this time is expected to be no different, although the idea is
gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
   In her annual state of the judiciary address on Monday, Chief
Judge Judith S. Kaye announced an investigation into political
patronage in the courts. She also outlined efforts to deal with
chronic low-level criminals who escape with light sentences, and
low pay for court-appointed lawyers. But her most far-reaching
proposal by far would broadly reconfigure the court system.
</P>
<P>
   The experts said that the proposals that Judge Kaye could
implement herself, like the patronage inquiry, would be carried
out. But they predicted inaction on the far more sweeping _ and
some argue far more necessary _ structural remedies that would
require the agreement of Albany's three top leaders _ Gov. George
Pataki, a Republican; Joseph L. Bruno, the Republican leader of the
Senate; and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that it doesn't need legislation, she will do
it,'' said Steven Zeidman, executive director of the Fund for
Modern Courts.
</P>
<P>
   Simplifying New York's courts is far from a new idea. Previous
chief judges and former Gov. Mario Cuomo have floated proposals,
but the same constitutional standards and political squabbling
between Republicans and Democrats that threaten Judge Kaye's
proposal scuttled those plans.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the two parties have cited a wide variety of
reasons for the lack of an overhaul, but the repeated deal breaker
has been the inability of the two sides to agree on the numbers of
judges for each jurisdiction. The key to a deal has been political
horse trades, in which an increase in judges for a
Republican-controlled area, for example, would be exchanged for a
similar increase in judges in a Democratic district. But the two
sides have been largely unable to agree for the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a series of patchwork remedies that have
created an arcane state court system that causes average citizens
to scratch their heads, wastes resources and in low-level criminal
cases is derided as a plea bargain mill.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Republicans and Democrats were unable to agree on
how to add more judges in New York City to deal with the flood of
cases generated by the state's tough new Rockefeller drug laws.
Democrats essentially favored changing the state Constitution,
which limits the election of state Supreme Court justices to one
for every 50,000 people. But upstate Republicans opposed that plan
because more judges in the city would have meant more Democratic
patronage.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise, legislators agreed to allow ``acting'' justices
appointed by court administrators and the governor. Twenty years
later, the compromise stands. As a result, in a state with a
Constitution that mandates an elected Supreme Court, nearly half of
the justices in the city are appointed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the sharp drop in serious crime in the city, the court
system has too many justices, according to court officials. More
lower-level criminal court judges are needed to handle the flood of
misdemeanor cases generated by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's crackdown
on quality of life crimes. The result is a system that pressures
judges to decide minor cases in as little as two minutes, which can
result in what critics call generous plea deals for chronic
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   And Family Court, which has seen its caseload rise by 30 percent
in the last decade, is also in need of more judges. Court
administrators shift judges back and forth to deal with the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Problems also exist in the appellate courts, whose districts
were last readjusted in 1894. Today, one appellate court hears all
cases from Manhattan and the Bronx, for example, while another
court hears all cases from Queens, Richmond, Nassau, Suffolk,
Westchester and four Hudson Valley counties _ an area holding half
the state's population.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye's broadest proposal would reorganize the nine courts
in the city into two courts, create a new appellate court and
generally give judges greater flexibility in handling cases. Pataki
and Bruno backed a version of the proposal last year. But Assembly
Democrats opposed it, offering their own plan, which died after it
left the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Pataki and Republican and Democratic leaders, as well
as a myriad of lobbying groups like the State Bar Association, all
say they support streamlining the system. But engineering a horse
trade that would ensure each party's de facto control over enough
judgeships remains, as before, the sticking point.
</P>
<P>
   If the Legislature fails to enact restructuring this year, it
will have to be put off for two more years, because it requires a
constitutional amendment approved by two consecutive state
Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   One lobbyist who supports the restructuring said the problem was
in part Catch-22. Other than lawyers, the people who deal the most
with the state court system are accused criminals, a group with
scant political power in Albany. And the public, he said, is either
uninterested or confused by the state's labyrinthine judicial
system, making restructuring less than a hot-button issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no political motivation,'' said the lobbyist. ``Most
people tend not to think of the courts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1752EST &QL; 
