<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     01-15 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: QUITE A NIGHT TO BEHOLD AT HOOPS CENTRAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It is quite enough just to walk into the
spacious, new, high-tech fieldhouse of Conseco Arena, with its
serious basketball jones _ in one of the display cases, Oscar's
jersey from Crispus Attucks High.
</P>
<P>
   But we'll talk about architecture and Hoosier madness down the
road. Friday night was about the Lakers and the Pacers, not just
another National Basketball Association midwinter plod-through, but
maybe an emotional prelude to finals in June.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of a night that clears the palate. Oh, yeah, that's why
pro basketball can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   The retro standings board told the story. At both ends of the
new arena, there are manual top 10 lists of the league's leading
teams. On Friday, the list began: L.A. Lakers 31-5. Portland 27-8.
Indiana 23-11. Two out of three ain't bad.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were on a 16-game roll. Big story in Sports
Illustrated. People were asking Phil Jackson if his team could beat
the league record of 33, set by the 1971-72 Lakers of Wilt and
Elgin and West.
</P>
<P>
   No, Jackson had been saying. Just no. Too many good teams these
days. He has shed his hermit sackcloth and ashes and instilled a
bit more discipline in these Lakers. But now, he has been saying
with deep gravity, the turnaround has been so sudden that everybody
is pointing at his team.
</P>
<P>
   One of those good teams is the Pacers, a clubhouse jammed with
adults like Reggie Miller, Sam Perkins, Chris Mullin and Mark
Jackson. After the sourness of the Knicks, what a concept.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's active skull was shimmering on the court at 5:30 p.m.,
fully two and a half hours before game time. He is from L.A. His
sister, Cheryl the great, would be doing color analysis for TBS. He
pumped shots from the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   Under the stands, Donnie Walsh, the New Yorker who runs the
Pacers, was talking about Phil Jackson's impact this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a confirmation that good coaches mean a lot in this
league,'' Walsh said emphatically. ``We've had Larry Brown and
Larry Bird. They've got Phil. If they keep getting better, they'll
be tough to beat. They are winning through their defense. Shaquille
O'Neal is playing great defense. He's as big a man as I remember,
and he's very agile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers began warming up and Jackson shambled into the media
room to cop a bit of dessert. The young woman with the clipboard at
the door asked who he was with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bulls,'' he said absent-mindedly, before realizing his
mistake. ``The Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson paused to talk about his old pal Bill Bradley, who is
running for president. He thinks Bradley is doing well in the
Democratic nomination process. He also advanced the theory that
George W. Bush desperately wants four long shots _ Keyes, Hatch,
Bauer and Forbes _ to remain in the Republican race as long as
possible, because they make Bush seem so, so, so safe. Phil Jackson
was always good on theories.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal rumbled back to the locker room and sat still for the
reporters. He had behaved remotely toward two previous coaches, but
O'Neal had respected Jackson before he even arrived because, he
said: ``I was raised to respect authority, and Phil is the guy
who'll take us over the hump. He's a no-nonsense guy. His record
speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The word has been that Jackson has not been up to his penchant
in Chicago for passing out selected books to his players, but
O'Neal revealed that Jackson has given him a book by Friedrich
Nietzsche.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq would not say which one, but, he added with his rapper's
knowing inventiveness, ``I'm analyzing it, scrutinizing it,
dissectisizing it.''
</P>
<P>
   First quarter. The two teams began dissectisizing each other on
the court. Shaq made a gorgeous bounce pass to Kobe Bryant early,
but the Pacers were digging in. With 15 seconds left in the period,
Bryant took a premature drive and missed, and Perkins fired the
ball to Miller who found his spot from the five-minute-30-second
workout, and drilled a jumper at the buzzer for a 33-30 Pacer lead.
</P>
<P>
   Second quarter. Mo Mullins, who had the first 12 DNP-CD (Did Not
Play-Coach's Decision) of his career this season, made two
3-pointers within 49 seconds. Lakers up at the half, 58-57.
</P>
<P>
   Third quarter. Bryant, still only 21 with no college experience,
kept freelancing, Spree-style, outside the familiar Bulls' triangle
offense. Lakers up, 77-75.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter. Two Indy subs, Travis Best and Austin Croshere,
scored 20 points between them, as O'Neal kept missing shots near
the basket. The public-address system blasted the annoying Indy-car
whine. Miller buried another three. His sister, standing near
courtside, sideline mike in hand, appeared to swallow a smile.
Pacers win. Final score, 111-102.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great basketball team, best we've seen so far,''
Bird said. ``A big win for us. It seemed like playoff intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Things come to an end,'' Phil Jackson revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been watching game films,'' said Sam Perkins, who played
two years for the Lakers. ``Teams just try to roll with them.
Showtime, you know. We figured, if you get down and dirty with
them, you might have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They played well but we beat ourselves,'' Shaq said. ``I'm
blaming the SI jinx.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams rushed separately out into the cold Indiana night.
The Pacers would play at Orlando Saturday night. The Lakers would
play at Minnesota Saturday night. Nobody will touch the 33-game
streak any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   However, in this high-tech fieldhouse, with memories of the past
_ photos of a young John Wooden, the team photo from ``Hoosiers'' _
there was a hint of late spring, when the evening sun might glow
through the huge windows at the top, as these two teams could be
back at it again, here in the heartland, here in Basketball
Central.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
