<HEADLINE>
WALSH FRUSTRATED WITH 49ERS AND CRITICS WHO SAY HE'S TOO OLD AT
68 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Walsh will always be known as one of the smartest men in
professional football. As the coach and architect of the San
Francisco 49ers throughout the 1980s, Walsh was the leader of a
football renaissance and one of the main reasons the franchise
captured five Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   But Walsh, the team's vice president and general manager the
past year, is no longer the strapping genius who patrolled the
sideline. When meeting with reporters for an end-of-the-season
briefing, he conducted a rambling and at times emotional session
that covered everything from the team's terrible salary-cap
situation to sleazy journalism. It was one of the oddest moments of
the 49er season and was exemplary of the state of disarray one of
the National Football League's most storied franchises.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked about suggestions that he should retire
because of his age, Walsh, who turned 68 on Nov. 30, angrily
responded: ``I think there is a form of discrimination related to
my age in years. I don't know. I think those who know me fairly
well can see that I'm physically fit and have my wits about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is captain of a rapidly sinking vessel, and many of the
openings in the hull are of his doing. His signing the troubled
running back Lawrence Phillips proved to be disastrous. Walsh
brought back Charles Haley, who was a failure, and he has managed
the team's draft and salary-cap situation poorly.
</P>
<P>
   But Walsh is not the 49ers' only problem. The owners of the
team, the DeBartolo family, have in the past few years engaged in a
civil war for control of the franchise, and those battles have
certainly been a major distraction. And stars like Steve Young, 38,
and Jerry Rice, 37, have aged to the point where they are not
effective players any more.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is $24 million over the projected $62.2 million
salary cap for the 2000 season. Six veterans have been asked to
take dramatic pay cuts, including Young (who is scheduled to earn
$8.1 million next year), Rice ($5.49 million), linebacker Ken
Norton ($3.572 million), guard Ray Brown ($3.492 million), safety
Tim McDonald ($3.035 million) and center Chris Dalman ($4.766
million). At it now stands, these players alone would count an
astounding $28.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The team has until March 1 to get back under the cap, or it will
face penalties of up to $1 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are in such a desperate situation that they have been
talking to other teams about trading their No. 3 overall pick and
moving lower in the round. The 49ers cannot afford the salary-cap
obligation that would come with paying the third selection.
</P>
<P>
   How do the 49ers fix their problems? There have been discussions
about trading or cutting Rice and Young, though it seems more
likely that the team will work out something so both can finish
their careers in San Francisco. The 49ers may also be considering
giving coach Steve Mariucci more say in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is bound for the Hall of Fame. It is to be hoped that what
is now happening with the 49ers will not irreparably damage what
has been a great career. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cutting Dilfer's Cost
</P>
<P>
   During the last part of the regular season Tampa Bay Buccaneers
quarterback Trent Dilfer spent most his time as the backup to the
rookie Shaun King. Occasionally television cameras would show
Dilfer on the sideline, cheering the team. And there is no question
that Dilfer, at one point the team's longtime starter, played the
good soldier while King led Tampa Bay to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer's stay in Tampa Bay has been largely unsuccessful.
Nevertheless, he is due $4.5 million if the team chooses to
exercise an option on the remaining two years of his contract.
General manager Rich McKay and coach Tony Dungy wanted to see how
King performed down the stretch of the regular season and in the
postseason before making any decision about Dilfer. But make no
mistake about it: The team is ready to cut Dilfer loose.
</P>
<P>
   King displayed tremendous poise for such a young player, going
4-1 as a starter in the team's final five regular-season games, and
avoided his previous trap of turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly Favors Houston &UR;  &LR;  Charley Casserly, the former general
manager of the Washington Redskins, who was fired by owner Daniel
Snyder, is one of the hot commodities in football. Casserly was
expected to have his second interview this weekend with Houston
owner Bob McNair about the football operations job there. Casserly
is also to meet with New Orleans Saints owner Tom Benson about the
same position.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly has privately said that if he were offered both
positions, his preference would be Houston. Casserly would have
lots of salary-cap room and plenty of extra draft picks since
Houston is an expansion franchise. With Casserly's skill at
evaluating talent and an abundance of picks, he could build a
playoff team faster in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints will have $17 million in salary-cap room for the 2000
season, but because of last spring's trade for running back Ricky
Williams, the team does not have a first- or third-round pick for
the April draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Casserly might have some stiff competition for both
openings. Tom Donahoe, another outstanding talent evaluator,
resigned on Friday as the director of football operations for the
Pittsburgh Steelers, mainly because of his differences with coach
Bill Cowher. Both Saints and Houston officials will almost
certainly interview Donahoe.
</P>
<P>
   Carson's Fleeting Fame
</P>
<P>
   One of the NFL's best run-stoppers was the former Giants
linebacker Harry Carson. He was a brilliant, ferocious player, and
he deserves to be in the Hall of Fame. Carson is one of 15
finalists for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Carson gets in is a close call. The Hall of Fame
bylaws state that at least 4 of the 15 finalists must be voted in,
but the total class cannot be more than 7, which means the
competition will be stiff. The San Francisco 49ers teammates Joe
Montana and Ronnie Lott are locks. Wide receiver James Lofton was
one of the most productive ever at his position and will most
likely make it, as will tight end Dave Casper, who spent much of
his career with the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   That is probably four spots taken there, and while a maximum of
seven players can get in, look for only four or five to do so,
which makes Carson's chances tough. Other candidates include
Pittsburgh Steelers teammates John Stallworth and Lynn Swann,
defensive end Howie Long and Los Angeles Rams defensive end Jack
Youngblood.
</P>
<P>
   Saban a Belichick Fan &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Nick Saban, the new Louisiana State coach who left Michigan
State, contacted Bill Belichick about becoming the team's defensive
coordinator, NFL team officials said. Saban knew it was a long
shot; Belichick is expected to become the head coach of the New
England Patriots once Belichick's contract mess is sorted out by
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue as early as tomorrow. Saban and
Belichick have been friends since Saban served as Belichick's
defensive coordinator when both were coaches with the Browns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
