</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DAVENPORT, Iowa -- Jan. 15, 2000 --
GORE-TRANSFORMATION-2 -- At the Center for Active Seniors in
Davenport, Vice President Al Gore, takes questions. At times,
especially when he touches on highbrow or intellectual topics, he
can come across as distant and professorial. Yet when he is fully
charged, Gore can juice up his audiences and keep Iowans almost
spellbound, alternately laughing at his jokes and riveted by his
stories. An emphasis on anecdotes, grandchildren and handshaking
means there is less time for hard-core discussions of the issues,
which plays into the campaign's decision to avoid controversy as
Gore sits on a comfortable lead in Iowa. (Paul Hosefros/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) DAVENPORT, Iowa -- Jan. 15, 2000 -- GORE-TRANSFORMATION-1
-- In Davenport, Iowa, last week, a relaxed Al Gore was happy to
take a question which sailed past him after being delivered via
paper airplane by Mrs. Alfred Whitaker, standing in rear. Audience
participation seems to have become a central tool for Gore. He
often begins an event by going around the room and shaking every
single person's hand, even if it takes nearly an hour. The emphasis
on anecdotes, grandchildren and handshaking means there is less
time for hard-core discussions of the issues, which plays into the
campaign's decision to avoid controversy as Gore sits on a
comfortable lead in Iowa. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PHILADELPHIA -- Jan. 15, 2000 -- PHILADELPHIA-COMMISH --
``Start locking them up,'' Philadelphia Police Commissioner John F.
Timoney has ordered as he has seen enough of the latest crime
statistics from a particularly rough southwest neighborhood. ``It
looks like it's out of control out there,'' he says, a touch of his
old side-of-the-mouth, New York Police Department roots showing in
his annoyance. ``I mean, two cars exchanging gunfire before
innocent civilians. That's crazy. We need a sense of urgency out
there,'' says Timoney. (Laura A. Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KATZRIN, Golan Heights -- Jan. 15, 2000 -- ISRAEL-GOLAN-6
-- Fearing the future as they look into Syria, with Mount Hermon in
the background, Erez Zur ,32, and Rachel Kogan. Erez's brother
Alon, from Kibutz Ortal in the Golan Heights, was killed in the war
between Israel and Lebanon in 1982. Wreckage of an Israeli tank in
the background is a clear reminder of the war. For decades, the
military, which captured the Golan after brutal battles in 1973,
considered the area a strategic necessity to defend northern Israel
against what used to be sporadic shelling by Syria. Now, though, in
the face of what some believe to be a severely deteriorated Syrian
army, it is reassessing its security plans. (Rina Castelnuovo/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KATZRIN, Golan Heights -- Jan. 15, 2000 -- ISRAEL-GOLAN-5
-- Moshe Zaidon, 59, a manager of a local cafeteria in Katzrin,
talks with some local children. Zaidon has possessed a deep-seated
belief that the time would come when all Israeli settlers in the
Golan Heights would have to pull up stakes and leave. ``I knew from
the beginning that we were living on Syrian land,'' he says. ``Over
time, the Golan became by law an inseparable part of Israel. But
deep inside, I knew this day might arrive. If there was a chance of
peace with the Syrians, I always knew that we were the bargaining
chip.'' (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MOUNT HERMON, Golan heights -- Jan. 15, 2000 --
ISRAEL-GOLAN-4 --An Israeli special forces sniper in position
during a drill on snowcapped Mount Hermon. Israel's electronic
espionage network, with its early warning system, unimpeded
surveillance and top-secret listening devices, sits way atop Mount
Hermon. The army's alpine skiers patrol the area. With the revival
of the Israeli-Syrian peace effort after a nearly four-year
stalemate, the Golan Heights has entered a state of flux. Any peace
agreement would entail an Israeli withdrawal from the Golan
Heights, experts agree. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MOUNT HERMON, Golan heights -- Jan. 15, 2000 --
ISRAEL-GOLAN-3 --Israel's electronic espionage network, with its
early warning system, unimpeded surveillance and top-secret
listening devices, sits atop Mount Hermon. The army's alpine skiers
patrol the area. With the revival of the Israeli-Syrian peace
effort after a nearly four-year stalemate, the Golan Heights has
entered a state of flux. Any peace agreement would entail an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights, experts agree. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LAKE TIBERIAS, Golan Heights -- Jan. 15, 2000 --
ISRAEL-GOLAN-2 -- The view down at Israel from the mountainous
surroundings of Lake Tiberias in the Golan Heights. With the
revival of the Israeli-Syrian peace effort after a nearly four-year
stalemate, the Golan Heights has entered a state of flux. Any peace
agreement would entail an Israeli withdrawal from the Golan
Heights, experts agree. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) KATZRIN, Golan Heights -- Jan. 15, 2000 -- ISRAEL-GOLAN-1
-- A series of photographs shows the panorama of the
Israeli-controlled Golan Heights, looking toward Israel and
Lebanon. The peaks of snow-covered Mount Hermon are in the
background, with the water reservoir in front. With the revival of
the Israeli-Syrian peace effort after a nearly four-year stalemate,
the Golan Heights has entered a state of flux. Any peace agreement
would entail an Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights, experts
agree. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Jan. 15, 2000 -- DRUGWARS-WOUNDED -- Andrew
Aiken, left, visits Daniel Appan in his Brooklyn apartment; both
are paralyzed and in wheelchairs from gunshot wounds. They are just
two of hundreds of young black and Hispanic men crippled by gunshot
wounds during New York's crack epidemic a decade ago. Across the
country, an estimated 4,900 blacks and 2,000 Hispanics were
paralyzed in violent incidents between 1987 and 1994, the peak of
the epidemic. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
