<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POWERBALL-595(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S POWERBALL PUSH: HIGH ODDS, BUT DON'T COUNT IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Would anyone turn down a lottery jackpot worth
$124 million a year? Certainly not all those frenzied New Yorkers
who flock to Connecticut for a shot at a bank-busting payout from
the Powerball lottery.
</P>
<P>
   And not Gov. George Pataki either, even though by most accounts,
he is not a betting man himself.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, lobbied again last week to bring Powerball
to New York even though a similar effort last year failed to win
support in either the Republican Senate or the Democratic-led
Assembly. His proposed budget counts on $124 million in revenue
from ticket sales in a multistate lottery game that would, at least
on paper, support education initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the Legislature has resisted buying into multistate
lotteries, putting New York at odds with its neighbors, Connecticut
and New Jersey, and a growing number of places across the country
where sky-high jackpots generate revenue for everything from new
schools to highways. Indeed, in recent years, lawmakers have
repeatedly rebuffed Pataki's overtures to expand gambling in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal for a multistate lottery is part of a running
budgetary numbers game in the back rooms of the Capitol, where
lawmakers hold out for their pet programs and then shuffle around
millions _ even billions _ of dollars to pay for everything. During
the 1995 budget crisis, for instance, Pataki won approval for a
Quick Draw lottery game from reluctant legislators with the promise
of new revenue. In the last four years, Quick Draw, a keno-style
game that is played on video monitors in bars and delis, has
generated more than $470 million for the state.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the law creating Quick Draw got caught up in a
budget battle and expired on March 31. Although lawmakers
eventually resurrected it, they passed on his request to expand
Quick Draw into more bars and delis. And in 1997, they turned down
a constitutional amendment that Pataki backed to allow casino
gambling in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's odds at getting Powerball this year may not have
improved much as a resilient economy pumps dollars into the state's
coffers and lawmakers are loath to alienate the powerful base of
conservative and religious voters fiercely opposed to gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one is counting Pataki out just yet.
</P>
<P>
   A multistate lottery would provide an influx of new money for
education programs, which are the cornerstone of the governor's
proposed budget and potentially the most divisive issue between
Republicans and Democrats this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to discount anything,'' declared the Senate
majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno, the powerful Republican from the
Albany area, when asked whether he would support the governor's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Although New York has the highest lottery sales in the nation,
those sales have flagged in recent years, in large part because of
fierce competition from multistate lotteries and casinos. For
example, tickets sales for the 34-year-old New York lottery
declined 7.5 percent to $3.69 billion in the 1999 fiscal year from
$3.99 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, countless New Yorkers jettison state loyalty and
take their dollars to Connecticut in search of $1 Powerball
tickets. Powerball, which is sponsored by 20 states and the
District of Columbia, has become wildly popular since it began
eight years ago, and its huge jackpots can make a million-dollar
payoff seems downright paltry. The Powerball jackpot starts at $10
million and climbed as high as $296 million in August 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the high stakes are addictive and cause people
to waste money on something they have little chance of winning.
``People have only so much money,'' said Sen. Frank Padavan, a
Republican from Queens who opposes expansion of the lottery. ``When
people gamble, they're not spending their money on goods and
services which create jobs and income for the local government.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what are the odds of hitting the Powerball jackpot, anyway?
Try 1 in 80 million (compared with, say, 1 in 18 million for the
New York State Lottery).
</P>
<P>
   George Wandrak, who oversees lottery operations in Connecticut,
said the long odds don't drive away the players _ in fact, quite
the opposite. His state added Powerball in 1995 after years of
waning lottery ticket sales. Last year, Powerball tickets raked in
$124.5 million in sales in Connecticut, or 14.3 percent of the
state's total revenue from gambling, including casinos and dog
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any product, there are choices _ you have Coke,
classic Coke, diet Coke, caffeine-free Coke, caffeine-free diet
Coke,'' Wandrak said. ``The lottery gets a bit stale, so we try to
freshen up the game and give them what they want _ higher
jackpots.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has sold three winning tickets in the Powerball
jackpot _ including the $10.3 million windfall that went to Sergio
and Elena Martini, of Brewster, N.Y., in January 1997. Wandrak
estimated that 10 percent to 15 percent of his state's Powerball
tickets are bought by New Yorkers and other out-of-staters.
</P>
<P>
   Since multistate lotteries were introduced in the mid-1980s,
state officials have come to depend on the high-profile games to
plug holes in their budgets. They typically share operating and
advertising costs for the lottery, and then keep a part of the
proceeds from ticket sales. In Powerball, for instance, the state
keeps half and the rest goes back for prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one states currently take part in one of three multistate
lotteries, said David Gale, executive director of the North
American Association of State and Provincial Lotteries. Last year,
these games helped propel ticket sales for all lotteries nationwide
to a record $36.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, for instance, joined its first multistate lottery in
May after a slump in its Pick 6 Lotto sales. Since then, lottery
players have spent more than $126 million for a crack at the Big
Game, which is also sponsored by Michigan, Maryland, Massachusetts,
Virginia, Illinois and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Powerball remains the undisputed king of lotteries with average
ticket sales of $1.2 billion a year, said Charles Strutt, executive
director of the Multi-State Lottery Association, which oversees the
game for the sponsoring states. Strutt predicted that New York,
with its 18 million residents, would fatten the jackpots even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very good for the game,'' said Strutt, who has
already been in touch with New York lottery officials. ``It would
increase sales in every state.''
</P>
<P>
   But no bets yet, please. Almost as soon as Pataki revived his
proposal for the multistate lottery last week, his opponents were
loudly protesting what they described as a major expansion of
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Grey, a United Methodist minister and executive director
of the National Coalition Against Gambling Expansion, said he was
surprised and disappointed that Pataki had again raised the issue.
``In good economic times, with no one clamoring for it, this seems
to go against what other politicians are doing,'' he said. ``In an
election year, to vote to expand gambling will only cost you
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   And Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, the influential Democrat
from Lower Manhattan, could barely wait to express his disapproval.
``I'm once again troubled by the re-emergence of the Powerball
lottery,'' he said at a news conference in the Capitol building
after the governor unveiled his budget.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bruno, Pataki's staunchest ally in the Legislature, said
that he was not optimistic about its chances. Without endorsing the
governor's proposal, Bruno pointed out only that another source of
money would have to be found if the multistate lottery were
scratched. ``You either cut something or do something to replace
the revenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawmakers were not swayed by that argument. ``That's
always a straw man,'' Padavan said. ``We're talking about a $77
billion budget _ this amount is infinitesimal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
