<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATE16-COX     01-15 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush tax plan `all hat and no cattle,' McCain says during debate
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSTON, Iowa _ GOP presidential front-runner and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush on Saturday took criticism in Texan and from Texans.
</P>
<P>
   At a nationally televised debate, top foe Arizona Sen. John
McCain opted for cowboy lingo in branding Bush's tax plan as ``all
hat and no cattle'' because it does not attack the national debt.
He also accused Bush of doing a ``Texas two-step'' on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The rare home-state Republican criticism of Bush came from a
former and a current member of the State Board of Education. Member
Bob Offutt of San Antonio and ex-member Donna Ballard of Midland
showed up in Iowa to endorse Bush rival Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's debate, the seventh of the campaign, was the final
GOP forum prior to the Jan. 24 Iowa caucuses that kick off the
presidential season.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show Bush with a commanding lead here. A Jan. 8-11
survey for two Iowa television stations showed Bush with support
from 46 percent of the respondents. Forbes was second at 20
percent, with McCain in third at 8 percent. GOP contenders Alan
Keyes, Gary Bauer and Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, who participated in
Saturday's debate, each have single figures in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is skipping the Iowa caucuses in favor of concentrating
on the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary and the Feb. 19 South Carolina
contest. Forbes is counting on a strong showing here to boost his
lagging standing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-McCain squabble on taxes, now played out on several
debate stages, centers on whether to spend projected budget
surpluses on tax cuts (Bush's preference), or a mix of tax cuts and
efforts to shore up Social Security and Medicare and chip away at
the national debt (McCain's idea).
</P>
<P>
   Bush ignited the tax talk by asking McCain why his plan taxes
some employee benefits, such as continuing education. Bush said it
amounts to a $40-billion tax hike on employee benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you say to a single mom who's getting educated that
she would have to pay taxes on those benefits?'' Bush asked McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the first thing I would say to that single mom is that
I've got a tax cut for you and Gov. Bush doesn't,'' McCain replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' replied Bush, whose tax plan does include
cuts at all income levels, albeit of varying amounts.
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, McCain issued a statement saying that his $240
billion, five-year plan, makes changes in taxes on benefits as part
of an effort to close ``a loophole that allowed corporations to get
a tax benefit for giving employes things like golf and health club
memberships and free parking.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain continued his criticism of Bush's plan as doing too much
for the rich and not enough to attack the national debt and
preserve crucial programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's plan has not one penny for Social Security,
not one penny for Medicare and not one penny for paying down the
national debt,'' McCain said. ``And when you run ads saying you're
going to take care of Social Security, my friend, that's all hat
and no cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's cute,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they're always cutest when they're true,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Forbes continued his effort to show that
Bush's much-touted Texas tax cuts have not cut taxes for all
Texans. Forbes also used Offutt and Ballard to dent Bush's
self-spun image as an education reformer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five years that I have served under Governor Bush have
been a series of one disappointing surprise after another,'' Offutt
said here. ``His failure to deliver on his campaign promise to `end
the regulatory authority' of the state education bureaucracy were
empty words.''
</P>
<P>
   Former board member Ballard, who was rejected in an attempt to
rejoin the board, said Bush's record is one of failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you determine improvement of education? By testing. The
problem with Governor Bush's claims of improving education is the
test in Texas is developed, distributed and assessed by the state
government. The fox is guarding the hen house,'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   But former Board Chairman Jack Christie of Houston, in Iowa to
help the Bush campaign, was ready with quick support for the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gone to more local control under Governor Bush,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Forbes got a Saturday boost from the Texans, he took a
hit from Bob Dole, the GOP's unsuccessful 1996 nominee who was a
target of Forbes' ads.
</P>
<P>
   Dole bought an ad in the Des Moines Register to warn Iowans
about Forbes _ without mentioning his name _ who has stepped up his
ad attacks on Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept full responsibility for our loss in 1996, but anyone
who followed that race closely would agree that the millions of
dollars of deceptive and distorted negative television ads were a
major factor in that loss,'' Dole said in the ad. ``I have been
virtually silent on this subject since 1996 and speak up now only
because it may be happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole has not endorsed anyone, but his wife Elizabeth, who
decided to bow out of the run for president, is backing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he could see the Bush campaign's hands all over the
ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is part and parcel of the Bush campaign of having
others do their attacks,'' he said. ``That ad was simply part of
the establishment attempt to try to create a coronation.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
