<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA16-COX     01-15 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ ``I'm going to Des Moines.'' This is what I
told the woman at the ticket counter at Austin-Bergstrom
International Airport on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sorry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, she didn't literally say that, but it was tonally
implied, as always. Tell anybody you're abandoning Austin, Texas,
for Des Moines _ a self-conscious, pimply adolescent of a town _
and you're barraged with Kleenex and hugs as if you've just
announced you've got some horrible progressive disease.
</P>
<P>
   But every four years something bizarre and amazing happens here:
It's where, at the Iowa caucuses, they start to pick presidents.
The politics and media road show: It's a lot like being on tour
with a rock band, except the participants have fewer piercings, the
sex is more furtive and the abused substances are different. And
there's no other place to watch this odd little scene than here.
</P>
<P>
   Des Moines happens to be in Iowa, which happens to be, like
Texas, a state. This is the beginning and end of their
similarities. Texas is big, boastful, freaky, ready to secede, just
say the word. Iowa has a not entirely unwarranted inferiority
complex. Its principal characteristic is inoffensiveness. Its
people are invariably described as plainspoken and polite. Even the
sound of the states' names is dramatically different: ``Texas''
with its hard ``T,'' line-crossing ``x'' and copperhead ``s'' comes
off the tongue hard and declarative. The sound of ``Texas'' says
don't mess with it. ``Iowa,'' with its three meandering vowels and
``W,'' the lone consonant, sounds tentative, if not questioning:
Iowa? I'm so sorry.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place that clings white-knuckled to its agricultural
tradition even as family farms have dwindled. It used to be that
farm families just required a little help from the government.
These days they need a little more help, meaning somebody has to
take a job in town.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place that consume enormous quantities of Jell-O and
crank, (Iowans love their methamphetamines) though usually not at
the same gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   It's where, a long time ago, a group of immigrant farmers
stopped their wagons and wondered, Should we stop or keep going
until we get someplace colder? And they stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Those would be my people. I'm from Iowa. To cop a line from
cranky author and former Iowan Bill Bryson, somebody has to be.
</P>
<P>
   Every four years, this place becomes, for a fleeting but intense
moment, the center of the media universe. The sound of satellite
truck generators rattle in the night. The city mice come visit the
country mice. They interview locals about the state of contemporary
politics. This confers upon Iowans a certain quadrennial status
they enjoy even as they acknowledge its fickle nature. The morning
after the caucuses, the
</P>
<P>
   media will stomp off to Manchester. But it's a welcome winter
distraction here, something to think about other than how far off
spring is, the answer being: quite a ways ... Look, it's Bob Novak!
Look, Thomas Oliphant! Look, the guy who wrote the book about the
guy! Believe me, if you are trapped in an Iowa winter, the
possibility of spotting a pundit or two _ doesn't even have to be
anybody A-list _ is to be highly anticipated, and Iowans hang
around hot spots like pensioners hovering over their mailboxes
around the first of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Jeff Greenfield munch supermarket-brand potato chips in
the media room of the Iowa Public Television studios _ from which
Saturday's underwhelming Republican debate aired _ might not be
much, but ... well, on second thought, it really isn't much, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to elect a president? Why should a state where
pigs outnumber people 10 to 1 _ 20 million to 2 million, and God
help us if they ever get the vote _ have such enormous and lasting
impact in selecting the leader of the free world?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the second question is, nobody really remembers.
It seems to have something to do with ``retail politics,'' a
``level playing field'' and someone named ``Jimmy Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter got a leg up here in '76, as did George McGovern four
years before. Gary Hart played well in '84. Caucus critics adroitly
note that not all these candidates technically were elected
president, that Iowa is full of nothing but wrinkly old white
people on tractors (except for the mayor of Des Moines who is,
inexplicably, African-American, and does not, so far as I know,
even own a tractor) that there's no good reason for everybody to be
stomping around here every four years and anyway it's too damn
cold. (Although not so far this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Iowans, ever-polite and deferential, absorb the criticism, note
that no state is a perfect microcosm of the country as a whole and
suggest that the process does a fair amount of culling the weak and
the delusional candidates from an unwieldy herd. Then they charge
you $150 for a night at the downtown Des Moines Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates win Iowa by having a message that sells and by
spending a punishing amount of time here building a network that
will get the faithful out come caucus night, when voters will stand
up before their neighbors and make the case for their guy. You
can't just buy a ton of media and move on to the next contest. Even
with his bursting war chest, George. W. Bush was reduced this
weekend to sucking up to prospective voters in person in small
towns, autographing golf balls, asking folks to remember in eight
days that he'd come to ask for their vote. He said it Friday before
handfuls of people in the hamlets of western Iowa, then he said it
before several hundred in the comparatively swanky headquarters of
the Iowa Farm Bureau Federation in West Des Moines on Friday night.
The Iowans in their winter coats laughed in the right places,
applauded in the right places and pretended they hadn't heard this
rap 632 times since last summer, when W., the Lone Consonant, began
</P>
<P>
   pitching serious woo.
</P>
<P>
   While all this was going on, the traveling press, who appear to
outnumber Iowa's porcine population by at least 10 to 1, roll their
eyes and ask their colleagues to throw them into the path of an
oncoming tractor-trailer rig before they have to listen to any more
stump speeches. In this respect the media have an advantage over
the presidential wannabes they cover: Members of the media are not
prohibited from openly hating the whole show _ the plowed-under
fields, the parochialism, the fact that you can't get a REAL New
York Times anywhere, the pointless travel and the fact that ...
Omigod I forgot to pack my Sharper Image Turbo Groomer 2.0 and now
my nose hairs will freeze while I'm doing my stand-up.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, dear readers, we members of the press are willing to endure
unimaginable hardships in the interest of keeping you enlightened
and informed.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, my rental car doesn't even have a CD player.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
