<P>
   SCHOOL-MICROCASTS _ WASHINGTON _ Only 300 or so of the nation's
115,000 schools have applied for and gotten one of the 1,000 free
satellite dishes offered by Echostar Communications of Littleton,
Colo., so that school leaders can get monthly briefings on
security, violence reduction and detection of serious mental health
problems in youth. The first monthly ``microcast'' will be Jan. 20.
Three federal departments, the National Education Association and a
dozen other big associations of K-12 educators co-sponsor the
effort, which was announced by President Clinton last June.
Organizers say they still expect success because lots of schools
already had satellite dishes. (Mollison, Cox News Service) EDs:
MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   APACHE-INVESTIGATION _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The U.S. Army has launched
a special investigation into a complex flight-control system
suspected in more than 60 aviation incidents involving Apache
helicopters, including a much-publicized May 5, 1999, crash near
Kosovo that killed both pilots. At least three major accidents
since 1985 are linked to problems with the Apache's flight control
system, a Dayton Daily News examination found. In addition, the
examination found, the same system remains a suspect in at least
two other major crashes. One of them is the crash near Kosovo,
which is now part of a separate U.S. Justice Department
examination, the Daily News has learned. The other is a December
1997 crash near Fort Hood, Texas, which also killed both pilots.
(Carollo, Dayton Daily News) 120. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: A shorter version of this story will move as well. A
graphic on the Backup Control System is available on the Cox
server/National folder.
</P>
<P>
   MLK-LESSONS _ ATLANTA _ The lessons of Martin Luther King's life
and legacy are taught to schoolchildren throughout metro Atlanta.
They see the black and white footage of dogs attacking youths in
Birmingham, Ala., study his life via computer programs, and act out
what life was like for their parents and grandparents as we
approach the official celebration of his birthday. (Carter-Poe,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MLK-AUTHOR _ ATLANTA _ Juan Williams, author of ``Eyes on the
Prize,'' comes to speak about King Day at Georgia Perimeter
College's celebration in metro Atlanta. (Anderson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. 15. EDs: ETA 5:15
</P>
<P>
   LITASULLIVAN _ ATLANTA _ Update on the contract murder of
Atlanta socialite Lita Sullivan, gunned down by a roses-carrying
gunman 13 years ago Sunday. The notorious Atlanta homicide has
become an international story, with a worldwide dragnet for the
elusive Palm Beach millionaire Jim Sullivan, who had built a home
in Costa Rica after fleeing the country. A North Carolina truck
driver, Tony Harwood, is in the Fulton County jail charged with
murder as the alleged hitman who carried a bouquet of pink roses to
the victim's door and shot in her the head. (Atlanta,
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO: File photo of Jim and Lita,
as well as mug shot of Harwood. MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   WACO-EVIDENCEDUE _ WACO, Texas _ Trying to get story on whether
feds deliver mass of documents to Davidian attorney Mike Caddell of
Houston. Jan. 15 is the deadline and federal judge Thursday refused
to give the federal prosecutors more time before they are required
to turn over huge volumes of evidence sought by plaintiffs. (Van
Auken, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
