<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7048 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-ADS-BOS &LR;      01-15 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AD PUTS FOCUS ON FORBES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSTON, Iowa _ The six Republican presidential candidates woke
up in Iowa Saturday to read an advertisement in the Des Moines
Register signed by their 1996 nominee, Bob Dole, warning that the
party's 2000 nominee ``could be damaged again because of distorted
negative television political ads'' in the current campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dole did not name names, the quarter-page ad was
directed at Steve Forbes, who roughed up Dole with a barrage of
negative commercials in the 1996 contest here, and who is now
targeting Texas Goveronor George W. Bush in a media campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The ad carried no imprimatur other than Dole's name, but it
represented an admonition from the Republican establishment, which
is coalescing behind Bush as next week's Iowa caucus approaches.
The message: Lay off.
</P>
<P>
   Before Forbes left his Des Moines hotel for Saturday's debate,
he was asked about Dole's broadside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that ad is typical of the whole George Bush campaign,
ducking and dodging,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes indicated that he had no intention of withdrawing an ad
running in Iowa, in which a Texas woman scolds Bush for breaking a
tax pledge. Indeed, he trotted out two more Texans Saturday with
connections to the state board of education, who lambasted the
governor on another issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true record of Governor Bush on education in Texas is one
of broken promises,' said Robert Offutt, a member of the state
education board.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he intended to continue to report ``stark
contrasts'' between Bush's statements and his record.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not until the debate was more than an hour old did Forbes
get around to challenging Bush on the tax issue.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Bush and Senator John McCain of Arizona as ``timid
tax cutters,'' Forbes looked at Bush and said: ``In Texas, George,
your tax cuts were more apparent than real. Most Texans have never
seen those tax cuts, and the same things are going to happen to
your proposal on the federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush laughed and recalled that during his re-election campaign,
``nearly 69 percent of Texas said overwhelmingly in 1998: You're
the man; we appreciate your tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes insisted that the cuts had failed to six out of 10
districts in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not true,'' said Bush, who followed with a lecture: ``Steve,
look, Senator Dole wrote a pretty interesting advertisement in this
morning's paper. If you're going to talk about a man's record, tell
the whole record.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the flap over the Dole ad was more interesting
than the debate itself.
</P>
<P>
   Because McCain chose not to campaign in Iowa, the contest here
has been effectively reduced to a clash between Bush and Forbes,
two candidates with almost unlimited funds. Forbes has eight days
to close a gap that some polls measure at more than 30 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Forbes's bravado before the debate, he barely nibbled at
the Texas governor Saturday, in their last public encounter
together before the caucuses. It was as though he recognized he had
been chastened by the party's titular head.
</P>
<P>
   Making his only appearance of the month in Iowa, McCain carried
the fight against Bush. He used Texas idioms, calling one Bush
proposal ``all hat and no cattle.'' At another point, McCain
parried with Bush over their respective tax-cut programs and said,
``Let's not do the Texas two-step here.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush, McCain and Forbes dominated Saturday's debate with
their colloquies, Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes and Utah Senator Orrin G.
Hatch were left battling for standing in the party's strong
conservative constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer sought to draw some distinctions by castigating the
Republican Party for opposing a patients' bill of rights. Keyes
countered by saying that Bauer's embrace of the bill would turn the
system over to judges and trial lawyers and become ``an excuse for
government domination.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch repeatedly touted his own 30-minute ``fireside chat,'' a
paid political advertisement scheduled to be shown on Des Moines TV
Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
