<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-YUGO-KILLING-1STLD-WR     01-15 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KILLING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARKAN,' SERB PARAMILITARY LEADER, SLAIN IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS throughout to update and add background: rewrites grafs 3-7
to update and move up info; adds to new 11th graf and rewrites 12th
graf to add info on Milosevic and Raznatovic; rewrites 13th graf to
clarify; deletes graf in original beginning `Raznatovic led a ...'
to delete info that now appears earlier; adds 2 new grafs before
last graf, with background info.) 
 (mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Zeljko Raznatovic, a notorious Serbian
paramilitary leader known as Arkan who was wanted on war crimes
charges in the Bosnian and Croatian wars, was shot and killed
Saturday in the lobby of the Intercontinental Hotel here.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was shot in the left eye by gunmen at about 5:15 p.m.
and was immediately taken to Belgrade's main emergency hospital,
where he was pronounced dead at about 6:40 p.m., reported Studio B,
the Belgrade television station.
</P>
<P>
   A witness at the Intercontinental, where blood still spattered
the entrance way an hour after the shooting, said a bodyguard,
whose name was reported to be Momcilo Mandic, known as Manda, had
also been killed. Other reports said an unidentified woman was
wounded. She was believed to be Lidija Velickovic, the sister of
Raznatovic's wife, Svetlana, a famous Serbian folk singer known as
Ceca.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified gunmen, described by the state news agency
Tanjug as masked assailants who used automatic weapons, apparently
escaped, although the police arrived quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic, 47, was said to be accompanied by his wife and their
two children, who were not reported to have been hurt. The attack
bore the hallmarks of political assassinations here, which have
been carried out in gangland style.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic's paramilitary group, called the Tigers, took part in
the brutal three-month siege of the Croatian city of Vukovar in
1991 and helped the Bosnian Serbs overrun northern and eastern
Bosnia a year later, where he was one of the pioneers of the
killing and violent expulsion of rival ethnic groups, a practice
that came to be known as ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   He was secretly indicted in 1997 by the international war crimes
tribunal for the former Yugoslavia, accused of crimes against
humanity in both Bosnia and Croatia. But his indictment was made
public by the tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, only during
NATO's bombing war against Yugoslavia, which began last March.
</P>
<P>
   He was thought to be dangerous to President Slobodan Milosevic
of Yugoslavia and other key members of the government because of
what he knew about the killings and atrocities of the war in
Bosnia. The Hague tribunal was said to be negotiating with
Raznatovic to get him to turn himself in and testify against
others, but Raznatovic regularly denied those reports.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate speculation here was that Milosevic, who has
already been indicted by the tribunal for war crimes during the
Kosovo war, and his government would benefit most from the killing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the very few occasions at which Milosevic and Raznatovic
were ever seen together was the 1997 funeral of Radovan Stojicic, a
former deputy chief of Serbian police whose name was linked to
atrocities during the Croatian war and who was gunned down in a
Belgrade restaurant. His killers have never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was said by friends to have been worried about his
safety in the last few months, said Zoran Djindjic, the leader of
the opposition Democratic Party, who had contacts with him.
Milosevic was particularly irked by Raznatovic's support of the
Montenegrin President, Milo Djukanovic, after the Montenegrin
turned against Milosevic in 1997, Djindjic said in an interview
Saturday evening. At the same time, Djindjic said, Raznatovic kept
strong contacts with the Yugoslav and Serbian security services on
whose orders he is said in the past to have carried out
assassinations in western Europe of exiles viewed as enemies of the
Belgrade government.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was also wanted by the international police body
Interpol in connection with bank robberies across western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He did not play a major role in last year's Kosovo war, though
some of his paramilitary Tigers were engaged in the forced
expulsion and killing of ethnic Albanians there.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said Raznatovic had been strongly urged to go to Kosovo
by authorities in the Milosevic government. In fact, Raznatovic
spent much of the war in the Hyatt Hotel in Belgrade, where many
foreign journalists were also staying, and which was perceived as a
place NATO would not bomb. As an English-speaker, he was sometimes
interviewed by CNN and the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic said Raznatovic had told him that in late 1996,
Milosevic's wife, Mirjana Markovic, offered Raznatovic and his men
money to break up pro-democracy demonstrations in Belgrade.
Raznatovic told Djindjic that he had refused.
</P>
<P>
   During the Kosovo war, Djindjic said, Raznatovic kept him
informed about threats to his life, one reason Djindjic left
Belgrade then to travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was one of the last of the criminal and paramilitary
leaders closely involved with both state security and the wars in
Bosnia and Croatia. Last month, Zoran Sijan, a mafia leader and a
man with experiences similar to Raznatovic's, was killed, Djindjic
said.
</P>
<P>
   The last such figure still alive is Ljubisa Buha, known as Cume,
who is based in Belgrade, Djindjic said.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic dabbled in politics in 1992-93, and was also involved
in business, both open and criminal, reaping what was thought to
have been a considerable fortune through his control of gasoline
smuggling and illegal sales during the international sanctions
imposed on Yugoslavia during the war years. He had been a
well-known soccer fan, leading the club of the fans of the famous
Red Star soccer team. Later, he bought his own soccer club,
Belgrade Obilic.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was a shrewd, intelligent and criminal personality,
Djindjic said, adding, ``He was baby-faced but very dangerous,
without moral scruples and a kind of beast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
