<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-POLICY-BOS &LR;      01-15 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-POLICY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEARSIGHTED CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, January 1y, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given what the candidates have left unsaid about foreign policy
and security issues, the presidential campaigns thus far might seem
to reflect a nation unconcerned with threats from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxical as it might seem, however, America's extraordinary
prosperity and its status as the sole surviving superpower combine
to make the international challenges awaiting the next president
more central than they appeared in 1992. Back then, just after the
implosion of the Soviet Union and the ejection of Saddam Hussein's
forces from Kuwait, President George Bush was defeated by Bill
Clinton, who suggested that he was more attuned to domestic
anxieties induced by corporate downsizing, budget deficits, and a
recession that was already ending.
</P>
<P>
   Today the candidates are debating the cost of health care, their
belief in God, the future of Social Security, and how to spend
budget surpluses that were unimaginable in the 1992 campaign. These
are arguments about choices only a prosperous people have the
luxury of debating. Very little has been heard about the country's
vulnerabilities: looming threats to national security; the wisdom
of commitments to peacekeeping and humanitarian missions; the
prospect of destabilizing conflicts in strategically important
areas of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom among political consultants is that
there are no votes in abstruse foreign policy matters. When the
next president takes office next January, however, his most fateful
decisions are likely to be about distant parts of the world such as
Russia, China, and Iraq. If foreign and security policies have not
been highlighted in the presidential debates, they ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   The voters are entitled to know how the candidates propose to
balance America's interest in dismantling Russia's nuclear arsenal
against American feelings of revulsion at the Kremlin's slaughter
of civilians in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been properly attentive to the
danger of loose nukes in Russia and other states of the former
Soviet Union. There are programs with bipartisan support for
dismantling Soviet warheads and finding employment for weapons
scientists who might otherwise accept contracts to work in Iraq or
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But candidates from both parties ought to be discussing whether
Washington has done enough to preempt the proliferation of a
nuclear capability and long-range ballistic missiles to Baghdad or
Tehran. There should also be debate about the tone and content of
the administration's relations with what Russians call the party of
power in Moscow. Was the enlargement of NATO wise or foolish?
Should the next president take steps to prove to Moscow that NATO's
bombing of Serbia does not presage a new Western attempt to contain
or humiliate Russia?
</P>
<P>
   The candidates have also produced a regrettable silence on the
subject of the nuclear tests conducted last year by India and
Pakistan. These hostile neighbors on the Asian subcontinent have
ushered in an era of nuclear anxiety. For both technical and
psychological reasons, they are more likely to launch their nuclear
missiles than were the Soviet and American superpower rivals.
</P>
<P>
   A closely related question the candidates should answer is what
their approach will be to the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban
Treaty, which the Senate refused to ratify this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The voters also deserve to hear the candidates' views on the
feasibility and wisdom of a national missile defense. And those
candidates who want to deploy antimissile systems ought to explain
how they intend to win the Russians over to a revision of the 1972
ABM Treaty limiting such defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most immediate security issue that will face the
next president is what to do about Saddam Hussein's regime, which
has had more than a year to rebuild its chemical, biological, and
nuclear weapons. Does it still make sense to impose sanctions on
Iraqis while allowing Saddam to keep out weapons inspectors?
</P>
<P>
   There are similarly important questions to be answered about
North Korea's nuclear programs and its export of long-range
missiles. And the candidates should say what price they think
Washington should be willing to pay for a peace treaty between
Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   If the candidates do not begin talking about the world beyond
America's borders, one of them will take office a year from now
with a blank check for existential decisions. When such electoral
distortions occur in Russia, Americans see them as symptoms of a
dysfunctional democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
