u k BC-EDITORIAL-KING-BOS &LR;      01-15 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING'S FARSIGHTED VISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, January 17, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1967, Martin Luther King was talking about technology. He saw
the ``worldwide neighborhood . . . brought into being largely as a
result of the modern scientific and technological revolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   As if he were speaking for listeners in the year 2000, King
offered this wise advise: Bridge the gap between scientific
progress and moral progress. Injustice, he argued, should have no
place in a world of jets, astronauts, and life-prolonging medical
advances.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Where Do We Go From Here: Chaos or Community,''
King wrote: ``Nothing could be more tragic than for men to live in
these revolutionary times and fail to achieve the new attitudes and
the new mental outlooks that the new situation demands.''
</P>
<P>
   King lamented what he saw: industry and government ``woven into
an intricate computerized mechanism'' that ``leaves the person
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts point toward goals _ as-yet unreached pinnacles _
where the best human values and the best human technology would
converge. At such heights, better cars and washing machines would
be mere byproducts. The most celebrated technology would embody
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways this revolution has begun. Even the language of
desktop and laptop computers extols individual, human-scale access
to the wired world. The genome project puts technology's machines
on a microbiological journey of exploration to map human DNA. And
good old e-mail is a simple but dynamic step toward the global chat
_ with both the neighbors down the street and the ones across the
ocean _ that could help lead to the global triumph of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Society, however, is still in a footrace, running hard so its
lagging values can catch up with the whirlwind pace of its gadgets.
In honor of King's birthday, this race ought to be joyfully run. As
serious as it is, the work of spreading just ideas amid
technological abundance should also be inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   The tally of failed moral progress is saddening. But the change
we have made is a beacon of the change we are capable of making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
