<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HORNETS-PHILLS-NY     01-15 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HORNETS-PHILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS PLAYERS PATIENTLY MADE DECISION NOT TO PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association and its players were faced
with a quandary last week: deciding when it is proper to play a
game in the wake of misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of Bobby Phills' grieving teammates and the
players union, the NBA eventually postponed Friday night's game
between the Hornets and Knicks in Charlotte, N.C. Released of the
burden to play that night, players and other employees of both
teams were able to attend an afternoon memorial for the Hornets
guard, who was killed in a car accident on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, arriving at that decision was agonizing for everyone
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't any guidebooks for this kind of thing,'' Russ
Granik, the league's deputy commissioner, said. ``Reactions to
tragedies like this become intensely personal. We just tried to do
what was right. Hopefully, we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond obvious problems in rescheduling _ the league had already
postponed Charlotte's home game against Chicago on Wednesday night
_ the union and the league weighed the request of Phills' grieving
widow to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 10 p.m. Thursday that the game was postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with members of the clergy and counselors, Hornets
players voted as a team on Thursday morning to honor the request of
Kendall Phills, Phills' widow, who urged them to play ``because
that's what Bobby would want.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials went so far as to research similar cases
involving the death of athletes during a season. They found that
the Yankees had played a day and a half after Thurman Munson died
in a plane crash in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years ago, the Philadelphia Flyers played their next
game five days after goalie Pelle Lindbergh was killed in a car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those deaths, Phills' teammates were on the scene
moments after he was killed, less than a mile from the Charlotte
Coliseum after a morning practice. Baron Davis, whose vehicle was
positioned behind Phills' and David Wesley's cars before they
accelerated when the stop light turned green, ran to Phills'
mangled car to look in and check on his teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a call sometime in the early part of the afternoon on
Thursday, and that's when Elden indicated he was starting to
legitimately worry about what they all knew would be an emotional
ceremony,'' Granik said, referring to Hornets center Elden
Campbell, who was conveying the wishes of his teammates via a
conference call with Granik; commissioner David Stern; the union
president, Patrick Ewing, and the union's executive director, Billy
Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had indicated to him that it was very difficult to postpone
games,'' Granik said. At some point, Granik said he and Rod Thorn,
the senior vice president of basketball operations, told Campbell,
``We owe it to our fans not to hold this off beyond today.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik was sympathetic to the players' concerns during that 4
p.m. conference call, union officials said. But a decision had to
be made in the next few hours to prevent a logistics nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and the Hornets were facing their own anguish. The team
did not want to postpone the game until Campbell talked to Kendall
Phills. He had no luck reaching her for the next six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter stayed in contact with Campbell, telephoning him each
hour. Finally, with the league offices closed and no announcement
made, the union released a statement from Hunter recommending that
the game be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Granik learned about the recommendation via a reporter's phone
call to his home at 9:15 p.m. The release mentioned the sensitivity
displayed by the NBA, but Granik was privately miffed that the
union seemed to be putting public pressure on the league to
postpone the game when the two sides had been working in concert
all day long.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 p.m., he had spoken again to Campbell and decided to
postpone the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much doubt that we did the best thing,'' Granik
said late Friday afternoon. ``The memorial service just ended. The
idea of having a game tonight would have been somehow wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran Bulls guard B.J. Armstrong, a friend and former
teammate of Phills, said: ``I don't think there's a right and wrong
way in how you handle that. You do what you believe is right and
hope it works out.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say when is OK to play, I can't answer that. But you need
time to heal. Those people close to the situation, they needed more
time than they probably first realized.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 1901EST &QL; 
