<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALK-JORDAN ONE-TO-ONE  
 WEIGHING THE EFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FALK-JORDAN ONE-TO-ONE  &LR;  David Falk is the man responsible for, in
his own words, ``projecting and protecting'' the image of Michael
Jordan for much of the last two decades. He has earned a reputation
as the league's most feared agent.
</P>
<P>
   The label is primarily based on his clientele, which includes
more than a dozen of the game's top players, and his negotiating
savvy. Falk is fond of telling team owners and general managers
during the crucible of contract dealings, ``Don't forget to protect
your investment.''
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when Falk's greatest investment, Jordan, stares
him down at the other end of the bargaining table? With Jordan
nearing completion of a part ownership stake in the Washington
Wizards, he may oversee all basketball operations and eventually
have to do battle with Falk over player contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Although David Stern would never admit it, the notion of the
relationship between Falk and Jordan disintegrating over the next
few years is a tantalizing proposition for the NBA commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   In Stern's world, Jordan would finally understand how dangerous
Falk is to the game. He would see firsthand the agent's meddlesome
ways in tearing apart franchises by leveraging his clients.
</P>
<P>
   In Falk's world, Jordan, the owner and general manager, would be
viewed as one of the few people who understand the dynamics of
superstar athletes and how they need to be compensated by their
teams.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan's basketball knowledge and Falk's clientele, they
could work together in creating a dynasty, usurp more of Stern's
power and make the commissioner yearn for the days of competitive
balance.
</P>
<P>
   Let the tug of war over the game's pre-eminent figure begin.
</P>
<P>
   Given the mammoth egos involved, it is tough to root for either
Falk or Stern at times. After all, for those who missed Falk's
special holiday greeting on his work voice mail, here goes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, this is David. With the holiday season upon us, the
words of the immortal Bing Crosby ring in my ears: I'm dreaming of
a White Christmas, just like the ones I used to know. Where the
treetops glisten, and the owners listen to the salaries continuing
to grow. I'm dreaming of a White Christmas, with every $100 million
contract I write. May your days be merry and bright and may the
clients always be right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WEIGHING THE EFFECT  &LR;  The Hornets entered this season with a
legitimate chance at contending for the Eastern Conference title.
Coach Paul Silas did not have the most talented team in the
conference, but the offensive firepower and depth was, and still
is, undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   And while it is much too early to discount their chances in a
conference without a dominant team, the death of Bobby Phills last
week could have major repercussions for Charlotte's success the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   More than a reserve, Phills was their leader, the co-captain who
approached Silas earlier this season and said he did not mind going
to the bench if it meant Derrick Coleman and Anthony Mason could
both start.
</P>
<P>
   In the mold of a Michael Curry in Detroit, P.J. Brown in Miami
or Charles Oakley in Toronto, he meant more than his modest
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the accident in which he was killed involved the
team's starting point guard, David Wesley, who was believed to have
been drag-racing with his best friend on the team when Phills lost
control of his Porsche and skidded into oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Charlotte-Mecklenburg Police Department who
spoke on condition of anonymity said Wesley may be facing a number
of charges like speeding, reckless driving, spontaneous speed
competition, the legal term for drag racing, and the more serious
charges of misdemeanor death by vehicle and involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was the second this season involving Hornets
players. In October, the reserve guard Eldridge Recasner was left
with a broken shoulder and partly collapsed lung after an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Coleman, driving the sport utility vehicle in which
Recasner was a passenger, was arrested on a drunken-driving charge.
A woman in the vehicle was hurt in the collision with a
tractor-trailer. Recasner remains on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Coleman and Kenny Anderson were two of the most
promising young players in the league on an up-and-coming team.
That summer, after the Nets' first playoff success in nearly a
decade, Drazen Petrovic _ an easygoing guy from Croatia whom
teammates liked and admired and also one of the game's top
perimeter threats _ was killed in a car accident in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   On and off the court, the reverberations of his death lingered
for years in the Meadowlands. You only hope the Hornets can recover
more quickly than the Nets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
