<HEADER>
A7067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-EVIDENCEDUE16-CO     01-15 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-EVIDENCEDUE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge's office still waiting for government to deliver Davidian
documents
 &HT;    By Cindy Van Auken
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Government officials had not delivered documents
in connection with the surviving Branch Davidians' wrongful-death
lawsuit against the government as of mid-afternoon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for Branch Davidian attorney Mike Caddell said
none of the files had been received Saturday and that Caddell
expected to receive them next week. Caddell could not be reached
Saturday afternoon because he left the office to attend a family
outing.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to produce the documents by the end of the day would
violate a federal judge's ruling which set the delivery deadline
for Saturday. However, a source from The Associated Press said
Caddell told her that Tuesday would be considered the unofficial
deadline since the date fell on the Saturday of a holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell reportedly said U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr.
had not realized the deadline was on a Saturday and thus there was
an unofficial agreement making Tuesday the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose office is in Waco, denied a request from the
Justice Department on Thursday to push the deadline back to Jan.
31. The motion, which was nearly 30 pages long, included affidavits
from record-keepers at the FBI, ATF and the Department of Defense.
It said ``competing interests'' would probably keep the government
from meeting the Saturday deadline. Justice Department attorneys
are producing documents for the court, Congress and the Office of
the Special Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell asked Smith earlier in the week to fine the government
$50,000 for its tardiness in producing the documents, saying he had
never had this much difficulty getting things done in a timely
manner in his 20-year law career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been told by people within the Justice Department that
the person running that particular division thinks this is some
kind of game and takes the attitude that it should all be
hardball,'' Caddell told the Waco Tribune-Herald on Thursday.
``They want to make everything a battle and do everything at the
last minute and delay as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Bradford, U.S. attorney for the Eastern Division of
Texas, denied the government was playing games. He said the large
volume of materials has caused the government to take longer than
anticipated to produce them. More than 30,000 pages of documents,
``numerous'' videotapes, 300 audiotapes, more than 4,600
photographs and 4,000 pages of documents from the FBI laboratory
have been made available to the plaintiffs, according to the
Justice Department motion.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said he got a letter Thursday from the government saying
he was being shipped 23,000 pages of documents, with another 50,000
to 100,000 pages to come later.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions for noncompliance were not included in Smith's order,
but Caddell said he thinks Smith will determine appropriate action
after seeing how diligent the government is in producing the
documents. The case is set to go to trial May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
