<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7072 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ARKAN-BOS &LR;      01-15 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ARKAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMEN KILL PARAMILITARY LEADER WANTED BY WAR TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX TODOROVIC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Masked gunmen Saturday killed the most public face of
Yugoslavia's last violent, gang-ruled decade, Zeljko Raznatovic,
better known as the paramilitary leader Arkan, who was wanted by an
international war crimes tribunal but lived openly in this capital
as an ally of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic, 47, was slain in a shootout in the lobby of
Belgrade's luxurious Intercontinental Hotel. The two gunmen
escaped, and there was no word of a motive.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what effect his death, if any, would have on the
internationally reviled administration of Milosevic, who has
presided over the disintegration of this Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
   Also killed in the evening attack were Raznatovic's associate,
Momcilo Mandic, and another member of his entourage known as Gera.
</P>
<P>
   According to unofficial reports, Raznatovic's sister-in-law
Lidia also was wounded in the gunfight.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the gunmen opened fire on Raznatovic's entourage
shortly after they exited the Intercontinental's restaurant.
Raznatovic was shot three times in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders said Raznatovic's death was a natural result
of the lawless society he helped create. ``We are living in a
country where the legal state is not functioning,'' said Vladan
Batic, coordinator of the opposition group Alliance for Change.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, assassins have killed Serbia's police
chief and a top official of Yugoslav Left, a party led by
Milosevic's wife, Mirjana Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign leaders shed few tears for the baby-faced Raznatovic,
who dominated television airwaves last year as Belgrade's de facto
official voice in the early days of NATO's air campaign to push
Milosevic out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arkan lived violently, so it is therefore no surprise that he
died violently,'' said British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook. ``I
regret his death because it prevents us doing justice to the
victims of his atrocities by seeing him in the dock at the Hague
tribunal,'' he added, referring to the war crimes panel.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic's well-scrubbed appearance and polite mannerisms
belied a criminal legend. The father of nine children and husband
of Yugoslavia's top folksinger, Svetlana Velickovic, Raznatovic
robbed numerous banks, escaped from European prisons and headed the
Tigers, considered the most brutal and efficient paramilitary force
during the wars in Croatia and Bosnia in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He was indicted on war crimes charges in Bosnia in September
1997, but the indictment was kept under wraps until the NATO air
campaign in the Balkans began last March. His paramilitary forces
also have been accused of involvement in atrocities during the
Croatian war, which broke out in 1991. His forces sided with Serb
rebels in both wars.
</P>
<P>
   Full details of the charges have not been released, but former
British defense minister George Robertson said last year that
Raznatovic was indicted for the 1991 massacre of 250 men taken from
a hospital in Vukovar, Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 1999 NBC interview, he said that his militia, whose
members wore distinctive black uniforms, had ``been under the
command of the Yugoslav Army'' at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic sponsored Raznatovic's brief stint in parliament as a
Kosovo legislator in 1992. The state-run media controlled by the
president lauded his ``heroism'' in Muslim areas. Milosevic
repeatedly rebuffed Western complaints about Raznatovic and once
told Warren Zimmerman, former US ambassador to Yugoslavia, that
``as I understand it, he is no more than a simple sweetshop
owner,'' referring to Raznatovic's ownership of a Belgrade ice
cream parlor.
</P>
<P>
   According to a December report by investigators with the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, Raznatovic's
Tigers militia committed atrocities in Kosovo between last March
and July.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic rose to become one of Yugoslavia's wealthiest
individuals. Making his fortune in black market currency trading,
oil smuggling, and arms dealing, he later bought a chain of
bakeries and the Obilic soccer club, which was banned last year
from all international competitions because of his links with war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Raznatovic married Serbia's most famous folksinger,
known popularly as Ceca, with whom he had two children. On Jan. 1,
Ceca released her most recent CD, Ceca 2000. In recent days, she
and Raznatovic appeared on television together promoting it.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Raznatovic's enemies is long. Some analysts say that
he recently distanced himself from the Milosevic regime, while
others noted that for years, Raznatovic had remained loyal to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   During NATO's 78-day bombing campaign of Yugoslavia last year,
Raznatovic was a fixture at the Hyatt and Intercontinental hotels,
where he enjoyed giving interviews to reporters, and repeatedly
claimed he was not active in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
