<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-COLOMBIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLOMBIA, ALBRIGHT BACKS PLEDGE OF US SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia _ Facing criticism in Washington and abroad
for a $1.6 billion, military-based aid package for Colombia,
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright reassured leaders of this
violence-scarred nation Saturday of Clinton administration support
in two struggles: against drugs and for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's two-day visit to Colombia, the first by an American
secretary of state in 14 years, marked another dramatic shift in US
policy toward Colombia and was meant to promote the assistance
proposal that President Clinton announced last week. The package
must be approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a top US official in Colombia will also be
likely to bolster President Andres Pastrana, whose popularity has
plummeted among citizens tired of a worsening economic situation
and continued violence from drug trafficking and a 40-year-old
civil war that shows few signs of ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a test that Colombians themselves must pass,''
Albright said at a news conference with Pastrana just before her
departure for Panama and Mexico. ``But I pledge that the United
States will do all that we could to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The aid package has been heartily supported by some Republican
members of Congress and Colombian leaders, who say more resources
are needed to stop the production of illegal drugs to the United
States. Some Democrats and human rights officials, however, have
warned that the plan's heavy emphasis on military equipment will
lead to more violence rather than less drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money for the package would pay for 60 US-made
helicopters, increased eradication of coca and poppy fields,
advanced intelligence equipment, and the creation of two more
antidrug battalions, whose members are trained by US personnel. A
smaller portion of funds would be used for crop substitution
programs and rural economic and social projects.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana said drug trafficking remains Colombia's greatest
threat. ``More than anything else, it fuels the insurgency, feeds
violence and delinquency, breeds insecurity and fear, and threatens
our democratic institutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is concern, even among US officials, that the aid
package could lead to more violence between the government and the
various left- and right-wing rebel groups operating in the country.
Many say the insurgent organizations, the largest being the Marxist
guerrillas known as the FARC, have become more dependent on
proceeds from drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   After several starts and stops during the past year, peace
negotiations between the Pastrana administration and the FARC began
again in October.
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the FARC's official reaction to the aid package,
however, has been difficult. On Thursday, a FARC spokesman, Raul
Reyes, said the aid package would make peace negotiations ``more
difficult.'' But on Friday, the group's longtime commander, Manuel
Marulanda Velez, also known as ``Tirofijo,'' spoke publicly for the
first time in months, hinting that peace was now within reach.
</P>
<P>
   General Fernando Tapia Sterling, the commander of Colombia's
military forces, said the aid money from the United States would go
strictly toward antidrug efforts. ``We are going to fight the war
against narcotraffic,'' Tapia said, ``And that includes everyone
who is mixed up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright's visit created a brief stir throughout this tropical
Caribbean city. National police officers, wearing fatigues and
wielding rifles, stood guard at most Cartagena street corners. The
colonial-era town center, where Albright and most of her aides
stayed, was closed to normal traffic.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, she attended a private dinner with Pastrana and
Nobel laureate author Gabriel Garcia Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Albright met with eight prominent Colombian
women in political and civil affairs. She then toured the city's
port facilities, where police have mounted new antidrug strategies
funded largely with US assistance. In a ceremony following the
tour, a marching band played traditional songs known as
``cumbias,'' as Albright danced with a local girl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
