<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Jan. 16. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DRUGS-BORDER-OVERVIEW (Introduction to an eight-day special report)
_ Every day, guerrilla smugglers invade Arizona's southern border
with payloads of pot, coke, meth and smack. The drugs are spread
across the country _ to schoolkids in New York, to stockbrokers in
Phoenix, to farm workers in Seattle. The United States has spent
billions of tax dollars on border checkpoints, undercover agents,
air patrols and money-laundering probes. But the truth is
inescapable: The fight against narcotics, which costs Americans
nearly $18 billion a year, is the nation's most failed police
action since Vietnam. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DRUGS-BORDER-1 (Day 1) _ If America's drug war is not already lost,
it is clearly unwinnable. Just ask Border Patrol and Customs agents
who chase pot runners through catclaw canyons west of Naco or the
inspectors pounding pavement at Nogales' ports of entry, using
everything from sniffer dogs to gamma rays to check for cocaine and
cash. After nearly a half-century of escalating efforts to stop
illegal drug smuggling, the casualty count is a litany of lives
wasted, tax dollars lost, corruption, violence and public cynicism.
By DENNIS WAGNER and PAT FLANNERY. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DRUGS-PATROL-1 (sidebar to Day 1) _ Drug smuggling in the United
States is being squeezed into an ever-smaller corridor, now
centered in Arizona. Illegal immigrants are flooding into the state
through the same corridor, and the smugglers have learned to use
the crowded conditions to their advantage. By PAT FLANNERY. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ (Phoenix) This is where 14-year-old Shannon Smith
stood on the night of June 14, 1999. It's in the small backyard of
a red brick home in central Phoenix. Shannon Smith on the
telephone, talking to a friend, when a bullet that had been fired
randomly into the air fell and fell and fell, and struck her on the
head, ending the lives of her parents. By EJ MONTINI. Story will
move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Undated) - Forget the hype, the critical acclaim, the
unreasonable love you have for the show. Despite all that, one
nagging question haunts fans of The Sopranos: Can the second season
possibly be as good as the first? Judging from the first three new
episodes, the answer isn't just ``yes.'' The answer is that it
might be even better. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
