<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-NOTEBOOK-1S     01-15 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTEBOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add new first item)  
(HLW) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Iowa, Dole Offers Assault on Attacks &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Just when it seemed there were enough
Republican candidates battling in the Iowa caucuses, another one
stepped into the fray: Bob Dole. In Saturday's Des Moines Register,
Dole took out a large ad as an ``open letter'' to Iowa Republicans
criticizing, in a thinly disguised way, television commercials for
Steve Forbes that attack Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dole should know well. In the 1996 Iowa caucuses, Forbes ran a
series of harsh ads that tarnished Dole's image and, many say,
harmed his candidacy. Now, Dole took it upon himself to say that
the Republican Party, and ``our eventual presidential nominee''
could be hurt by Forbes ads running in Iowa and New Hampshire. In
his ad, Dole criticized ``distorted negative television political
ads'' and said he was speaking up now ``because it may be happening
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes ad in question is a 30-second television spot in
which the head of a Texas anti-tax group complains that in 1994,
Bush broke a promise when he supported raising the Texas sales tax
in a plan that was not enacted, but that overall, would have
lowered taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Dole also said, ``I accept full responsibility for
our loss in 1996, but anyone who followed that race closely would
agree that the millions of dollars of deceptive and distorted
negative television ads were a major factor in that loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole has not endorsed anyone in the campaign, but says he is a
close friend of Sen. John McCain. Dole's wife, Elizabeth Dole,
recently endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Blackwell, the Forbes campaign's national manager, said
it was ``purely foolish'' to suggest that the 1996 Forbes ads led
to Dole's loss. ``Mr. Dole's vision never took root with the
American public,'' Blackwell said. The Bush campaign, he said, was
just ``whining.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling comment about this back-and-forth was
in Dole's open letter: ``Politics is rough and tumble and all who
enter the arena do so at their own risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Iowa? And Why New Hampshire?
</P>
<P>
   Should Iowa, which holds the nation's first presidential
caucuses, and New Hampshire, which holds the first primaries, be
allowed to dominate the early going in the nominating process?
</P>
<P>
   It's an old question. But once again it is up for consideration,
with Iowans scheduled to caucus only eight days from now and New
Hampshirites set to vote just eight days later.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who fare poorly in either or both states could very
well end up dropping out of the race, unable to raise enough money
to continue because they will be perceived as weak. That is what
has happened so often in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors of this early winnowing system contend that it is
unfair and no way to begin picking the leader of the world's most
powerful nation. They argue that neither state is typically
American, with Iowa being too rural and New Hampshire too small.
</P>
<P>
   Iowans and New Hampshirites do not see it that way, of course.
They say their states are ideal political laboratories because
voters in both states still insist on ``retail politicking'' _
getting to know and test candidates firsthand, at town-meeting
style forums, in coffee shops and, indeed, in their own living
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   To do well in Iowa and New Hampshire, they argue, candidates
must have a ``ground game'' of hand shaking, eye contact and
one-on-one conversations because the ``air game'' of television
sound bites and advertising blitzes so often used elsewhere just
won't cut it in Hawkeye and Granite country.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a lot of political hokum?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say. But consider:
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, when The Des Moines Register polled Iowans
whom it considered likely to vote in caucuses on Jan. 24, one of
every three said they had met at least one candidate in this
election cycle. More to the point, one in four reported meeting the
candidate of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier survey in New Hampshire found that one of every five
voters had met at least one candidate, and often two, three or
more.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, a voter could probably go close to a lifetime
without meeting a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A Kennedy Stirs The Political Waters
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, Maryland's lieutenant governor and a
daughter of Robert F. Kennedy, showed up in Des Moines the other
day to campaign for an old political friend, Vice President Al
Gore. And guess what?
</P>
<P>
   By the time she left town _ this being Iowa and she being a
Kennedy _ there was speculation that maybe, just maybe, she was
testing the presidential waters a bit herself.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, she told The Des Moines Register, noting that she was
considering running for governor in Maryland and therefore was
``committed to Maryland politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But then she added, ``For a good period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever that meant, if anything, it didn't quiet the buzz that
followed her speech.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack, a Democrat, proclaimed that ``she has a
legitimate shot to be the first woman president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   And two Democratic legislators in Iowa agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has all the makings,'' said state Rep. Pam Jochum of
Dubuque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got that Kennedy flair,'' added state Rep. Polly Bukta of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A Call for Action On Matters of Faith
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the Interfaith Alliance, a five-year-old
national organization of religious leaders and members of some 50
faiths and movements, expressed concern that while White House
hopefuls were increasingly talking about their religious beliefs,
they were nevertheless failing to live up to them on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance urged all the presidential candidates to reject
``degrading, disparaging or demeaning'' personal attacks and to
avoid ``innuendo or stereotyping or references likely to
dehumanize.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after several debates in which White House aspirants
discussed their personal faith at considerable length, comes
another expression of concern about mixing politics and religion.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Industrial Areas Foundation, a national
organization of church-based community action groups that seeks to
improve the wages and living conditions of the poor, is calling on
candidates to back up their professions of faith with concrete
action.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally a few days ago at St. John's Episcopal Church in
Washington, across Lafayette Square from the White House, leaders
of the organization declared that they would follow the candidates
``to New Hampshire, Delaware, the Hamptons and the Texas hill
country, if necessary'' to pressure them to halt ``the rhetoric of
religiosity that permeates the presidential campaign.'' Instead,
the foundation speakers said, candidates should put their professed
faith in action by working nonstop on ``the central public issue of
this period,'' closing the gap between the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a moratorium on the empty religious rhetoric from the
presidential candidates,'' said Bishop John Hurst Adams, the senior
bishop of the African Methodist Episcopal Church. ``We demand that
they address the real faith issue of our time. We will not let this
issue go.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Virginia Democrat Thinks Independent
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Virgil Goode, a Democrat from Virginia's solidly
conservative 5th Congressional District, often breaks party ranks
and votes Republican. In fact, he breaks ranks so often that
Republicans leaders, scrambling to keep their narrow edge in the
House, are pressing him to seek re-election this fall as one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   If he does, and if Republicans hold onto the House, party
leaders have hinted, he would be in line for some congressional
power perks. And if he doesn't, some have hinted darkly that, well,
it now looks like Republicans will be in political command of the
Old Dominion come redistricting time in 2001, and as a Democrat he
just might find himself gerrymandered out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   The talk in state political circles is that Goode has about
decided to split things down the middle and run as an independent,
trusting he can keep his seat in the House by pulling conservative
votes from every political direction in the district, which is in
south-central Virginia and is fairly evenly divided between
Democrats and Republicans, with many of the Democrats as
conservative as any Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Then, so the talk goes, if Goode makes it back to Capitol Hill,
he plans to strike a deal with Republican leaders, agreeing to vote
mostly Republican in committees and on the floor in return for some
power perks.
</P>
<P>
   Such a plan may or may not work, and there is some talk that if
he wins as an independent he may end up dickering with both
parties. But in any case, it is not a unique plan. Rep. Bernard
Sanders of Vermont, the only independent in the House, worked out
such a deal with House Democratic leaders years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Are Term Limits The Final Answer?
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Tillie Fowler, a Republican from Jacksonville, Fla.,
said last fall that she was thinking about breaking her pledge to
serve only four terms in the House, U.S. Term Limits, the leading
term-limits advocacy organization, began saturating her district
with sharply worded television and radio advertisements accusing
her of political dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago she announced that she would stick by her
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just in case some of her constituents had missed her
announcement and might be left with the impression that she was
just another politically dishonest public servant, she took the
unusual step of running television commercials explaining what she
had done and why.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Term Limits was impressed, and last week it took an unusual
step of its own. It began running advertisements congratulating Ms.
Fowler for doing ``the right thing'' and for being ``a person of
real character.''
</P>
<P>
   A footnote: In the case of Rep. George Nethercutt, a Republican
from Spokane, Wash., who has broken a term limits pledge, U.S. Term
Limits is stepping up its broadcast criticism. Its latest
commercial, a takeoff on the television game show ``Who Wants To Be
A Millionaire,'' goes like this, in part:
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ``Welcome to `Try to Be a Millionaire.' Name the
Washington state politician who said, `Your word is your bond,' and
then broke his word. Is it Tom Foley, Slade Gorton or George
Nethercutt?''
</P>
<P>
   Contestant: ``Well, the politician best known for breaking his
word is George Nethercutt.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ``Is that your final answer?''
</P>
<P>
   Contestant: ``Final answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ``You're right! Nethercutt's the one who broke his
word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
