<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BEAT ISLANDERS, 5-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The longer Petr Nedved's slump continued, the
less other teams felt they needed to go after the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they thought, `Let him sleep,''' Nedved said.
</P>
<P>
   Not now. Nedved has been very much awake since the Rangers
acquired his countryman Radek Dvorak on Dec. 30 and then paired the
two with Jan Hlavac to form a Czech Connection line. Nedved had
better be prepared for a lot more attention, as was evident after
he scored a goal and set up two by Hlavac to lead the Rangers to a
5-2 victory over the Islanders Saturday afternoon before a sell-out
crowd of 16,297 at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Nedved accused the Islanders' Steve Webb of
delivering a cheap shot with an elbow in the third period, a charge
Webb denied _ more or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no elbow,'' Webb said. ``He was admiring a pass he
had made. And if he wants to admire his passes, he should look out
where he's going, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedved was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't intimidate me,'' Nedved said. ``But he should be
ashamed of what he did. He's going to say he's a pretty tough guy.
To me, that's not tough. Somebody could get seriously injured like
that. I got a little whiplash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an elbow. I didn't have the puck. And I didn't see him
behind me. Obviously, that was intentional. I think he should get
suspended. That's brutal. And I'm not crying or whining.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our game, until somebody gets seriously hurt, it's OK. But
this is not OK. He should find me clearly when I have the puck. I
don't mind if he gives me a concussion, as long as I have the
puck.''
</P>
<P>
   In a strange way, however, perhaps Nedved should consider the
attention a compliment. At least teams are starting to pay
attention to him again.
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable.
</P>
<P>
   In the four games Nedved has centered for his Czech mates, he
has five goals and two assists. In the previous 12 games, Nedved
had gone without a goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since being united, the Czechs have teamed for seven goals and
seven assists and the Rangers have outscored their opponents, 13-8.
Most important, they have won three of the four games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Nedved's line teamed for the purest of hat tricks: an
even-strength goal; a short-handed goal (the Rangers' first this
season, in their 42nd game), and a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hlavac might be the only player in the league who likes Nassau
Coliseum. A second-round draft choice of the Islanders in 1995, he
has scored four of his six goals here this season. His first goal
Saturday came 50 seconds into the game, on the first shot of the
contest _ a wrister from the left circle that beat Islanders goalie
Kevin Weekes, who had been 2-0-1 against the Rangers this season.
</P>
<P>
   After Jorgen Jonsson evened things at 12 minutes 45 seconds,
Nedved scored his 12th goal of the season. It came short-handed off
a brilliant feed from Dvorak, who somehow passed the puck to Nedved
in the slot from the right circle while falling to the ice because
Dave Scatchard had hooked Dvorak from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved then held the puck long enough to fake both Jamie Heward
and Weekes down to the ice, before shooting over Weekes for the
go-ahead goal at 19:08 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Radek's goal,'' Nedved said. ``He made that play
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hlavac made it 3-1 Rangers at 3:42 of the second on the power
play.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers Coach John Muckler said the assistant coach Keith Acton
had been having Hlavac practice shooting the last two or three
days. ``He must have shot a thousand pucks,'' Muckler said. ``And
it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hlavac said he did not want to shoot on this occasion, though.
But when the Islanders' penalty killers lagged off him as Hlavac
held the puck in the right circle, he finally shot through traffic.
It beat Weekes through the goalie's five hole.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, even Valery Kamensky and Theo Fleury got into the act.
Kamensky's goal at 5:04 of the second made it 4-1 Rangers and
chased Weekes from the game in favor of Roberto Luongo. The goal
was just Kamensky's second of the season and his first since Oct.
19, snapping a 15-game drought for the 33-year-old left wing, who
has been hampered by a sore right forearm.
</P>
<P>
   After Mats Lindgren cut the lead to 4-2 at 9:49 of the third,
Fleury beat Luongo (who made 15 saves in relief of Weekes) with a
wicked wrister from the left circle on a breakaway at 18:11 to
finish the scoring. For Fleury, it was his first goal since Dec.
29, snapping a drought of five games.
</P>
</TEXT>
