u a BC-MLK-AUTHOR16-COX     01-15 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-AUTHOR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vision of King legacy blurred by family acting on poor advice,
author says
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Juan Williams, who authored one of the most definitive
accounts of the civil rights era, says the family of Martin Luther
King Jr. should let history rest _ at least when it comes to King's
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, author of ``Eyes on the Prize _ America's Civil Rights
Years, 1954-1964,'' spoke Saturday at a King birthday celebration
for Georgia Perimeter College.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a recent decision in a civil suit filed by the family,
finding the 1968 King assassination was the result of a widespread
conspiracy involving everyone from two-bit hustlers to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have is a jury saying to a family, `If you want to say
there was a conspiracy, go ahead,''' said Williams, a Washington
Post columnist. ``In many ways, they saw that verdict as a
vindication, but in terms of actual evidence, I haven't seen a
scrap.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dec. 8 decision by a Memphis, Tenn., jury also concluded
that the late James Earl Ray, who spent the last 30 years of his
life in jail for the murder, was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't find anything that says that James Earl Ray
didn't commit the murder or that he was aided by a large
conspiracy,'' said Williams. He said the King family is not getting
the best advice from outside advisers on the assassination, and
also matters of money and their rights to King's words and works.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting arguments, he said, threaten to tarnish the
family's image _ and King's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is still loved and respected all over the world,
but the problem is they get involved in petty squabbles. It takes
away from King's electrifying legacy,'' said Williams, whose latest
book chronicles the life of Thurgood Marshall. ``Where is the large
vision and passion?'' Williams asked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
