<HEADER>
A7087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-BUCCANEE     01-15 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-BUCCANEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMPA BAY BEATS WASHINGTON, 14-13  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Trailing by 6 points and facing a third down at
the Washington Redskins' 1-yard line Saturday, Tampa Bay Coach Tony
Dungy did not entrust his season to his Pro Bowl fullback, Mike
Alstott.
</P>
<P>
   An Alstott rush up the middle might have been expected, but
Dungy instead put the playoff game in the hands of his rookie
quarterback, Shaun King, and John Davis, a third-string tight end
who had two catches during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   With 7 minutes 29 seconds remaining in the game, King took the
snap and rolled out to his right. Washington defensive end Ndukwe
Kalu met King there and was soon draped around his waist, but King
jumped and threw to Davis in the right side of the end zone for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The score gave Tampa Bay a 14-13 victory in a game in which it
had trailed by 13 points midway through the third quarter. The
Buccaneers will play in the National Football Conference
championship game next Sunday against either St. Louis or
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   King's dramatics were nearly upstaged by a final Washington
drive, which led the Redskins to line up for a 52-yard field-goal
attempt by Brett Conway with 1:08 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Conway never got to attempt his kick. The snap by Washington's
Dan Turk bounced to the holder Brad Johnson, who scooped up the
ball and tried unsuccessfully to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins had moved to the Tampa Bay 40-yard line with an
11-yard completion from Johnson, the Redskin quarterback, to Skip
Hicks on a screen pass. Three plays netted 7 more yards, which
brought Conway onto the field. He had kicked three field goals of
50 or more yards this season.
</P>
<P>
   For King, the first rookie to start a National Football League
playoff game in nine years, the touchdown pass brought a winning
conclusion to an erratic game.
</P>
<P>
   King had played poorly for most of the first three quarters and
completed only 4 of 14 passes for 45 yards in the first half. But
in the second half, he completed 11 of 18 passes for 112 yards.
</P>
<P>
   After a listless first half, which ended with Washington leading
by &QC; 3-0, the Redskins greeted the second half with a sudden and
startling strike as Brian Mitchell returned the kickoff 100 yards
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell stumbled through a pileup of players near the right
sideline before breaking into the open virtually untouched. Martin
Gramatica, Tampa Bay's kicker, made an attempt to tackle Mitchell
at the Redskins' 42-yard line, but Mitchell stiff-armed Gramatica
to the ground and outran the rest of the Buccaneers to give
Washington a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's score was the longest kickoff return in NFL playoff
history. The previous record was a 99-yard return by Desmond Howard
in the 1996 Super Bowl for Green Bay against New England.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the third quarter, after Darrell Green intercepted a
pass by King, the Redskins extended their lead to 13-0 with a
48-yard field goal by Conway.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it looked as if the NFC Central champion
Buccaneers were going to be run out of the playoffs without
scoring, Tampa Bay moved downfield and cut Washington's lead to
13-7 after John Lynch intercepted a pass by Johnson. Alstott scored
on a 2-yard run, a spectacular carry on which he eluded several
tackle attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Alstott was nearly tackled by middle linebacker Derek Smith in
the backfield just after the handoff from King, then was hit by
three Redskins in the middle of the line. Alstott kept his feet as
he backpedaled before dashing to his left and outside the pileup
into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Alstott's touchdown was set up by a pass-interference penalty on
Washington's Leomont Evans at the Redskins' 11. Evans had run over
Warrick Dunn as Dunn awaited a pass from King along the left
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Although it appeared at times in the first half that neither
team would ever break the shutout, the Redskins eventually mounted
a second-quarter scoring drive behind the running of Stephen Davis
and the blocking of left tackle Kipp Vickers.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers was filling in for the usual starter, Andy Heck, who
tore his hamstring in last weekend's playoff victory over Detroit.
Vickers was making only his eighth NFL start in seven seasons, but
on two long runs by Davis, Vickers opened gaping holes while
blocking Tampa Bay's Pro Bowl tackle, Warren Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins' drive stalled at the Buccaneers' 10, but Conway's
28-yard field goal gave Washington a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By this point, the Buccaneers were scrambling defensively, and
at times playing without two of their best defenders. Their best
defensive back, Donnie Abraham, had limped off the field with 9:33
left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham, who tied for the league lead in interceptions with
seven, missed most of practice this past week with a hamstring
strain, then sprained his left knee in Saturday's game. He returned
in the second half, but was clearly hobbled.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp, the Associated Press defensive player of the year, injured
his left leg in the first half. Although he returned to play, he
was limping noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers came into Saturday's game with the league's
third-ranked defense, while the Redskins' defense was ranked 30th.
But for most of the first three quarters, Washington's defense
dominated the game.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the Redskins seemed intent on pressuring
King in the pocket. And King seemed to be hurrying his throws in
the first quarter, as if he were a bit nervous. Washington was
happy to add to King's anxiety by frequently blitzing strong safety
Sam Shade. With Shade in his face, King misfired on four of his
first five passes.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's running game did not do anything in the first half
to relieve the pressure on King as Washington's defensive tackles,
Dana Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson, stuffed the middle of the
line, which is the Buccaneers' usual point of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alstott could not get the Bucs going early _ he was stopped
short on third-and-1 in the first quarter and was held to 4 yards
on his first five rushing carries. Of the Buccaneers' first five
possessions, four lasted for only three plays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
