<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     01-15 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONTIERE IS LUCKY LADY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the giant figures of the 20th century ranking right up
there with the Einsteins, Salks, Churchills and FDRs, Georgia
Frontiere seems destined to continue her matchless success into the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The trailblazing owner of the St. Louis Rams is on the threshold
of taking her football team into the Super Bowl, reaffirming that
hoariest of axioms that good things inevitably happen to good
people.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, the Rams are strong favorites in Las Vegas to make
such an appearance on Jan. 30 in Atlanta, a reflection of the
dazzling leadership of Frontiere, whose discerning personnel eye
has resisted all criticism since she somehow was able to bring to
gaffe Carroll Rosenbloom as her sixth husband.
</P>
<P>
   Before she pulled off that unlikely coup _ she had served as the
married Rosenbloom's mistress for a number of years _ she was just
plain old Georgia Hayes of Fresno, a nightclub singer of
appallingly limited talent who had survived her share of private
grief.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, she hit the lottery with Rosenbloom, then a
multimillionaire businessman who owned the Baltimore Colts and
later would wind up with the Los Angeles Rams.
</P>
<P>
   There is no rhyme or reason for one being bestowed with good
fortune in life. There are those individuals who stumble through
their days under the darkest of clouds. And then there are those
whose footsteps are paved with gold.
</P>
<P>
   For much of her early years, Georgia Frontiere wasn't covered
with four leaf clovers. Her choice of men was disastrous. Her music
career was stumbling. And even during her marriage to Rosenbloom,
she wasn't exactly treated like royalty.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who attended dinner with the Rosenblooms who
would blanch perceptibly when Carroll would make cruelly derisive
remarks directed at his wife, who would endure such taunts in
silence.
</P>
<P>
   But the instant Rosenbloom took his ill-starred swim into the
Atlantic Ocean on April 1, 1979, the fate of his wife would turn
dramatically around, especially when his will would reveal that she
would inherit 70 percent of the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Upon the advice of the late owner of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers,
Hugh Culverhouse, Georgia borrowed $10 million from a New York bank
and bought out the remaining 30 percent of the team from
Rosenbloom's five children that included two of her own.
</P>
<P>
   The milk of human kindness, a person of staggering charity and
goodwill, Georgia, obviously, wanted to make sure each Rosenbloom
heir would be well-indemnified for the tragic loss of the family
patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   But the $2 million each would receive turned out to be a mere
pittance, in light of the fact the Ram franchise has increased in
value the past 20 years a staggering 2000 percent, from an
estimated $30 million when Rosenbloom died to more than $600
million at the current time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Georgia would never do harm to anyone, even though
moments after she took over the Rams she reluctantly fired her
stepson, Steve Rosenbloom, who had been designated by his father to
run the team.
</P>
<P>
   And soon after that, Georgia, an avowed astrologer who claimed
the alignment of the stars dictated her actions, cleaned out her
organization, expunging from it such noble individuals as Don
(Duke) Klosterman, Harold (Sqeezer) Guiver and even E. Gregory
Hookstratten.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams would appear in a Super Bowl during her first year as
caretaker _ they would lose a thriller at the Rose Bowl to the
Pittsburgh Steelers _ and they would go on to have some fruitful
seasons in the early coaching tenure of John Robinson when Eric
Dickerson was dispensing his heroics in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Shockingly, Georgia's newest squeeze, Hubby VII, Dominic
Frontiere, got nabbed in a Super Bowl ticket scandal, which
resulted in his winding up in a federal prison. Natch, even though
Georgia owned the team, she claimed to know nothing about her luvvy
dear's shenanigans, and came out of the mess with her reputation
intact.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia in the subsequent years began spending more time in
London vainly seeking the Fountain of Youth, turning control over
her organization to a penny-pinching accountant named John Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams slowly began to unravel _ the watershed moment came in
1987 when Dickerson was peddled to the Indianapolis Colts _ and the
team and Georgia soon became the laughingstocks of professional
athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   This sterling lady became a hated figure in these parts, even
being showered with a chorus of angry boos when she made her
traditional appearances on the Ram sidelines. How could such a
kind-hearted person described glowingly in the Ram press guide as
the latest incarnation of Mother Teresa be treated so savagely?
</P>
<P>
   Hurt beyond comprehension, Georgia decided to stay detached from
the Rams during their final years in Orange County, and gave Shaw
the go-ahead to cut a lucrative deal with the politicians of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL-starved city of St. Louis presented Georgia with a new
domed stadium and hefty relocation fees, and she moved the Rams out
of Southern California after the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the team continued its ignoble struggles in its new venue,
but Somebody Up There likes Georgia Frontiere and you just knew
this decent woman soon would once again be riding a crest of
success.
</P>
<P>
   As though by divine intervention, the Rams came up with a
storybook quarterback out of nowhere named Kurt Warner to go with a
lot of other talented players that have fashioned a 13-3 season and
are expected to dump the Minnesota Vikings in today's playoff
match.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure Georgia Frontiere will be seen on the Ram
sidelines late in the game bestowing kisses on her minions if her
team is heading for a stirring victory.
</P>
<P>
   And who deserves it more than Georgia Frontiere, a God-fearing
septuagenarian who has lived such an exemplary life?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
