u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JAGUARS-     01-15 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JAGUARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSONVILLE BEATS MIAMI, 62-7  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The pass fluttered out of Dan Marino's hand
on Miami's first offensive play, like the first rock that slips
down a cliff, portending a landslide. It was easily picked off _
the first of seven Miami turnovers in what became the second-most
lopsided game in National Football League postseason history:
Jacksonville 62, Miami 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars (15-2) scored 38 points before Marino had even
completed a pass, moving into their second American Football
Conference championship game in their first five seasons. The
Dolphins (10-8) were sent reeling into an uncertain off-season in a
humiliating conclusion to an enigmatic season.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest blowout in NFL playoff history came in 1940, when
the Chicago Bears overwhelmed the Washington Redskins, 73-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never experienced a game like this in my life, since I
was a kid,'' Marino said after playing perhaps the final game of
his career. He was 11 of 25 for 95 yards, with two interceptions
and one touchdown before being replaced in the third quarter by
Damon Huard. ``Nothing went right for us early and it just
snowballed.''
</P>
<P>
   What an understatement. This was an embarrassment from the
start.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Coach Jimmy Johnson, trailing by 41-7 at halftime, had
wanted to replace Marino to start the second half. Marino had asked
for another chance from Johnson, with whom he has had a fractious
relationship. Johnson gave it to him, then watched, stone faced, as
the Dolphins went three plays and out to start the third quarter.
That was a typical series for the Dolphins, who had hoped to use
the run and their defense to slow the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Miami came out passing _ and then had to pass some
more as their deficit grew. The results were disastrous. On the
first nine times Marino dropped back to pass, he was intercepted
twice, sacked twice, fumbled once, and contributed to two quick
Jacksonville scores, all without completing a single pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing the team, about halfway through the second quarter we
knew we had the game,'' said Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell, who
was able to rest his weary and braced knees after little more than
a quarter of work and two touchdowns. ``We were up 38 points and
our defense was playing well. I felt it was ours at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami would have no chance to recover, not with the Jaguars
capitalizing on almost every one of the frequent opportunities the
Dolphins gave them, including a blocked punt. The Jaguars, who will
play the winner of Sunday's Tennessee-Indianapolis game, outgained
the Dolphins by 530 yards to 131 (including 197 yards to minus-1 in
the first quarter), tearing through the Dolphins' defense as if it
had stayed on the field ever since last week's wild-card victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars scored 24 points in the first quarter and eight
touchdowns in all, on everything from a playoff record 90-yard run
on a simple draw play by Fred Taylor (135 yards in just one half of
play) to a 70-yard catch and run by Jimmy Smith (five catches, 136
yards) in concert with backup quarterback Jay Fiedler. Included was
a comical 16-yard fumble return by Tony Brackens after he sacked
Marino in the first quarter, stripped the ball and then received a
few pats on the back from teammates before realizing nobody had
touched him and he could run the ball into the end zone for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars scored with such ease, including three touchdowns in
the second half when the game was well out of reach, that Coach Tom
Coughlin might face a few questions about why the score was so
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we wanted to start fast,'' said Jacksonville offensive
tackle Leon Searcy. ``We wanted to put them in a situation where
they had to play catch-up. When we had a big lead, we had to stay
focused. We knew we had the game won. But we wanted some
carry-over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who have home-field advantage throughout the
playoffs, must wonder how they managed to luck into what amounted
to little more than an intrasquad scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson took the blame for the defeat afterward, saying he had
worked his team too hard in the short week after it had made the
cross-country trip to Seattle and back to win the wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we would have had a chance to win if we were
fresh,'' he said. ``I tried to prepare them too much. I should have
pulled back after Seattle. Obviously, we were dead-legged.
Unfortunately, we left it on the practice field.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is the reason for this debacle, the Jaguars finally
proved that they could beat a winning team. Entering the game, the
Jaguars had been ornery, annoyed at reporters and opponents who
suggested that, though they finished the regular season with the
league's best record at 14-2, they were a bit soft because they had
not beaten a team with a winning record all season and that they
had lost both times they faced a winning team _ Tennessee. The
truth is they still don't know how they will perform when they are
in a tight game against a quality opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins were certainly not that on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
