<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-FLAMES-B     01-15 2277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-FLAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPARK FOR THE FLAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a roster boost, a dash of character on the wing, the
Flames last week called up Chris Clark, ex- of South Windsor,
Conn., and Clarkson, and dropped him into his first NHL game.
</P>
<P>
   Results: 14 shifts, 10 minutes of ice time, a couple of shots _
and, oh, a 2-1 overtime victory over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all pretty exciting,'' said Clark, reached by phone late
last week in Calgary. ``I was in the minors all last year and
didn't get a call, and I wasn't expecting anything this time; I
wondered if this would ever come. I thought I was having a good
season, but it's one of those things, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 22, had 13 goals and 28 points at St. John, Calgary's AHL
affiliate. More important, or more appealing to Calgary management,
he also led the club with 119 penalty minutes, showing the kind of
pluck he displayed during his four years at Clarkson (392 PIMs in
142 games).
</P>
<P>
   One thing we all know is that Flames coach Brian Sutter likes
feistiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys told me, whether I'd want to or not, I'd have
to fight _ because of the kind of game I play,'' said Clark, who
showed in his first Flames camp, in September 1998, that he
wouldn't shy away from the fight game. ``The fights are OK. For the
most part, they're fun. Most of them aren't nearly as bad as they
look.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's overall game is to be physical, always on the puck,
doing what he can to frustrate the opposition. He didn't have to
answer the fight bell in his NHL debut, but the Flames were back on
the ice again Saturday night against Toronto. As a kid who grew up
dreaming he could play in the mold of a Cam Neely or a Kevin Dineen
(Whaler fans never die), inevitably he'll have his pugilistic
interludes.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the 77th pick in the '94 draft, was supposed to be in
Rochester, N.Y., this weekend, participating in the AHL's skill
competition (Sunday) and All-Star game (Monday). For now, he's
staying in southern Alberta, his pay bumped from $65,000 to
$350,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, he couldn't be quite as aggressive as he's been in
the pros,'' said Clark's Boston-based agent, Mark Witkin, who also
represents Bruins Don Sweeney and Hal Gill. ``But he's always been
an aggressive, very honest player. No yapping. Just a good,
hard-nosed kid who isn't flashy but has shown what he can do at
every level.''
</P>
<P>
   It's rare in today's game for a rookie, especially an American
college player, to step into the league and fill a character role.
Those jobs still typically go to the quickly-disappearing Canadian
farm kid or the strapping European (hello, Krzysztof Oliwa), eager
and hungry enough to step in and make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fool's work to project Clark now as a budding power
forward, but he has a role and a method in mind, and it's that kind
of foundation that can lead to turning dreams into reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to do what I did in college,'' said Clark, who
was called up ahead of two prized first-round draft picks, Rico
Fata and Daniel Tkaczuk. ``It's the way I've played my whole life:
up and down the wing, bang and crash. If I make it, it's not going
to be on flash.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor unmade
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers last week were shuffling lines again. ``The question
is, what do we do with (Tim) Taylor?'' coach John Muckler told the
New York Daily News. ``Taylor's played really well and he's really
contributed to this club. We've asked him to play against the best
lines and check the best player on the other side, and he's done a
great job of that. I don't know where we would be if he hadn't done
that good of a job.'' The Bruins know that answer. With Taylor in
their lineup last season, they had the No. 1 penalty-killing unit
in the league. This year, they've gone from first to worst . . .
Ex-Bruin Andy Brickley, convinced more than ever that he wants to
get back in a broadcast booth, was back at Channel 38 last week,
compiling a resume tape. Brickley was impressed with the ESPN
telecast Sunday night that had analysts Bill Clement and Darren
Pang handling live questions submitted over the Internet during the
Colorado-Chicago matchup. ``The whole broadcast field, and
especially sports, is such a growth area right now,'' said
Brickley, who stopped by the Vault to see Thursday's Bruins-Leafs
game. ``I think I've got something to offer, and I'm working hard
to get that opportunity again.'' . . . Imagine what Boston's future
would look like with Jason Allison, Joe Thornton, and Keith Primeau
penciled in as the pivots for the better part of the decade . . .
Word around the Senators is that Vaclav Prospal, ordered to have a
refresher course in sensitivity training after his disparaging
remarks directed toward Patrice Brisebois, suddenly is a hot
commodity in the trade market, with Edmonton, Phoenix, Florida, and
Vancouver showing interest. Prior to the Christmas roster freeze,
when Prospal couldn't crack Jacques Martin's lineup, Ottawa
reportedly couldn't give him away. But it's not Prospal's tongue
that has 'em talking. Placed on a line with Daniel Alfredsson and
Shawn McEachern, he had 12 points in 10 games as of late last week
. . . Local player rep Matt Keator, who helped UMass-Lowell
netminder Scott Fankhouser catch on with the Thrashers, has a David
Robinson-like story unfolding in the minors. Andy Lundbohm, a
6-foot-3-inch, 215-pound center at West Point the last four seasons
(168 points), signed a two-way deal with San Jose over the summer
and recently reported to Ted Sator's New Orleans Brass (ECHL) for a
tuneup before heading for the AHL. Lundbohm, with at least another
18 months of Army time to serve, will play for the Kentucky
Thoroughblades while stationed at Fort Knox . . . Ex-Bruins
defenseman/coach/assistant GM Mike Milbury likes the idea here of
leaving the icing rule intact, for both sides, during penalty
situations. ``I'd also be in favor of making the net bigger,'' said
Milbury. ``If you go back and look at film from years ago, the
goalies have much less protection, they all look skinny by
comparison to what we've got today.'' . . . It's possible that
Scotty Bowman's 3-0 loss behind the Detroit bench Tuesday night in
Montreal will be the last game he coaches in his hometown. That's
assuming, of course, that Bowman retires at the end of this season,
which still isn't a fait accompli . . . The Lightning said they
wouldn't give Stephane Richer away, and Thursday they ended up
moving him to St. Louis, in yet another nicely-orchestrated deal by
Tampa Bay GM Rick Dudley. The Blues shipped out ex-Devils
defenseman Chris McAlpine, 28, and 27-year-old netminder Rich
Parent, a seventh-year pro who has seen very limited NHL action.
McAlpine brings immediate depth and experience to a young defensive
corps, while Parent might never be more than a minor leaguer. But
the Lightning were on the hook for another $3 million (through next
season) with Richer, and this move will save them at least $2
million. Now, can Richer rekindle that sniper's touch with fellow
ex-Canadien Pierre Turgeon dishing him the biscuit? It's a
tantalizing thought. Remember, they were Montreal teammates for
only nine games in '96-97, prior to Turgeon getting moved in the
Shayne Corson exchange . . . Ex-Bruin Andy Moog, under contract as
Vancouver's goaltending consultant, is working with Felix Potvin,
who has gone a lackluster 1-4-1 since getting swapped to Vancouver
from the Islanders. Moog was a consultant with Atlanta last year .
. . with Alexei Yashin in their lineup, the Senators had 51 points
in the first half of last season. This year, they had 50 points.
For a guy who wants $8 million or better _ and who snubbed his nose
at the $3.5 million he agreed to play for _ the numbers haven't
exactly gone his way . . . Coach of the Czech Republic squad that
won the recent World Junior title was Jaroslav Holik, father of
Devils center Bobby Holik . . . The Jan. 21 edition of The Hockey
News ranks Boston College defenseman Brooks Orpik the seventh-best
positional player available in the June draft at Calgary. Associate
editor Bob McKenzie also rates Boston University's Rick DiPietro as
the best available goalie . . . Another BC product, Jeff Farkas, is
expected to sign with Toronto at the conclusion of the Eagles'
season and report to St. John's in the AHL. The Leafs made him the
No. 57 pick overall in the '97 draft . . . Ex-Bruin Ken Linseman is
in Ontario this weekend to play in three old-timers' games. ``They
call us the Legends,'' said the 41-year-old Linseman, who now makes
a living in commercial real estate. ``Actually, it's a lot of fun,
especially when they put me out there with Guy Lafleur.'' Linseman
will head to Chile next week to pursue his other longtime passion:
surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Tricks of the trade
</P>
<P>
   Only 58 days to go before the NHL's March 14 trading deadline.
By then, the Bruins will have played 69 of their 82 regular-season
games . . . The read here is that the Coyotes have almost no option
but to trade Keith Tkachuk following the failed Primeau-for-Tkachuk
deal. But with the new economics evolving in the league, there
probably isn't a single team out there willing to pay Tkachuk the
$8 million-plus he has coming in 2000-01. If the money cut is that
important to the Desert Dogs, they might be best to deal Tkachuk
for a cheaper talent and agree to pick up a portion of his future
earnings . . . To avoid losing Calle Johansson to free agency last
summer, the Capitals tossed the veteran point man $6.6 million last
week _ an average of $2.1 million for three years, with a $300,000
sweetener this season that amounted to a 20 percent salary bump as
a bonus . . . Word out of Toronto is that Allison's one-year
contract extension with the Bruins will bring him $3.5 million _ a
$900,000 increase over his 1999-2000 wages. Please stop saying
they're cheap on Causeway Street. Allison had the advantage of
choosing arbitration next summer, and Mssrs. Harry Sinden and Mike
O'Connell made the prudent, fiscally-sound decision to pay Allison
right around _ perhaps slightly more than _ what an arbitrator
would dictate . . . Jay Fee, the player rep with Woolf &AMP;
Associates, earlier this season lost a gentlemen's bet with
ex-Bruin Glen Sather, boss of the Oilers. The payoff was a case of
wine. ``An Australian red,'' declared Fee, whose clients include
the Oilers' Mike Grier. ``I couldn't go with the cheap stuff _ I
mean, how would that look, right? The first time I saw Glen after
sending it, he said, `Yeah, I got that wine, and it looked pretty
good, thanks. But I had someone taste it first.' '' . . . It cost
the Leafs only $200,000 to bring Wendel Clark back for a third tour
of duty. Sure, it's short money, but Clark couldn't cut it in a
playoff run with the Wings last season and quickly was bought out
in Chicago this season. Three's either a charm or a waste of
$200,000 _ more likely the latter . . . It appears even the
spend-free Red Wings are looking at the bottom line these days.
Management unexpectedly cut off contract talks with veteran center
Igor Larionov, after narrowing in on a two-year extension. The
front office not long ago agreed to extend Steve Yzerman at $8
million a year, only to see Pat Verbeek walk in for just over $1
million and provide some true pop. With so many vets willing to
work for pennies on the dollar, GMs leaguewide are going to stop
paying premiums to older unrestricted free agents. Larionov, making
$1.7 million this season, is a special person and a special talent,
but he also turned 39 last month. Chances are, the front office,
referring to ``payroll concerns,'' figured they were about to pay
him two or three times what he could get on the open market (maybe
$1 million, plus incentives) and decided to close the checkbook . .
. Prior to returning Thursday night, ex-Bruin Garry Galley had been
out of the LA lineup since Dec. 18, recovering from his fifth
career concussion. The Kings probably won't have him back next
year, which means the 36-year-old blue liner likely will return to
suburban Ottawa and retire. He and ex-Bruin Dave Ellett recently
sold the sports bar they co-owned in Almonte, Ontario . . . The
Thrashers, here Monday afternoon, last month added Nigerian-born
Rumun Ndur to their backline. Originally a Sabres pick (No. 69,
'94), Ndur was claimed off waivers by the Rangers last season, only
to be picked off again by the Thrashers on Dec. 11 . . . Thrashers
GM Don Waddell on Dean Sylvester, the ex-BC High winger from Hanson
who popped in a hat trick shortly after arriving in Atlanta this
season: ``Dean's fine. His scoring has tailed off a little, but
I've told him to relax about that. He's a goal scorer, and that
will come. If you start beating yourself up when the puck's not
going in, it can drive you crazy.'' Headed into weekend play,
Sylvester had 10 goals and 17 points . . . Joe Sakic, finishing out
his three-year, $21 million deal in Colorado, misses unrestricted
free agency by only six days this summer (he's 31 on July 7). He's
looking for a long-term, no-trade deal from the Avalanche. Don't be
surprised if he gets wheeled, possibly to Vancouver, where he would
be a perfect fit to improve the Canucks and also groom Swedish
twins Henrik and Daniel Sedin . . . Bruins coach Pat Burns, to the
Toronto Sun last week: ``One day it will happen to (Montreal coach)
Alain Vigneault and even to (Toronto coach) Pat Quinn. The clock
starts ticking backwards on a coach from the moment you take a
job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
