<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARNING TO RAMS FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital)``The Rams'll slaughter 'em.'' -- A Southern
California talk-radio caller this week(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   To that guy I'd like to say: You're not from around here, are
you? Either that or you're a fresh-faced youngster, innocent in the
ways of the Rams and the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   You say the Rams will beat the Vikings in the NFL playoffs?
Right, and Tony Soprano is planning a big Mother's Day party.
</P>
<P>
   I write this not as a Vikings fan. I write this as someone who
grew up a Rams fan in the days when the Rams belonged to Los
Angeles -- except in the postseason, when the Vikings absolutely
owned them.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, the Dodgers were tortured by the Yankees, the
Lakers by the Celtics, the Kings by, well, everybody. And the Rams
had the Vikings. The damned Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' collision with the Vikings in an NFC division playoff
game today, even though it's taking place at the Trans World Dome
in St. Louis, brings home a million memories, all bad.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)St. Louis 7 Minnesota.'' -- Point spread favoring
the Rams(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if they're playing in a dome. Check the Weather
Channel before you bet. Where the Vikings are involved, it always
rains on the Rams. Unless it snows. Four times from 1969 to 1977
the Rams met the Vikings in the playoffs. Twice a Rams victory
would have sent them directly to the Super Bowl. Two different Rams
coaches, George Allen and Chuck Knox, led the team into those
games. Two owners, Dan Reeves and Carroll Rosenbloom. Three
quarterbacks, Roman Gabriel, James Harris and Pat Haden.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents changed, too. The Rams faced three Vikings
quarterbacks, Joe Kapp, Fran Tarkenton and Bob Lee. It didn't
matter. By the time the Vikings won their fourth consecutive
playoff meeting with the Rams, the phenomenon was openly referred
to as a jinx.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)``Speed Pulls Rams Away from Vikes'' -- Prediction
in a national newspaper this week(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   OK, the Rams are playing at home, and they're heavily favored.
Sounds l ike Minnesota has them right where it wants them. The
Vikings ``jinx'' reached its painful peak in a 1977 NFC divisional
playoff game. The Rams were 9 1/2-point favorites. They'd beaten
Tarkenton and the Vikings 35-3 in the regular season. Now Tarkenton
was injured and Lee was starting. The Rams were finally getting
them in the Coliseum, where it would be warm and dry. ``This Time
It's Advantage Rams,'' a headline declared.
</P>
<P>
   Right. It rained and the Coliseum grass turned to mud. The
Vikings took an early 7-0 lead on a short Chuck Foreman run.
Lawrence McCutcheon matched Foreman with a 100-yard day but Haden
had passes intercepted by Nate Allen and Paul Krause. It was 14-0
Vikings until the final minute. Then Haden threw a touchdown pass
to Harold Jackson and the Rams recovered an onside kick. Then Had
en threw his third interception of the day to Jeff Wright to end
any hope of a miracle. (begin ital)``Do the Vikings wear
lavendar?'' -- A talk-radio host this week, suggesting the Vikings
wear a less manly shade of purple these days(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   If memory serves, the purple found a hundred ways to win, and a
hundred guys to play hero. They came from 17-7 behind in 1969 to
win 23-20 when Kapp passed and carried them 65 yards to a go-ahead
touchdown in the fourth quarter at Bloomington. Carl Eller tackled
Gabriel in the end zone for the game-clinching safety.
</P>
<P>
   They used defense -- a Wally Hilgenberg interception in the end
zone, a Wright tackle at the Minnesota two after a 73-yard Harris
pass and Harold Jackson run -- to hold on 14-10 at Bloomington in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   They let the Rams figure out a way to lose 24-13 in 1976 on a
12-degrees-below day in Bloomington. The game was scoreless when
the Rams moved within the cold shadow of th e Vikings' end zone. On
second down, they ran a flanker reverse and Ron Jessie ruled down
short of the goal line. On third down, Haden tried to sneak for the
touchdown, but was the officials said he was stopped before his
second effort put the ball over the line. On fourth down from 6
inches, Knox sent in Tom Dempsey to try a gimme field goal. The
kick was blocked, the ball took an easy hop to Bobby Bryant, and he
ran it 90 yards for a touchdown. The Rams forever contended that
replays showed Jessie and Haden (begin ital)both(end ital) scored.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)``Rams 27, Vikings 17.'' -- Prediction in a Chicago
newspaper this week(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   I know, times change, teams change. None of those '70s Vikings
and Rams are playing today. The Vikings have moved to a dome. The
Rams have moved to the Midwest. Nevertheless: If you were a Rams
fan back then -- even if you're not a Rams fan anymore -- you
cringe at the thought of a Rams-Vikings playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   I know, too, that those Rams did finally beat the Vikings. It
happened in 1978, when the Vikings were showing their age. Tied at
halftime, the Rams broke the game open with a Jessie touchdown --
this time it counted -- and won 34-10. At least I think I know
this. It was in all the papers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure I believe the Rams beat the Vikings in the playoffs
because I didn't see it. When it finally happened, the game at the
Coliseum wasn't sold out, so it wasn't on local television. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
