<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7101 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-COACHES-     01-15 2461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-COACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHES GET CAPSIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are the Patriots on the cutting edge of football marketing for
the 21st century?
</P>
<P>
   Think of how beautifully they've created free publicity for
themselves in this Bill Belichick situation. Firing the coach or
creating a coaching controversy is becoming one of the great
marketing tools for the NFL. That's because you can't fire the
player anymore. Salary caps have made that almost impossible
because signing bonuses are pro-rated over the number of years of a
contract, so if you get rid of a player with a substantial number
of years remaining, you're charged with his salary cap number even
if he's not with you anymore.
</P>
<P>
   If you fire the coach, you just pay him off, nothing's charged
to your cap and, well, you create media interest.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, newspapers, talk shows, and TV outlets were
abuzz when Bill Parcells staged his departure from New England.
After the Super Bowl loss to the Packers, the story created huge
interest in the Patriots because Parcells had left to go to the
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the masses wanted Pete Carroll out as coach.
What did Kraft do? He fired Carroll, then almost simultaneously
(this was a closer call than the Tennessee lateral) faxed a request
to interview Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   It has been in the papers and on talk radio for two weeks. This
is free and valuable advertising for the Patriots, at a time when
they need to sell luxury boxes and those expensive club seats for
the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say, why don't they just let the Parcells-Jets
controversy go? Why not let it die?
</P>
<P>
   Why would they? This is a bonanza for the Patriots. Go out and
get Belichick, Tuna's Helper, and hope Parcells coaches again,
which would keep the New England-New York intrigue hot. People
would be very interested in the Patriots and the little soap opera
that plays out twice a year when the teams meet.
</P>
<P>
   It's great for the team. Great for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   It obviously stinks for Carroll, who is sitting home in Medfield
without a job, but Kraft will take care of him, too, paying him for
the two years left on his contract while probably urging some of
his owner friends to hire Carroll so they can pay all or part of
the remaining salary.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, whatever the Patriots have to pay Carroll is worth
the publicity the team is getting.
</P>
<P>
   Offseason interest in the Patriots now towers over offseason
interest in the Red Sox. The majority of radio hosts and callers
still talk Patriots over Red Sox despite the wonderful season the
Red Sox came off and Carlton Fisk being elected to the Hall of
Fame. The Patriots are foremost on the mind of the Boston sports
public.
</P>
<P>
   Teams will resort to these marketing manuevers more in the
future, because it's the most inexpensive major change they can
make.
</P>
<P>
   This new trend is really bad for coaches. This is why you see
few top-name college coaches coming into the NFL. The job security
is terrible.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft actually showed the patience of Job in giving Carroll
three years. Jerry Jones gave Chan Gailey two years in Dallas, Ray
Rhodes got one year in Green Bay. All coaches with 8-8 records were
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, 8-8 claimed Dennis Erickson in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That's four coaches in two years who were fired because their
teams fell to .500. From 1990-97, only five coaches with .500 marks
were fired.
</P>
<P>
   This shows the increasing impatience of NFL owners, who are
beginning to pay exorbitant amounts for franchises and need a kick
to get their business jump-started.
</P>
<P>
   Washington owner Daniel Snyder was on Norv Turner's case from
the moment he paid $800 million for the Redskins. Win now or die.
</P>
<P>
   Owners like Kraft, who have seen the value of their franchises
soar, are building or have built new stadiums that require huge
investments by the local business community for luxury boxes.
</P>
<P>
   When a team is sliding, the owner responds swiftly. The coach is
gone. That's just the way it is. The day of riding through the hard
times as you build a program is over. The players can complain all
they want about the lack of continuity from year to year, but they
just have to adapt. Drew Bledsoe will have to learn yet another
offensive system next year. Sorry, Drew. Nobody is exempt. Even
with the great reputation Jimmy Johnson has, there has been talk
about his firing or resignation because he hasn't gotten the
Dolphins as far as many thought they should have come since
Johnson's tenure began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   These are the things that prosperity brings.
</P>
<P>
   Money is a good thing for everyone, and it has come mainly from
the $17.6 billion TV deal Kraft helped put together.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of money to go around, but coaches have
incredible pressure on them because the trend is to sign 5-7
players to huge contracts, then split the rest up among the
remaining 45 or 46 men on the roster. The mid-range players _ the
Todd Collins-Willie Clay-Sam Gash types _ are getting priced off
teams in favor of lower-priced players who can limit a team's
spirit and depth.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ink even dried on the TV contract, the players,
rightly so, were holding out their hands for their share. The
owners instituted tight salary caps to limit spending. But now they
have done what NBA teams have done: found ways around it. Now they
issue massive, pro-rated signing bonuses that enable them to fiddle
with the cap. The Patriots, for instance, paid out $75.2 million
last year, which is about $18 million over the salary cap. This
enables them to sign their top free agents, but when they want to
get rid of a player who is not producing, they can't, because the
hit on the cap would be so great. Though NFL player contracts
aren't technically guaranteed, they in essence become so.
</P>
<P>
   The cap is the single most compelling issue in the NFL. It has
become a coach-killer.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, for instance, have $35.17 million tied up in seven
players against next year's salary cap, which will rise to about
$62 million from $57.2 million. That's more than half the payroll.
The other 46 players will split $26 million. Bledsoe's cap number
is $8.66 million, followed by Willie McGinest's $5.7 million, Bruce
Armstrong's $5.06 million, Ted Johnson's $5 million, Ty Law's $4
million, Ben Coates's $3.5 million, and Chris Slade's $3.25
million. Bledsoe's deal will likely be redone to lower his number,
but that by itself won't clear room for potential new megabuck
deals for Lawyer Milloy, Troy Brown, or Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the Patriots' big seven had healthy, productive
years, Johnson and Law, for example, missed significant portions of
the season, leaving Carroll with depth problems.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the big money players are now making: This season,
there were 514 players who made at least $1 million and 266 players
who made at least $2 million. Since 1994, the number of players who
make $1 million has doubled. There has been a 50 percent increase
in that number since 1997, when there were 340 millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have 21 of those players, tying Atlanta and
Carolina for the most.
</P>
<P>
   Of the league's 514 millionaires, 104 are offensive linemen, the
most at any position. The Patriots have five on an average to
below-average line.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend is teams trying to find themselves a nondrafted
free agent or two or three, as the Patriots did with Kato Serwanga.
Of the 1,643 players who played in the league this season, 393 were
nondrafted free agents; 249 were first-round picks, 218 were
second-round picks, and 197 were third-round picks. This shows that
teams are filling out rosters with undrafted or cheap players. Some
teams get lucky with such players, but most don't. When a coach has
to play these inexperienced players, there's a dropoff in quality
that eventually is reflected in the team's final record.
</P>
<P>
   Then, fans become restless, the coach is fired, and new hope
springs eternal _ until the new coach finds that the salary cap
will kill him, too.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions. Pittsburgh has had Bill Cowher since 1992.
Ditto Dennis Green in Minnesota. The Oilers/Titans have stuck with
Jeff Fischer and the Redskins with Norv Turner since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But patience is no longer a great virtue of NFL owners. And now
the Patriots have demonstrated that, in the immortal words of Globe
baseball writer Larry Whiteside, ``In confusion, there is profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nose smells of trouble
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot who may benefit most from a coaching change is Chad
Eaton. Despite Eaton's loyalty to Carroll, the team's postseason
evaluations and projections had him slated as a backup next year
unless he picked up his level of play. The Patriots felt Eaton's
play dropped because he wasn't fighting for a starting job, as he
had been the previous season with former nose tackle Mark Wheeler.
Toward the end of the season, the Patriots had Henry Thomas playing
a lot in Eaton's nose position. The coaching staff also was
concerned that Eaton was spending too much time on radio shows _
especially after a subpar performance by him or the team _ and
spoke to him about it . . . Clay has one piece of advice for his
good friend Milloy, who may consider offers from other teams:
``Life isn't always better someplace else.'' Clay called his
experience with the 3-13 Saints ``the worst of my NFL career.''
Clay spoke of complete chaos on the team and indicated that Mike
Ditka did not live up to the expectations he had of him. Clay also
had a beef with the Saints over compensation. He needed 20 plays in
the final game to kick in a $400,000 bonus; he got five plays. Clay
made the mistake of signing with the first team that called after
he was cut by the Patriots, but he won't make that mistake again.
``You've got to understand what you're getting into,'' he said.
``You have to do the research. No matter how much they pay you, if
you're in a bad situation, you're going to be miserable.'' . . . If
the current scouting and personnel staff remains in New England, a
top priority will be linemen on both sides of the ball. The
Patriots would like a big interior lineman on defense, another pass
rusher, and a young tackle or guard on offense. The Patriots were
pleased with the performance of veteran Ferric Collons and Chris
Sullivan at the end of the season, and with Brandon Mitchell's
emergence. The team has leaked reports that Steve Israel won't be
back, but Serwanga's stock rose significantly with two strong games
at the end of the season. And if they lose Milloy to free agency,
don't be surprised to see Tony George at strong safety and Tebucky
Jones at free safety next season . . . Former Boston College coach
Jack Bicknell hasn't gotten a sniff in the NFL, despite his
excellent records at BC and for eight years with Barcelona in NFL
Europe. One aspect of coaching quarterbacks he's going to get back
to this winter is working on play-action fakes, which Peyton
Manning has turned into an art form. ``It's one of those basics
that you teach, but maybe you don't spend as much time on it as you
should,'' said Bicknell. ``When you watch Manning and how well he
does it and how he can sell the run, it just makes you excited
about going back to the practice field and perfecting this with
your own guys.'' . . . It hit Rod Rutledge pretty hard when he
found out that Charlotte Hornets forward Bobby Phills had died in
an auto accident while racing against teammate David Wesley last
week. The Patriots tight end was involved in a similar incident
last year but is alive to talk about it. ``I guess I'm blessed,''
said Rutledge from his home in Birmingham, Ala. ``When you hear
things like that, you realize how lucky you are to be alive. That
could have been me.'' Back in September, just three days before the
first game of the 1999 season, Rutledge was driving in excess of 90
miles per hour on I-95, racing with Coates. Rutledge lost control
of his car and veered into a rest area, smashing into two
tractor-trailer trucks. He walked away from the accident with only
scratches. ``I realize now what could have happened,'' said
Rutledge. ``A tragedy like this just hits it home harder.'' As part
of his sentence for operating to endanger, Rutledge has done
community service work for the Brains at Risk organization, which
helps trauma victims. ``At first I didn't think it was going to be
something I wanted to do, even though I was required to do it,'' he
said. ``Now it's become more like something I look forward to
doing. I have a wife and kids, and when I think about the fact that
Bobby has left a wife and young kids . . . wow. I just feel like I
can thank God for the chance to live and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Tug-of-Warrick
</P>
<P>
   Even though Florida receiver Peter Warrick has signed with agent
Michael George's Marquis Group in New York, other agents are still
trying to steal Warrick away. The agent business has become
cutthroat, and look for the NFL Players Association to lean on more
agents who break the rules. Once a player signs with an agent,
others are not supposed to speak to him or attempt to lure him
away. But it happens often . . . Irving Fryar is having so much fun
in Washington that he may want to return next season. Let's see if
the feeling is mutual . . . Where does Jefferson fit in the free
agent market? Possible parallels are Darnay Scott of the Bengals,
who signed a four-year, $12 million deal, with a $3.5 million
signing bonus, last season; Denver's Rod Smith, who signed a
five-year, $11 million deal, with a $2 million signing bonus;
Detroit's Johnnie Morton, who was in the four-year, $11 million
range, with a $3.5 million bonus; and Philadelphia's Charles
Johnson, with a five-year, $13 million deal, with a $2 million
bonus . . . If Belichick comes to New England, one player who may
benefit is Fall River's Marc Megna, who was activated toward the
end of the season. Megna was in the Jets' training camp last summer
and Belichick took a liking to him. But the Jets had other needs
and couldn't find room for him on the practice squad . . . The
Bills projected Doug Flutie and Rob Johnson to play together for at
least two years of Flutie's four-year, $22 million deal. Flutie is
scheduled to be paid $3 million next season. If he plays through
the third year of the deal, he doesn't have to give back any of the
$7 million signing bonus, a deal that was structured by former
agent and current Patriots executive Jack Mula. The Bills are
hoping to create a two-quarterback system in which the hot man
plays . . . Mark Feigenbaum of Andover has been chosen the
``ultimate Patriots fan'' by the Visa Hall of Fans. He will be
honored at the Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio, Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
