<HEADER>
A7103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-USSOCCER-IRAN-BOS     01-15 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCER-IRAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT A POLITICAL ARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The United States national team might feel
like it is under siege against the Islamic Republic of Iran at the
Rose Bowl Sunday. Most of the expected 55,000 crowd will be from
the Iranian community, which has renamed this area Tehrangeles.
</P>
<P>
   But once the match begins, the US will be the team on the
attack. Iran, as it did in a 2-1 victory over the US in Lyon during
the France '98 World Cup, likely will retreat into defense and
launch counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a good style of play and they are confident with
it,'' US coach Bruce Arena said. ``It's been very effective. They
are a good defensive team and they are going to be difficult to
break down. They are experienced in midfield and they are better in
goal than they were in '98.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena has relaunched the national team after replacing Steve
Sampson following a disastrous World Cup performance. The US is
8-4-3 under Arena, and only four players from the Lyon loss _
Frankie Hejduk, Cobi Jones, Claudio Reyna, and Brian McBride _
likely will be in the starting lineup. The rest of the team had not
been determined, though goalkeeper Brad Friedel and midfielder Tony
Sanneh were likely to start and the Revolution's John Harkes was
slated to enter as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has lost to Mexico (2-1) in Oakland and defeated Ecuador
(2-1) in Los Angeles in the last week. The team is led by
Germany-based strikers Ali Daei and Khodadad Azizi, and will have
veterans such as its goal-scorers from Lyon, Hamid Estili and Mehdi
Mahdavikia, MetroStars defender Mohammad Khakpour, and goalkeeper
Hadi Tabatabei.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what to expect, Arena said: ``We'll find out. It's
important we play well and get a positive result. But the world
won't be over if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena has injected spirit and confidence into a US team that was
in a mutinous mood after France. He has rehabilitated Harkes and
Marcelo Balboa and turned Chris Armas, Robin Fraser, and Eddie
Lewis into high-profile players, though Fraser will miss this match
with a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   Arena has brought a hawklike attacking attitude to the team, but
also has kept the defense organized, largely through the deployment
of Armas in midfield and strong central defending. But for the US
to transcend its status as a persistent, physical but naive
opponent, the spark will have to come from midfield. The US has yet
to discover high-level creative midfielders who can take the game
to another level, and Arena cannot be expected to alchemically
produce such a player.
</P>
<P>
   So, the US will depend on Reyna, who has proven himself with
competitive clubs in Europe (Wolfsburg, Glasgow Rangers) but has
yet to make his mark on the national team. Reyna was especially
disappointing during the '98 World Cup as the US converted only one
goal in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``'98 is in the past,'' Arena said. ``If we used that as a
measure, we wouldn't have any players at all. We've played a lot of
games without Claudio and done all right.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first of several matches for the US against nations
that recently have been marginalized, pariah, or considered
outright ``enemies of the state.'' The US will meet Russia in
Moscow in April, play host to South Africa in June, and visit Cuba
in July.
</P>
<P>
   But Arena is being pragmatic. The US also will visit Chile Jan.
29 in preparation for the Gold Cup Feb. 12-27. Then, it will play
host to Tunisia in Birmingham, Ala., March 12. World Cup 2002
qualifying will begin in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The romance is over,'' Arena said. ``Forget about the results
in '99, the objective now is to qualify for 2002.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
