u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-JORDAN-B     01-15 1836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS JORDAN READY TO BITE THIS BULLET? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good luck, Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan is about to find out what many before him have
discovered. It's different when you're not on the court.
</P>
<P>
   If the reports are true, and Jordan will take over the
basketball business for the notoriously underachieving Washington
Wizards, he'll have his hands full. The Wizards have a gigantic
payroll dominated by a 30-something backcourt that hasn't clicked
and a frontcourt anchored by arguably the most overpaid player in
the game, no small feat in the petrodollar life of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Jordan will have one distinction no other GM has:
He'll be happy to take a call from David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to see Mike doing the detail work, like working the
phones or sneaking into a gym to see a prospect. He's never been
one of those guys; his name always has been enough. That may work
with restaurants, and it may work in getting some equity in the
franchise. But it won't work in rebuilding the Wizards, who are on
the hook next year for more than $52 million in player salaries and
more than $54 million the year after that. (Eight players divide
that mother lode. Juwan Howard will make $18.75 million next season
and more than $20 million the next. Meanwhile, both Rod Strickland
and Mitch Richmond are ``base-year'' guys, making them hard to
move.)
</P>
<P>
   Washington managed to go through an entire decade, the 1990s,
without winning a playoff game. Only one other non-Canadian team
can make that claim: Dallas. (Milwaukee won one game in the 1990
playoffs.) Washington appeared in only one playoff series in the
decade, sneaking in as the No. 8 team in 1997 and then getting
swept by Jordan's Bulls. It has not won a playoff series since
1982, and that was a bogus best-of-three affair. You have to go
back to 1979 _ 21 years ago _ to find an occasion when the
franchise last won any kind of meaningful playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   They've had the same owner for decades, a well-intentioned,
loyal man named Abe Pollin. He and Jordan had a few words during
last season's lockout when Jordan had the temerity to suggest that
Pollin sell the Wizards if he can't make a go of it. That turned
out to be the first wise thing Jordan said to Pollin.
</P>
<P>
   Pollin has stuck with Wes Unseld in more than one management
role despite pretty convincing evidence that the Hall of Famer has
not done the job. Unseld coached the team for 6 1/2 seasons, not
one of which ended with a winning record. In his last three years,
Unseld's teams won 25, 22, and 24 games. For that achievement, he
was promoted to general manager. Since then, he has traded Chris
Webber and Rasheed Wallace and kept Howard.
</P>
<P>
   For a competitive, driven, used-to-having-his-way guy like Mike,
it's going to be an eye-opening experience. Can you wait to see him
try to stare down an agent? He always was in control on the court.
He is about to find out that, despite his retirement, the tail
still wags the dog in the NBA. His magnetism, charm, and smarts can
go only so far.
</P>
<P>
   We've already seen once that Jordan is not afraid to fail. His
baseball experience showed a distinctly human side unknown to those
who saw him strictly as a basketball player. And, let's not forget,
he always saw himself as a quasi-GM in Chicago, where his public
personnel preferences were, you might say, suspect. He vehemently
opposed the Charles Oakley-Bill Cartwright trade. He wanted Scottie
Pippen out more than once. Generally, if a player had an Atlantic
Coast Conference pedigree, or had Falk as his agent, then Jordan
liked him.
</P>
<P>
   Washington presents a monumental challenge. If all the details
can be worked out _ we have to assume Jordan also will get a piece
of the team, a la Pat Riley _ and Jordan gets the power he needs,
then he should start the rebuilding process quickly: with a
flamethrower.
</P>
<P>
   No better in Boston
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the subject of struggling teams, we would be
remiss not to at least note our local five. We're now into Year 3
of the Rick Pitino Era, and can you honestly say you see any sign
of improvement? Or hope? You could even argue that there's been a
regression; they at least played hard in the first year. Pitino won
36 games that year. He won the equivalent of about 36 last year.
He's on track to win about 36 this year, although he said it's too
soon to make an assessment. He's made countless trades and other
moves and the team still is struggling. This can't be what he had
in mind. It certainly can't be what Paul Gaston had in mind.
Interest in the team is at an all-time low, as evidenced by the
paltry crowds at the FleetCenter and the pitiful television
numbers. Pitino, as undisputed hoop el jefe, is on the hook for all
of this. Generally, when a team isn't performing as well as people
think it should, you can look at a couple of main reasons: The
players have been overrated or the coach's message isn't getting
across. In either case, it's Pitino's problem. Those are his
players. Yes, they're young. But he brought them here. If they're
not responding, that's his problem as well, because it doesn't
matter how much talent, or purported talent, you have, or how well
you can coach; if the players aren't listening, you get nowhere.
Pitino insists he isn't going anywhere. ``I'm here for 10 years _
six years of coaching and four more as president,'' he said.
``Where am I going to go? I moved my family here. I love the
area.'' Where would he go? College? Been there, done that. And he
has said he hates the state of college basketball. If he were to
leave, it would run counter to his track record. Needless to say,
if he were to be fired, that would run counter to Gaston's track
record.
</P>
<P>
   Can't judge book by cover
</P>
<P>
   One of the many moves Pitino made was to pave the way for Dino
Radja to head overseas. (Looking back, that may have been Rick's
best moment.) Well, Radja has just published his autobiography in
Croatia, and the cover of the book shows Dino in a Celtics uniform
. . . Going into weekend games with Denver and Vancouver, the Heat
expected Tim Hardaway to make his long-awaited return to the
lineup. Though Hardaway has been out almost two months with a sore
knee, Miami has managed not only to stay afloat but to stay atop
the Atlantic Division. In the process, Riley found a serviceable
backup in rookie Anthony Carter . . . The Grizzlies may have
stormed through the East at a 4-1 clip, but, as Dennis Scott
pointed out, that shouldn't be cause for a parade. ``I remember
when we were 3-3 and guys were running around all over the place.
We were saying, `Whoa.' Let's see us win 14 out of 15, something
the good teams do. If we do that, then the arena will be packed,
there'll be more attention, more media people, and everything will
fall into place.'' Scott played for ex-Grizzlies coach Brian Hill
in Orlando and Vancouver. What did he think of the coaching change?
``In Orlando, we had horses,'' Scott said. ``It was the same system
there as we had here. But Country (Bryant Reeves) isn't Shaq. And
Mike (Bibby) is different from Penny (Hardaway). Maybe (Hill) could
have tweaked it a little bit, I don't know.'' . . . Speaking of
Penny, it has not been lost on a lot of people that the coach he
now has, Scott Skiles, was the man he supplanted in Orlando. Skiles
didn't take it well then. He also was enormously popular. ``Scott
was absolutely the hero of this town,'' said Magic executive Pat
Williams. ``And Scott wasn't going to give up anything. In Scott's
mind, he had a lot of basketball left in him. But he also handled
it very well. He never sulked. He never complained, although I'm
sure it was hard on him. But he could also see the handwriting on
the wall. But this is a guy who never wanted to come out of a game,
let alone not play. The only guy I've seen like that in all my
years was Jerry Sloan for sheer competitiveness, intensity, never
backing down to anybody. When Scott got the Suns job, (owner) Jerry
Colangelo said the team was going to become a little more snarly.
How snarly is he? Every night he comes home, he flosses the
piranha.'' Williams said projecting Skiles as Hardaway's coach
would have been tough, and it's further complicated by Hardaway's
(foot) injury: ``Scott was like Ty Cobb. He'd spit tobacco juice on
his foot and then say, `Let's play two.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Room to maneuver
</P>
<P>
   As we approach February and the trading deadline, two teams _
Chicago and the Clippers _ will be fielding a lot of calls. They
are the only ones with any kind of cap room for a three-team deal.
The Bulls are about $6 million under the cap after they gave Matt
Maloney a one-year deal in the $600,000 range. The Clippers are
almost $8 million under. But the team to watch is Orlando, listed
as $7 million over the cap, mainly because it is paying money to 28
players. On the books are the likes of Louis Bullock ($10,000),
Yinka Dare ($1.8 million), Terry Davis ($1.9 million), Armen
Gilliam ($3.7 million), and Harvey Grant ($1.2 million). But when
July 1 comes around, the Magic will have a ton of money to spend on
free agents. They also could have three lottery picks in next
June's draft, as they have their own pick, Golden State's, and
Denver's . . . Pitino mentioned that the Celtics considered signing
Maloney last fall, but decided it was not smart because Maloney's
agent wanted Boston to use its $1.1 million exception to do so.
Well, that's not quite how agent Keith Glass remembers it. ``I
never asked for the exception,'' he said. ``I never asked for
anything. I talked to Miami for two months and never got around to
money. Matt already had $17 million in hand, so I wanted to see
where there was interest and where he would have a chance to play.
But if you're not willing to use the exception, is he a priority?''
Celtics GM Chris Wallace said, based on his discussions with Glass,
he felt the agent was headed toward asking for the exception.
``That's tying up an option you have which you may want to use in
the summer,'' Wallace said. (The exception is available once every
two years.) Said Glass, ``I know Rick does it for the love of the
game. Sometimes, I have to do it for the money.'' . . . John
Calipari thinks he knows one reason why Keith Van Horn is
struggling: ``He was really good with Sam (Cassell). A lot of guys
didn't like Sam because he was outspoken and things like that.
Well, Keith loved him because he got him the ball.'' . . .
Congratulations to former University of Massachusetts center Lari
Ketner, who will be playing in the CBA's Rookie All-Star game
Tuesday in Sioux Falls. Ketner started out the year with the Bulls,
then was released and found work with the Fort Wayne Fury. He was
averaging 11.9 points and 6.1 rebounds a game . . . Condolences to
agent Frank Catapano and his family. Catapano's wife, Terry, died
this past week after a tough battle with cancer. She was 55.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
