<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DEBATE-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCERPTS FROM REPUBLICAN DEBATE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from an exchange about taxes by Sen. John
McCain of Arizona and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas during the
Republican presidential debate on Saturday in Johnston, Iowa, as
recorded by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH. During the last Iowa debate we had a disagreement over
ethanol. I support the tax credit on ethanol, you don't. As part of
your plan to pay for your tax cuts, you say we ought to eliminate
what's called employer-provided benefits to workers. These are
benefits where transportation or meals or continuing education is
given to a worker tax-free. That's $40 billion of your $170 billion
tax-reduction plan. __
</P>
<P>
   My question to you is, why would you say to a single mom who's
working, who's getting educated, that she would have to pay taxes
on those benefits? If you get rid of the employer-related benefits
the workers are going to have to pay taxes. It's a $40 billion tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN: Well, the first thing that I'd say to the single mom is
that I've got a tax cut for you and Governor Bush doesn't. That's
the first answer.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: That's not true.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN: Yes, it is. But let's talk about the real issue here.
The real issue is, my friends, is we've got a surplus. And for the
first time since Dwight David Eisenhower, we got a surplus and the
question is, what do you want to do with it? I want to give it to
low- and middle-income Americans as a tax cut. I want to give them
the benefits from this that they need that lower- and middle-income
Americans need.
</P>
<P>
   But I also think we got a ticking time bomb out there called
Social Security. That has got to be fixed. We've got a national
debt of $5.6 trillion that we need to pay for because we're laying
that debt on young Americans. We need to pay down that debt.
Governor Bush's plan has not one penny for Social Security, not one
penny for Medicare and not one penny for paying down the national
debt. And when you run ads saying you're going to take care of
Social Security, my friend, that's all hat and no cattle.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: _ that's _ that's _ that's cute, but ...
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN: You know, they're always cutest when they're true.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It's not true.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN: Yeah, it is. It truthfully is.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I've got two trillion set aside for Social Security ... My
question to you is, and we can talk about taxes, I hope.
Everybody's got an interesting idea on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN: I thought that's what we were talking about.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: My _ my _ no, we're talking about why would you _ why
would you have a plan that, in essence, raises taxes on working
people by $40 billion? Why would you support a plan that caused _
why would you take away benefits that people then have to pay tax
on _ taxes _ taxes on education and transportation and meals?
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN: I'm giving them a huge tax cut and that is a fact and
the _ and the reality is that your tax plan has 36 percent of it
going to the richest 1 percent in America. I don't do that. I think
that we ought to give a tax relief to the people that need it the
most.
</P>
<P>
   But I also think the best thing I can do for that woman you're
talking about is save her Social Security. Two trillion dollars is
in the Social Security trust fund. You know that. Let's not do the
Texas two-step here. It needs five to seven trillion dollars more
and we've got to do it soon so that they can invest their _ their
retirement into savings and investments of their choice. _ So we
can save the system.
</P>
<P>
   A transcript of the debate is available from The New York Times
on the Web: www.nytimes.com/politics
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
