</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS EMBARRASS DOLPHINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The night before the game, Jimmy Johnson
gathered his Miami Dolphins in a meeting room at a nearby hotel and
gave them what will most likely be the last motivational speech of
his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, Johnson called five huge linemen to the front of the
room and challenged them to win their individual battles, telling
them that if they did, his team would beat the Jaguars in their
playoff game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson made one mistake: He challenged the wrong guys. He
should have put his defensive backfield on the spot, because when
the game arrived, they were the most guilty parties in Miami's
crushing 62-7 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said after the game that he was guilty of overcoaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to prepare them too much,'' he said. ``I take the
blame for this one. I should have pulled back after the long trip
to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious from the start we were dead-legged. That's one
reason why we couldn't bring our feet, go through the tackles, or
couldn't run. I thought we had good practices, but unfortunately we
left it on the practice field.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's rout will be remembered as a record-setting
performance by the Jaguars and, in all probability, as the last
game for two future Hall of Famers, Johnson and Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Some think Johnson will resign as head coach of the Dolphins as
early as Sunday afternoon. Marino's closest friends expect him,
too, to finally give up on his career, which will put him in the
books as the finest passer in the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wait to see as time goes on what the circumstances are
with the Dolphins, myself, and how I feel,'' said Marino. ``I still
think like I can win games in this league. I've proven that and
will continue to do that. So we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a game here Saturday; it was more like an upscale
scrimmage for the well-rested Jaguars. They dominated from start to
finish, scoring the first six times they touched the ball to build
to a 41-0 lead with 1:51 left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami secondary, supposedly one of the team's strengths, was
torn apart by land and through the air.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half alone, Jacksonville ran up 313 total yards,
while Miami responded with only 92 yards and 7 points.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville running back Fred Taylor humbled the Miami
secondary. In the first period, with his team ahead, 10-0, Taylor
ran at right end with no help and with four defenders in his way.
He beat them all on his own, racing 90 yards for a touchdown, the
longest scoring run in NFL playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins were out of it after that. It took Marino 20
minutes to complete his first pass, and, after one series, he sat
out the rest of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Johnson told me at the half that he was going to put
Damon (Huard) in,'' said Marino. ``I asked him for another shot,
and it didn't go so well.''
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart, Mark Brunell, hobbling on braced knees, also
didn't play the second half, but for different reasons. Coach Tom
Coughlin pulled him out three minutes into the second quarter to
save him for next week's AFC Championship Game here. ``Our first
drive was important,'' said Brunell, who completed 5 of 9 passes
for 105 yards and two touchdowns. ``We haven't been starting games
well. We talked about it all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs felt great today. I felt confident I wouldn't have a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino just doesn't have it anymore. On his first pass, with his
team trailing, 7-0, he threw a floater that Aaron Beasley
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   After Taylor's 90-yard run, Marino got hit and fumbled just 25
seconds later. Tony Brackens, who caused the turnover, pounced on
the ball and, after some cajoling from teammates when they realized
the play wasn't over, ran 16 yards for a touchdown to make it 24-0.
</P>
<P>
   The game was out of control. The Dolphins couldn't do anything
right.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 seconds into the second quarter, Miami blitzed but the
Jaguars had the perfect response. Taylor checked through the line
of scrimmage, took a little flip pass from Brunell, and danced 39
yards for a touchdown, embarrassing three defensive backs in the
final 15 yards as they all missed him with feeble tackling
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Johnson became animated on the sideline, waving
his arms in a tackling motion, trying to motivate his troops. They
didn't respond.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin had preached to his players that they needed to make
big plays to beat Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 30 minutes, aside from Taylor's heroics, Jimmy
Smith caught a pass for 41 yards to set up the first touchdown, the
special teams blocked a punt, and the defense collected five of
their seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very crisp,'' said Coughlin. ``A lot of good things
happened to us. The reason that came about is that we had a good
week on the practice field. Our preparation was good. We got some
things done with X's and O's, and our players made some great
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino had 11 completions in 25 throws for 95 yards and a
touchdowns, but he was zero for his first 10, and eight of his
completions came on his final drive of the first half. If this is
the way it is to end, then his last important throw was a 20-yard
touchdown to Oronde Gadsden with time running out in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   There was some question before the game about the legitimacy of
the Jaguars as the No. 1 seed in the AFC; they ran up a 14-2 record
but had one of the league's easiest schedules.
</P>
<P>
   However, after this powerful performance on both sides on the
ball, there is little doubt that they will be favored next Sunday
when they play for a chance to go to the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
