<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-AUSSIEOPE     01-15 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-AUSSIEOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSSIES WHET APPETITE, HOPE TO END DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ The painted patriots of the general-admission pews
are ready to party again as the first summer sunshine of a new
century, and a hailstorm of tennis balls, descend in a golden glow
on the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   No major championship is as much fun as the Aussie, where
sitting space is more readily available and cheaper than at the
other three (French, Wimbledon, US Open), and young hordes fleeing
European winter show up in warpaint to boisterously cheer their
compatriots. Swedes in blue and yellow faces, Germans in red and
black, Dutch in orange, to cite the largest regiments, are clearing
their throats to ``barrack,'' as Aussies put it, with abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the natives at Melbourne Park, predominating in green
and gold makeup, may be the most passionate during the fortnight
that commences Monday, their passion born of staggering deprivation
for a people so rich in championship history. Not for 24 years has
a homeboy won the title, Mark Edmondson, or a sheila, Chris O'Neil,
two years later in 1978. As the worst dry spell for the Down
Underdwellers in their 95-year-old tourney, it brings to mind the
saddest of all Australian songs: Slim Dusty's country dirge, ``The
Pub With No Beer.''
</P>
<P>
   And this time it won't be the dashing ex-US Open champ Patrick
Rafter, everybody's choice _ from wailing teenage girls to their
more subdued parents _ to end the big thirst and set off malten
toasts in every pub across the continent. Rafter's
surgically-carpentered right shoulder will permit him no more
exertion than doubles alongside Wayne Arthurs. That bit ``only as
long as I don't feel it tightening up.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Rafter is mourned, and the female decline deplored,
there is definite hope in the forms of the guys who won the Davis
Cup: the feisty 18-year-old Lleyton Hewitt, and a quiet latter-day
Adonis with a Greek bloodline, 6-foot-4-inch thunderbolt hurler
Mark Philippoussis. Philippoussis stirred this town with
anticipation Friday by beating a tourist named Pete Sampras, 7-6,
7-6. It was only an exhibition at Kooyong, former home of the Open,
but it rekindled memories of the last Wimbledon when Philippoussis
seemed on his way to jolting champion Sampras, only to crumble and
surrender in the second set as a knee gave out.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis, frequently clueless, goes in and out with his
public. He thought he could pull a Sampras two years ago by
shunning Davis Cup. In this country that plays about as well as
peddling military secrets or kicking koalas. The national response
was so negative that he knew he'd have to win the Cup in '99 (which
he did, with two singles victories in the 3-2 final over France) to
avoid deportation.
</P>
<P>
   All's forgiven was the ecstatic turnaround reaction _ until the
other day when he said he might pass on the Cup opener next month
against Switzerland. Another firestorm. He quickly ran a reverse,
pleading misquotation, and the blaze went out. But if he goes all
the way through seven rounds to the trophy presentation,
Philippoussis might be a candidate for posthumous taxidermy to
stand beside the fabled Aussie race horse, Phar Lap, in the
Melbourne Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, he's in the minefield, the top half of the draw that
also contains the co-favorites, world Nos. 1 and 3 at the close of
1999, Andre Agassi and Sampras, plus an ex-Wimbledon victor,
Richard Krajicek. That's why the old champ, Davis Cup captain John
Newcombe, likes the chances of unseeded Hewitt at the other end,
where the most formidable name belongs to No. 2, the defending
champion but often indifferent Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago Kafelnikov portrayed himself as the stern
schoolmaster who would ``give a lesson'' to the ``unimpressive''
novice Hewitt _ only to be impressively caned by the kid, clinching
the Davis Cup semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall Hewitt in Boston last July impersonating a
whirlwind at Longwood. Called ``the fastest man in the game'' by
Davis Cup coach Tony Roche, he made Todd Martin resemble a
Commonwealth Avenue statue in sprinting to the leadoff victory that
virtually settled the quarterfinal decision over the US.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, like Philippoussis, will not be getting an honorary
degree in public relations from Boston University or anybody else
soon. Recently, while winning the ATP Tour tourney in Adelaide, his
hometown no less, he chastised the customers as ``stupid'' for the
sin of also applauding his outgunned foes. It was suggested by many
that his mother wash his mouth out with soap. But he's on a
squeaky-clean 10-0 toot for 2000, having added the Sydney title
Saturday, and thus stands as current No. 1 on the planet according
to the newly installed ATP ranking system. This is based on a
season-long race rather than a cumulative ranking calculated weekly
on results of the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, who specialized in charming crowds, undoubtedly is
offering a PR seminar or two, while delighting in his protege's
promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lleyton just goes all out in every direction,'' Newc says. ``I
wouldn't be surprised if he went all the way here. We know the
ceilings of Sampras, Agassi, and the other big guns. But Lleyton
hasn't come close to his yet. It's getting higher all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for another dynamite 18-year-old, Serena Williams,
the US Open champ who has arrived alone. No Venus, whose excuse is
tendinitis of the right wrist. Who knows with those mysterious and
wondrous movers, the Sisters Sledgehammer? Does the master plan of
father Richard Williams call for a Serena solo this time, as Venus
performed at Wimbledon?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the presence of Wimbledon ruler Lindsay Davenport
along with Serena and the triumvirate of Agassi, Sampras, and
Martin give the far-far-from home Americans an excellent shot at a
double, last achieved in 1982 by Chris Evert and freshly
naturalized, South African-born Johan Kriek.
</P>
<P>
   But in this summer of their great content, Aussies are flexing
the muscles of empire, commanding the globe in the international
games that mean the most to them. They won World Cups in cricket
and rugby as well as the Davis Cup. Those were team diversions. Now
in a land the inhabitants call ``Oz'' they're looking for a wizard
with racket to bust their own championship drought, someone to
restore the glory days of Rod Laver, the double Grand Slammer for
whom the principal stadium will be named Sunday. Someone to bring
widest smiles to those green-and-gold faces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-BOS     01-15 2251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-WARNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER ARRIVES AT TOP SHELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL MADDEN 
c.2000 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EARTH CITY, Mo. _ Only three times in its history has the Des
Moines Register devoted a special section to a sports figure. One
was for the Cubs' Sammy Sosa, one was for the Cardinals' Mark
McGwire, and this weekend's _ the third _ was for Kurt Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The six pages were well done, but it was the sixth and final
page that was fascinating. A full-page advertisement. An
advertisement for Hy-Vee supermarkets, a chain throughout Iowa and
southern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Hy-Vee to MVP,'' it read, promoting itself as well as
``Warner's Crunch Time Frosted Flakes'' ($2.99 for a 20-ounce box).
The full name of the athlete is nowhere mentioned in the
advertisement; it doesn't have to be, for Kurt Warner is now Iowa's
favorite son. Bill Bradley, Al Gore, George Bush, and all the other
politicos traipsing around Iowa these days must play second fiddle
until the uplifting saga of Kurt Warner is done. Whenever that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Making of an MVP,'' the ad went on, detailing how Kurt
Warner _ somehow, some way _ got to the top. And then Hy-Vee listed
the itinerary of Warner's trip: ``Cedar Rapids Regis High School,
University of Northern Iowa, Cedar Falls Hy-Vee, Iowa
Barnstormers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cedar Falls Hy-Vee''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Stocking shelves for $5.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   From there to starting quarterback for the St. Louis Rams, who
face the Minnesota Vikings in the playoffs Sunday. Not to mention
MVP of the NFL, even if he is paid only the NFL's minimum salary,
$254,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But just before that critical stop at Hy-Vee, Kurt Warner had
made a detour to Green Bay. Fresh out of Northern Iowa, where he
was part of a team that lost to Boston University in the NCAA
Division 1-AA playoffs at Nickerson Field in 1993, Warner had
signed a training camp contract with the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few clubs were interested in me, but Green Bay said they
were going to bring only three quarterbacks to camp,'' said Warner.
``So I figured that was my best opportunity. Other teams were
bringing in three or four rookie quarterbacks, so I figured this
might be my best opportunity to make a football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Three quarterbacks?
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre. Mark Brunell (now with Jacksonville). And Ty
Detmer, who just happened to be a Heisman Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was too young and innocent to know that the fourth QB in
an NFL camp is little more than fodder, needed only to make sure
the receivers get enough passes to catch during the endless drills.
Coaches don't look at the fourth QB; they're looking at the
receivers to whom the fourth QB is throwing. So it might be trite
to note that former Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren missed a good
one; Holmgren probably wasn't looking. For sure, with Favre and
Brunell around, Holmgren had no reason to look.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, Warner was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little bit discouraged, more so because I didn't get
an opportunity than I didn't make it in Green Bay,'' said Warner.
``I knew the guys I was competing against were really good and I
was hoping to get an opportunity to play and show people I could
play at that level. But I also gained a lot of confidence that I
could compete against those three guys and really feel I stacked up
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Now what? Middle of the summer. No job. What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Back to Iowa. Back to Cedar Falls. And Hy-Vee's. Stocking
shelves. At 2 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew at the time it wasn't going to be a long-term
commitment _ I mean, I wasn't going to be stocking shelves the rest
of my life,'' said Warner. ``I knew I was going to be playing
football. But I knew I had to take care of my family to get through
that situation at that critical time. I was sure I was going to be
playing football somewhere. But I was stocking shelves for $5.50 an
hour.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the fiction business would dare write this tale. Too
preposterous. Even Hollywood would toss out the script.
Unrealistic. Completely. Unbelievable. Totally.
</P>
<P>
   Twist of fate in Arena League
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holmgren is far from the only coach who had overlooked Kurt
Warner. Gaylord Haushildt, the coach at Regis HS in Cedar Rapids,
knew that Warner had a great arm and could see the field. ``But the
NFL?'' Haushildt said. ``You don't know that in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   And Terry Allen, Warner's coach at Northern Iowa and now the
Kansas coach, sat Warner on the bench for four long years becuse he
felt Jay Johnson was a better quarterback. ``I was as responsible
for holding him back as anyone,'' Allen told the Des Moines
newspaper. Warner, a fourth-year junior, was so discouraged that he
wanted to quit after a game at McNeese State in 1992, but his
parents talked him out of it.
</P>
<P>
   But for the true fickleness of fate, consider what happened to
Warner when he signed on with the Iowa Barnstormers of the Arena
Football League in 1995. Arena Football, for the cable-deprived, is
played indoors on a field 50 yards long and 25 1/2 yards wide, with
end zones 8 yards deep. With the field about half the size of an
NFL field, and with fans leaning over from the front row and
dumping beer on or socking players running by, it is a quite
different game from the NFL. Much quicker, too.
</P>
<P>
   Warner wasn't sure he wanted to play in the Arena League. He had
watched the summer games on ESPN, but only ``because that was the
only thing on television. It was better than `Love Boat' reruns.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was football. And Warner was terrible in his first
exhibition game, against the St. Louis Stampede in St. Louis,
throwing two interceptions in the first half. But John Gregory, the
Barnstormers' coach, stood firmly behind Warner even when Willis
Jacox, Iowa's major offensive threat, complained to the coach that
he had seen better quarterbacks in the Canadian Fotball League.
Jacox would argue that the Barnstormers needed a new QB; Gregory
stood by Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the interceptions piled up _ 11 in Warner's first four
games. Before a game against Memphis, Warner was sure he was going
to be benched or even cut. And after two interceptions in the first
half, Gregory did what Jacox had urged him to do and what Warner
had feared he would do: He benched Warner.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth quarter, with Iowa trailing, 25-20, Warner was
sent back in because he was more familiar with the two-minute
offense. Warner dropped back to pass and threw the ball directly
into the hands of Memphis defender Jerry Pitts (``It was there and
the game was over'') but Pitts dropped the almost-certain
interception.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, with a new chance to win the game _ and, actually, to
save his career _ threw a winning TD pass as time expired. And his
record as a starting quarterback since that day is 50-10.
</P>
<P>
   So all of this may have been possible only because Jerry Pitts
dropped a sure interception, an interception that might have sent
Kurt Warner back to the Hy-Vee supermarket in Cedar Falls. Instead
of St. Louis, where he is second now only to Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Triumph of spirit
</P>
<P>
   Ask Warner about the importance of Sunday's game and his mind
flashes back to what he considers the most important game of his
life, the 1996 Arena Bowl, Iowa against the Tampa Bay Storm, on
Aug. 26, with 11,411 hot and sweaty fans packing Iowa's home
stadium, ``The Barn.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay was leading, 42-38, when Warner directed the last
drive of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my most memorable game, the first championship game
we played, the second year in the league,'' said Warner. ``And
actually we got to the 1-yard line.''
</P>
<P>
   A pass failed, a run failed, and then two more passes were
stopped. Warner just could not move the ball that final yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of those situations where we felt we had won the
game, and we should have won the game,'' said Warner, ``but we
didn't do it. And it's something that has stuck in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That game, said Warner, is still the most important he's played
``because it's about as close as I've ever gotten to winning a
championship game. We were that close and we felt we should have
won it but we didn't win it. It's something I obviously want to
achieve and that's the closest I've ever come.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Warner knew ``my only chance to get to the NFL was to
go to the World League.'' But he was not burning to get to the NFL
because his salary at Iowa was good (about $60,000 a year) ``and I
was happy where I was. If I stayed there, I wouldn't have minded.''
</P>
<P>
   And nothing he has done this season with the Rams _ the 41 TD
passes, the MVP, the sudden glory _ compares with the thrill he got
when he met Billy Graham at a crusade in St. Louis last autumn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the most thrilling thing that's happened,''
said Warner. ``To be able to share my story, to use this platform,
share what God has allowed me to do. There's nothing better.
Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner's personal life seemingly is as inspiring as his
professional life. When he was a senior at Northern Iowa, his
roommate suggested they go out to Wiley Coyote's, a country and
western bar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhwile, Brenda Meoli's mother insisted that her daughter, a
divorced mother of two, also needed a night out. Warner didn't want
to go, and neither did Meoli, a former intelligence officer in the
Marines. Eventually, though, both changed their minds and went to
Wiley Coyote's.
</P>
<P>
   Warner and Meoli met and hit it off. They talked, and Meoli
disclosed that one of her children, Zachary, had been accidentally
dropped when he was four months old, by her former husband. Doctors
told her the infant would die. The mother prayed and prayed.
Zachary lived. But he is blind, and Meoli was told he may never sit
up, walk, or talk.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Warner showed up at Meoli's apartment with a
rose and said he wanted to meet the kids. He and Meoli soon were
married. In addition to the two children, they now have another
son, Kade.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary is now 10 and can do many of the things doctors said he
would never do, although he does them with difficulty. And each
Sunday, wearing a jersey with Warner's No. 13, he presses his nose
against the TV screen in the day care room at the TWA Dome and
watches his father win another game for the Rams. His mother
believes Zachary, though legally blind, can see Warner throwing all
those touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   Warner merely says, ``He's our gift from God.''
</P>
<P>
   Europe, then the NFL
</P>
<P>
   Many phone calls were made to get Kurt Warner out of Arena
Football and into a better league. The Chicago Bears wanted to try
him out in 1997 but Warner told them the tryout would have to wait;
he was going on his honeymoon in Jamaica with Brenda.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, a tropical critter bit him on that honeymoon
and his right arm swelled so much that he couldn't throw a
football. The workout was canceled; the Bears never called back.
</P>
<P>
   But Al Lugenbill, the coach of NFL Europe's Amsterdam Admirals,
persisted. It is much easier for all concerned if an NFL team signs
a player to a contract before he goes off to play in NFL Europe.
Lugenbill had called 12 teams; his 13th call was to Charlie Armey,
the vice president of personnel for the Rams. Armey, convinced of
Warner's potential, signed the quarterback to a Rams contract and
Warner was off to Amsterdam in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember the most,'' said Armey, the former New England
director of college scouting, ``was I met Kurt with Al in a
restaurant over in Amsterdam. And I can remember this so clearly.
Kurt looked into my eyes and told me, `Just give me a chance and I
won't prove you wrong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Warner remembers the conversation with exactly the same words.
``I knew if I just got the chance, it would be all I needed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the number of calls Lugenbill made for
Warner _ 13 _ is not lost on the quarterback, who wears that number
on his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not superstitious,'' he once said. ``I just want to show
the number is not all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey was impressed with how quickly Warner released the ball
and how accurate his passes were. Both Armey and Warner utter
virtually the same words, that Arena League football, with the game
played at warp speed and virtually every play a pass, can hone a
passer's skills to the finest of edges.
</P>
<P>
   But, once again, Warner would not have had a chance to display
those skills if fate hadn't paid another visit last August. During
the offseason, the Rams had dumped their unhappy quarterback, Tony
Banks, and signed former Redskin Trent Green to a
multimillion-dollar deal with a guarantee that he would be the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Green went down with a season-ending injury in August, and
coach Dick Vermeil and Armey had to decide whether to go the safe
route _ sign a tested veteran such as Jeff Hostetler _ or go with
the untested Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All credit for what's happened has to go with two people,''
said Armey. ``Kurt Warner, for his persistence in all he's gone
through to get here, and Dick Vermeil, for deciding he had seen
enough in the drills and was confident enough in Kurt to give him
the job. Those two men, and those two alone, deserve all the
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday afternoon, Kurt Warner, anxious, nervous, and
probably sleepless (``I was having trouble sleeping last Monday'')
will take the field for an NFL playoff game that just may be bigger
than that game in ``The Barn'' in 1996 when the Iowa Barnstormers
were stopped at the 1-yard line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
