<HEADLINE>
GAUGING THE DIRECTION OF AL EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the opening of training camp almost a month away (the
earliest reporting date is Feb. 18; Sox pitchers and catchers
report the following day), here is a look at what has transpired
this winter, division by division, starting with the AL East:
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Orioles
</P>
<P>
   (FR) 1999 finish: 78-84, fourth, 20 games behind.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Additions: Manager Mike Hargrove, LHP Buddy Groom, RHP Mike
Trombley, C Greg Myers, DH Harold Baines.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Subtractions: Manager Ray Miller, GM Frank Wren, LHP Jesse
Orosco, LHP Arthur Rhodes, RHP Scott Kamieniecki, INF Jeff
Reboulet, RHP Mike Fetters, RHP Doug Linton.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Prospects: LHP Matt Riley, 3B Ryan Minor, 1B Calvin
Pickering, C Jayson Werth, RHP Jose Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE &QC; 
(FR) Runs for/against: 851/815, +36.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Home runs: 203.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Walks/strikeouts: 615/890.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Leadoff on-base percentage: .393.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Stolen bases/caught stealing: 107/46.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: Big-spending O's, despite bringing in Albert
Belle and Will Clark, were cooked not long after Patriots Day, a
6-16 start leaving them reeling until the All-Star break, when they
were 15 games under .500. Belle, as he'd done the year before in
Cleveland, finally got cranking after the break, when he hit 27 of
his 37 homers and knocked in 82 runs. O's obviously aren't daunted
at the prospect of reuniting Hargrove with Belle, whom the manager
left alone in Cleveland. O's veterans were openly contemptuous of
the departed Miller, but the O's are old and brittle. After his
first two trips ever to the DL because of back problems, it remains
to be seen what Cal Ripken has left in his 20th season. The Iron
Man turns 40 this year.
</P>
<P>
   PITCHING &QC; 
(FR) Overall ERA: 4.77.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Starters: 61-57, 4.71.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Relievers: 17-27, 4.89, 33/58 saves.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Strikeouts/walks: 982/647.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: They were poised to have Aaron Sele, winner of 37
games the last two seasons, join Mike Mussina and Scott Erickson to
form a Big Three at the top of their rotation, with kids Sidney
Ponson and Jason Johnson filling it out. But owner Peter Angelos
had second thoughts after Sele's medical exam, and the Mariners
quickly pounced on the former Sox curveballer. The O's remain in
the market for another starter, though Mercedes's strong showing in
the Dominican Republic makes him a sleeper candidate. The O's, who
blew 25 saves last season, have stocked their bullpen with former
Twin Trombley and lefty ``Nutty'' Buddy Groom from the A's, with
Mike Timlin retaining a shaky hold on the closer's job for now.
Timlin picked up 18 saves in 19 chances in season's second half. It
will help if Erickson improves on his 1-7 start from last season,
while O's also will be focused on locking up ace Mussina in his
walk year.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE &QC; 
(FR) Fielding percentage: .986.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Errors: 89.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: The numbers are misleading, inasmuch as they hide
the shortcomings of range the O's had at both corners. O's could
use a faster, younger fly-catcher in center field than Brady
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox
</P>
<P>
   (FR) 1999 finish: 94-68, second, wild-card qualifier; defeated
Indians, 3-2, in Division Series; lost to Yankees, 4-1, in ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Additions: OF Carl Everett, LHP Jeff Fassero, SS Manny
Alexander, OF Jermaine Allensworth, LHP Sang-Hoon Lee.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Subtractions: DH Butch Huskey, OF Damon Buford, INF Lou
Merloni, RHP Pat Rapp, DH Reggie Jefferson, LHP Kent Mercker.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Prospects: C Steve Lomasney, 1B Dernell Stenson, 3B Wilton
Veras, OF Michael Coleman, RHP Tomo Ohka, RHP Juan Pena.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE &QC; 
(FR) Runs for/against: 836/718, +118
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Home runs: 176.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Walks/strikeouts: 597/928.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Leadoff on-base percentage: .401.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Stolen bases/caught stealing: 67/39.
</P>
<P>
   (FR) Comments: With the addition of Everett _ he'll probably hit
in the No. 4 spot behind Nomar Garciaparra, allowing him more
chances to run _ the lineup matches up nicely against anybody in
the division, one through five, and maybe even deeper. Jose
Offerman, a healthy John Valentin, the AL batting champion (Nomar),
a prime-time player in Everett, and Troy O'Leary, whose postseason
performance took him to the next level, prompts Dan Duquette to
ask, ``Who are they going to pitch around now?'' Brian Daubach's
second half raised some questions, but the Basher/Mike Stanley
combo should settle nicely lower in the order, and C Jason Varitek
shows promise of being an offensive force. Having three switch
hitters in his starting nine (Offerman, Everett, Varitek) gives
Jimy Williams terrific flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   PITCHING &QC; 
