<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-LPGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNSIZING LEAVES LPGA IN GREAT SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He doesn't have Tiger Woods, the one-man ratings insurance
policy. Sponsors aren't knocking at his door with blank checks. And
major network exposure remains a luxury he can only wish for.
</P>
<P>
   But what Ty Votaw does have is a firm grip on reality, a healthy
dose of perspective, if you will. He is the commissioner of the
Ladies Professional Golf Association Tour, which has been an
organized part of the sports landscape for 50 years. That makes it
the longest-running women's sports association in the world, a fact
that it will trumpet in celebratory style throughout 2000. Votaw is
rightfully proud of the LPGA Tour's place in history, but he
deserves credit for assuming a strong leadership at a time when it
is needed most.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people in charge subscribe to the theory that more is
better. Votaw thinks quality, not quantity, is the goal. ``I think
there was much discussion (after he took over for Jim Ritts in the
spring of 1999) _ do we have too many events, do we have too few
events, what's the right number?'' said Votaw during a State of the
LPGA Tour address a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The answer for 2000 is 40, down three events from a year ago.
Some would see that as not a very good indicator, but Votaw isn't
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very good that 40 is certainly right there in the
middle of our range,'' said Votaw. ``I am very confident in saying
that the LPGA is in its best position, both financially and
competitively, from an operational point of view, than it's ever
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tournaments were lost (including the one at Pleasant Valley
in Sutton) and some sponsors left (Sara Lee among them). But
tournaments were added (including the Evian Masters in France) and
new sponsors (Electrolux and State Farm most significantly) joined.
The purses aren't the $3 million-$5 million jackpots that the men
play for, but they are nothing to snicker at, unless $550,000 to
$800,000 is pocket change to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the purse amounts of the events that have gone
off our schedule versus the purse amounts that we are adding to the
schedule,'' said Votaw, ``there is no question in our minds that
the LPGA is in a very healthy position.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a tribute not only to the stars of today, but to those
who blazed a difficult trail. Again to his credit, Votaw made sure
the women of yesteryear were honored at the LPGA Tour's 50th
anniversary gala last Monday in Palm Beach, Fla. The night of
champions, which honored present standouts such as Karrie Webb
(Player of the Year), also saluted eight LPGA Tour founders (Alice
Bauer, Patty Berg, Bettye Danoff, Marlene Hagge, Betty Jameson,
Marilynn Smith, Shirley Spork, and Louise Sugg), not to mention
pioneers such as Susie Berning, Peggy Kirk Bell, and Shirley
Englehorn.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700 people attended the dinner, and while much of the
attention would soon shift to the season-opening tournament _ The
Office Depot _ it was rewarding to see such a significant sports
group pay homage to players from previous eras.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger beat
</P>
<P>
   Woods's streak of consecutive victories is at five, his uncanny
ability to rise to the occasion is unmatched (12 victories the 13
times he has had a 54-hole lead), his thirst for success is
unrelenting, and somehow he seems to be getting better and better.
It's frightening, perhaps, to the lads whose livelihood requires
them to tee it up against him, but it is a delightful time for
those of us who love to follow the PGA Tour. We live in an age in
which we are hardly ever delivered what is advertised, but in Woods
we have the rarity _ someone who has not only lived up to the hype
but far surpassed it. Though just 24, Woods has been ballyhooed for
more than 10 years and he has been securing national championships
annually since 1991. Except for a few public relations hiccups, he
has done it all with an honest work ethic and great character. The
most serious charge against him? That perhaps he displays too much
emotion on the course. Compare that with the behavior of the pro
and collegiate athletes who at times make reading the sports
section a nauseating endeavor and there's no wonder Woods that has
taken over for his pal Michael Jordan as the world's most engaging
sports personality. As Jordan did before him, Woods makes you stop
and watch, regardless of your interest in golf. Critics can nitpick
and say the streak is spread across five months and two different
seasons, or that four of the victories have come in limited-field
events. But isn't it better to enjoy the ride he is giving us? He
has, after all, outplayed some iron (Phil Mickelson, Davis Love,
Ernie Els twice) during this streak, and for perspective on what he
has already accomplished at 24, consider these numbers: In 71 PGA
Tour starts, Woods has 16 wins and two majors; Jack Nicklaus, in
the same number of events, had 14 and three. In other words, if his
goal is to be the best ever, he seems to be right on schedule . . .
Woods has missed just one cut in his PGA Tour career (we do not
count that AT&AMP;T debacle two years ago), and is riding a streak of
44 straight. Chris Perry is next with 27 . . . Speculation is that
Woods will next tee it up at the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach (Feb. 3-6),
which would likely start a stretch of four straight events (Buick
Invitational, Nissan Open, and Andersen Consulting World Match
Play). There is, however, the possibility that he could play
Phoenix, then skip the AT&AMP;T, but with the US Open at Pebble Beach
in June, it seems likely he'll put up with a few rounds of
celebrity silliness (perhaps paired with Jordan?) to brush up on a
layout you can always learn something about . . . On the day he
would have turned 43 _ Jan. 30 _ Payne Stewart will be remembered
with a special slate of programs on The Golf Channel. Officials at
The Memorial, meanwhile, have taken the unusual step of announcing
Stewart as the special honoree for 2001. Nicklaus will be honored
this year on the occasion of the event's 25th anniversary . . .
Monday marks the fifth anniversary of The Golf Channel, prompting
many of us to wonder how we survived without it. At the end of
1999, some 30 million homes worldwide had been plugged in to TGC .
. . Casey Martin's debut as a member of the PGA Tour is Wednesday,
in the first round of the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, but what
should be a moment to embrace is approaching beneath a cloud of
worry. First, Martin's right leg, the one ravaged by
Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber Syndrome, is giving him problems. ``It
doesn't feel very good at all right now,'' Martin said via
teleconference the other day. ``I've been struggling.'' There is
also the matter of the PGA Tour's appeal, which was heard by the
9th Circuit Court late in 1999, with a decision possible at any
day. If the PGA Tour were to win the appeal and Martin's right to a
cart were taken away, it would be a huge loss in the court of
public opinion at a time when pro golf is riding a wave of
popularity. Here's hoping that the Tour, if it were to win on
appeal, would do the decent thing and make a special exception for
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Changes ahead
</P>
<P>
   Two recent developments demonstrate that the superstars of golf
certainly have a collective voice that is listened to. First, by
all accounts, the PGA of America has agreed on a plan to distribute
funds to members of future Ryder Cup teams so that they can
determine which charities will benefit. It is something the players
had lobbied for, but it took a messy public controversy a month
before last September's matches at The Country Club to bring it to
a head. Chalk up a victory for the players, as you must regarding
another issue they had raised. Players did not like the fact that
the prestigious Tour Championship had lost its end-of-the-year
status when it was played the week before the inaugural American
Express Championship. David Duval was among those who thought the
trip from Houston (Tour Championship) to Spain (American Express)
was too much, and he skipped the $5 million WGC event to show that
he was serious. Jesper Parnevik also skipped Spain and Love gave
serious thought to doing so, though he eventually played. It is a
dilemma the players will face again this year (Nov. 2-5 for the
Tour Championship in Atlanta; Nov. 9-12 for the American Express in
Spain), but things will change. The PGA Tour announced that in 2001
the Tour Championship will be the season-ender, with the WGC
American Express moved up to September. While that solves one
problem, it creates another interesting scenario, as the Ryder Cup
will also be played in September 2001 at The Belfry in England.
Which probably explains why Tour officials are talking about moving
the WGC American Express to Scotland or Ireland in 2001, a long
iron from The Belfry. Few things make a golfer smile like a short
trip between events . . . Woods's triumph at the Mercedes
Championship had to be a tad unsettling to the folks at Buick who
recently turned over millions to the phenom to carry a golf bag
with the Buick name on it and to play in their tournaments. There
he was, pictured with important sponsors, accepting part of his
prize _ that's right, a Mercedes . . . This week's Office Depot
went off without Annika Sorenstam, who doesn't like to play much
early in the season. Grace Park, a rookie who very well could take
the Tour by storm, also was not in the field . . . Frequent-flier
mileage is piling up for Els. He crossed through 12 time zones to
get from his home in South Africa to Hawaii for the Mercedes and
this week's Sony Open. He goes next to Australia, then races back
to Los Angeles for the Nissan Open Feb. 17-20 . . . Greg Norman was
in a courtroom last week, one of the witnesses against Jack Hasson,
who is charged with selling fake or flawed jewelry to the rich and
famous of Southern Florida. One item in question was a diamond pin
that Norman later discovered had been treated with radiation to
bring out the color. He paid nearly $50,000 for it. Walter (``I
don't want to be a millionare; I just want to live like one'')
Hagen never had such worries. He merely had to find a place in
which to change into his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   A mulligan
</P>
<P>
   There was an erroneous report circulating last week that Billy
Andrade and Brad Faxon had canceled the CVS Charity Classic, their
three-day event that made such a splashy debut last summer.
Fortunately for local golf fans, it was a reporter's mistake. All
systems are go for July 9-11 at Rhode Island CC in Barrington . . .
Massachusetts Golf Association officials have secured one of the
most spectacular layouts, Kittansett GC in Marion, to host their
first State Team Net Championship. It's great news for those who
enjoy competition but don't have a low enough handicap to get into
the State Amateur or State Four-ball. It will be a two-player
format, with clubs either choosing their representatives or
conducting a tournament to send the winners to one of perhaps three
statewide qualifying sites in September. The final at Kittansett
will be held Oct. 5 . . . If you squint and focus hard enough, you
can see the US Senior Open on the distant horizon _ the 2001 event
at venerable Salem CC, that is. Volunteers are being sought, and if
you are interested, call 978-927-4350.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
