<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS CELTIC PUZZLE FALLING TO PIECES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no need to be coy, so I'll tell you now that the next
paragraph contains a trick question. It is tricky because it has
2+2 in its eyes and calculus in its soul. I don't think I've ever
seen a question wink and smirk, but if one could, this one would.
Now that you have been warned, here it is:
</P>
<P>
   What is wrong with the Boston Celtics?
</P>
<P>
   The first part _ the easy part _ of the answer is that,
statistically, they are the worst defensive team in the NBA. If you
watch the Celtics play on the road, you need subtitles to
understand what they are doing. They have a power forward, Antoine
Walker, who has already taken 135 3-pointers, or 65 more than
necessary, after 35 games. (In fact, one day I'll tell you about my
Walker 3-point Budget Plan. He would be budgeted for 164, or 2 per
game, the entire season. If he exceeded his budget, he would be
penalized with over-the-limit fees and finance charges.)
</P>
<P>
   Those are the simple issues, but the Celtics have more
complicated ones:
</P>
<P>
   --They have Rick Pitino on their masthead as ``president,''
although Pitino believes he needs to clarify that title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a president,'' Pitino said, ``but I'm not a Red
Auerbach-type of president. I'm basically the president of
basketball operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this is not what Pitino had in mind when he signed
his 10-year contract in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   --They have their Merrimac Street offices buzzing over the
firing of Joe DiLorenzo, a popular executive whose most recent
project was pushing for the team's $32 million training facility
(and subsequent multimillion-dollar naming-rights deal). Because of
the suddenness of the firing (``I found out a half-hour before it
happened,'' Pitino said), several employees are afraid that they
will be next.
</P>
<P>
   --They have a problem selling tickets. Last Monday they had a
head-shaving promotion to lure fans into the FleetCenter. The
promotion made one wonder whether a tripleheader featuring the
76ers and Knicks were next.
</P>
<P>
   --They are simultaneously thrifty and excessive. During the
holidays, some employees were said to have personally delivered
ornaments to businesses because the Celtics didn't want to pay
extra postage. In 1997, the Celtics renovated their Merrimac Street
offices and now have significant space there. But they have chosen
to take on an additional bill so M.L. Carr, who criticized the team
last season, will be away from Merrimac Street and in a Woburn
office.
</P>
<P>
   If you examine each of the previous items, you will probably see
what I see: an organization that is on the verge of turning over.
These are the things that happen in most businesses in transition.
There are ego clashes, broken promises, expense reports examined
with magnifying glasses, and several employees sending out resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Pitino. He is the president of the Celtics.
Consider that the president of the Boston Celtics found out about a
firing 30 minutes before it happened. In other words, the decision
was made without his input.
</P>
<P>
   When Pitino was asked about DiLorenzo, the president-coach was
sitting in one of the training facility's extra rooms. Pitino
realized the importance of that fact. Before DiLorenzo worked to
bring the new building to life, Pitino, his coaches, and his
players didn't have any extra space at Brandeis University. There
was a cramped weight room, a cramped coaches room that was used by
seven men, and the reality that the Celtics were visitors in the
home of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sad to see him go,'' Pitino said. ``He did a wonderful
job for us. Now, if you ask me why he was fired, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   I get the feeling that this is not the first difference of
opinion Pitino has had with Paul Gaston and Richard Pond, the
team's chief operating officer and chief financial officer. Pond
said he could not comment on the specifics of the firing. But when
he was told that some employees had described the firing as cold
(DiLorenzo found out before leaving on a Caribbean vacation), he
said, ``It's clear that (the employees) don't have knowledge of the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach DiLorenzo, who was scheduled to return from his
vacation Saturday, were unsuccessful. The irony is that DiLorenzo
once had one of Pond's job titles _ chief financial officer _ and
received the news of his firing from Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to see anybody get fired,'' Pitino said. ``I've
never been fired, but I know it affects your self-esteem. Your
family suffers. It's a very difficult thing for anybody to go
through because there is a perception that you didn't do a good
job, and that wasn't the case with Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   This appears to be the preliminary stage for an offseason
upheaval. If the playoffs began today, the Celtics would be out of
them for the fifth consecutive season. Say Pitino's team finishes
37-45 and out of the playoffs. He reflects in the offseason about
his presidency, and how he doesn't have the control and budget that
he thought he would have. Would he leave, $21 million and bruised
ego in tow?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would I go?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   To the college game, I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see if I hadn't been at Kentucky,'' he said. ``But I
was at Kentucky, I came here and I'm going to do the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   But, I said, you could revive someone else's program.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he wouldn't ``feel comfortable'' leaving Boston
without completing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, everyone is having a hard time doing a good job for
the Celtics. Pond said the business has changed dramatically since
the days the Celtics sold out Boston Garden. He also said that he
is ``absolutely in support'' of Pitino. Next to Gaston, Pond is the
most powerful man in the organization. Pitino didn't acknowledge
it, but perhaps he thought he would have that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   What he has is a bad team that plays before decent crowds. He
probably doesn't have the budget he wants. His Celtics winning
percentage is 42, which is about the same as the last two seasons
of the Chris Ford era. He has seen one very good employee,
DiLorenzo, fired and another one, Mark Lev, leave for a better job.
If his team keeps losing, there will be more problems. There are
always magnified problems on bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   What is wrong with the Boston Celtics?
</P>
<P>
   A lot. And I think things will get worse before they get better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
