<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM TALKING A GOOD GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While awaiting the arrival of ESPN The Suburb and ESPN The
Sanitarium, we will satisfy our craving for the almighty boo-yaw by
ripping through another printing of ESPN The Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   This issue is a brutally hip read, and the generous graphics are
almost as easy on the eyes as a Bo Outlaw jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Of interest to those of us who, ahem, jones on the NBA is its
profile of Clippers rookie Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   The title of this piece is ``O-Time,'' which (we checked our
cool conversion chart) ranks as an ironic echo of ``Showtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Boo-yaw.
</P>
<P>
   If asked to deliver the USA Today analysis of the ESPN Odom
story, we'd conclude that - as a Clippers employee - Lamar-velous
is attempting to conduct himself as a true pro while feeling as
miscast as Johnny Mathis in a karaoke bar.
</P>
<P>
   But its observations of the team's Odom risk-management history
are beyond played. Not to mention wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's source for Odom acquisition protocol is Jerry
DeGregorio, the high school coach hired by then-University of Rhode
Island coach Jim Harrick to recruit Odom and his NYC pals.
</P>
<P>
   After Harrick abandoned URI for Georgia, DeGregorio was given
his job as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   After Odom left school and was drafted by the Clippers, team
sources say DeGregorio sought employment as a Clips assistant coach
or personal mentor for the prized rookie.
</P>
<P>
   He shoots, he doesn't score.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps coincidentally (insert wink here), DeGregorio supplied
ESPN The Magazine with quotes that suggest the Clippers did little,
if any, background check on Odom. Coach Chris Ford and Elgin
Baylor, the team's VP of basketball operations, didn't talk to him
about Lamar, Jerry D said.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said he did have a chat with DeGregorio, but usually
prefers a more objective witness to a prospect's character. As is
common practice among NBA teams, the Clips hired an investigator to
run a background check on Odom and were satisfied with the report.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jeff Weltman, the Clippers' director of player
personnel, did have several phone conversations with DeGregorio
about Odom. Weltman risked dialing-finger amputation in his attempt
to lure the 6-foot-9 forward to L.A. for a pre-draft mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, that news escaped the ESPN dragnet.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the burden of cashing Clipper paychecks might be more
enjoyable for Odom if he walked more of his talk. To be sure, he's
a terrific kid who hates losing and generally competes like a
budding champion.
</P>
<P>
   But his solemn oaths to become physically stronger and add
considerable muscle to his mid-range jumper will sound hollow until
he begins arriving for practice early and leaving late.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan rules again?
</P>
<P>
   In a move that rivals the hiring of Wolfgang Puck to buy your
groceries, the Washington Wizards are about to give Michael Jordan
the power to make their player personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Those who admire his portfolio expect MJ to become a huge
front-office success.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they're right.
</P>
<P>
   But this task could be far more challenging than winning NBA
titles with Bill Cartwright and Luc Longley in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Jordan name could be a bonanza in the free-agent derby
... if he can juggle the books and find salary cap room.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards currently have the sixth-highest payroll in the
league. Next year, they're on the hook as No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   After this season, they still owe Tracy Murray $10 million over
three seasons. Ike Austin, who lost the starting center gig to
Jahidi White, is due $11 million over two. Rod Strickland will
receive another $20 million over the next two seasons, while Mitch
Richmond is on the books for $30 million over three.
</P>
<P>
   The big ticket is forward Juwan Howard, a one-time Jordan
favorite whose contract is worth $56 million over the next three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, MJ can wait before spying on college prospects the
Wizards don't have a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's first crucial move may be choosing a coach who can help
him motivate the aforementioned millionaires after nobody bites on
a trade offer.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects in this rumor-driven cavalcade will include Kansas
coach Roy Williams (who recruited MJ for North Carolina), Jordan
pal Rod Higgins (a Golden State assistant) and former Georgetown
boss John Thompson, who happens to be a close personal pal of Dean
Smith and agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to beat the drum for Seattle's Gary Payton as
the game's best point guard, we turn your attention to Suns
playmaker Jason Kidd. Kidd frequently is credited with making his
teammates better, but could only make 26 of 88 field-goal attempts
(29 percent) while Phoenix's lost four of its last six games. ...
Although he still seems reluctant to take a big game by the throat,
Maryland forward Terence Morris remains high on everyone's list of
potential early picks in the 2000 draft. But many league watch dogs
report the 6-9 junior is leaning toward staying for his senior
season. ... According to a league source, Clipper guard Derek
Anderson will join Charlotte's Ricky Davis and Denver's Ron Mercer
in dumping the representation of Master P's No Limit Sports.
Anderson, in the last year of his initial three-year contract,
could go with Falk. The former Kentucky star is one of six NBA
players hand-picked by Jordan to wear his ``Jump Man'' shoes and
apparel. ... While posting an NBA-record 72 wins, Phil Jackson's
Chicago Bulls had six opportunities to avenge losses incurred in
the same 1995-'96 season. They won all six by an average of 20
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
