<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN-WIZARDS: TROUBLING QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington forward Juwan Howard and assistant coach Wayne
``Tree'' Rollins nearly came to blows after a loss last week, so
the Wizards definitely need a distraction from their miserable
existence.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has been going nuts this week with the news Jordan would
try to assume a minority interest in the Wizards and be named
director of the team's basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations became so prolific in D.C., that even President
Clinton was asked for his opinion. ``It will be fun,'' he said.
``That's a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the glee, there are some troubling questions about
Jordan assuming control of a club. For one, there's his
relationship with super - agent David Falk, who has a stable of
superstars including Howard and Wizards point guard Rod Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   Agents are prohibited from having management positions with
teams, but it's no stretch to think Falk would play some type of
``unofficial'' role if Jordan is the Wizards' CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Another sticking point is whether Falk would be able to
represent Jordan as his agent. Under the NBA's player union rules,
agents cannot represent management.
</P>
<P>
   These are potential conflict-of-interest issues the NBA will
have to address.
</P>
<P>
   Falk's already the master of steering clients into certain
cities (see Alonzo Mourning to Miami), and there would probably be
some speculation about whether any his high-profile stars would
suddenly develop an interest in the Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention that if this deal ever gets finalized, it's
difficult to imagine how hard Jordan will work on the less
glamorous aspects of the job. Is someone who is used to having his
way prepared to haggle with other GM's, or work the phones
tirelessly seeking trades to improve the club?
</P>
<P>
   Will any of this get in the way of his golf game?
</P>
<P>
   What happens when the Wizards need more attention than the next
endorsement?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, no one will probably care, once Jordan joins the
Wizards. The positive P.R. will be too much for the Wizards to
worry about the little things.
</P>
<P>
   Give Jordan credit for one thing: At least he has the sense not
to try and coach -- so far.
</P>
<P>
   Survival story: Former Mavericks forward Roy Tarpley, banned
from the NBA for life in 1995 after substance abuse violations, has
gone to the league's version of Siberia. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley is playing for a team in Perm, located in Russia's Ural
Mountains, before crowds of 800 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really good team, and I want to be part of something
good,'' Ta rpley told the Dallas Morning News. ``They make me
really comfortable and make me want to go out and give 200 percent
on and off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley is so happy to be playing again he isn't even
complaining about the Siberian winters: ``I was born in New York,
and I'm used to the cold. I missed it. I wanted a white
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Not their Master: Denver guard Ron Mercer and Charlotte gua rd
Ricky Davis recently fired rapper Master P as their agent, and
Davis sai d Clippers guard Derek Anderson would also follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper, whose real name is Percy Miller, has tried out for
the Horne ts and Raptors the past two seasons. ``It started to fall
apart when he started trying to play basketball and stopped
concentrating on business, '' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ignored rookies: When the NBA announced who would play in the
rookie game on All-Star weekend, it gave an indication of who isn't
tearing up the league so far.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 3 overall pick, Charlotte's Baron Davis, No. 5 pick,
Jonathan Bender of Indiana and No. 7 pick, Richard Hamilton of
Washington, were the notable omissions.
</P>
<P>
   The bargain picks invited to the game were Celtics swingman
Adrian Griffin (undrafted), Sixers center Todd MacCulloch (second
round) and Nuggets forward James Posey (No. 18).
</P>
<P>
   A Hughes deal: The Sixers are offering point guard Larry Hughes
to virtually any takers. They asked Orlando for rookie Corey
Maggette, and the Magic are thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   You'll know how desperate the Sixers are to get rid of Hughes if
they accept the Warriors' offer of Chris Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, talk of the Wizards shipping Ike Austin to Milwaukee
for Robert Traylor won't go away. The Nets are believed to be
interested in Hawks guard Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Popular coach: Vancouver's new coach, Lionel Hollins, continues
to impress his players.
</P>
<P>
   After playing five road games in seven days, the tired Grizzlies
arrived for practice this week. Hollins promptly canceled practice
and arranged a private screening of the Denzel Washington movie,
``The Hurricane,'' at the movie complex next to the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins also had players draw teammates' names out of a hat to
exchange Christmas gifts. Shareef Abdur-Rahim drew Doug West's name
and gave the injury-prone guard the game Operation.
</P>
<P>
   West gave veteran power forward Antoine (Big Dawg) Carr a dog
calendar that had every dog's face replaced with Carr's picture.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: There's a lot of talk about whether the Lakers are
interested in Chicago's Toni Kukoc, but it should never be
forgotten that Bulls GM Jerry Krause has absolutely no interest in
helping former coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
