<HEADER>
A7117 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e TV-GOODY-AZR     01-15 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
`SOPRANOS' BACK, AND EVEN BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
 TV-GOODY-AZR  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the hype, the critical acclaim, the unreasonable love you
have for the show. Despite all that, one nagging question haunts
fans of The Sopranos:
</P>
<P>
   Can the second season possibly be as good as the first?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the first three new episodes, the answer isn't just
``yes.'' The answer is that it might be even better.
</P>
<P>
   Already one of the greatest television series ever made, the HBO
hit about Tony Soprano, a New Jersey mobster with family problems _
of both the nuclear and criminal variety _ begins its second season
tonight, and it hits the ground running.
</P>
<P>
   It would be dirty pool to give too much away, but you will see
plenty of familiar faces. More important, stagnation hasn't set in
_ you'll meet compelling new characters as well. Which means new
headaches for beleaguered Tony, the psychiatrist-seeing capo played
so brilliantly by James Gandolfini.
</P>
<P>
   Gandolfini is, in fact, the not-so-secret ingredient of the
show's greatness. Even without him, The Sopranos would be
fantastic. But whenever he's on screen, it ups the intensity a
notch; you can't look away. NYPD Blue's Dennis Franz beating
Gandolfini for a Best Actor Emmy is a crime worthy of Tony himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good as Tony Soprano, and as born to the role, as
Regis was to host that stupid game show,'' says Bob Thompson,
founding director of the Center for the Study of Popular Television
at Syracuse University. ``It's one of those matches made in
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   But everyone else in the cast is perfect, whether it be Emmy
winner Edie Falco as Tony's wife, Carmela; Dominic Chianese as
Uncle Junior; or Nancy Mar chand, so good as Tony's mother, the
evil Livia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just are all so interest ing, and they all blend
together,'' says Dorothy Swanson, founder of Viewers for Quality
Television. ``You could almost not find fault with it, no matter
which charac ter you examine.''
</P>
<P>
   Cast additions Aida Turturro, as Tony's earth-mother sister,
Janice, and David Proval, as an old-time thug named Richie Aprile
just out of the joint, live up to that standard as well. I'm dying
to tell you how and why, but it wouldn't be fair to ruin it for
you.
</P>
<P>
   But that's how it is with great shows _ you want to run out and
blab about them with your friends. And make no mistake, The
Sopranos is a great show _ maybe even (dramatic pause) the greatest
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the best dramas ever done,'' Thompson says.
``It is one of the best series after only 13 episodes. Maybe it's
because there's only 13 episodes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good point. Television traditionally has been a
series-based medium, and a successful series normally lasts at
least 22 episodes. And if a series gets good ratings _ and
therefore makes money for advertisers _ networks want to run it
forever, or at least until the dollars dry up. Quality be damned:
If it's making money, it stays on the air. That's why so many shows
fizzle out (MASH, Happy Days, Seinfeld) and so few have the courage
to end on a high note (The Mary Tyler Moore Show).
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, Beethoven would have written the Fifth Symphony,''
Thompson says. ``At the end of the Fourth Movement, (the net work)
would say, `Could you add a movement?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet since it's not on a network, The Sopranos isn't bound by a
lengthy schedule. As with the excellent Larry Sanders Show and Oz _
also HBO products _ less can be more. The quality of the
productions is so high, it leaves you hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got this hybrid _ the long, extended story that can
take its time in the telling,'' Thompson says. ``But it doesn't
need all this padding. It doesn't have all these dog episodes in
between.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. So far, no Sopranos episode has missed the
mark. Part of the reason is realism. The Fox network, and later CBS
and ABC, famously passed on the series, and David Chase, the show's
creator, wound up looking to cable, wondering if anyone would ever
bother to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But network rejection was Chase's creative salvation. Cable gave
him a freedom he never would have enjoyed at a network. He didn't
have to write a mob series in which gangsters use words like
``dang'' and ``rats.'' And when someone gets shot, they actually
bleed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's HBO, so they can talk like gangsters really talk, which
gives it a sense of reality that we haven't had before,'' Swanson
says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the violence, it is more graphic than what you'll find on
network television. But it's never gratuitous. There are always con
sequences, and for all the talk about bloodshed, there is actually
surprisingly little on screen. Thus, when you do see someone
whacked, it carries that much more impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It advances the story,'' Swan son says of the show's violence.
``It's a part of who they are and what they do. I think the
sophisti cated viewer realizes that to them (mobsters), that's not
vio lence. That's the norm. That's what they do for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   But airing on HBO has its disadvantages. Not everyone sub
scribes to cable. That means two things: Those who don't get HBO
are missing out on a great show, and those who do get HBO are
besieged by requests to tape the show and pass it along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take HBO for The Sopra nos,'' Swanson says. ``Otherwise, I
probably wouldn't. The Sopra nos is really what I sit down to watch
TV for.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what we all should watch TV for. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7118 &Cx1f; ttx-z
