<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLA.-ST.-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINT GUARD GOTTLIEB LEADS COWBOYS PAST BEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When Oklahoma State needs an assist, it calls on
Doug Gottlieb. This time the request was of a different nature.
</P>
<P>
   The 14th-ranked Cowboys, who have been battling post-holiday
offensive depression, received an unexpected offensive boost from
Gottlieb, their senior point guard. The nation's leader in assists
responded with a team-high 13 points as Oklahoma State overcame
Baylor, 56-41, in a Big 12 Conference game yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb, a 41.9 percent shooter who is averaging 7.2 points per
game, rescued an Oklahoma State team that had made under 40 percent
of its shots in two of its past three games. Against the battling
Bears, the Cowboys (13-1, 2-0) had stretches where they missed 14
of 19 shots in the first half and nine of 12 in the second half.
``We've been working on things in practice where we simulate the
other team backing off me,'' said Gottlieb, who is averaging 9.9
assists per game. ``I've gotten more confident on what shots are
going to be there. I've got to make teams pay for leaving me
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Most defensive strategies used against Oklahoma State involve
forcing Gottlieb to shoot. Yesterday, the Bears (9-5, 0-3) allowed
Gottlieb to sneak inside for five layups. And when he wasn't
scoring, Gottlieb was making Oklahoma State's offense click. As the
Cowboys broke open a close game midway through the first half,
Gottlieb either scored or assisted on 12 of the team's next 17
field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State closed the first half by hitting nine consecutive
shots, taking a 31-20 lead. Baylor pulled to within 35-29 in the
first eight minutes of the second half. But, with the shot clock
fading, Gottlieb _ a 17 percent shooter from 3-point range _ hit a
3-pointer to make restore order. The cold-shooting Bears never
threatened again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 3-pointer he hit was the shot of the game,'' Baylor coach
Dave Bliss said. ``He's a man among boys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gottlieb picked a fine time to lead his team in scoring.
Yesterday was his birthday. So how old are you, Doug?
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty four,'' he said, trying his best to whisper.
``Everybody was calling me grandpa, but I'm not the only old guy on
the team. Two years ago, I played one of the worst games of my
career here. It was good to come down here this time and play
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, which has lost 19 consecutive regular-season conference
games, is averaging 42.3 points in Big 12 play. The bad-news Bears
are shooting 32.6 percent from the field and a woeful 16.3 percent
from 3-point range in three Big 12 games. And five of their 16
field goals yesterday were the result of Oklahoma State turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried hard on defense,'' said Bliss, noting his team took
more shots, had more steals and forced more turnovers than the
Cowboys. ``If we could score ... that's a big if. We're just not a
good shooting team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
