<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-VETS-KAN &LR;      01-15 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-VETS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ITS POVERTY, SCHOOL DISTRICT RICH IN PATRIOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALENA, Kan. _ Before the holiday break last month, the Galena
High School junior class gave plaques to Principal Ray Dykens,
media instructor Terry Grotheer and American history teacher Brad
Krouse. The plaques were a thank-you for a Veterans Day program in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa,'' Dykens thought. ``It's supposed to work the other way.
Teachers award plaques, not the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dykens relished the role reversal. Galena's students have
turned Nov. 11 into a day when elderly men and women tell stories
about sacrifice, loss, and love; and teen-agers reveal themselves
not to be the hobgoblins often portrayed in the news.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Day, usually a ho-hum, get-it-over-with day in many
schools, has become a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It was even bigger last year. Galena kids _ kindergarten through
12th grade _ raised $1,000 for the National World War II Memorial
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the $100 million cost of the memorial, due for its
groundbreaking next fall and its opening in 2002, that's chump
change.
</P>
<P>
   Except: Families of 60 percent of the students here are beneath
the poverty line, and the district is the state's poorest in terms
of assessed valuation. A thousand bucks here is serious money.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my brothers is 18, and I can't imagine him having to do
what they did back then,'' said Leslie LaTurner, a junior. ``I
think it (the memorial) will be wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, said Bob Lewis, education director for the memorial's
campaign, based in Arlington, Va., about $60 million has been
raised, the majority from corporations, foundations, veterans
organizations, the states, and civic and fraternal groups.
Individuals have donated about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the campaign, which is led by former Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas, was beginning its school program this winter in conjunction
with cable TV's History Channel. The aim, he said, was to alert
youths to the memorial and teach them why World War II was
important.
</P>
<P>
   Which has been the idea here in Galena for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember exactly the circumstances, '' said Dykens,
who spent 30 years in the Missouri National Guard and whose father
landed at Omaha Beach on D-Day. ``But you know the drill. You get a
kid in the office who's been acting up, he rolls his eyes and says,
in so many words, that this country owes him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykens said that attitude didn't wash here. Galena, he said, a
``kind of a stiff blue-collar town,'' has for years had a goal in
its curriculum to teach students to ``honor your country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every school district has something like that,'' Dykens
said. ``But things get busy, there's other things to do, and those
words just stay there in the handbook. Nothing happens. Well, we
decided writing it down wasn't enough. Kids needed to know others
had made sacrifices for them. Those words meant something.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea here was simple. On Nov. 11, veterans would be asked to
come to school as guests. Any man or woman veteran _ World War II,
Korea, Cold War, Vietnam, Grenada, Panama, Desert Storm, even
Bosnia. Plus their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   There would be a lunch, music and some visiting between the
students and the veterans. The program would last a hour, maybe
two.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started in a classroom, then it grew bigger and bigger, and
now we're in the auditorium,'' said Grotheer, whose father was with
the Army's 76th Division in Europe in World War II. ``Now it's the
students and the veterans talking nonstop. And now it's all day,
even more with the kids and the vets talking after school.''
</P>
<P>
   Krouse said the anticipation of the students, who organize and
run the program, was amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids get real excited,'' he said. ``Already they are
talking about next year. How we can make it bigger and better. It's
important to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykens, Krouse and Grotheer agreed that the magic of the day was
the interaction between the students and the veterans and their
spouses. What were called ``interviews'' quickly became
storytelling sessions. Not of blood and guts, hairbreadth escapes
or heroism.
</P>
<P>
   Likely as not the tales were about young men and women, not much
older than the listeners, who rode lonely trains to isolated army
posts; the last sight of a high school buddy who disappeared
forever into the maw of war; or even the shortages and tiny ration
stamps that were needed to buy everything from tires to beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids hear that sugar or coffee was almost impossible to get,
and you can just see their eye get wide,'' said Grotheer. ``What's
amazing is that some of the veterans now show up with mementos,
stuff you just know they've never shown to anybody outside their
family before.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, said junior Kerry Green, the older people get to look
at today's youth up close and personal ``and find out that we're
really interested in them. And that we're not the kids that get all
the publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's grandfather, Terry Ward, a Korean War veteran, went to
the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Dykens said it was not unusual to see tears _ from young and
old.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the National World War II Memorial, the school
bought a 20-foot flagpole and raffled it. A chance was $1. The
winning ticket was sold by a second-grader. That brought in $1,000.
Other money came in later as memorials, bringing the total to
$1,155.
</P>
<P>
   Two schools, one in Tennessee, the other in Oregon, each raised
$10,000, said Lewis. The still-fragmentary records the campaign had
of school giving showed Galena as about average or above, he said.
He added that he was amazed at the giving in light of the school's
assessed valuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful,'' he said of the donation. ``Give me their
number. I want to call them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Emerson, state director for Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas,
who accepted the donation, said the program in Galena was something
to see _ flags, a military helicopter parked out front,
enthusiastic young people and more-than-pleased older ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something,'' she said. ``I was just blown away.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson pointed out that World War II veterans _ there were 13
million _ now were dying at a average rate of about 1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   LaTurner, who took her grandfather, Korean War veteran Joe
LaTurner, to the program, said it made her appreciate him all the
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was neat,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
