<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-OKLASTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Gottlieb lifts Oklahoma State over Baylor
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ Doug Gottlieb celebrated his 24th birthday Saturday by
helping the 14th-ranked Oklahoma State Cowboys to a 56-41 Big 12
Conference victory over the struggling Baylor Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``About as pretty as a train wreck'' is the way the Cowboys'
senior guard described the rugged afternoon at the Ferrell Center
as Baylor fell short of the 43 points it had scored against both
Oklahoma and Texas in losing its first two conference games of the
year by a combined 61 points.
</P>
<P>
   This time, against their third consecutive nationally ranked
opponent, the Bears (9-5, 0-3 Big 12) remained in contention past
the midway point of the second half before losing their 21st
consecutive Big 12 game.
</P>
<P>
   But Gottlieb (13 points, seven assists, two steals) wasn't about
to let the Cowboys (13-1, 2-0) fold in their first conference road
game of the season. At one stage, from late in the first half until
eight minutes remained, he scored or assisted on 11 of Oklahoma
State's 14 field goals during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb, who led the Cowboys in scoring for the first time this
season, reached double figures for only the fourth time in a
conference game.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb's only 3-pointer of the day (after shooting only 18
percent from the arc coming into the game) was a shot that Oklahoma
State coach Eddie Sutton and Baylor coach Dave Bliss called the
game's key basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure when I shot it, guys on the bench were saying `No'
before it went in,'' said Gottlieb, whose previous career high was
15 last season against Southern Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Launched from just in front of the Cowboys' bench with the shot
clock winding down and 12:09 left to play, Gottlieb's 3-pointer
ended a four-minute Oklahoma State scoring drought during which
Baylor trimmed a 13-point deficit to 35-29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were staggering a little at the time,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Bliss: ``That was the big shot of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gottlieb followed Joe Adkins' outside shot with a steal
and short jumper to make it 42-31 with 7:53 to go, the Cowboys'
lead fell below double digits only once more. Glendon Alexander's
3-pointer then put the Cowboys back up 47-35. After that, the Bears
scored only one more field goal and six points in the closing 6:42.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were without starting center Alex Webber, who will
undergo further examination Monday for his ailing back and might
need disk injury. Fredrik Jonzen, a 6-10 sophomore, replaced Webber
and had eight points, eight rebounds and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor started freshman Wendell Greenleaf of North Shore in
place of Tevis Stukes, whom Bliss disciplined for a curfew
violation. Greenleaf scored five points, while Stukes, the Bears'
leading scorer, had five points in 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
