<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7223 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARINO-H     01-15 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARINO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Marino's agonizing day becomes longer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ When the final second ticked off the clock in
the most embarrassing game of his 17-year career, Miami Dolphins
quarterback Dan Marino walked across the field toward the tunnel
that led to the visitors' dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville safety Carnell Lake, who played against Marino with
the Steelers until this season, hugged the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just congratulated Dan on a great career,'' Lake said after
the Jaguars won the AFC divisional playoff game 62-7. ``After 17
years, Dan's got nothing left to prove if he wants to retire. The
only reason he'd come back would be to get another crack at a Super
Bowl, but I don't think anybody will look down on him if he chooses
to not come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember ever playing against a player of his
magnitude and it possibly being his last game.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's interview room, Marino snapped at anyone who asked
about it being his last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me that question now,'' he said the first time.
</P>
<P>
   After he heard the retirement question again from a friendly
face from the South Florida media, Marino said: ``I've answered
this question so many times. Look, I'm going to wait and see what
circumstances develop, and I'll decide later on.''
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation coach Jimmy Johnson will retire, which
might prompt Marino to play another season if the new coach will
have him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I can still win games in this league,'' said
Marino, 38, who is signed through the 2001 season. ``I've proven
that and will continue to prove that. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino was so tired of the retirement questions he almost begged
for some about the worst game in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played horrible,'' he said. ``We never even challenged.
I've never experienced anything like it, even when I was a kid. I
actually felt good about our chances going in, but nothing went
right early, and it snowballed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Johnson took the blame for working the players too
hard after the long trip to Seattle for the first-round victory,
Marino said, ``I'm not sure, but if he says so, I guess it is.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Johnson wanted to remove Marino because Miami
trailed 41-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime, he told me he would maybe put Damon (Huard) in
because of the circumstances of the game,'' Marino said. ``I asked
him if I could have another shot, but it didn't go well.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Dolphins' first series of the third quarter, Marino
left with Miami behind 48-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about it,'' Huard said of replacing Marino.
``You have to be ready when it's your turn and give it your best
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Players in both dressing rooms have been aware of the
speculation about Marino's possible retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I never felt sorry for him at any point in the game,''
said Jaguars defensive end Tony Brackens, who sacked Marino and
returned the fumble for a first-quarter touchdown. ``Down the road,
if this does turn out to be his last game, I might feel
differently. But I hope he comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   So do many of Brackens' teammates who helped make Marino's
afternoon miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's a great quarterback, and if this was his last game, it's
hard to see him go out like this,'' Jacksonville receiver Keenan
McCardell said. ``I hope he comes back. He's great for the game.
I'd hate to see him leave.''
</P>
<P>
   If Marino retires, let the record show Oronde Gadsden caught his
last TD pass, a 20-yarder with three seconds left in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even thought about that,'' Gadsden said. ``I don't
really want to think about it. That's all in Dan's hands. I guess
he'll sit down with his family, reflect and come up with a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
