<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7318 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN     01-15 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA UPSETS NORTH CAROLINA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ It won't make the record book, but UCLA's
game against North Carolina was the longest in school history.
</P>
<P>
   It began Wednesday night, after the embarrassing loss to USC,
and ended Saturday afternoon with a 71-68 victory over the Tar
Heels that was, quite simply, UCLA's most significant win in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   In passion, purpose and predicament, the Bruins recreated their
stunning 1998 NCAA Tournament second-round victory over Michigan.
Back then, they regrouped from a lethargic performance against
Miami to defeat the heavily favored, higher-seeded Wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, before 21,572 in the Smith Center, the Bruins (10-4)
played with unprecedented urgency, snapped a four-game losing
streak to North Carolina and and took a major step toward
qualifying for March Madness. (In their quest for 18 victories,
Saturday's win makes up for the loss at Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have given up on our season after that USC game,''
Bruins guard Earl Watson said. ``If we had lost this, then with
Arizona coming in, it would have been rough.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had myriad heroes. Big men Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric
combined for 29 points and 21 rebounds and outplayed their UNC
counterparts. Watson had a solid floor game with six assists and
two turnovers. Forward Jason Kapono scored 14 points in 22
foul-plagued minutes, and reserve Ryan Bailey made the
game-clinching free throws with 14.9 seconds remaining. He banked
home the first, drawing groans from the fans and giggles from the
UCLA bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never banked a free throw in my life,'' Bailey said.
``The main thing I was thinking was that if I missed them, my dad
was going to kick my butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, this victory was about Bruins coach Steve Lavin, who
has always done his best work in crisis situations _ whether it's
replacing Jim Harrick, recovering from a 48-point loss at Stanford
or keeping his players confident after 12-point losses to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Lavin did a great job keeping it in perspective for
us,'' Kapono said. ``He told us not to worry about what people were
saying. No one was feeling any pressure. He kept us loose, and he
had us ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's preparation began with a long postgame speech in the
Sports Arena catacombs. He implored the Bruins to learn from the
loss (ie: play with passion) and, at the same time, to forget it.
If they fretted about the Trojans, Lavin warned, they'd crumble
against the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   But Lavin learned something that night, as well. Watching the
Trojans rip UCLA's pressure defense for 91 points, he realized the
Bruins play best when using a compact, half-court defense that
keeps Moiso and Gadzuric close to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt responsible for not putting the players in a position
to beat USC,'' Lavin said. ``The thinking was sound: Our 10 could
beat their five. (The Trojans aren't very deep.) But we're just not
effective when we extend our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   During a crisp, two-hour practice Friday in the Smith Center,
Lavin was more vocal than usual as he installed a compact 3-2 zone.
If the Tar Heels could win the game from 3-point range, fine; they
weren't going to beat the Bruins underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same defense we played against Michigan (in
1998),'' he said. ``We treated (North Carolina center) Brendan
Haywood the same way we treated (Michigan's) Tractor Traylor. It
was the same concept we used against Oklahoma State and Mississippi
State and Arkansas (in the 1995 NCAA title run). Make teams beat
you from outside, but protect the paint.''
</P>
<P>
   The zone worked perfectly. Haywood took six shots and scored
seven points. UNC power forward Kris Lang had seven shots and nine
points. UCLA outrebounded the Tar Heels 38-30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their zone was very good, very active,'' Tar Heels coach Bill
Guthridge said. ``They accomplished what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The final piece to UCLA's preparation puzzle came Friday night,
when the players gorged on a home-cooked meal of fried chicken,
beef ribs, cabbage, collared greens and sweet potato pie with Rico
Hines' family. (He's from nearby Greenville, N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   A fabulous meal by all accounts, it actually did more for their
spirits than their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to get to a family atmosphere,'' Hines said.
``Everybody felt at home. My family was hugging and kissing the
guys. It put everything back in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   When the discussion turned to the Tar Heels, who, like UCLA,
have not played to expectations, Lavin spoke up. He told the Bruins
that UNC fans have been critical of the players and of Guthridge,
and they'd start booing (like UCLA fans) if the Tar Heels fell
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get ahead,'' Lavin told his team, ``the pressure will be
on them. They're supposed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, the Bruins jumped to a 10-2 lead and never
trailed.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Lavin celebrated with a brief, upward thrust
of his arms. Nor did he let loose in the locker room. Instead, he
walked to the greaseboard and made two lists: UCLA's losses this
season (Gonzaga, Colorado State, Washington and USC), and its best
wins (DePaul, South Florida, Purdue and North Carolina).
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys we were capable of being (a good team) if we
grew and learned, but we were also capable of being (a bad team) if
we didn't,'' he said. ``Then I gave the guys a hug because of what
they went through after USC.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
