<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7319 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR &LR;      01-15 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLACE WHERE THE SKY IS FALLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(Phoenix) - This is where 14-year-old Shannon Smith stood on the
night of June 14, 1999.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the small back yard of a red brick home in central Phoe
nix. Shannon walked out the door of the family room and onto the
grass, not far from a rose-colored block wall, next to a hammock.
She was speaking to a friend on a portable tele phone. She'd gone
outside be cause she heard something that sounded like a car crash.
She was an inquisitive girl, as girls should be.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house, on the pi ano, are two large photographs of
Shannon, smiling, as if she sees the prospect of a glorious life
before her.
</P>
<P>
   That night in June, she was on the telephone when a bullet that
had been fired randomly into the air fell and fell and fell, and
struck her on the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I found her,'' says Otis Smith, Shannon's fa
ther, pointing to where his daughter's head came to rest. Nearby,
his wife, Lory, watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knew she was shot until they did the X-ray at the
hospital,'' Lory says.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Otis believed his daughter had fallen asleep on the
lawn while looking up at the stars. When he saw she wasn't
breathing, he performed CPR until an ambulance arrived. He didn't
notice the blood on his hands until much later.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since their child's death, Otis and Lory have
pushed for a change in the law they say will make it easier to
prosecute those who fire weapons into the air. The legis lators
sponsoring the bill call it ``Shannon's Law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to create some kind of legacy for our daugh
ter,'' Otis says. ``That kind of thinking only denigrates her
memory. We only want a law that might keep what happened to our
child from happening to someone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can argue with that?
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, anyone who believes Shannon's Law is un
necessary, either because it won't change people's behavior, or
because it won't be strin gently enforced, or because the crime is
covered under existing laws, should come to this back yard and
stand next to Shan non's parents in the spot where she died.
</P>
<P>
   So, that's what I did.
</P>
<P>
   Otis invited me. I've said any one firing a weapon into the air
could be charged with a felony under endangerment and disor derly
conduct laws. He wanted to convince me otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County prosecutor Rick Romley supports Shan non's Law.
He told me it would make prosecution easier by eliminating the need
to prove ``intent.'' Then he added, ``There's still a problem
getting witnesses, or having them tes tify. It'll still be very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Otis Smith says, ``So what? Let's assume that's true.
Let's assume the laws overlap. What does it hurt? If it helps even
a little, wouldn't that be worth it?''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon's Law will inhibit random gunfire only if it's backed by
enforcement. Police and prosecutors could have done that already,
but haven't. Maybe they're overworked or maybe they believe it's
not worth it, but there's never been a serious crackdown here.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe Shannon's Law would embarrass them into doing
something, at least for a while. And it might provide some comfort,
at least for a while, to a grieving couple. Ev ery parent who loses
a child de serves that much.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would it hurt?'' Otis Smith asks again.
</P>
<P>
   And he's right.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths aren't crusaders. They have no hidden agenda. They
aren't zealots or pawns or political operatives.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't a couple of wild-eyed Chicken Littles tell ing us
the sky is falling. They're the people it fell on. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
