<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE KEEPS ROLLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ The real test lies ahead for Pepperdine. Over the next
three weeks the Waves take two trips north, where they'll play West
Coast Conference power Gonzaga, surprising San Francisco and always
tough Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   The next five games will reveal everything, tell all.
</P>
<P>
   By then Pepperdine (12-5, 2-0) will know what to make of its
terrific start under first-year coach Jan van Breda Kolff, whether
it's the precursor to something big or just something to enjoy
while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, the Waves take satisfaction from what
they've accomplished _ and they should.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 76-68 WCC victory over the University of San
Diego before 1,783 at Firestone Fieldhouse, they've earned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Record-wise we feel great, two straight wins in conference, we
feel good,'' said Pepperdine's Tezale Archie, who scored 10 points.
``We're definitely not playing our best ball, but we like the way
we're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's second straight conference win didn't come against
a mediocre St. Mary's team, as was the case Friday night. San Diego
(10-5, 1-1) came in red hot after destroying Loyola Marymount 82-38
the night before. The Toreros had won three straight, and six of
their last seven.
</P>
<P>
   This win had some merit, giving the Waves two straight wins to
begin conference play for the first time since 1992-93. It also
provides much needed momentum heading into the next five games.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Armstrong scored 20 points to lead the way, Kelvin Gibbs
added 13 and Nick Sheppard had 12. Andre Laws had 15 to lead San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Waves head north. It's a challenge Archie looks forward
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me personally, this is my senior year, I've been playing
against those guys for years and this is the best team I've played
on since I've been here,'' Archie said. ``I definitely want to get
tested and see where we stand with the big dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine took control early in the second half, building a
48-30 lead four minutes in. The Waves used a familiar method to
break it open, blanketing the Toreros with a full-court press,
forcing turnovers and getting points in transition.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there _ that's how Pepperdine does things this year
under van Breda Kolff, whose uptempo philosophy is a hit with his
players and even seems to be catching on with the student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The success so far) all starts with the coaching staff and
their style of play,'' Archie said. ``The trapping and all that. We
haven't done that since I've been here. Having it uptempo and using
the athletes we have, I think it starts with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves survived a mini-scare down the stretch, committing
some silly fouls and taking some questionable shots to help San
Diego climb to within four points with a little more than a minute
to play. Aside from that stretch, van Breda Kolff was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked the way we came out aggressive in the second
half and built the lead up,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``We executed
well, and got a couple of five-second calls on them. Overall I'm
pleased with the whole weekend.''!dlim! &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
