<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-JAGUARS-DOLPHINS-     01-15 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-DOLPHINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jacksonville plays Miami's swan song with all its might
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ If Miami's AFC divisional playoff loss to
Jacksonville turns out to be the last for quarterback Dan Marino
and coach Jimmy Johnson, Dolphins fans will try hard to forget
their putrid performances that contributed to one of the strangest
games in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   In Jacksonville's astonishing 62-7 victory that was the
second-most decisive in NFL playoff history, the Dolphins were as
awful as the Jaguars were awesome during a bright and beautiful
Saturday afternoon that turned so dark and ugly for Miami that
seeing was almost disbelieving.
</P>
<P>
   Before an Alltell Stadium-record crowd of 75,173, the Jaguars
led 24-0 in the first quarter and 41-0 in the second before
Marino's 20-yard touchdown pass to Oronde Gadsden with three
seconds left in the half produced Miami's only score.
</P>
<P>
   In securing the AFC Championship Game at home against
Indianapolis or Tennessee, Jacksonville's domination was so
convincing it was almost cruel, especially for Marino, who
completed 11 of 25 passes for 95 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was intercepted twice and mercifully removed for Damon
Huard after one series of the third quarter with the Dolphins
behind 48-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars forced seven turnovers and generated 520 yards to
Miami's 131.
</P>
<P>
   Many who follow the Dolphins closely and know Marino and Johnson
well believe the crushing defeat will be the last of their
illustrious careers, although neither would admit it afterward. The
feeling is Johnson will retire shortly but that Marino may wait a
few weeks, which means he could change his mind, depending on what
happens with the coaching situation.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a chance the decisiveness of Saturday's defeat may
have cost assistant head coach Dave Wannstedt a chance to replace
Johnson because owner Wayne Huizenga will be so embarrassed he may
want to erase all evidence of the debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the blame for this one,'' Johnson said. ``I didn't give
them a chance, and that's what we've got to live with. I tried to
prepare them (players) too much. I should have pulled back after
the long trip to Seattle (for a 20-17 wild-card win). It was
obvious from the start that we were dead-legged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had great practices, but, unfortunately, we left
it on the practice field. That was poor judgment on my part. We
were dominated in all three phases. I should have tried to keep
them fresh for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville was so magnificent that it probably wouldn't have
made any difference what Johnson did to prepare. Coach Tom Coughlin
played everyone but the cheerleaders during the game, but the
Jaguars still could do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm stunned,'' said Jaguars defensive tackle Gary Walker, who
had two sacks. ``To score this many points and win like this is
just unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this was a case of Marino having a bad day. It
was a case of us putting a lot of pressure on him by playing great
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino threw a terrible pass on Miami's first series that was
intercepted by cornerback Aaron Beasley to set up a field goal for
a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure (pass rush) got to him, and he had to get rid of
the ball,'' said Beasley, who will see on film that there was no
pressure on Marino on the play. ``Dan's the kind of quarterback who
won't take a lot of sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he feels pressure, he's going to throw it. I just turned
around, and the ball was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars were great in every area. They have taken a lot of
heat for not beating a team with a winning record, but critics
can't use it against them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we proved today is that we won and that it's
going to be tough to win here,'' said receiver Keenan McCardell,
who caught four passes for 52 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in this situation in 1996 when we played in the AFC
Championship Game (a loss at New England). We won't prove anything
until we reach our goal (Super Bowl XXXIV).''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Mark Brunell proved he is healthy. Playing for the
first time since suffering a sprained knee Dec. 26, he hardly broke
a sweat before departing for good early in the second quarter. He
completed five of nine passes for 105 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback Jay Fiedler hit seven of 11 for 172 yards and
two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who also rushed for 257 yards, had a yardage
advantage of 197 to minus-one when they led 24-0.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Fred Taylor put on an incredible exhibition with
135 yards rushing on 18 carries. He caught a 39-yard touchdown pass
and, in a series of unusual plays, scored on a 90-yard run, the
longest in NFL playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran a hell of a lot faster than I thought he could,'' Miami
safety Calvin Jackson said. ``He's just so explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins defensive end Trace Armstrong was even more
complimentary of Taylor, who missed much of the season with a
hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits the hole quicker than any back I've seen,'' Armstrong
said. ``He runs outside and inside and breaks tackles and makes
guys miss. He's just tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's 90-yard touchdown wasn't the only thing unusual about
this game.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Jaguars end Tony Brackens sacked Marino,
forced a fumble, recovered the fumble and, with the Dolphins either
standing around looking at him or trying to play two-hand touch,
let his teammates push him into the end zone for a 16-yard
touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy to get the sack and recover the fumble,''
Brackens said. ``I thought I was down, until one of our guys pushed
me in the back and said to run. I felt a bunch of guys on top of
me, but they said it was our guys. I didn't know I was in the end
zone until the official signaled touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   And the weirdest of the weird, the sprinkler system came on in
the south end zone in the third quarter, but the Dolphins, who have
been outscored 100-10 in divisional games the past two years, were
already washed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came in at halftime, we knew the game wasn't over,''
said Jaguars receiver Jimmy Smith, who caught five passes for 136
yards and a touchdown. ``But once Dan went out in the third
quarter, we felt they were out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game got so out of hand that Chris Howard, a third-string
running back, scored on a five-yard run. Alvis Whitted, a
third-string receiver, caught a 38-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play our best game now,'' said McCardell, who
really thinks the Jaguars can play better. ``We've still got a lot
of work to do. No matter who we play, we've got to bring our `A'
game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
