u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-BUCS-HNS     01-15 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-BUCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bucs rely on defense, bit of luck
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TAMPA, Fla. _ Great defense, timely offense and a little luck is
what it took to end a two-decade wait and send the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers back to the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs came from behind to beat the Washington Redskins 14-13
on Saturday at Raymond James Stadium after trailing 13-0 late in
the third quarter of the NFC divisional playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Washington watched the final opportunity at victory end in
disaster. Brett Conway lined up to try a 52-yard field goal on
fourth-and-four with 1:17 left in the fourth quarter. But the snap
from Dan Turk rolled to holder Brad Johnson, Washington's starting
quarterback. Johnson got up and looked for a receiver, but was
tackled by cornerback Floyd Young as he threw incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conway's a good kicker and he probably would have made it,''
said Tampa Bay cornerback Ronde Barber. ``You can say we got lucky,
but to me, luck is preparation meeting opportunity, and that's what
we did today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay will meet the winner of today's game between Minnesota
and St. Louis. A victory by the Vikings will give Tampa Bay the
home field for the second NFC Championship Game in franchise
history and the first since the 1979 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rooting for my buddies in Minnesota,'' said Tampa Bay
coach Tony Dungy, a former defensive coordinator at Minnesota. ``We
would love to play those guys next week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay defense did not allow a touchdown Saturday, but a
100-yard kickoff return by Brian Mitchell to start the third
quarter and two field goals by Conway gave Washington a 13-0 lead
before the Tampa Bay defense forced two key turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't looking real good, but we just needed to make one
big play and (strong safety) John Lynch got it for us,'' Dungy
said. ``That got the crowd back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Things began to change for the Bucs after an interception by
Lynch. Johnson tried to throw to Albert Connell on a deep turn-in,
but Lynch stepped in front of the pass at Tampa Bay's 31 with 5:06
to go in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we knew we needed to make something happen
offensively and make the most of how well our defense was
playing,'' said Bucs receiver Jacquez Green. ``We started executing
on the plays we were missing earlier in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs drove to the Washington 42, when quarterback Shaun King
threw a deep sideline pass for Warrick Dunn. Safety Leomont Evans
was flagged for interference when he knocked down Dunn before the
ball arrived, giving the Bucs a first down at the Washington 11.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Mike Alstott did the rest, first on a catch-and-run to
the two, then an amazing second-effort touchdown run. Alstott was
grabbed in the backfield before being hit head-on by three Redskins
at the four, but he backed up, reversed field and ran in to make it
13-7 with 2:03 remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play symbolizes the whole day,'' Dungy said. ``We just
weren't going to be denied. Our guys don't give up. They hung in
there and overcame some adversity. We saw some great individual
efforts when we needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another example came when Tampa Bay's defense made a big play
early in the fourth quarter to set up the game-winning touchdown.
Johnson fumbled when he was blind-sided by defensive end Steve
White. Defensive tackle Warren Sapp dove on the loose ball, giving
the Bucs possession at Washington's 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tampa's big plays on defense made the difference,'' said
Washington coach Norv Turner. ``We competed as hard as we could,
but we were not able to handle every circumstance that we needed
to.''
</P>
<P>
   A lucky break enabled Tampa Bay to keep alive the second scoring
drive when Dunn scooped up a fumble and gave the Bucs a first down
at Washington's 17. On a third-and-three at the Washington 25, King
scrambled and dropped the ball at the 30 when he was hit from
behind, but Dunn picked it up and got the first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got that one I kind of thought it might be our day,''
Dungy said. ``I kind of felt it was meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs had a third-and-goal at the one when King threw a TD
pass to tight end John Davis. King ran a bootleg right and threw
the ball as he was clobbered by Ndukwe Kalu. It gave the Bucs their
first lead with 7:29 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play great today, but I didn't lose the game,
either,'' said King, 22, a rookie. ``Our defense is the strength of
our team and all we needed was two scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington maximized its last possession, going from its 38 to
the Tampa Bay 34 before lining up for a field goal that wasn't
kicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad never had a chance,'' Turner said. ``One guy didn't get
the job done, not the whole unit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in franchise history Washington lost a
playoff game when it led after three quarters. The Redskins were
20-0 in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough to lose a game that was going our way for so
long,'' said Washington receiver Michael Westbrook. ``We didn't
finish them off when we had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
