<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7336 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN     01-15 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAINT'S HONOR SCORES UPSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ Cat Thief won the fight over General Challenge.
Saint's Honor won the San Fernando Stakes over both.
</P>
<P>
   While Cat Thief, the Breeders' Cup Classic winner, and General
Challenge, the Santa Anita Derby winner, exchanged bumps midway
through the 1 1/16-mile race Saturday, Saint's Honor and jockey
Kent Desormeaux stayed clear of the warring favorites on the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of strategy _ or luck _ helped the 24-1 shot go on to
win the $300,000 race for 4-year-olds before a Laffit Pincay Day
crowd of 19,875 at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I was the only one who didn't get banged
around,'' said Desormeaux, who picked up the mount after Corey
Nakatani, brother-in-law of winning trainer Craig Dollase, chose to
ride fifth-place finisher Cliquot.
</P>
<P>
   Saint's Honor ($50.60) won by 1 1/2 lengths over Cat Thief and
Pat Day, who held on for second by a head over Mr. Broad Blade and
Pat Valenzuela. General Challenge and Chris McCarron wound up fifth
after getting the worst of the bumping.
</P>
<P>
   On the far turn, Cat Thief was moving up inside pacesetter
Straight Man and General Challenge was advancing quickly between
Cat Thief and the rail. The next thing the naked eye saw was
McCarron pulling General Challenge out of the tight squeeze _ and
virtually out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   The stewards watched the videotape for nine minutes before
deciding not to disqualify Cat Thief, ruling it was Straight Man,
ridden by David Flores, who started the chain reaction. Straight
Man faded to sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Day blamed himself for getting Cat Thief in trouble in the D.
Wayne Lukas-trained colt's second consecutive defeat since his 19-1
upset in the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My horse ran a game, game race,'' Day said. ``I just didn't
ride a very good race.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron said he simply ``ran out of room.... That's not a good
place to be moving backward in a race.'' Trainer Bob Baffert had
replaced Flores with McCarron before General Challenge's Native
Diver Handicap victory last month.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay didn't ride in the San Fernando but rewarded his fans
with a $10.80 payoff on his 8,852nd career winner,
Continentalsuccess in the second race.
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-minute ceremony following the fifth, Pincay was honored
for breaking Bill Shoemaker's record with No.8,834 on Dec. 10 at
Hollywood Park. Pincay received a medal signifying Panama's highest
civilian honor, and President Clinton praised him via videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that his mother, Virginia Kelley, was a horseplayer,
Clinton called it ``a particular pleasure'' to honor Pincay. ``You
gave us a great thrill with one of the last great sporting
achievements of the 20th century,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: In early season 3-year-old races, Hal's Hope ($82.40)
scored his first stakes victory in the $100,000 Holy Bull at
Gulfstream Park, and Golden Eagle Farm's New Advantage won the
$150,000 Golden Gate Derby on a rain-soaked track. Greenwood Lake
was a punchless sixth in the Florida race.... Irish Nip finished
last in his first start since becoming Laffit Pincay's
record-breaking winner. Brice Blanc, the colt's original jockey,
was back aboard.... Budroyale is a 7-5 morning-line favorite for
the San Pasqual Handicap today.... The pick-six carryover today is
nearly $193,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
