<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET BACK TO BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS -- Failure was an almost foreign feeling to the
Lakers by the time their 16-game winning streak came to a halt
Friday night in Indianapolis, but coach Phil Jackson said it didn't
take long for them to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pouted like 3-year-old kids,'' Jackson said Saturday,
``but they got over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the end result was still a winning streak that tied
for seco nd best in franchise history and eighth best in NBA
history.
</P>
<P>
   So there wasn't much for Jackson to say to his team afterward,
other than to analyze the mistakes that led to their 111-102 loss
to the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said a lot of things, but nothing of great importance,''
Jackson said. ``We played a team with a little experience, they
pulled some rinky- dink stuff that they like to do. Then you learn
that stuff. When you're prepared for them, you know what they're
going to do, and these things d on't come up.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant things like Reggie Miller flaring out a leg on his
jumpshot to draw a foul, but also silly Laker errors like fouling
on 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Jackson has said all along that a team needs to lose
to learn . So maybe this wasn't such a bad thing to have happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't coach unless there's a loss, you mean? ... There is
some truth to that. A lot of truth,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq-daddy: Shaquille O'Neal quietly became a father again last
week, when his girlfriend gave birth to a baby boy, Shareef Rashaun
O'Neal, on Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am a proud father of a little baby boy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was up late the night of Shareef's birth, before the
Lakers embarked on their three-game road trip, but he said that
wasn't the source of his recent fatigue, and some subpar shooting
the last few games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired, kind of beat up,'' he said. ``I'm going to
take the day off (Sunday), then I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot-button issue: Jackson is doing his best to plug former
Knicks teammate and presidential candidate Bill Bradley,
occasionally wearing a campaign button on his lapel. But he's
failed in one respect --he hasn't yet been ordered by the NBA not
to wear the button on TV, thus creating a story, and some
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's stuck their head in the sand, they kind of didn't
want to mention it,'' he said, sounding disappointed. ``I haven't
heard anything . I was hoping to get some kind of declaration on
it, so I can at least make a statement and eveybody would pick up
on it and bring some focus.' '
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
