<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-15 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-REPUBS-DEBATE-980(2     01-15 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REPUBS-DEBATE-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN CANDIDATES CRITICIZE BUSH TAX PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct coding)  (ko) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSTON, Iowa _ Seeking to undermine Gov. George W. Bush in the
last Republican debate only nine days before the caucuses here, his
rivals Saturday questioned his credentials as a tax cutter and
ridiculed his centerpiece plan to reduce taxes by $483 billion over
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks were led by Sen. John McCain, who warned that Bush's
plan favored the wealthy at the expense of lower and middle income
taxpayers. His own proposal, he said, would address a more pressing
matter of paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's plan has not one penny for Social Security,
not one penny for Medicare and not one penny for paying down the
national debt,'' McCain said. ``And when you run ads saying you're
going to take care of Social Security, my friend, that's all hat
and no cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush shot back, ``That's cute, but it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' McCain said, ``they're always cutest when they're
true.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush defended his proposal, saying, ``I've got 2 trillion
set aside to Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush provoked the quarrel when, posing a question to McCain, he
accused the Arizona senator of backing a loophole that would
essentially amount to a $40 billion tax increase for working
Americans through worker-related benefits.
</P>
<P>
   McCain repeatedly tried to turn the attention back to Bush's
plan, at one point tossing off a another quip by suggesting that he
was dancing a ``Texas two-step'' in trying to justify a plan the
would not benefit working-class Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The sparring between Bush and McCain made for the most stirring
moments of a 90-minute forum _ the seventh debate with all six
candidates _ at the Iowa Public Television studios here that
otherwise was striking for the lack of hard-edged exchanges this
close to the first actual voting.
</P>
<P>
   While the event was billed by its sponsor, The Des Moines
Register, as a debate, the candidates did not take much of an
opportunity to challenge each other; instead they mostly restated
their stands on matters like health care and helping family farmers
to foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the event four years ago, when the combatants at this
event ganged up on Steve Forbes and ridiculed his flat-tax plan,
which had been gaining steam, this time they were far more
cautious. Polls show that Bush is well ahead of the pack of the
Republican candidates campaigning here, with Forbes a far distant
second. McCain, who is neck and neck with Bush in polls in New
Hampshire, is not actively campaigning in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, several candidates, led by McCain, did raise questions
about Bush's tax plan. Forbes questioned the governor's record on
taxes as governor of Texas. ``Most Texans have never seen those tax
cuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah repeatedly said he was the only
contender who could steer a sweeping tax cut through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to have somebody who knows how to get a
tax plan through congress,'' Hatch said. But he also aimed his fire
at McCain, saying, ``I think we could have gotten President Clinton
to give us a bigger tax cut than John McCain's.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the 90-minute event, Bush appeared somewhat
rattled, and sought to defend his credentials as a tax cutter by
declaring, in a response to a question by Forbes, ``Well you know
something Steve, nearly 69 percent of Texans said overwhelmingly in
1998, `You're the man. We appreciate your tax cuts.''' He added,
``It's really real for a lot of folks who live in my state.''
</P>
<P>
   During the exchanges, the candidates differed chiefly on
questions of taxes, ethanol subsidies and China policy, but spent
much of their time taking turns railing against the ethics of the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about the country, I'm worried about whether we
are going to have a continuation of the current leadership,'' Sen.
Hatch said at the debate's opening. ``I want to see the
Clinton-Gore team go.''
</P>
<P>
   The main point of disagreement in foreign policy came when Gary
Bauer, long a critic of the Clinton administration's China policy,
declared that he would revoke China's trading status with the
United States, at a moment when the Clinton administration is
trying to make China's ``normal trade status'' permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That policy has failed,'' Bauer said, adding that China was
``in a mass build-up'' of its military forces. ``We need a Reagan
policy,'' said Bauer, who worked in the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, China has been granted what was previously known as
``most favored nation'' status every year since 1980, including
every year of Reagan's presidency, on Reagan's initiative and with
the approval of Congress. But none of the Republican candidates who
agree with the Clinton administration and favor the extension of
normal trade relations with China made that point. Alan Keyes, a
former ambassador, asked Bush about the town of El Cenizo in Texas,
which he said had passed rules to conduct all its business in
Spanish. Bush quickly responded in Spanish that ``it's not the
truth.'' Keyes shot back, also in Spanish, ``It is the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush countered that he had consulted with the attorney general
of Texas and that all of the town's meeting are now ``conducted in
English under the laws of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for English-plus,'' said Bush, describing his approach,
chiefly for the schools, that English must be the main language of
instruction, but that other languages also be used in school
environments.
</P>
<P>
   All the candidates talked about aggressively opening up foreign
markets for farm goods, from Iowa and elsewhere. But none referred
to the series of trade agreements struck by the Clinton
administration in recent years to do just that, and only Keyes
described a general strategy for forcing Europe to open its markets
to American-made agricultural products.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But much of the session was devoted to taxes. The candidates
used a question posed by Bernard Hayes of Cedar Rapids on the
marriage penalty to defend their own tax plans and attack those of
the others.
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued, once again, that the government budget surplus
should be used primarily to pay down the nation's debt and support
the Social Security program. ``I do want to give middle and lower
income people a much needed tax break,'' he said. ``But we have to
take care of other obligations over the years. We are staggering
under a $5.6 trillion debt and cannot lay that on future
generations. And the Social Security fund is a ticking time bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bauer assailed Bush's plan of ``rearranging the deck chairs
on the Titanic,'' Bush visible bristled and said: ``I'm the one
person who has fought for and signed tax cuts. I've laid out a plan
to make sure the economy continues to grow and to make the tax code
more fair. My plan hears the call of people who live on the
outskirts of poverty. I believe it is important to have to have tax
programs that keep money away from Washington where people will
spend on more and bigger programs. The best way to reduce the fat
is to send money back to the people who pay that taxes and that's
what I intended to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain used the opportunity to pick up on his centerpiece attack
on corporate influences in Congress. ``Last fall Congress passed
one of the most obscene pieces of legislation, a pork-laden bill
that would have spent the entire budget surplus. I fought against
it and I railed against it. The president should force Congress to
spend less money.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the strongest language on taxes, Keyes, who wants the
income tax eliminated, said: ``The simple logic of the income tax
is that it is a slave tax and we are a tax and slave people.''
</P>
<P>
   And Forbes, who first raised the issue of tax cuts with his
calls for a 17 percent flat income tax criticized McCain and Bush
as ``timid tax cutters'' and said Bush's tax cuts in Texas were
``more apparent than real.'' Currently, Forbes is running attack
television ads saying Bush broke an anti-tax pledge while governor
of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   To this, Bush responded by pointing to an advertisement run in
Saturday's Des Moines Register by Bob Dole, whom Forbes attacked in
a negative television campaign in the 1996 Iowa primaries, that was
a thinly veiled criticism of Forbes' attack ads in this campaign.
``Bob Dole wrote a pretty interesting advertisement today,'' Bush
said. ``He said if you talk about the record talk about the whole
record. I cut taxes. If not, our budget would have grown by $3
billion. Ask the elderly person whose homestead exemption was
raised by $10,000. That's real. It may not be real to those who
live in million dollar houses. But it is real for the people who
live in my state.''
</P>
<P>
   Switching to a question about religion in schools, the
candidates were asked whether they would support the posting of the
Ten Commandments. . Forbes favored it and Bush said, ``It seems
like to me that thou shalt not kill is pretty universal and I think
our districts ought to be allowed to post the Ten Commandments.
These are inherent values that make our society better for
everybody. Our schools ought to expand character educations. We
have to have character education that teaches our children right
from wrong, good from bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-15-00 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000115.0252 </DOCNO>
