<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 23)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE ORCHID THIEF &LR;  By Susan Orlean. Ballantine, $14. The
author's first book-length narrative is a journalistic account of a
thief caught pilfering 200 rare orchids and plants in Florida, but
its true subject is the monomania of collectors and growers, who
can wait seven years just to see a new plant bloom. This peculiar
mania is revealed as ``a small thing of grandeur, a passion with a
pedigree,'' Ted Conover wrote in The New York Times Book Review
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOURS &LR;  By Michael Cunningham. Picador USA, $13. The theme
of this Pulitzer Prize-winning novel is the haunting of present
lives by memories and books, and it evolves in three connected
narratives _ those of a New York woman whose life echoes events in
Virginia Woolf's ``Mrs. Dalloway''; a housewife in 1940s Los
Angeles who reads the book; and Woolf herself in 1923, living near
London and writing her novel. ``The overall impression is that of a
delicate, triumphant glance, an acknowledgment of Woolf that takes
her into Cunningham's own territory, a place of late-century danger
but also of treasurable hours,'' Michael Wood wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROCKET BOYS: A Memoir &LR;  By Homer H. Hickam Jr. Delta, $12.95.
This nostalgic coming-of-age story is set during the Sputnik era in
dreary West Virginia coal country, where the author (a future NASA
engineer) and five pals undertook an audacious series of rocket
launchings that captured the imagination of a dying region. ``He is
a very adept storyteller,'' James R. Gaines wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAD CHEMISTRY &LR;  By Gary Krist. Berkley, $7.50. A headless body,
a combustible dog and ``The Tale of Peter Rabbit'' are among the
plot elements in this taut mystery about an ex-policewoman trying
to track down her missing husband. ``Fascination with the power of
secrets ... holds the book together,'' David Willis McCullough
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVENTING WYATT EARP: His Life and Many Legends &LR;  By Allen
Barra. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $15.95. In 1881, a 30-second gunfight helped
create an American hero and a stirring myth of frontier justice. It
turns out that accounts of Earp's career and the shootout were full
of ironies, confusion and outright falsehoods. This ``refreshingly
pugnacious book'' aims to set the record straight, Richard E.
Nicholls wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELEGY FOR IRIS &LR;  By John Bayley. Picador USA, $13. The British
literary critic chronicles his long, rich relationship with his
wife, the novelist Iris Murdoch, and her descent into Alzheimer's
disease. ``In its evocation of the lyrical, the comic and the
tragic, this splendid book enlarges our imagination of the range
and possibilities of love,'' Mary Gordon wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THERE ONCE WAS A WORLD: A Nine-Hundred-Year Chronicle of the
Shtetl of Eishyshok &LR;  By Yaffa Eliach. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $25.
A historian recreates in intensely rendered detail the daily
rhythms of life in her family's shtetl, a town in what is now
Lithuania whose 3,500 Jews were nearly all murdered. Her account
contains numerous photographs and interviews with survivors. In
1998 the reviewer Stephen J. Dubner called this ``an exhaustive and
kaleidoscopic history.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REST OF US: The Rise of America's Eastern European Jews &LR; ,
by Stephen Birmingham (Syracuse University, $22.95), is the final
installment in the author's trilogy on Jewish immigrants in
America. It is a broad canvas filled with portraits of colorful
characters like Irving Berlin, Meyer Lansky and Ralph Lauren.
``Trenchant observations permeate this book,'' Sydney Zion wrote in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACE-TIME &LR;  By Erik Tarloff. Pocket Books, $12.95. A rising
White House speechwriter is horrified when the president takes a
shine to his girlfriend. She's flattered, of course, and tempted by
the prospect of ultimate insider access. The result is a novel
``about sex and power in Washington that goes behind the headlines
to a darker place,'' Patricia O'Brien wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FALLING SLOWLY &LR;  By Anita Brookner. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
This novel focuses on two willfully hermitic sisters torn between a
desire for connection with the larger world and a greedy
complacency about their carefully sheltered existence. Brookner is
``the unrivaled mistress of the stifled life,'' Claire Messud wrote
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOREIGN BODIES &LR;  By Hwee Hwee Tan. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $12.95. This first novel is about a young lawyer in
Singapore who has nine days to prove that her English boyfriend is
not the mastermind of an international gambling ring. ``Tan spins
out a gripping story,'' Anderson Tepper wrote in The New York Times
Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINTER COUNT &LR;  By Barry Lopez. Vintage, $11. Many of these
stories focus on obscure figures and incidents in the Plains and
Rockies, and are informed by American Indian culture and mystical
wisdom. Each tale ``is as economical in design, as painstakingly
crafted and as resonant as a good classical guitar,'' David Quammen
wrote in 1981.
</P>
</TEXT>
